<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Schroeder     03-24 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Schroeder,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jay Schroeder's Restaurant Victim Of Second-String Quarterback
Woes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FALLS CHURCH, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Being a second-string quarterback can
be hard on business, as the Washington Redskins' Jay Schroeder has
discovered.
   Schroeder, backup to starter Doug Williams, says the restaurant
operating in this Washington suburb under his name ``was a business
venture that didn't work out.''
   The owners of J. Schroeder's All-Pro Restaurant recently decided
to close the eatery because of mounting debts. Schroeder allowed
his name to be used for the establishment in exchange for a small
percentage of its profit and an agreement to appear there several
times a week. He declined to discuss the closing, saying the
restaurant's problems were ``for me to know.''
   Schroeder lost his position as the Skins' starting quarterback
in midseason last year. The Skins went on to win the Super Bowl
under Williams.
   ``Having the second-string quarterback's name on the restaurant
did not help business,'' said Bruce Sandground, general manager at
the Sign of the Whale, another Falls Church restaurant.
   Former Redskins' quarterback Joe Theismann owns three
restaurants in the area that bear his name. But Theismann began his
career as a restaurateur just as his career was beginning to take
off, while the opening of J. Schroeder's last year coincided with
Schroeder's slump.
   Schroeder said he was looking into other business opportunities.
</TEXT>
