<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SunriseWind     03-24 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sunrise Wind,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Sunrise Wind' Bodes Ill For Farming Conditions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POST, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tough year for farmers is in the wind _
that is, if an old Comanche Indian legend holds true.
   According to the legend, the wind direction at precisely sunrise
on the day after the first day of spring will tell what kind of
weather and farming conditions the next year will hold for the
region.
   If the wind, called Taba'na Yuna'e in Comanche, comes from the
east or northeast, good harvests should follow; if it blows from
the north or northwest, conditions will be average. A west or
southwest wind doesn't bode well, and a south wind is just plain
bad news.
   Records on the annual ceremony are said to show a 92 percent
success rate since 1906, the first year settlers gathered to see
what the winds had in store.
   ``Chief'' Frank Runkles, who has been performing the ceremony
for 15 years, began his dance Tuesday with supplications to
Wakantanka, the Father Spirit, and Mikeana, Mother Earth, as well
as the winds.
   ``The Mother Earth is revered because she gives us food to
eat,'' he said. ``Wakantanka is the Great Father above _ we seek
his blessings.''
   As he spoke, a southerly wind blew so hard that Indian dancers
from an Amarillo Boy Scout Explorer Post had to shield a ceremonial
fire as it was ignited.
   The gusts died down as sunrise neared. Seconds before Runkles
caught the first glimpse of the sun over the distant horizon, a
gust whisked in from the north, then reversed direction at the
moment of sunrise, giving an official reading of west-southwest _
bad news for farmers.
   Despite the Indians' claims of predictive accuracy, however,
farmers don't necessarily need to worry.
   Last year, smoke from Runkles' fire indicated a south wind and
poor conditions, but Southern Plains farmers ended up with one of
the best cotton harvests on record.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
