<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0142EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Cyprus-Archaeology     03-24 0816</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cyprus-Archaeology,0845</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cyprus' Civilization May Be 1,500 Years Older Than Believed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AKROTIRI, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New discoveries by American
archaeologists indicate that humans could have settled on Cyprus
around 9000 B.C., 1,500 years earlier than previously thought.
   The finds also indicate that some species of ancient animals
survived here at least 1,000 years after they were believed to have
become extinct.
   If proven correct, the discoveries mean that Cyprus was one of
the earliest human settlements north of Africa, along with the
island of Corsica, also in the Mediterranean.
   ``If these dates are corroborated, the site will have provided
by far the earliest archaeological evidence for island colonization
anywhere in the Mediterranean,'' Dr. Stuart Swiny, director of the
Cyprus American Archaeological Research Institute, reported in a
recent lecture.
   Scientists had previously dated man's arrival on Cyprus around
7500 B.C.
   But archaelogists digging on a slope near the sprawling British
air base at Akrotiri on Cyprus' south coast recently found pygmy
hippopotamus and dwarf elephant bones, some mixed with shells,
flint and ash.
   Archaelogists believe the flint, an early cutting tool, was used
to slice meat from the animals. The ash indicated cooking fires.
   Carbon dating placed the remains at around 9000 B.C., a
millenium after those species of animals were believed to have died
out.
   Swiny said that the animals, common to many Mediterranean
islands thousands of years ago, were wiped out by climatic changes
during the last Ice Age that ended around 12,000 years ago.
   ``We thought ... these animals died out because of natural
causes _ they couldn't get enough food or enough water,'' Swiny
said in an interview after the lecture.
   ``But now it looks as if man was also responsible for wiping
them out.''
   The Akrotiri excavation is sponsored by the University of Nevada
and the American Schools of Oriental Research, which sponsors the
Cyprus American institute. The dig is under the direction of Dr.
Alan Simmons, who currently is in Nevada.
   The original discovery was made in 1980 by a British security
officer at Akrotiri, Maj. Brian Pile, then a lieutenant, while he
was training his men to seek out unusual objects.
   Underground excavation at the site, eight miles south of the
port city of Limassol, started last July and will continue this
summer.
   Swiny said the actual age of the site will remain questionable
until results of further tests are obtained.
   The finds are only some of the important discoveries unearthed
by American archaeologists in the last few years on Cyprus, the
center of trade routes between Europe and the Middle East for
centuries.
   The island is studded with relics of a history that spans more
than 10,000 years, during which more than a dozen civilizations,
including Achaean Greeks, Egyptians, Romans, Armenians, Venetians
and Ottoman Turks left their imprint.
   Americans are involved in six of the 20 digs currently being
made in the Greek-controlled southern part of Cyprus.
   The Cyprus American institute provides logistical help at one
sponsored by Brandeis University, of Waltham, Mass., at the Late
Bronze Age town of Kalavasos-Ayios Dhimitrios, 18 miles northeast
of Limassol.
   It was one of the biggest Bronze Age settlements on Cyprus and a
center for the island's ancient copper trade. Cyprus is the
Phoenician word for copper.
   Last summer archaelogists uncovered the remains of a 13th
century B.C. building, covering more than 10,764 square feet and
once at least two stories high, that was apparently destroyed by
fire.
   ``It's the biggest and most important building at the site and
one of the biggest of that period in Cyprus,'' said Dr. Alison
South Todd, the dig's co-director.
   ``We also found some inscriptions which are very rare to the
period in Cypro-Minoan script,'' she added.
   Cypro-Minoan, which resembles the script used in Minoan Crete
4,000 years ago, has never been deciphered.
   The presence of these inscriptions and the huge storage capacity
of the building, known as Building X, suggest it was either a
palace or a town hall.
   The storage room, more than 60 feet long and 24 feet wide,
consists of an outer wall and six stone pillars that once supported
the roof.
   The shards of at least 47 jars, some once as tall as six feet,
have been found. All apparently had been smashed in the fire. But
six intact jars were later discovered in pits below the floor.
   Todd discovered a tomb, considered one of the richest and best
preserved ever found on Cyprus, while digging an exploratory trench
out from the building.
   The oval-shaped tomb contained the skeletons of three young
women, a child about 3 years old and three infants. They apparently
had social status and wealth.
   The women had been buried with gold and silver jewelry, bronze
and bone artifacts, containers of wine with small cups inside and
cylindrical ivory cosmetic boxes.
</TEXT>
