<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0143EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ProstateTreatment     03-24 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prostate Treatment,0629</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Enlarged Prostates Treated Without Hospital Stay, Researcher
Reports</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An experimental treatment for enlarged prostate
glands shows promise as an outpatient alternative to surgery that
hospitalizes about 400,000 American men a year, researchers say.
   An enlarged prostate makes urination difficult by constricting
the urinary tract, and the experimental procedure widens the
narrowed portion by inflating a balloon, said Flavio Castaneda of
the University of Minnesota.
   Test results show complete or significant resolution of the
urination problem in about 80 percent of patients with the most
common type of enlargement, he said.
   The half-hour procedure is done with only a local anesthetic and
without an overnight stay in the hospital, he said.
   Standard surgery requires general anesthesia or a spinal
injection that numbs the lower part of the body, and a hospital
stay of several days.
   The prostate is a walnut-sized gland that surrounds the
urine-carrying urethra. In older men, it frequently enlarges and
puts pressure on the urethra, making urination more difficult.
   The experimental technique is to be described Thursday by
Castaneda's colleague, Wilfrido Castaneda-Zuniga, at a meeting of
the Society of Cardiovascular and Interventional Radiology in
Orlando, Fla.
   More than 60 patients have been treated with the experimental
procedure, called balloon urethroplasty, at the University of
Minnesota, Castaneda said in a recent telephone interview.
   The patient takes a tranquilizer and the urethra is numbed with
local anesthetic. A thin, flexible tube with the balloon on its tip
is inserted into the urethra and guided to the narrowed portion,
where the balloon is inflated.
   For the Minnesota patients, the urination problem was erased or
significantly eased in almost 80 percent of cases in which most
enlargement was from the side lobes of the prostate, rather than
the middle lobe, Castanada said. Most patients have predominant
enlargement of side lobes, he said.
   When the main problem was the middle lobe, the success rate
dropped to about 30 percent to 40 percent, he said.
   No recurrence of symptoms has been seen in any patient helped by
the procedure, he said. Forty-eight have been followed for more
than six months after the procedure, including one followed for
three years, he said.
   ``We're at this point unable to know how long it (symptom
relief) will last on the average,'' Castaneda said.
   Abraham Cockett, professor and chairman of the urology
department at the University of Rochester Medical Center in New
York, called the concept interesting.
   But he said more patients must be studied, and for periods
longer than at least a year following the procedure, to better
assess its effectiveness.
   Removing prostate tissue with standard surgery relieves symptoms
for some 15 years, said Cockett, who is secretary of the American
Urological Association.
   In another presentation at the meeting Thursday, participants
are to discuss an experimental alternative to removing gallbladders.
   About 500,000 gallbladders are removed in the United States
annually. Gallstones are the most frequent reason, said Eric
Martin, director of cardiovascular and interventional radiology at
the Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center in New York.
   In two patients, Italian scientists have instead guided a
flexible tube through the skin and into the gallbladder, used it to
remove gallstones and injected a solution to turn the gallbladder
into scar tissue.
   ``I still think it needs a lot of work, but it's exciting,''
said Martin.
   He noted that machines called lithotripters, now used to
pulverize kidney stones, are also being studied for destroying
gallstones.
   It is too early to tell how lithotripters and the surgical
technique tried in Italy will fit in to future management of
gallbladder disease, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
