<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--Zaccaro-Drugs     03-24 0146</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Zaccaro-Drugs,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Charge Dropped</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RUTLAND, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of two drug charges against John Zaccaro
Jr., the son of 1984 vice presidential candidate Geraldine Ferraro,
has been dismissed for lack of evidence.
   District Judge Francis McCaffrey on Monday threw out a charge of
possession of cocaine with intent to sell.
   After Zaccaro's 1986 arrest, McCaffrey ruled inadmissible eight
grams of cocaine and records of drug transactions seized by police
from Zaccaro's car. The judge said at the time that the search
warrant was based on insufficient evidence.
   Zaccaro still faces an April 4 trial on a charge of selling a
quarter-gram of cocaine to a state trooper while Zaccaro was a
student at Middlebury College.
   McCaffrey also said defense attorneys cannot claim at the trial
that Zaccaro was a victim of selective prosecution because the
issue does not relate to guilt or innocence.
</TEXT>
