<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0207EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     03-24 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0598</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oscar the Grouch, the guru of garbage on
television's ``Sesame Street,'' has been asked to remove all
recyclables from his trash can home.
   The famous character on the long-running PBS-TV children's show
recently received a letter from Paula S. Barnabie, who works for
the Camden County Office of Solid Waste.
   Every day, Ms. Barnabie wrote, the clank of aluminum, the crunch
of newspapers and the tinkle of glass can be heard as Oscar fights
his way to the surface of his trash can to snarl at Sesame Street
residents.
   ``I watch the program every day with my nephew and I just
couldn't take it any more,'' she said. ``It would be so much nicer
and environmentally sound for you to have a recycling bucket near
your trash can.''
   Camden County will even give the tetchy titan of trash one of
its brand new recycling buckets, she informed Oscar. The bright
yellow buckets ``can be dirtied up in no time flat'' to match the
rest of his dirty, dented decor, she said.
   The producers of Sesame Street are considering Ms. Barnabie's
suggestions, said Gail Y. Miyasaki, a spokeswoman for Children's
Television Workshop, the show's producer.
   Ms. Barnabie said she has not heard from Oscar, however.
   ``If he recycled, he'd be able to find a pen and paper in that
can to write back to me,'' she said. ``I hope he doesn't tell me to
go `scram.'''

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIRAMAR, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Don Bailey's face and Burt Reynolds' body
have been sprawled across the side of a warehouse for 10 years, but
City Commissioner Vicki Coceano says she wants to beautify the area
_ starting with Bailey.
   The 19-foot wide mural on Bailey's carpet store has Bailey's
head superimposed on Reynolds' body _ a takeoff on the actor's
centerfold pose in Cosmopolitan magazine several years ago. The
body reclining on a shag rug is nude except for flesh-tone bikini
trunks.
   ``He needs to be dressed or he needs to get off the rug,'' Ms.
Coceano said Tuesday.
   The issue arose when the commission rejected Bailey's request
for a variance to expand his store. Ms. Coceano said the city has
chosen to start its beautification program with him.
   ``People know me for this sign,'' Bailey said. ``I'll put a dark
swimsuit on this next time, but skimpier.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TELLURIDE, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suzanne Carrell beat a filing deadline
by 10 minutes to become a candidate for town moderator, a job most
residents had forgotten existed and which rarely has any duties.
   The unpaid job calls for her to moderate at town meetings, if
they ever are called under Telluride's custom-made home-rule
charter, which gives either the town council or residents the right
to call a town meeting twice a year.
   There have been only three such town meetings in the last nine
years, although there was an attempt to call one last year. That
failed for lack of a quorum.
   ``It is not a job with a lot of use,'' confirmed Town Clerk
Leslie Sherlock, who admitted forgetting about the opening until
someone brought it to her attention for this year's election.
   Carrell, who works in a liquor store and a bookstore, said she
decided to file for the post on Tuesday because she didn't have the
time to serve on the town council.
   But she said she was surprised to learn she may not have any
work to do.
</TEXT>
