<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Burnley-FAA     03-24 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burnley-FAA,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burnley Says FAA Can Be Slow in Improving Air Safety Rules</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary James H. Burnley IV
says the Federal Aviation Administration sometimes needs ``the
bureaucratic equivalent of a cattle prod'' to move on safety issues.
   In an unusual condemnation of an agency by the Cabinet officer
who oversees it, Burnley accused the FAA of frequently harboring
``institutional resistance'' when the time comes to move harshly
against the nation's aviation industry.
   At times, he said, ``it has been necessary to use the
bureaucratic equivalent of a cattle prod to get the FAA to take
needed safety actions.''
   Burnley blamed the problem on the agency's structure and not its
employees. The FAA is charged with writing and enforcing safety
regulations for U.S. aviation, running the nation's air traffic
control system and promoting American air commerce.
   ``Because the FAA is charged with promoting and protecting the
industry's commercial interests, it is sometimes reluctant to take
safety and enforcement actions that impose significant costs and
burdens on that industry,'' Burnley told the Senate aviation
subcommittee.
   As an example, Burnley said FAA officials and industry
representatives opposed a 1986 proposal that airline and airport
employees be screened by security devices, arguing that the plan
was ``too burdensome.'' Even when the proposal was changed, the FAA
delayed implementing the proposal for a year, he said.
   Two weeks ago, Burnley told reporters the FAA was not being
strict enough in punishing airlines whose employees did not
effectively screen passengers for weapons. He sent FAA
Administrator Allan McArtor a memo March 8 asking him ``to give his
personal attention to this matter.'' McArtor agreed, Burnley said
Wednesday.
   ``Often it takes someone from outside the organization to insist
that there may be ways to enhance safety that are being
overlooked,'' he said.
   Burnley said the FAA ``is filled with competent, dedicated
professionals'' who are placed in ``an inherently untenable
position'' by the agency's structure.
   Asked after the hearing if he believed McArtor was responsible
for any of the agency's problems, he said, ``Allan's doing a fine
job, doing an outstanding job.''
   In a statement, McArtor said the FAA is taking steps to improve
its efficiency. ``The current system for dealing with aviation
issues is too slow and cumbersome,'' he said.
   The FAA has been criticized by some lawmakers in recent years
for failing to move quickly enough to expand the number of air
traffic controllers and for a lack of aggressiveness in making
other safety improvements.
   Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky., chairman of the aviation panel, has
introduced legislation that would make the FAA an independent
agency in hopes of giving it the ability to respond more quickly to
problems.
   Burnley said the FAA could do a better job if its promotional
duties and the air traffic control system were removed from its
responsibilities. The agency should continue overseeing safety as a
part of the Transportation Department, he said, so, ``If you don't
get what you want out of an administrator, there's a secretary you
can collar.''
</TEXT>
