<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Vietnam-Congress     03-24 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-Congress,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Administration Opposes Greater Contact with Vietnam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration is resisting calls
to raise the level of U.S. diplomatic contact with Vietnam, saying
it wants to maintain pressure on the Vietnamese to withdraw their
troops from Cambodia.
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., and Rep. Tom Ridge, R-Pa., on
Wednesday called for the establishment of a ``working U.S.
presence'' in Vietnam. They said little progress has been made on
numerous issues which remain as the ``legacy'' of the Vietnam War,
despite numerous visits to Vietnam by congressional and
administration delegations.
   The administration, however, said it opposed the lawmakers' call
for the creation of ``interest sections,'' which are typically
established between nations that don't recognize each other but
acknowledge mutual concerns.
   The United States and Cuba, for example, have interest section
personnel stationed in third-party embassies in each others'
nations.
   ``We continue to believe that political and economic isolation
is the most effective way of pressing Vietnam to end its occupation
of Cambodia,'' the State Department said in a statement released
Wednedsay.
   ``We are prepared to discuss normalization with Vietnam,
therefore, only in the context of an acceptable settlement in
Cambodia which includes the withdrawal of Vietnamese troops,'' it
said. Vietnam's military occupation of Cambodia is in its ninth
year.
   McCain and Ridge are both Vietnam veterans and McCain is a
former prisoner of war. They issued their call for greater
diplomatic contact with Vietnam on the 15th anniversary of McCain's
release after five years of captivity.
   McCain said establishment of interest sections ``falls far short
of diplomatic recognition, and certainly implies no approval of a
nation's policies.''
   He said that if no progress is made on issues such as Americans
still listed as missing from the Southeast Asian conflict, then
``the option of further normalization'' could always be set aside.
   McCain said several members of the administration had indicated
privately that they supported better communication between the
nations, but that he expected that the administration's
``official'' position on Vietnam would remain the same.
   McCain and Ridge said greater contact also is needed to
administer a two-year program to bring 8,000 to 12,000 children of
American soldiers to the United States.
   ``There is a tremendous logistical problem and barrier to
progress, just by the fact that all of our technical people must
travel in and out of Bangkok every time there is to be
communication,'' Ridge said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880324-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0235EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TongassForest     03-24 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tongass Forest,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Moving to Cut Timbering in Alaska Rain Forest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Interior Committee is chopping away
at the huge timber harvests in Alaska's Tongass rain forest, the
nation's largest national forest and the timber cutting programs's
biggest money loser.
   The panel gave voice vote approval Wednesday to legislation
pushed by hard-lobbying conservation groups to scrap the 1980 law
guaranteeing that the U.S. Forest Service gets at least $40 million
a year to spend on Tongass timber sales.
   The money, much of it for logging roads to ancient stands of
huge trees, was mandated as part of the compromise that apportioned
public lands in Alaska for various uses, including commercial
development and wilderness.
   The compromise gave protected wilderness status to 5.4 million
acres of the 17.9 million acre Tongass, which has the nation's
largest populations of bald eagles and grizzly bears.
   The 1980 law, in what backers said represented economic
guarantees for southeast Alaska, set a goal of commercially
harvesting 450 billion board feet of Tongass trees every 10 years
from non-wilderness sections.
   No other national forest has a congressionally mandated harvest
goal or gets its appropriations without the year-by-year review
Congress gives to spending requests for other federal forests.
   Rep. Bruce Vento, D-Minn., said that because of low demand and
falling prices for wood pulp from Tongass, taxpayers have lost 99
cents for each $1 in sales, with some old trees going for $2 apiece.
   Vento called the 1980 law ``a mandate to overcut ... one of the
world's only temperate rain forests.''
   ``We're changing the entire environment when we cut 400- and
500-year-old trees,'' he said.
   Approved by the committee was a package put together by Rep.
George Miller, D-Calif., to scrap the 1980 timbering guarantees and
assure that the Tongass is subject to the same timber-harvest
planning practices applied to all other national forests.
   The bill would put a five-year moratorium on commercial logging
in about 1.7 million acres considered by the Southeast Alaska
Conservation Council to be prime fish and wildlife habitat
threatened by timbering.
   Miller's plan also would require the Agriculture Department to
renegotiate its long-term contracts to supply Tongass timber to two
large mills owned by Louisiana Pacific-Ketchikan Corp. and Alaska
Pulp Corp.
   About two-thirds of the Tongass production goes to these mills,
which convert it to pulp, principally for export to Japan. Critics
say the 50-year contracts, executed in the 1950s, give the
companies a regional monopoly and too large a voice in Forest
Service management decisions for the Tongass.
   Miller said the Tongass now is ``almost a scandalous operation.''
   ``We have a process that is not driven by rational forest
management,'' he said. ``We have cuttings driven by a political
bargain.''
   Don Young, Alaska's only House member and the ranking Republican
on Interior, opposed Miller's plan because ``it basically shuts
down the mills. ... We're talking about 6,000 jobs.''
   Young said the committee was being unduly influenced by
conservation groups such as the Wilderness Society and Sierra Club,
which have made the Tongass and a proposal to drill for oil in the
Arctic National Wildlife Refuge their major Capitol Hill
battlegrounds in 1988.
   Young called the environmental groups ``special interests'' and
said, ``The national environmental community is jerking our
string.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880324-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0236EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Koop-Aging     03-24 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koop-Aging,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Surgeon General Says Old Age Should No Longer Mean Poor Health</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Surgeon General C. Everett Koop says old
people don't have to suffer poor health just because they're old.
   ``The whole theme of this meeting is it's never too late to
start prevention,'' Koop said Wednesday at the close of a three-day
workshop on health promotion and aging.
   How do older people maximize their health? The same way younger
people do, said Koop: don't smoke, don't drink too much, rest, eat
right and exercise.
   ``Old age is not a disease and there are many oldsters who are
disease free,'' said Koop. ``You don't necessarily have to have
your kidneys fail, you don't necessarily have to have dementia. ...
My plea would be to separate old age and disease. They don't
necessarily go together.''
   Smoking is a prime example of the never-too-late approach, said
Koop.
   ``There is a tremendous tendency on the part of physicians to
say, `Well he's over 65, he hasn't got many vices, hasn't got many
years left, why bother the poor old fellow?''' he said.
   ``But if they would just look him straight in the eye and say,
`You're not going to live as long or have as good a quality of life
as if you stop smoking,' if he stops he will note an immediate
benefit.''
   Koop, 71, said he is convinced older people will shift to
healthier diets and exercise more if properly counseled by their
doctors.
   ``I do think you can change a person's behavior,'' he said. ``If
somebody is willing to look at him from a bird's-eye view and try
to rearrange his life and point out how he could do these things
and what the benefits would be, people listen and they benefit.''
   Even though the U.S. population is aging, he said, it is not
becoming less healthy.
   ``As we see people who are now in middle-age come along into the
graying years they are going to be far healthier than this
generation was when it entered the 65-and-older group,'' he said.
   ``These are the people who are jogging and swimming and hiking.
These are the people who are snacking on salad and yogurt. These
are the people who are wearing sensible shoes. They have stopped
smoking. They have given up hard liquor. They wear seat belts. They
understand the things they can do to preserve the quality of life
and the function they already have.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
