<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Orchestra-Baseball     03-24 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Orchestra-Baseball,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>European Symphony to Play at Baseball Game</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brahms and Berlioz will be featured in the
concert halls, but the European Community Youth Orchestra has also
been asked to belt out the U.S. and Canadian anthems at a baseball
game between the Atlanta Braves and the Montreal Expos.
   The orchestra's brass ensemble is scheduled to play at an
exhibition game March 31 at Municipal Stadium in Palm Beach, Fla.
   The orchestra's 140 musicians, aged 14 to 23, come from all 12
countries of the European Community: Britain, France, West Germany,
Italy, Ireland, Denmark, Belgium, Holland, Luxembourg, Spain,
Portugal and Greece.
   For the orchestra's 10th anniversary, it is making its first
tour of the United States, arriving from London in Palm Beach on
Monday.
   ``They've asked us to send the brass ensemble for the game,''
explained Boston-born Joy Bryer, the orchestra's secretary general.
She has lived in Britain for 31 years.
   ``We've mailed the scores to them all around Europe. They don't
know anything about America but what they see on television. Now
they'll be finding out more for themselves.''
   The brass section consists of 20 instruments _ trumpets, French
horns and others that furnish a maximum of volume.
   Mrs. Bryer gave reporters details about the trip on Wednesday in
Washington.
   During its stay in Florida, the orchestra will also send groups
to schools, hospitals and a community center at Belle Glade on Lake
Okeechobee, where the audience will be mostly migrant farm workers.
   Its first formal concert will be on April 10 in the West Palm
Beach Auditorium. Later concerts will be at Clearwater, Fla., April
11; New York's Avery Fisher Hall on April 13; Boston's Symphony
Hall on April 15; and a final performance at the Kennedy Center
Concert Hall in Washington on April 17. The conductor will be Erich
Leinsdorf.
   Part of the proceeds will go to anti-drug efforts and to Very
Special Arts, the fund set up by violinist Itzhak Perlman to help
handicapped musical students.
</TEXT>
