<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Workers     03-24 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Workers,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Reviews Federal-State Roles in Protecting Fired Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress never intended to outlaw state rules
against retaliatory firings when it gave the federal government the
authority to protect union workers, the lawyer for a Southern
Illinois woman says.
   Paul Alan Levy told the Supreme Court that lower courts erred in
ruling that Illinois could not penalize a company for firing a
union employee who filed a workers' compensation claim.
   He asked the court to overturn the decision and rule in favor of
Jonna Lingle, a Machinists union member dismissed from her job at
the Norge Division of Magic Chef Inc. in Herrin, Ill.
   ``The right of (state) action is available to both union and
non-union employees alike,'' Levy told the court in oral arguments
Wednesday. ``That right is independent of the rights enjoyed under
a collective bargaining agreement.''
   Illinois is one of 21 states with laws against retaliatory
firings.
   But a lawyer for Norge said the federal Labor-Management
Relations Act makes enforcement of union contracts _ through the
decisions of an arbitrator _ the province of the federal government.
   ``If independent state laws were enacted that flew in the teeth
of a labor contract, they were pre-empted,'' attorney Charles C.
Jackson told the court. ``Permitting the Illinois law to stand
would be an incentive to undermine collective bargaining.''
   Jackson conceded that states may act on health and safety
matters but said Mrs. Lingle's firing was a contract issue covered
by federal labor law.
   According to court records, the woman notified the Herrin-based
Norge in late 1984 that she was injured on the job and asked the
company to pay her medical bills, as provided for by the Illinois
workers' compensation law.
   Norge fired Mrs. Lingle a week later, contending she filed a
false claim.
   However, the Machinists' contract with Norge contained a
provision protecting workers from dismissal without just cause, and
the union filed a grievance the day she was fired.
   An arbitrator later ordered her reinstatement with back pay.
   But in the interim, Mrs. Lingle filed a circuit court lawsuit
contending the dismissal violated Illinois law and seeking
additional compensation.
   The relief available through the Illinois court was greater than
what she could receive through arbitration, which did not include
punitive damages and compensation for lost overtime.
   Norge shifted the case to U.S. District Court, where a judge
threw out Mrs. Lingle's lawsuit, ruling that state law was
pre-empted by the arbitration remedy provided by federal labor law.
   The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Chicago upheld the
dismissal in June 1987.
   The Supreme Court is expected to rule on the appeal in July.
   The State and Local Legal Center in Washington said 21 states
and the District of Columbia have laws protecting workers who file
compensation claims.
   It identified the states as California, Connecticut, Hawaii,
Illinois, Louisiana, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, Missouri,
Montana, New Jersey, New York, North Carolina, Ohio, Oklahoma,
Oregon, South Carolina, Texas, Virginia, Washington and Wisconsin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880324-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0716EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DisabledMotorists     03-24 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Disabled Motorists,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disabled Drivers Claim Out-Of-State Discrimination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disabled motorists suffer from a patchwork of
state regulations that leaves them vulnerable to parking tickets
when they drive to other states, say advocates of a national
parking symbol for the disabled.
   ``It is ludicrous for us to remove one barrier to the
handicapped by offering handicapped parking spots, only to erect
another by refusing an out-of-state resident the right to park
there,'' Rep. Sam Gejdenson, D-Conn., told a House subcommittee
Wednesday.
   ``If a person is disabled in one state, does not logic dictate
that the same person is disabled in another state?'' he asked.
   Gejdenson has drafted legislation that would require states to
use a national handicapped access symbol and have reciprocity with
all other states. States that do not comply would have federal
highway safety funds withheld.
   A measure to withhold 2 percent of a non-complying state's
highway safety funds was approved by the Senate last year. The
House has not acted.
   Gejdenson said he raised the issue after being contacted by Ruby
DeGiovanni of Middletown, Conn., who started a campaign against the
system three years ago after she was ticketed in Lynn, Mass., while
parked in a handicapped zone.
   ``When states are allowed to ticket people for merely exercising
their right to a handicapped parking space, it discourages
handicapped people from going out,'' Mrs. DeGiovanni told the House
Public Works and Transportation subcommittee on surface
transportation. She called the current system ``ridiculous'' and
discriminatory.
   There are 6.5 million disabled Americans who use special parking
permits. Only 15 states honor handicapped parking permits from
every state, according to a Federal Highway Administration study
conducted last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
