<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-Bradley     03-24 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Bradley,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Gets Bradley's Backing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERSEY CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis has
a respected new ally in his presidential campaign: Sen. Bill
Bradley of New Jersey, who hopes his Dukakis endorsement will end
speculation about a last-minute Bradley bid.
   Dukakis picked up fellow Democrat Bradley's endorsement here
Wednesday. The two held a news conference near the Statue of
Liberty staged to highlight the presidential hopeful's immigrant
roots.
   Bradley said he believes the Massachusetts governor is the best
Democrat to beat Republican front-runner George Bush.
   ``I believe Michael Dukakis can win. I believe he will be the
next president of the United States,'' Bradley told a crowd of
reporters and supporters at Liberty State Park.
   The senator promised to campaign for Dukakis both in New Jersey
_ which holds its primary on June 7 _ and around the nation.
   Bradley said Dukakis can defeat the vice president ``because he
is tenacious, innovative, resilient and disciplined.''
   ``This is a very important endorsement because it comes from one
of the most respected and one of the most accomplished public
figures in America today,'' Dukakis said, adding that Bradley would
be ``very, very important to our success.''
   Bradley said he hoped the endorsement would end talk about his
entering the race. The senator, a former Rhodes scholar and New
York Knicks basketball star, has said repeatedly he does not feel
ready for the White House.
   ``The plan I have for 1988 is helping Michael Dukakis,'' Bradley
said.
   He also said he did not expect to be considered as Dukakis'
running mate. Bradley said such a ticket would be too heavily
weighted toward the Northeast.
   ``I think Massachusetts and New Jersey have a lot in common, but
I don't think they go together on a national ticket,'' Bradley said.
   Bradley jokingly pushed aside a common criticism aimed by some
at him and Dukakis: that they are boring.
   ``It has been said of Michael Dukakis that he is dull, a charge
with which I am not unfamiliar,'' said Bradley, known as a somewhat
wooden speaker. ``But governance is not an amusement park.''
   Bradley also praised the other Democrats seeking the nomination,
singling out Jesse Jackson as ``running a campaign that challenges
the best in all of us.''
</TEXT>
