<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FacesDeath     03-24 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Faces Death,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunman Pulls Trigger Twice; Clerk Unhurt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The gunman leveled his pistol at the
convenience store clerk and pulled the trigger, twice. Click,
click. It didn't fire either time.
   ``I think I am pretty lucky to be alive,'' said 64-year-old Nick
Daugherty, who had come to the aid of the manager during a robbery
Tuesday at a Cumberland Farms store.
   Manager Thelma Jones, 50, said the man first pointed his gun at
her, demanding ``all the money.'' She refused and screamed for help
from Daugherty, who was stocking shelves in the back.
   Ms. Jones said the man reached for the cash register but pointed
the gun at Daugherty as he approached to within 5 feet. Ms. Jones
said she heard two clicking sounds from the gun.
   ``I was shaking,'' said Daugherty, adding he yelled for the
gunman to get out of the store. ``He didn't say a word. I think he
was probably as scared as I was.''
   The gunman ran out, virtually into the arms of a police officer
who had spotted him earlier as a possible robbery suspect and
radioed for help. Detective Carl Oestreich ordered the man to drop
his gun, but the suspect continued to run.
   Oestreich ran after him and was soon joined by 15-20 other
officers who ran him down and arrested him. Police said they found
a gun that been dropped during the chase. It was fully loaded.
   ``I bet one guy better count his lucky stars,'' said police
investigator Jeff Gauntlett.
   Phillip Moultrie, 27, was charged with attempted murder and two
counts of armed robbery with a firearm, Gauntlett said.
   He was jailed without bond.
</TEXT>
