<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TridentCut     03-24 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trident Cut,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seapower Panel Deletes Trident Sub In Favor Of Two More Aegis
Destroyers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stage for congressional warfare has been
set by a House subcommittee's vote to kill funding for the Trident
submarine in the 1989 budget and use the $1.4 billion savings to
build two more Aegis destroyers.
   The House Armed Services seapower subcommittee voted in closed
session Tuesday for the funding switch, conceived by the panel's
chairman, Rep. Charles E. Bennett, D-Fla.
   Word of the vote came Wednesday from Rep. Sam Gejdenson,
D-Conn., who vowed to fight it and predicted Trident funding would
be restored. Gejdenson's district includes the Electric Boat
shipyard, the division of General Dynamics Corp. that builds
Tridents.
   Bennett promised to defend the change when the full committee
looks at the fiscal 1989 budget next week.
   The subcommittee vote reflects congressional opposition to an
administration plan to sell two Aegis DDG-51 destroyers to Japan.
Bennett and others fear the United States would lose technological
secrets as a result.
   Under the subcommittee plan, the government would order five
Aegis warships in 1989 instead of the three requested by the
administration. The two extra destroyers would be deployed in Japan
under U.S. control, protecting Japanese security interests while
keeping the Aegis technology under wraps.
   Lt. Cmdr. Chris Baumann, a Pentagon spokesman, said Congress is
``very leery'' about selling the warships to Japan because of
revelations last year that Toshiba Corp. of Japan sold submarine
technology secrets to the Soviets. But Baumann said the Pentagon
has confidence in the Japanese government.
   ``Japan has held many of our secrets, so we don't seem them as a
security risk at all,'' he said. ``Toshiba is a company, not the
government.''
   The request from Japan for two Aegis ships has not been formally
made, but is expected, Baumann said.
   Navy officials had no immediate response to the Bennett plan,
but any suggestion to eliminate a Trident would likely be attacked
by the Pentagon.
   James H. Webb quit as secretary of the Navy last month in part
because Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci refused to allow him to
cut the Trident from the budget.
   Gejdenson, who is not a member of the Armed Services Committee,
noted that the seapower panel deleted funding for the Trident two
years ago, but funding was later restored by Congress.
   ``While I am clearly disappointed by the decision of the
seapower subcommittee, the subcommittee's decision is only the
first step in a lengthy and complex budget process,'' Gejdenson
said.
   But Bennett said in a telephone interview that he would fight to
keep the Trident out and the two extra Aegis ships in. He said the
program, which traditionally calls for one new Trident each year,
would be continued in the 1990 budget.
   Electric Boat is the sole builder of the 18,750-ton submarine,
which is armed with 24 long-range, multiwarhead missiles. The subs
are built at the company's yards in Groton, Conn., and North
Kingstown, R.I.
   The 8,300-ton Aegis destroyer, equipped with 90 missiles, is
being built by Bath Iron Works in Bath, Maine, and the Ingalls
Shipbuilding in Pascagoula, Miss.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
