<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0322EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AnimalFarm Bjt   03-24 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Animal Farm, Bjt,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Psychiatric Hospital In Dispute Over An Animal Farm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sam the dog, Merlin the goat and scores of
rabbits, chickens, finches and mice have been declared fauna non
grata at the state hospital where they have helped soothe and
socialize mental patients.
   Mark Stebbins is the recreational therapist responsible for the
animal farm known since 1970 as the Stress Reduction Learning
Center at the Creedmoor Psychiatric Center. The hospital has
ordered the program to shut down and the animals off the grounds by
Friday.
   ``At this point what I'm doing is putting myself in the position
of willing insubordination,'' said Stebbins, 48.
   He said the hospital administration engaged in ``a sham and a
dupe job'' by investigating his program.
   ``We have many concerns,'' hospital spokeswoman Rita Amatulli
said Wednesday. Chief among them are Stebbins and his unorthodox
approach to protocol in that most bureaucratic of institutions, a
state mental hospital.
   Stebbins says his eight patients _ down from 16 a few months ago
_ feed, groom, exercise and care for about 60 animals.
   ``It opens them up to wonder. ... It makes them come alive,'' he
said of the patients. ``There's an incredible sense of purpose and
achievement because they know that these animals are dependent on
them.''
   ``It's just a really beautiful program,'' said photographer
Grace Harrington, who has been documenting the animal farm on the
Queens hospital grounds for 11 months. ``It's just so beautiful to
see how not only the animals are nurtured, but the patients are
nurtured.''
   Stebbins contends that hospital director Alan Weinstock targeted
the animal program for elimination shortly after he took over at
Creedmore about nine months ago.
   Stebbins said Weinstock asked him for information about the
patients in the program, which he provided, and then asked him for
budgetary and other information.
   Stebbins said he refused to provide the information because by
that time, he was convinced the hospital only wanted to shut down
his program. Among other things, he said, the administration
confiscated the stress center's van, which he said was needed to
transport both animals and patients.
   Recently, he said, he and his patients were ordered reassigned
and he was told to get rid of the animals. He said he reacted
``maybe arrogantly, maybe defiantly,'' and refused.
   Ms. Amatulli denied that the hospital set out to destroy
Stebbins' program. Weinstock merely wanted to evaluate its
effectiveness and costs, she said, and had no choice but to suspend
the program when Stebbins refused to cooperate.
   Stebbins said Creedmoor pays $200 a year for the program, and
that he pays about $2,000 annually out of his own pocket for many
of its costs. Many thousands of dollars worth of goods and services
are donated, he said.
   Stebbins has his supporters outside the hospital who have
rallied around him every time he has run afoul of the hospital
administration.
   State Sen. Frank Padavan, who acknowledges ``pulling Mark's fat
out of the fire for about 10 years,'' said problems with the
program mainly involve Stebbins' refusal to accommodate
bureaucratic procedures, many required by law.
   Padavan said he will meet with Weinstock in about two weeks to
see if he can work out a compromise that will save the program.
   ``The bottom line is that (Stebbins) gets very good results,''
said Padavan. ``Unfortunately, he listens to the beat of a
different drummer.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
