<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0753EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Budget-Highlights     03-24 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget-Highlights,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Budget Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are some highlights of the
fiscal 1989 budget approved Wednesday by the House.
   _TOTAL SPENDING: The budget envisions $1.098 trillion in
government spending in the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1. Total new
budget authority, which would stretch past the end of the fiscal
year, would be $1.232 trillion. The totals are roughly the same as
in President Reagan's proposed budget.
   _REVENUES: The government would collect $964 billion in taxes
and other revenues, based on Reagan administration estimates. That
includes $14 billion in new taxes already enacted into law for next
year, beyond which no new levies are anticipated by Congress this
year.
   _DEFICIT: $134 billion in red ink would be added to the national
debt, under the goal of $136 billion in the Gramm-Rudman
budget-balancing law.
   _PROGRAMS ELIMINATED: None. The president had proposed
abolishing several subsidies, including Amtrak, urban mass transit,
and some urban and rural development programs.
   _DOMESTIC SPENDING INCREASES: Budget increases for AIDS
research, airline safety, education, science and space, anti-drug
programs, and a pot of $100 million for possible boosts in Medicaid
and other entitlement programs.
   _FEDERAL PAY: Federal civilian and military employees would get
a 3 percent pay increase. Reagan had requested 4.3 percent for the
military and 2 percent for the civil service.
   _DEFENSE SPENDING: $294 billion, $8.6 billion over the current
year but short of the amount needed to keep pace with inflation.
   _FOREIGN AID: $16.1 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
