<1ST_LINE>u i AM-NicaraguaTalks 4thLd-Writethru a0449 03-24 0883</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua Talks, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0449,0904</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sandinistas, Contras Sign 60-Day Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with President Ortega comments,
more details of agreement; background. EDITS to TRIM and conform.
No Pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAPOA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leftist Sandinista government and
U.S.-supported Contra rebels signed an agreement Wednesday for a
60-day cease-fire to start April 1, both sides announced in a joint
communique.
   It was the first concrete step toward ending a six-year-old war
that has killed more than 40,000 people. Both sides scheduled a
meeting in Managua, the capital, for April 6 to start negotiations
on a definitive truce.
   ``I think, I hope and I believe that we have made a start, a
firm start to end this war that is killing ... sons of the same
country, sons of the same mothers,'' said Contra leader Adolfo
Calero.
   President Daniel Ortega said he hoped a regional peace plan
signed last August by the presidents of five Central American
nations would ``bury once and for all the military confrontation''
and ``end the hate and strengthen the brotherhood of Nicaraguans.''
   ``As president of Nicaragua, I hope this peace plan becomes a
reality,'' said Ortega, who had arrived unexpectedly for the
announcement.
   Within the first 15 days of the 60-day truce, the rebels agreed
to move into specified zones in Nicaragua. Delegations from both
sides scheduled a meeting in Sapoa on Monday to work out those
zones.
   The issue of the rebels laying down their arms will be discussed
at the April 6 talks.
   The Contras agreed to accept only humanitarian aid from a
neutral organization. That would exclude military aid from the
United States, which has been supporting the Contras since the war
began in 1982.
   In Washington on Wednesday, President Reagan tried to revive his
stalled effort to get Congress to resume aid to the Contras, which
ended Feb. 29.
   Joao Baena Soares, secretary-general of the OAS, announced the
details of the agreement after Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo, the
Roman Catholic archbishop of Managua, offered a brief prayer asking
that Nicaragua be blessed for ``all it has suffered.''
   Both men attended the three days of talks as observers and
signed the agreement as witnesses. Gen. Humberto Ortega, the
defense minister and head of the Sandinista delegation, signed for
the government and Calero signed for the Contras.
   The Sandinistas agreed to release 100 Contra prisoners on Sunday
and said the rest of the 1,500 jailed rebels would be released at a
date to be worked out at the April 6 meeting.
   The 1,800 former National Guardsmen in prison will be released
after a final truce agreement is reached. The army was called the
National Guard under the late President Anastasio Somoza, who was
overthrown by the Sandinistas in July 1979.
   The government also said it would guarantee freedom of
expression without restrictions, in accordance with the regional
peace plan. Many press liberties were barred for almost six years
under a state-of-emergency decree.
   The Nicaraguan government said it would grant gradual amnesty
and allow all political exiles to return to the country without
fear of persecution. It agreed to discuss the issue of military
service in a national dialogue with the internal opposition.
   The meeting at Sapoa, a town on the Costa Rican border, was the
first time the two sides met on Nicaraguan soil.
   Both Contras and Sandinistas earlier had agreed to a battlefield
truce while the negotiations, which began Monday, took place. A
reported Contra breach apparently did not affect the talks.
   The Voice of Nicaragua radio said earlier that Contras ambushed
an army truck at 2 p.m. Tuesday near Mulukuku, in the northern
province of Matagalpa, killing two soldiers. It did not appear
affect the negotiations.
   Contra spokesman Bosco Matamoros told reporters earlier that
``there could be isolated'' truce violations, ``but there is a
clear will from both sides to respect that decision.''
   U.S. troops in Honduras again held military exercises staged as
what officials called a show of force against Nicaraguan
aggression. White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the
withdrawal would be ``gradual.'' Pentagon officials said they
expected it to come next week.
   The U.S. troops were sent to Honduras as the request of the
Honduran president, who charged that Sandinista soldiers had
penetrated Honduran territory chasing Contra rebels as part of a
major military offensive. The Contras maintain base camps in
Honduran territory.
   At the time, Nicaragua said it had forced 2,000 Contras out of
its territory. Contra forces number an estimated 10,000 troops.
   At the start of the talks, the Sandinistas had said they would
only discuss a cease-fire. Two previous rounds of talks ended in
stalemate when the government maintained that position while the
Contras insisted on broadening discussions to include political
reform within Nicaragua.
   But they agreed to discuss political issues with the rebels on
Monday after signing an agreement with eight opposition parties in
Nicaraguan.
   The national dialogue as well as the cease-fire are included in
the regional peace plan signed by the presidents of Nicaragua, El
Salvador, Costa Rica, Guatemala and Honduras.
   The peace plan seeks to end civil wars in Nicaragua, in El
Salvador and Guatemala. It also calls for amnesties, democratic
reforms and an end to logistical and strategic support for
insurgencies.
</TEXT>
