<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Lower In Morning Tokyo Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed lower against the Japanese yen in
Tokyo Thursday, while stock prices also fell moderately.
   After opening at 126.75 yen, the dollar slid further and closed
at 126.30 yen, down 0.85 yen from its close of 127.15 yen on
Wednesday. It ranged between 126.15 and 126.81 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 52.48-point gainer Wednesday, lost 113.95
points, or 0.44 percent, and ended the day at 25,781.28.
   ``Foreign exchange trading was quiet in Tokyo today without any
notable movements,'' said an official of a major commercial bank,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The dollar's marginal decline in Tokyo followed a lower closing
in New York. Analysts attributed the shift to a remark Wednesday by
Martin Feldstein, former economic adviser to President Reagan,
predicting the dollar could fall to a level of 120 yen or lower
over the next six months.
   Stock investors appeared to be staying on the sidelines to wait
out the results of the current fiscal year, which ends March 31,
said Hiromi Yoneyama of Wako Securities.
   But Yoneyama said many market participants remained optimistic
about market conditions after April.
   Share prices on the first section were mixed in lackluster
trading of about 500 million shares in the morning session.
</TEXT>
