<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PrisonAIDS     03-24 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison AIDS,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AIDS Study Finds 15 Percent Of Incoming Inmates Test Positive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 15 percent of inmates entering
state prison from New York City have tested positive for the AIDS
virus, officials say.
   The finding, from anonymous blood tests of 500 inmates over two
weeks early this year or late last year, will prompt further
anonymous tests, said Peter Slocum, a spokesman for state Health
Commissioner Dr. David Axelrod.
   The blood tests were part of a state program to check more than
100,000 blood samples statewide in an attempt to determine how far
acquired immune deficiency syndrome has spread, Slocum said
Wednesday.
   The blood samples are being collected at prisons, where all
entering inmates are tested, as well as at family planning clinics,
tuberculosis clinics and other health centers, he said.
   About 70 percent of the prison system's 41,559 inmates come from
New York City, which has the nation's highest concentration of AIDS
victims.
   The inmate test results were disclosed after state Sen. Israel
Ruiz met with Axelrod and Corrections Commissioner Thomas Coughlin,
and called for the prison system to offer AIDS tests to inmates
about to be released.
   Ruiz said Axelrod told him that tests had indicated between 15
percent and 20 percent of the inmates might be carrying the AIDS
virus.
   The senator said that with about 16,000 inmates being released
annually, there could be 2,400 or more who are infected and don't
know it.
   Slocum said Ruiz was making ``a crude extrapolation based on
very limited data'' that might not give a clear picture of the
prison system as a whole.
   Slocum said Ruiz must have been basing his projections on what
Axelrod had told him about blood tests from inmates entering the
system at Downstate state prison in Dutchess County, about 50 miles
north of New York City.
   Corrections spokesman James Flateau said inmates are now tested
for the virus only on a doctor's orders for diagnostic purposes.
   Flateau said that as of the end of last year there had been 597
confirmed cases of AIDS among inmates. Of those, 346 died in
prison, 152 had been released and 99 remained in custody.
   Coughlin, Axelrod and Gov. Mario Cuomo have resisted calls for
mandatory AIDS testing of inmates and have thus far refused to
permit voluntary testing in prisons. Ruiz said he would propose
legislation to require it.
   Slocum said inmates about to be released are given counseling
about AIDS.
   Some researchers have estimated that up to 50 percent of those
testing positive for the virus will develop the deadly disease,
which cripples the body's immune system and leaves victims
susceptible to infections and cancer.
   Most cases of AIDS have appeared in homosexual men and
intravenous drug abusers. By March 21, 57,024 AIDS cases were
reported in the United States, and 31,836 victims have died.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
