<HEAD>Courant Poll Shows Bush And Dukakis Favored</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Connecticut voters overwhelmingly favor
Vice President George Bush in the Republican presidential race and
strongly support Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis in the
Democratic contest, according to a Hartford Courant-Connecticut
Poll.
   The survey showed that Bush is favored by 64 percent of likely
GOP voters polled, while his nearest opponent, Sen. Robert J. Dole
of Kansas, is the choice of 20 percent. Fourteen percent of those
polled were undecided and 2 percent selected former television
evangelist Pat Robertson.
   Among likely Democratic voters, Dukakis leads Jesse Jackson, 50
percent to 16 percent of likely voters, with 27 percent undecided,
the poll showed.
   Trailing far behind were Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee with
3 percent, Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois with 3 percent, and Rep.
Richard A. Gephardt of Missouri with 1 percent.
   The Institute for Social Inquiry at the University of
Connecticut conducted the random telephone poll between March 9 and
Sunday. The final sample consisted of 990 people statewide who said
they were likely to vote in Tuesday's primary. At stake in the
primary are 52 Democratic delegates and 35 Republican delegates.
