<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Bush Lead Their Parties, Poll Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis has a comfortable lead among
Pennsylvania Democrats, while Republican George Bush leads his
closest rival by a 3-1 margin, according to results of The
Pennsylvania Poll.
   With more than a month to go before the April 26 state primary,
the Massachusetts governor took a 2-1 lead over Jesse Jackson, his
closest competitor, among all Democratic respondents, The
Pittsburgh Post-Gazette reported in today's editions.
   On the Republican ballot, the vice president led Sen. Bob Dole
of Kansas by more than 3-1, the newspaper said. Dole followed Bush
with 18 percent and former television evangelist Pat Robertson had
5 percent, while 11 percent said they were undecided.
   Among all Democrats, Dukakis led with 37 percent, followed by
Jackson with 18; Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri with 8; Sen.
Albert Gore of Tennessee with 7; and Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois
with 6. About 24 percent said they were undecided.
   The Pennsylvania Poll is sponsored by the Post-Gazette and the
Philadelphia Daily News. The telephone survey of 1,094 randomly
selected registered voters from across the state, 563 Democrats and
531 Republicans, was conducted March 16 to March 20.
   The margin of error is plus or minus 4 percentage points on
figures from all respondents, and plus or minus 6 points for the
293 Democrats and 293 Republicans identified as those most likely
to vote in the primary.
