<1ST_LINE>r i PM-US-PLO     03-24 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-PLO,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. General Assembly Slaps United States For PLO Eviction Attempt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only General Assembly members to vote
against a resolution condemning a U.S. attempt to close the PLO's
United Nations observer mission were Israel and the United States.
   The non-binding resolution was approved 148-2 on Wednesday, a
day after the Justice Department filed suit in federal court
seeking to close the New York City townhouse where the PLO has its
offices.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization vowed to fight the
attempted closure, mandated by an anti-terrorism law passed by
Congress last year.
   The U.N. resolution calls on the United States to obey the
international U.N. headquarters treaty, which permits foreign
missions to operate and calls for arbitration of any dispute with
the host country.
   ``What pride do you have in throwing your guests out?'' shouted
PLO envoy Zehdi Labib Terzi after the vote.
   ``Is this the message the U.S. delegation wants to bring to the
world? That guests have no respect, the United Nations has no
respect, international law has no respect?'' he asked.
   The U.S. government said it will not take any physical steps
against the PLO until the issue has been settled in court.
   ``Let me assure you, we will not disregard the summons by the
U.S. District Court,'' said Terzi. ``But we will tell the court
this is a dispute between the United Nations and the United States,
and that the only forum where such a dispute can be settled is
found in section 21 of the Headquarters agreement.''
   Israeli Ambassador Johanan Bein rose to denounce the PLO for, as
he put it, seeking the protection of the U.N. charter as it pursues
a goal contrary to that charter: the destruction of Israel.
   ``The PLO, since its inception, has been the principal terrorist
organization of our time. It has systematically targeted and
murdered innocent civilians,'' said Bein.
   The PLO, which has retained former U.S. Attorney General Ramsay
Clark as its counsel, has 20 days from the filing of the lawsuit on
Tuesday to respond.
   The United Nations announced it will file a brief in support of
the PLO's defense motion. It retained attorney Keith Highet, who is
also president of the American Society of International Law.
   Sixty-five American organizations and citizens filed suit on
Wednesday in federal court in Manhattan challenging the
Anti-Terrorism Act.
   They included former Beirut hostage Rev. Benjamin Weir, author
Studs Terkel and actor Ed Asner, and the American Friends Service
Committee, the Arab-American Institute and the International Jewish
Peace Union.
   The lawsuit argues that the law infringes on the constitutional
right of Americans to hear all sides of the Middle East controversy
by barring the PLO from public debate.
   A March 29 hearing date was set in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan.
   Wednesday's vote was the third time the General Assembly
condemned U.S. legal attempts to close the PLO mission. The world
body also condemned the Anti-Terrorism Law last December after it
was passed by Congress, and rebuked the United States on March 2
after the United States announced that it would seek to close the
PLO mission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
