<1ST_LINE>d a PM-In-VitroBirths     03-24 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-In-Vitro Births,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In-Vitro Babies Gather for Birthday Party</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY24 of March 23</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Australian company that developed an in-vitro
fertilization technique celebrated its second anniversary with a
party attended by some of its success stories.
   Fifty-four babies and toddlers, all from the New York area,
gathered with their families at a Manhattan party Wednesday. All
were conceived through the programs of the IVF Australia company,
which has fertility clinics at United Hospital in Chester and
another in Alabama.
   ``All we see are positive pregnancy tests in ultrasound scans,''
said Dr. John J. Stangel, the program's medical director. ``We
never get to see the babies.''
   Nurses, doctors and other members of the medical team handed out
stuffed koala bears to the children, and a birthday cake was rolled
out with 168 blazing candles to represent the number of babies born
using the IVF Australia technique.
   The oldest on hand Wednesday was 16-month-old Matthew Martinez.
The youngest was 5-week-old Michael Kiddo, who slept through the
party.
   The IVF technique involves removing mature eggs from a woman's
ovary, fertilizing them with sperm in a petri dish and implanting
them in the woman's uterus.
   Multiple births are more common in such pregnancies, with
between 15 and 20 percent of IVF Australia births being twins. The
procedure costs $5,000, usually covered by medical insurance.
</TEXT>
