<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Armenia     03-24 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Armenia,0720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Helicopters Patrolling Yerevan to Ensure Order; Calm Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Witnesses in the Armenian capital of Yerevan today
said Red Army helicopters circled the skies to guard against unrest
after the government described Armenian claims to an area in
neighboring Azerbaijan as intolerable.
   Moscow dissident Valery Senderov said a correspondent for an
unofficial human rights journal had called from Yerevan to say that
helicopters were patrolling the city, but that there was no
widespread disorder reported.
   Regyen Sarkisyan, a senior editor of the Communist Party
newspaper Kommunist in Yerevan, confirmed in a telephone interview
with The Associated Press that there were helicopters overhead, but
described the city as calm.
   He said most Armenians were showing patience in awaiting
resolution of the contentious national issue.
   Armenians want the Nagorno-Karabakh region of Azerbaijan annexed
to Armenia because more than three-quarters of the population in
the region is Armenian.
   The annexation appeal was rejected by the party Central
Committee in early February, which triggered massive demonstrations
in the region that is smaller than the state of Delaware.
   The unrest spread to Yerevan in late February, when hundreds of
thousands of Armenians marched through the streets bearing banners
linking the Nagorno-Karabakh issue with Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's social reforms.
   The Yerevan demonstrations subsided after Gorbachev appealed for
calm and promised a party review of the annexation question. But
the issue touched off rioting in the Azerbaijani city of Sumgait on
Feb. 28, when at least 32 people were killed in a rampage by ethnic
extremists.
   Soviet officials reported earlier this week that 197 people were
injured in the Sumgait rioting and that more than 400 have been
arrested or charged in murders, rapes, looting and other violent
acts.
   Armenian activists claim the casualties were much higher and
predominently among Armenians at the hands of enraged Azeris, the
dominant population of Azerbaijan.
   Sarkisyan, the newspaper editor, said soldiers were deployed
around Yerevan to ensure order today, but no outbreaks of unrest
had occurred to his knowledge since a government statement on the
issue was made public Wednesday night.
   The demonstrations had subsided until early this week, when
reports in the party daily Pravda said the annexation drive had a
``clear anti-socialist spirit.'' Activists in Yerevan said about
7,000 people protested that report, and one of the journalists
whose name had been attached to it disavowed it.
   As recently as March 17, party officials in Nagorno-Karabakh
appealed for permission to join the Armenian republic.
   Activists in Yerevan had called for another show of support for
the annexation appeal with demonstrations and strikes beginning
Saturday, when a self-appointed committee of activists and
officials plans to meet and discuss a future course of action.
   Sarkisyan, a 32-year-old candidate for membership in the
Communist Party, said he supports the proposal for returning
Nagorno-Karabakh to Armenia, but doesn't expect the matter to be
resolved soon.
   ``I believe that some day it will be united with Armenia, but in
the nearest days I don't expect this to happen. It is a very
complicated issue, and I think most people understand that now,''
he said.
   He said he did not expect a large turnout at the demonstrations
or widespread participation in the strikes called for by activists,
although Moscow-based dissidents say they've been told thousands
plan to show their support for the Nagorno-Karabakh appeal by
taking to the streets.
   The Soviet government on Wednesday rejected as ``intolerable''
the Armenian campaign for annexation, indicating it would not bend
to the pressures brought to bear by demonstrations and strikes.
   The meeting, attended by Gorbachev, President Andrei A. Gromyko
and other senior party officials, was held after carefully
orchestrated appeals by subordinate legislative bodies in 13 Soviet
republics _ all but Armenia and Azerbaijan.
   The official Tass news agency said the Presidium of the Supreme
Soviet, the nominal parliament, considered it ``intolerable when it
is attempted to resolve complicated national-territorial issues
through pressure on state authorities, in an atmosphere when
emotions and passions are whipped up.''
   The statement did not categorically deny the appeal, but
declared that such issues would be resolved on the basis of
economic concerns rather than ethnic differences.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
