<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Biaggi-Wedtech     03-24 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Grills Ex-Wedtech Exec</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted former Wedtech Corp. executive, who
has confessed to stealing $1.5 million from the bankrupt defense
contractor, admitted he has not had to give back any of his illegal
earnings.
   Under cross examination by the defense at the racketeering trial
of Rep. Mario Biaggi, D-N.Y., and six others Wednesday, Mario
Moreno was asked about his plea bargain with federal prosecutors.
   Biaggi attorney James LaRossa got Moreno to admit he sought to
avoid a racketeering charge ``which could carry up to 20 years in
prison and forfeiting your assets.''
   ``And you told your lawyer you didn't want that, right?'' asked
LaRossa, ``and that is one of the things they negotiated and got
for you, isn't that right?''
   ``Yes,'' said Moreno, who later admitted his lawyer also got
``one of the most lenient judges'' to take his guilty plea.
   Moreno is among four ex-Wedtech officials who have admitted
bribing public officials and other state and federal crimes in a
plea bargain for leniency. All are cooperating witnesses for the
prosecution. None have yet been sentenced.
   Moreno faces a maximum 15 years in prison after pleading guilty
to federal charges of bribe conspiracy and mail fraud. He also
faces an additional seven years after pleading guilty to state
larceny and bribery charges.
   LaRossa also got Moreno to admit that ``not a penny'' of his
assets have been seized or forfeited despite his numerous guilty
pleas.
   Biaggi, his eldest son, Richard; Wedtech founder John Mariotta
and four others are charged with turning Wedtech, a Bronx defense
contractor, into a vehicle for paying millions of dollars in bribes
to obtain government no-bid contracts.
   Wedtech, currently in bankruptcy proceedings, grew from a small
machine shop into a $100-million-a-year business through a series
of no-bid contracts set aside for companies controlled by minority
group members.
   Earlier, Moreno claimed attorneys at the firm of Squadron,
Ellenoff, Plesent and Lehrer were aware of another Wedtech scheme
to make it appear the company was minority controlled in order to
qualify for no-bid contracts.
   He said the lawyers knew the agreement to sell majority control
of the stock to Mariotta, who is of Hispanic descent, was ``a
sham.''
   ``So they participated in your fraud, is what you are telling
us, right?'' asked LaRossa.
   ``Yes,'' replied Moreno after a short pause.
   Howard Squadron, a partner in the firm, later issued a statement
calling Moreno's testimony ``untrue.''
   ``Neither he nor anybody else from Wedtech advised anybody at
this firm that Mr. Mariotta had agreed not to buy shares of stock
pursuant to the purchase agreement,'' said Squadron, noting that
Moreno previously testified he and other Wedtech officials
concealed other illegal activities from the law firm and ``if there
was such an agreement with Mr. Mariotta, it too was concealed.''
</TEXT>
