<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Storm Brings Snow, High Winds to Rockies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   High winds and snow today buffeted mountain areas of Wyoming and
Colorado, which braced for gusts up to 80 mph and more than a foot
of snow from a fast-moving cold front.
   Strong winds blew through sections of South Dakota, California,
Washington state, the Midwest, and the East Coast. Showers and
thundershowers fell in much of the Midwest.
   A warning for heavy snow was issued for the northern mountains
of Colorado, where 8 to 14 inches was expected. The snow and winds
predicted to hit 80 mph were expected to create blizzard conditions.
   An advisory for snow and blowing snow was posted for the
mountains of southeastern Wyoming, where 4 to 8 inches was expected.
   On Wednesday, the front spawned 80 mph winds in the Northwest,
forcing Army officials to cancel military helicopter flights and
training with anti-tank missiles at the Yakima Firing Center in
central Washington.
   Up to 18 inches of snow fell Wednesday in the Cascade Range, and
a snow advisory remained in effect for the mountains.
   The high winds have been blamed for the death of a 15-year-old
Portland girl, who was struck by falling trees at a state park in
Oregon on Tuesday.
   Showers and thunderstorms extended from northeastern Missouri
and southeastern Iowa across northern Illinois to northern Indiana,
and were scattered over the lower Mississippi Valley. Showers fell
over Minnesota and the lower Great Lakes region.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
in the Mississippi Valley, the eastern Plains, Alabama, the lower
Great Lakes and the northern Ohio Valley; severe thunderstorms with
tornadoes possible from Arkansas and eastern Oklahoma northeastward
to the middle Mississippi Valley; rain from the northern Pacific
Coast to northwest Montana, with snow in some higher elevations;
scattered rain and snow showers in the northern and central High
Plains and strong, gusty winds in the Rockies, the High Plains and
the middle Mississippi Valley.
   Temperatures were expected to reach the 50s, 60s or 70s for most
of the nation; the 40s from the northern and central Rockies across
the northern Plains, from northern Minnesota to the upper Great
Lakes and across sections of northern New England; near 80 degrees
over the central Gulf Coast states, the Florida Peninsula and
southern West Virginia; and the 80s to near 90 degrees over the
desert Southwest and much of Texas.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 17
degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 73 degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 55 partly cloudy; Boston 46 windy; Buffalo 44
cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 55 foggy; Cincinnati 60 partly cloudy;
Cleveland 52 cloudy; Detroit 48 showery; Miami 72 fair; New York 43
partly cloudy; Philadelphia 46 foggy; Pittsburgh 57 fair; Portland,
Maine 37 cloudy; Washington 53 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 37 cloudy; Chicago 47 cloudy; Dallas-Fort
Worth 65 cloudy; Denver 40 cloudy; Des Moines 52 cloudy;
Indianapolis 59 cloudy; Kansas City 61 windy; Minneapolis-St. Paul
38 partly cloudy; Nashville 60 partly cloudy; New Orleans 65
cloudy; St Louis 63 cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 53 fair; Anchorage 22 fair; Las Vegas 70
windy; Los Angeles 57 fair; Phoenix 67 fair; Salt Lake City 37
windy; San Diego 59 fair; San Francisco 51 fair; Seattle 41 windy
   _Canada: Toronto 36 partly cloudy
</TEXT>
