<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0520EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua-Highlights     03-24 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Highlights,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Main Points Of Peace Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Nicaragua Talks, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAPOA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Highlights of the cease-fire agreement
signed Wednesday night by the Sandinista government and Contra
rebels:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _A 60-day cease-fire begins April 1, with a temporary truce that
began Monday remaining in effect until then.
   _Two sides meet in Managua April 6 for talks on a permanent
truce.
   _Rebels move into specified zones in Nicaragua during the first
15 days of April. Zones to be determined through special
commissions at meetings beginning in Sapoa on Monday.
   _Government will grant gradual amnesty and allow all political
exiles to return to the country without fear of persecution. It
will release 100 Contra prisoners on Sunday. Half the remaining
1,400 jailed rebels are to be released when the rebels are in
specified zones, the other half when a permanent truce is in place.
   _1,800 former National Guardsmen in prison since the 1979
Sandinista revolution to be released after a final truce agreement
is signed.
   _Contras will accept only humanitarian aid from a neutral
organization. That excludes military aid from the United States.
   _Government guarantees freedom of expression without
restrictions, in accordance with a regional peace plan signed last
August by President Ortega and the presidents of four other Central
American countries.
   _Contras are guaranteed representation in Sandinista talks with
internal opposition and participation in the electoral process.
   _A verification commission will be formed with the assistance of
Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo, Nicaragua's Roman Catholic leader,
and the secretary general of the Organinization of American States,
Ambassador Joao Baena Soares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
