<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0617EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Summit     03-24 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Summit,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet TV Viewers Learn of Summit Two Hours Into Newscast</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only after Soviet television broadcast a 1{-hour
speech by Mikhail S. Gorbachev on agriculture and news on a
territorial dispute did viewers learn President Reagan will meet
their leader in Moscow in May.
   The brief announcement came about 11 p.m. Wednesday, two hours
into the news program ``Vremya,'' or Time, which has an estimated
audience of 150 million. Tass, the official news agency, announced
the summit in a one-paragraph dispatch issued more than 2{ hours
earlier.
   ``Vremya'' showed videotape of Reagan meeting Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze outside the White House earlier in
the day.
   An announcer said Reagan reported that the superpowers settled
on the dates of May 29 through June 2 for the meeting, his fourth
summit with Gorbachev and first trip to the Soviet Union.
   The five-day visit will mark the first trip to the Soviet Union
by an U.S. president since Richard Nixon's 1974 summer meeting with
Leonid I. Brezhnev.
   ``Vremya'' customarily lasts an hour or less, but its lead item
Wednesday was a long speech by Gorbachev, the Communist Party
chief, at the opening of a collective farmers congress. His
remarks, which lasted 1 hour and 40 minutes, apparently were
broadcast in their entirety.
   The evening newscast also reported that the Soviet government
rejected as ``intolerable'' a campaign by Armenian activists to
annex Nagorno-Karabakh, a predominantly Armenian area of
neighboring Azerbaijan.
   That campaign fueled ethnic strife that led to rioting in the
Azerbaijani city of Sumgait on Feb. 28. Officials say 32 people
died.
   State-run media had no initial comment about the summit, whose
projected centerpiece is the signing of a treaty now being
negotiated that would reduce long-range nuclear weapons on both
sides by 30 percent to 50 percent.
   Tass gave no details in its dispatch beyond the time and place
fixed for the meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
