<DOCNO> AP880324-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0633EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WaterEmergency     03-24 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Water Emergency,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Possible Water Shortage Already Causing Battles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY McGRATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A critical water shortage east of San
Francisco threatens to pit suburban homeowners against city
dwellers as officials consider the most severe water conservation
measures since a 1977 drought.
   State Water Resources Department engineers said Wednesday that
low precipitation since October means river runoffs from snow melt
will be 40 percent below normal statewide between April and July _
and even lower if spring rainfall is below average.
   East Bay Municipal Utility District reservoirs that are
half-full now could be one-quarter full by September unless there
are major storms during the next two months, officials said.
   The district board declared a ``water shortage emergency''
Tuesday and warned that as of June 1, they may ration water to
their 1.1 million customers for the first time in a decade.
   The district, however, already is divided over whether to allow
more water in warmer, drier areas such as the affluent San Ramon
Valley than in the often foggy and rainy inner-cities should
rationing becomes necessary.
   ``We are the hot weather part of the district. Our needs are
different than the cooler parts of the district,'' said Mayor
Beverly Lane of Danville, a middle-class community about 10 miles
east of Oakland.
   Utility board directors from urban Berkeley and Richmond argued
it would be unfair for the suburbs, with their sprawling lawns and
gardens, to receive an extra share.
   If a voluntary conservation plan approved by the district fails,
the agency may impose water restrictions of up to 25 percent for
homes and businesses in inland counties like Alameda and Contra
Costa from May through September.
   During the drought 11 years ago, water customers were charged up
to ten times the normal rate for excessive water use.
   San Francisco and coastal counties face possible water shortages
next year, but are in better shape than the inland counties because
they have more water sources and have received more storms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
