<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0649EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador-Elections     03-24 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador-Elections,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rightists Charge Fraud Attempt in Recent Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angry rightist leaders accused
the governing Christian Democrats of trying to steal this week's
legislative and municipal elections by manipulating returns.
   The charge of attempted fraud was made Wednesday by leaders of
the Republican Nationalist Alliance, or Arena. They warned that
violence could occur if the incumbents continued the alleged
attempt to rig results.
   Hours after polls closed, leaders of all the parties recognized
Arena as the big winner in Sunday's vote.
   Comments Monday by Mario Samayoa, president of the Central
Elections Council, implied Arena would have at least 30 seats in
the new 60-seat National Assembly, the unicameral legislature.
Arena had said Tuesday its projections gave it 35 seats, but the
party said Wednesday it had 31 seats guaranteed.
   The election panel, an independent body including
representatives of the three major parties, has repeatedly
postponed announcement of official nationwide results.
   Samayoa said on Wednesday the commission has received several
challenges to preliminary official results reported from various
provinces, and that final official results would be withheld until
those challenges were resolved.
   Arena founder Roberto d'Aubuisson, an ex-army major and alleged
leader of early 1980s death squads, said at the news conference,
``If they continue with this fraud that they're trying to pull off,
who knows what could happen here.''
   Leaders of the National Association of Private Enterprise, or
ANEP, called a news conference to back Arena's claim and warn
against attempts to manipulate results. They held out the
possibility of a business strike if the gathering of official
results is flawed.
   ``If there is an attempt at fraud, there could be a violent
public reaction that would endanger the institutional existence of
the country,'' said ANEP leader Miguel Angel Salaverria.
   D'Aubuisson called on the armed forces' high command to ensure
the honesty of the vote count.
   ``If they do not, the accusing finger will point to them too,''
he said.
   Guillermo Guevara Lacayo, the Christian Democratic president of
the outgoing National Assembly, denied the fraud allegations.
   ``The leaders of Arena, being the experts in psychological
warfare that they are, raised expectations with inflated early
returns,'' he told reporters.
   He said his party's figures gave Arena 27 to 28 deputies, with
25 to 26 for the Christian Democrats. Such a final tally could
leave the balance of legislative power with smaller parties.
</TEXT>
