<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Swaggart     03-24 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Swaggart,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Swaggart Says He Expects to Preach Again Within Three Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jimmy Swaggart said he's going
out of his mind not preaching, but he expects to be back within
three months and urged his followers to ignore ``innuendos that are
flying like confetti.''
   ``This ministry is not going down, it's not ever faltering,''
Swaggart told a congregation at the Family Worship Center at the
Jimmy Swaggart Ministries here Wednesday night.
   On Monday, the 250-member General Presbytery of the Assemblies
of God church plans to decide the fate of Swaggart, who tearfully
confessed on the pulpit Feb. 21 that he had sinned. He has been
following a three-month suspension recommended by state church
leaders.
   The Executive Presbytery of the church met soon afterward in
Springfield, Mo., and sent a harsher recommendation back to the
state council, calling for a year's suspension from the pulpit.
   But after meeting again, the state council voted to return its
original recommendation to the executive council of the church, the
nation's largest Pentecostal denomination. A final decision will be
made by the General Presbytery.
   Swaggart, who occasionally addresses his old congregation at
services conducted by his assistant pastor, the Rev. Jim Rentz,
indicated on Wednesday that he expects the presbyters to approve
the three-month suspension.
   He told about 400 congregants that he was going out of his mind
away from his pulpit, but ``when I'm back in the pulpit on May 22,
I'll be back in my mind.''
   Swaggart urged the congregation ignore ``innuendos that are
flying like confetti'' and said he believes that God is going to
help his ministry ``touch the world like it's never been touched
before.''
   The Jimmy Swaggart Ministries, whose television broadcasts reach
several countries, took in an estimated $150 million in 1986.
   Church officials have confirmed that Swaggart, one of the
nation's most popular television evangelists, was photographed with
a known prostitute outside a New Orleans area motel last October. A
woman who claimed she was that prostitute said Swaggart paid her to
perform pornographic acts.
   Also Wednesday, a state district court jury in Texas held that a
radio station owned by the Swaggart organization owes $28,000 in
real estate taxes, instead of the $64,043 claimed by the city of
Shenandoah.
   The jury voted 10-2 Wednesday that the ministries should pay the
smaller amount because only half of the building was a church and
the other real estate and leased property. The ministry had claimed
the radio station qualifies as a place of worship, and therefore
was tax exempt.
</TEXT>
