<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0726EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica     03-24 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Journalists, Activists Protest Closure Of Newspaper</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Journalists and white civil
rights activists held demonstrations in downtown Johannesburg today
to protest the government's closure of an anti-apartheid newspaper.
   The latest edition of the New Nation, a black-oriented weekly
published by the Roman Catholic Church, was to have gone on sale
today.
   But on Tuesday, Home Affairs Minister Stoffel Botha ordered the
paper shut down for 12 weeks, saying it had published ``subversive
propaganda'' in violation of state-of-emergency censorship
regulations.
   More than 30 journalists from the New Nation, the liberal Weekly
Mail, and The Star, the country's largest-selling daily, held up
placards at busy downtown intersections during the morning rush
hour.
   ``Hands off the press,'' read one placard. Another asked,
``Who's next?'' on one side, and answered, ``You're next.'' on the
other.
   White women from the Black Sash civil rights group held a
similar demonstration outside the Johannesburg Stock Exchange.
Their placards read: ``Press in chains'' and ``Free New Nation.''
   The Weekly Mail is among six other anti-apartheid publications
notified by Botha that they face possible closure or appointment of
an in-house censor if they continue carrying material that
dissatisfies the minister.
   Under apartheid, South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote
in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
   In other developments:
   _Administrators at the University of the North, a college for
blacks in Transvaal province, today announced that student
dormitories have been closed indefinitely because of disruptions
and vandalism on campus. The university's rector, P.C. Mokgokong,
said the trouble began after politically oriented boycotts of
classes Friday and Monday.
   When classes resumed Tuesday, the rector said, there was an
upsurge of ``anti-social and criminal conduct'' he blamed on
militant students.
   _Police said a 23-year-old female constable was shot and killed
Wednesday night while sitting in a car with her boyfriend near the
port city of Durban. Police said the constable, of Indian descent,
was shot by a black assailant after another had smashed the car
window with a brick.
</TEXT>
