<DOCNO> AP880324-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0731EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ConfiscatedCaviar     03-24 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Confiscated Caviar,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Customs: Fish Eggs Were Ill-Gotten By Caviar Expert, Dealer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A renowned caviar expert and a Miami roe dealer are
accused of importing $1 million worth of Iranian caviar in
violation of a presidential trade embargo with that Middle Eastern
nation.
   George Stein, 49, a wholesaler and author of ``Caviar! Caviar!
Caviar!'' and Patrick Bachelier, 32, a caviar dealer, are charged
with violating the Oct. 29, 1987, ban on Iranian imports, said U.S.
Customs spokesman Michael Sheehan.
   ``I'm innocent,'' Bachelier told The Associated Press Wednesday.
``It's a mistake.'' Telephone calls to Stein's wholesale company
went unanswered.
   If convicted as charged, the two could face up to 16 years in
prison and $150,000 in fines, Sheehan said when the agency
announced its case Wednesday.
   The fish-egg probe began last December when customs officials
received a tip about illegal Iranian caviar, Sheehan said. Customs
agents believe that Bachelier sent Iranian caviar to Europe, where
the shipments were disguised as Soviet caviar and then flown to
Miami.
   ``The caviar was in fact falsely labeled in Western Europe in
order to circumvent the embargo,'' Sheehan said.
   ``After the cavier was released by customs, Bachelier would
transfer the caviar into Iranian tins, which he had imported
separately,'' said Sheehan.
   Customs agents followed a one-ton shipment from Miami to New
York before search warrants were served March 15, Sheehan said.
   The search netted 1,400 pounds of caviar worth $400,000 at
Caspian Caviar Co., 1,000 pounds of caviar worth $400,000 at
Stein's firm, Iron Gate Caviar Co., and 1,000 pounds of caviar
worth $200,000 at Epicurean International Inc., a Rockville, Md.,
company, Sheehan said.
   Stein is scheduled for an appearance at federal court in Miami
April 5 and Bachelier was arraigned March 16. The seized caviar is
on ice as evidence.
   Bachelier said he imported some Iranian caviar under a permit
issued to a person he declined to identify. The rest of the caviar
was genuine Russian caviar, he said.
   ``I feel like I'm being treated unfairly,'' he said. ``I'm
innocent. I have nothing to fear.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880324-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0948EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--AutoRecall     03-24 0146</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Auto Recall,0148</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Recalls Corvettes, Vans For Safety-Related Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. is recalling about 4,900
1988 Chevrolet Corvettes to fix defective wheel welds that could
cause the wheel center to separate from the rim during braking or
cornering.
   The automaker said Wednesday it is also recalling about 460 1987
GMC and Chevrolet full-size vans to correct fuel tank filler pipes
that could cause fuel to leak during refueling or turning.
   No accidents or injuries have been linked to either problem, GM
said. Vehicle owners are being notified of the recall by dealers,
who will correct the problems at no charge, the company said.
   The Corvettes, all equipped with 17-inch wheels, may be missing
a weld on some wheels, GM said. The condition could result in
partial loss of steering control and a sudden changed in vehicle
direction, the automaker said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880324-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0807EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico-Politics     03-24 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Politics,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexico's Next Likely President Promises Fraud-Free Voting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER PICHARDINI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHIHUAHUA, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carlos Salinas de Gortari, almost
certain to become Mexico's next president, is promising a
fraud-free election in the state that allegedly was a hotbed of
bogus balloting two years ago.
   ``I come with the firm decision to respect the will of the
people of Chihuahua,'' he said at the outset of his five-day
campaign swing through the northern border state of Chihuahua, the
largest of Mexico's 31 states.
   The trip that concludes Friday is being watched closely
throughout Mexico.
   ``The Chihuahua Case'' has become shorthand for alleged fraud
that took place during state and local elections in 1986. At that
time, Salinas de Gortari's Institutional Revolutionary Party dealt
a major setback to its rival National Action Party, which had won
an unprecedented victory in Chihuahua three years earlier.
   The governing party never has lost a presidential election or a
gubernatorial race since its inception in 1929.
   As the party's candidate, Salinas de Gortari is virtually
certain to win a six-year term on Dec. 1 and succeed President
Miguel de la Madrid.
   ``I come here with you to outline the strong commitment to
govern with absolute respect for democracy,'' Salinas de Gortari
said during his Chihuahua campaign. ``Of course we are going to
war; that's why we come to Chihuahua _ to win.''
   On Tuesday, Salinas de Gortari stopped in the southern towns of
Parral, Camargo and Delicias before returning to the state capital,
the city of Chihuahua. All were won by National Action in 1983 and
regained by the Institutional Revolutionary Party party in 1986.
   A campaign official, who asked not to be named, said crowds of
more than 5,000 people in those towns were considered a major
achievement.
   The conservative National Action Party won seven mayoralties in
1983, including the state capital and Ciudad Juarez on the border
with El Paso, Texas. It predicted an even greater victory three
years later, but Salinas de Gortari's party won 65 of 67
mayoralties, the governorship and all 14 state legislative posts at
stake.
   It insisted throughout that the vote was fair.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
