<HEAD>Government Shells Rebel Positions In Southern Sudan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government shelled positions held by
guerrillas in southern Sudan, killing 295 rebels and regaining
control of a town, an army statement said.
   Government troops moving toward rebel-held Nasir town in the
southern upper Nile region found the bodies of 250 rebels killed
from shelling, according to the Wednesday statement.
   It said that at the outskirts of Nasir, the soldiers killed 45
other rebels. Two government troops were killed and eight wounded
before the army took over full control of the area, it said.
   It did not say when the operation took place.
   In other clashes, the statement said soldiers killed 19 rebels
in an army attack Saturday on the rebels' Bekwy camp, near Mundari
town in the Equatoria region.
   In another operation near the border with Zaire, government and
rebel troops fought Saturday and a number of rebels were killed and
wounded. The statement had no casualty numbers.
   The rebels began their insurrection in 1983 and are demanding
more autonomy and administrative and economic reforms.
