<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FBI-Harassment     03-24 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FBI-Harassment,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Orders Meese ``Hands Off'' in FBI Harassment Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge says Attorney General Edwin Meese
and the head of the Justice Department's civil rights division
cannot take part in the department's criminal investigation of
alleged harassment of a black FBI agent.
   Meese and Assistant Attorney General William Bradford Reynolds
are parties to a civil lawsuit in Washington, D.C., alleging racial
harrassment by white FBI agents against agent Donald Rochon.
   U.S. District Judge John F. Grady said Wednesday he wants a
``Chinese wall'' between the Justice Department attorneys handling
the criminal investigation and Meese and Reynolds.
   Grady suspended a grand jury investigation in Chicago until
government lawyers file a statement agreeing to abide by the order
barring Meese and Reynolds from having access to the criminal file.
   ``The grand jury, the court and the public have a right to know
that the grand jury proceedings are in the hands of persons who
have no apparent interest other than to ascertain the truth,''
Grady said in response to a request by Rochon's attorney.
   Justice Department spokesman Terry Eastland said late Wednesday
that the department had just become aware of Grady's ruling and it
would have to be reviewed before there was any comment.
   Rochon, 37, now assigned to Philadelphia, filed suit Nov. 5 in
Washington against the FBI and the Justice Department, accusing
white fellow agents in Chicago and Omaha, Neb., of racial
harassment and threats of death and mutilation against him or
sexual assault against his wife, Susan, who is white. They are now
separated.
   The federal Equal Employment Opportunity Commission has upheld
Rochon's racial discrimination allegations in connection with his
stay in Omaha in 1983 and 1984.
   ``Supervisory and high-level officials of the FBI never
confronted, stopped, investigated or even took seriously the
sometimes daily racial degradation and the blatantly discriminatory
employment actions,'' Rochon's lawsuit contended.
   The Justice Department initiated the grand jury investigation
after Rochon's suit was filed.
   The Senate Judiciary Committee also has conducted inquiries into
Rochon's allegations.
   Meanwhile, in Philadelphia, an attorney for Rochon's former
girlfriend, Rosemary Coleman Peszko, said Wednesday the woman was
pressured by FBI agents to make false statements about Rochon.
   Ms. Peszko was interrogated for 20 hours over a three-day period
earlier this month regarding her relationship with Rochon, attorney
Stefan Presser said.
   Ms. Peszko said in an affidavit the FBI took advantage of her
emotional state after a lovers' quarrel and pressured her to make
statements she feared were inaccurate. She said she did not want
those statements used against Rochon.
   ``They wanted me to sign statements they prepared, but I
refused,'' she said. ``I did not and do not intend to hurt Don,
whom I love, and I was misled by the FBI's frequently saying that
all they wanted to do was help Don by my saying what they wanted to
hear.''
   ``I was so tired, hungry and upset, I do not know what I told
them or whether what they wrote down is accurate,'' she said.
``They were often suggesting things and leading me in certain
directions, and much of what is in the statements they have may
well be inaccurate.''
   Two FBI agents from Philadelphia apparently tried to persuade
Ms. Peszko to say that Rochon first hit her during an argument
March 4 at an apartment they shared in Pennsauken, N.J., then broke
his own nose to convince investigators both had been acting
violently, Presser said.
   Rochon and Ms. Peszko filed simple assault charges against each
other in Camden County, N.J., then dropped them.
   The FBI said in a statement that the questioning followed normal
procedures taken any time allegations of impropriety or criminal
wrongdoing are leveled against an FBI employee.
</TEXT>
