<HEAD>Latin American States Call Emergency Meet On Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An organization of 25 Latin American
nations will hold an emergency meeting Monday to discuss the crisis
in Panama, the group said.
   The meeting of the Latin American Economic System was requested
by Panama.
   Panama's ambassador to Venezuela, Marcel Salamin, said Wednesday
that economic sanctions against his country by the United States
constitute an ``economic and financial aggression.''
   Panama is in the throes of a general strike aimed at ousting
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, the chief of the nation's defense
forces and the power behind the government.
   The United States is using economic pressure to help oust
Noriega, withholding payments for use of the Panama Canal and
freezing Panamanian accounts in U.S. banks.
   The Caracas-based Latin American Economic System was founded in
1975 as a forum for the Latin American countries to debate their
economic relations with the U.S. and the industrialized nations.
