<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Satellite,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Launch Satellite Bound for Mir Space Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union today launched a satellite with
supplies for the Mir space station, whose crew is trying to set a
record for time in orbit, Tass reported.
   The official news agency said the Progress-35 cargo satellite
was carrying food and other supplies, but it did not provide
details. Data transmitted from space indicated the satellite was
functioning normally, Tass said.
   It was the second supply mission since cosmonauts Vladimir Titov
and Musa Manarov blasted off Dec. 21 to replace Yuri Romanenko and
Alexander Alexandrov on the Mir spacecraft.
   Romanenko had spent 326 days in space and thus holds the record
for the longest manned space mission. Soviet space officials say
Titov and Manarov will stay aboard the Mir for a year in an effort
to break Romanenko's record.
   The account of the launch did not say when the link between the
Mir and the cargo spacecraft was expected.
</TEXT>
