<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0566,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Warplanes Attack Bases In Lebanon Again; Nine Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with nine people reported
killed; ADDS byline. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `An Israeli ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By AHMED MANTASH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli warplanes divebombed Palestinian
guerrilla bases on the outskirts of this southern port city today
for the second day, killing nine people and wounding five, police
said.
   A police spokesman said six Israeli fighter-bombers hit the
bases six times in 55 minutes with 30 rockets and bombs, starting
at 1 p.m.
   The bases were manned by Abu Nidal's Fatah-Revolutionary Council
and the Moscow-oriented Democratic Front for the Liberation of
Palestine, police said.
   It was the third Israeli strike against Palestinian bases in
Lebanon in a week and the fifth this year. Forty-seven people have
been killed and 6 wounded in Israeli air strikes on guerrilla bases
in Lebanon this year.
   An Israeli army statement identified the targets as buildings
used by the guerrillas to store weapons and equipment. The
statement said Israeli pilots returned safely and reported accurate
hits on the targets.
   Smoke and dust engulfed the villages of Bekasta, Majdelyoun,
Saliyeh and Abra after the raids, and ambulances raced to the
scene. All but Abra had been bombed by Israeli jets Wednesday.
   A police spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity under
standing regulations, said guerrillas sealed off the villages on
the southern and eastern edges of Sidon, 25 miles south of Beirut.
   The villages were once populated by Christians. But they fled in
April 1985 when leftist Moslem militiamen drove right-wing
Christian irregulars, allied with the Israelis, out of the region.
   Police said seven people were killed and 15 wounded when 12
Israeli jet fighters raided six Palestinian guerrilla bases in the
Sidon region in Wednesday's attack.
   Five were manned by Abu Nidal's fighters and one by the
Moscow-oriented Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine.
The front, led by Nayef Hawatmeh, is part of Yasser Arafat's
Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Abu Nidal, whose real name is Sabri al-Banna, broke away from
the PLO in 1974 to found his own group. He tops the list of
terrorists wanted by the United States and Western European
countries.
   Abu Nidal's group, in a statement issued after Wednesday's
raids, threatened to ``severely strike back against the Zionist
enemy's arrogance and barbarism ... at the right time and place.''
</TEXT>
