<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FondaHearing     03-24 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fonda Hearing,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Admirers, Detractors Hold Forth At Jane Fonda Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICOPEE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Jane Fonda was both cheered and
booed for her work against the Vietnam War during a hearing on
whether to snub her when she visits to shoot scenes for a movie.
   About 250 people attended Wednesday night's public hearing at
Chicopee City Hall, where the state commissioner of veterans
service, John Halachis, called an end to the arguments over Fonda.
   ``Arguing about the appropriateness of this movie will not heal
one wound ... or provide jobs for one man or woman,'' Halachis said.
   Applause, cheers and whistles punctuated the remarks of Bud
Gagnon, head of veterans services for Chicopee, who referred to
Fonda's 1972 trip to Hanoi during the Vietnam War.
   ``She did make the statement she was sorry (and that) people
misunderstood her intentions. It was our fault we misunderstood
her. What was Jane Fonda's punishment? Enormous wealth! Jane Fonda
is not welcome in Chicopee!'' Gagnon said.
   Fonda's planned presence this summer has stirred strong passions
in the mill city of 55,112 people along the Connecticut River
outside Springfield.
   The movie, ``Union Street,'' is about an illiterate mill worker.
Fonda is to play a woman who teaches the man to read.
   Veterans from out of state have come to town to lend Fonda their
support, and even former U.S. House Speaker Thomas P. ``Tip''
O'Neill Jr. issued a statement praising her for her anti-war
activism.
   But several veterans' groups throughout western Massachusetts
have voiced their displeasure because of her trip to Hanoi. At the
urging of local veterans, aldermen in nearby Holyoke voted 11-4 on
Feb. 2 to consider Fonda a ``persona non grata'' if she comes to
their city to work.
   Chicopee aldermen called Wednesday's hearing on a request that
they pass a resolution similar to the one in Holyoke.
   The Holyoke aldermen, however, said they would not try to block
the shooting of the movie. And the mayors of Holyoke and Chicopee
have said they support the veterans' right to protest Fonda's visit
as well as her right to set foot in their communities.
   Charles Liteky, a Medal of Honor recipient, came from Washington
to speak on behalf of Fonda.
   ``I'm very grateful for those who protested against the U.S.
involvement in Vietnam. Had they not done that, I think we would
have had more people die,'' said the former chaplain, whose trip
was paid by a group of Vietnam veterans who are now peace activists.
   Before the hearing, Vietnam veteran Delfo Barabani Jr. said a
dozen veterans' groups in the city, representing hundreds of
people, unanimously approved a resolution opposing Fonda's visit.
``She's got a right to her opinions. I've got a right to mine. This
is my town. I don't feel particularly comfortable with her coming
here.''
</TEXT>
