<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0510,540</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Eliminates 2nd item, headlined ``Safeway Settles Commerce
Department Anti-Boycott Charges,'' which duplicates story moved
March 15 under a Los Angeles dateline.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Legislators: $2.2 Billion Anti-Drug Bill Turns Up Heat in Drug War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $2.4 billion ``self-funding'' anti-drug bill
is ``the beginning of the first major assault'' on the nation's
drug problem, according to one of the legislation's principal
sponsors.
   ``We have to be more forceful,'' Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.,
said at a news conference Wednesday with more than a dozen of the
bill's 35 House and Senate co-sponsors. ``We have mobilized a few
assets; we have a lot more to do.''
   The cost of the Omnibus Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988 would be
offset by an estimated $3.2 billion in debt collection mandated by
the bill, DeConcini said in introducing the legislation.
   The bill would add staff to the Internal Revenue Service and the
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms to collect an additional
$1.25 billion in taxes owed the government, and direct other
federal agencies to collect $2 billion in non-tax debt owed to
Uncle Sam. The money would be placed in a new Anti-Drug Abuse
Treasury Fund to help pay for the bill, DeConcini said.
   The 199-page bill calls for resurrecting the state and local
narcotics control grant program by providing $1.5 billion over
three years, including $250 million next year.
   Additionally, the bill moves the Coast Guard from the Department
of Transportation to the Treasury Department to provide better
coordination with the U.S. Customs Service, and creates a
streamlined deportation process for aliens who have been convicted
of a drug-related or violent crime.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Group Says EPA Report Will Show Many Eastern Streams Too Acidic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major environmental group says an unreleased
report of the Environmental Protection Agency shows that up to 14
percent of streams in sampled areas of eastern mountains are too
acidic.
   The Natural Resources Defense Council Wednesday accused the EPA
of ``sitting on'' the stream findings, and said it had been
rebuffed in requests for release of the final report made under the
Freedom of Information Act.
   Richard Ayres, a council staff lawyer who chairs the Clean Air
Coalition of environmental groups, said: ``We tried to give them a
break. We have had this document for over a year and have been
urging them to release the final report. They stiffed us at every
turn.''
   As part of its research on the effects of acid rain, the EPA
extensively sampled lakes and streams in 1985 and 1986. Lake
results have been reported extensively.
   But the EPA criticized the use of preliminary data by the group.
Spokesman Chris Rice said many tables would show ``significant
changes'' when the document is ready for release, probably in May.
