<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 3rdLd-Writethru   03-24 0790</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0583,0812</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Reported Killed; Mass Arrests Continue</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Arab death reported. Picks
up 4th graf pvs, `In Lebanon...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HEBRON, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot dead an
Arab today and wounded four others, including a 12-year-old, in
clashes across the occupied territories, hospital officials said.
   Overnight, troops swept through the occupied lands in a mass
arrest of Palestinians.
   Majid Mohammed Ahmed Sawalma, 21, died of two bullet wounds to
the chest and heart during a clash in the Balatta refugee camp near
Nablus, Al Ittihad Hospital officials said.
   Among the four Palestinians wounded in scattered clashes frm
Hebron to Nablus was a 12-year-old girl from the village of Tamoun,
10 miles west of Nablus, the officials said.
   Arab media reports said troops were using several West Bank
schools as detention centers.
   The army said it was checking the reports of casualties and
declined to comment on reports that schools were being used as
detention centers.
   In Lebanon, Israeli warplanes attacked Palestinian guerrilla
bases on the outskirts of Sidon for the second straight day. There
was no immediate word on casualties.
   It was the third Israeli strike against Palestinian bases in
Lebanon in a week and the fifth this year.
   Because of the ongoing violence in the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
Monsignor Michel Sabbah, Jerusalem's Roman Catholic patriarch,
decided to cancel the traditional Palm Sunday procession from the
Mount of Olives to Jerusalem's Old City.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, acting in his capacity as
interior minister, ordered the Haifa-based Al Ittihad, a communist
newspaper, closed until the end of the month on charges it was
inciting Arab unrest.
   An Israeli court ordered the army to return film confiscated
earlier this week from Time and Newsweek magazines and the Reuters
news agency but said Israeli authorities had the right to process
the film first. The film, taken Sunday, showed an Israeli soldier
moments after he was shot and killed in Bethlehem.
   The soldier was the first Israeli soldier to be killed since the
unrest in the occupied territories broke out Dec. 8. According to
U.N. figures, 107 Arabs have died in the unrest, most of them
killed by Israeli gunfire.
   ``We're not satisfied with the decision,'' said Robert Slater, a
Time correspondent and chairman of the Foreign Press Association.
``We had demanded the return of the film immediately without it
being processed.''
   Israeli officials rounded up at least 12 Palestinians in the
occupied Gaza Strip overnight, bringing to more than 107 the number
of Arabs arrested there in the past four days, the Gaza Lawyers'
Association said today.
   One attorney, Raji Sourani, said the lawyers' association counts
only those reported by family members and estimated the actual
number of arrests in the past four days in Gaza at about 350.
   An Islamic official in Hebron said Israeli soldiers had detained
more than 150 imams, or Moslem religious leaders, in nighttime
roundups this week. The official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said most of those detained were members of the
fundamentalist Islamic Jihad movement.
   The army has confirmed it is making arrests but has refused to
give details. Israeli officials have said the tactic has reduced
Arab violence.
   The patriarch decided to suspend this Sunday's procession
because of the possibility of violence along its narrow, winding
route through Arab east Jerusalem, said the Rev. Cladio Baratto,
director of the Christian Information Center in the Old City. The
procession commemorates Jesus' entry into Jerusalem before his
crucifixion.
   ``Prudence suggests this decision. It was a personal decision of
the Patriarch and no other forces influenced him,'' Baratto told
The Associated Press.
   Baratto denied reports that Sabbah, Jerusalem's first Arab
patriarch for Latin-rite Catholics, had been pressured by the
underground leadership of the Palestinian unrest to call off the
ceremony, which has been canceled only three times since 1932.
   Baratto told the Jerusalem Post there were fears that Christians
from the occupied territories would be prevented from attending due
to curfews.
   On Tuesday, Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin reportedly told a
parliamentary committee that Israel has jailed 3,000 Arabs since
anti-occupation violence began Dec. 8. An additional 1,000 Arabs
were arrested but set free, he said.
   Rabin on Wednesday told officers in the Gaza Strip that
large-scale rioting ``has been substantially reduced ... as a
result of the general activity of the army, the security forces,
the riot police.
   ``We feel a certain tiredness among the (Arab) population,'' he
said.
   Chief of Staff Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron said in Bethlehem on
Wednesday that Israel's policy was ``a prolonged combined action
accompanied with patience and built on three elements: the military
force, local punishments and economic pressure.''
</TEXT>
