<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Schools-Bennett     03-24 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Schools-Bennett,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Education Secretary Tours Two Chicago Public Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Education Secretary William Bennett visited
two schools here but said he saw nothing to change his assessment
of Chicago's system as the nation's worst, based on student
achievement on standardized tests.
   ``Of course, there are successes here. Of course, there are
positive things going on that deserve recognition,'' he said
Wednesday. ``But things are going to have to improve. We're going
to need more than a few success stories.''
   Bennett visited an all-black elementary school in a crime-ridden
neighborhood and an integrated high school at the invitation of
Jacqueline Vaughn, president of the Chicago Teachers Union.
   Last fall, Bennett said Chicago's public schools were suffering
an ``educational meltdown,'' and Mrs. Vaughn hoped to change his
views with a look at what she called daily educational successes.
   Bennett's first stop was Mary Terrell Elementary School, where
all the students in the upper grades are reading below their grade
level, though scores have improved in the last year. The school
serves the Robert Taylor Homes, a decaying public-housing project.
   At William J. Bogan High School in a predominantly white
neighborhood, Bennett visited a computer lab and an advanced
algebra class where he saw a teacher he later described as
excellent.
   Bennett said he saw superb teachers at both schools and thought
both had good principals. ``But two schools do not a system make.
The facts remain the facts,'' he said.
   Earlier, he had cited problems with the nation's third-largest
school system that include a dropout rate approaching 50 percent
and low standardized test scores. Half of Chicago's high schools
ranked in the bottom 1 percent of U.S. schools for scores on the
American College Test.
   Mrs. Vaughn, sitting beside Bennett at a news conference after
the tour, said a recent survey showed Chicago students ranked 20th
out of 41 large urban school systems in scores on the Scholastic
Aptitude Test.
   She said a survey of 21 large urban school systems found that
Chicago ranked 16th for student performance on the ACT.
</TEXT>
