<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MoscowMickey     03-24 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Moscow Mickey,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disney Nixes Invite To View Mickey Painting; Sends Legal RSVP
Instead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Mihail is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An exiled Soviet artist who painted
a picture of Mickey Mouse partly as an expression of his love of
American life has incurred the wrath of the Walt Disney Co.
   Artist Mihail Chemiakin said he wrote to Disney chairman Michael
Eisner inviting him and other company officials to see the painting
``Sorokin Soup,'' then on display at the Bowles-Sorokko Gallery in
Beverly Hills. He even suggested Disney might want to buy it.
   Instead, he said Wednesday, he was answered with a March 11
legal response saying not only would Disney not accept his
invitation to look or buy, the company objected to the gallery
display and to any attempts to sell the painting because the face
of Mickey Mouse belongs to Disney alone.
   ``It is sad and ironic that an artist who was forced out of the
Soviet Union because of political censorship for his artwork would
come into the West ... and be hit by censorship here,'' gallery
co-owner Serge Sorokko said Wednesday.
   The painting since has been taken down, said Sorokko, who called
from San Francisco, where he co-owns another gallery.
   Sorokko said the New York-based artist chose the image of Mickey
Mouse more as a tribute to the late artist Andy Warhol, who reveled
in pop icons, and certainly not to rip off the good Disney name.
   ``Mickey Mouse is a symbol of America. ... Their approach is
just totally ludicrous,'' he said.
   Chemiakin, who came to the United States in 1978, is known for
creating a painting style called ``metaphysical synthesis,'' which
combines images from various cultures and times, Sorokko said.
   He was exiled from the Soviet Union in 1971, according to
information released by his publicist here. He had been accepted at
the Soviet's Repin Academy of Art at age 14, but was thrown out two
years later for failing to conform to the traditional ``Socialist
Realism'' style of painting.
   Recently though, Chemiakin has been invited back to the Soviet
Union to display his work, Sorokko said.
</TEXT>
