<2ND_LINE>PM-Northwest-Smoking, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0529,0716</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Other Airlines Reluctant to Follow Northwest Smoking Ban</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after the 5th to update with passenger
reaction. A longer version moved on the financial wire.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines' bold step in banning smoking
on most of its flights is not expected to be followed soon by other
major U.S. airlines, industry analysts say.
   Northwest, the nation's fifth-largest airline, announced
Wednesday it will prohibit smoking on all its domestic flights
except those to and from Hawaii and on some foreign routes.
   The ban makes Eagan, Minn.-based Northwest the first major U.S.
airline to mandate a smoke-free environment, surpassing federal
regulations that on April 23 outlaw smoking on all domestic flights
less than two hours.
   ``It does run the risk of some loss of business,'' said James V.
Cammisa, publisher of Travel Industry Indicators, a New York-based
newsletter. ``I guess they (Northwest officials) really stuck their
neck out.''
   Wall Street seemed unimpressed by Northwest's move. The
airline's stock closed on Wall Street at $45.75 a share, down 12{
cents from Tuesday.
   Several smokers waiting to depart on Northwest flights Wednesday
from Minneapolis-St. Paul International Airport said they don't
object to the smoking ban.
   ``It's probably a good idea,'' said Janice Davis, a Boston real
estate broker. ``I can get by without smoking.''
   Some Northwest flight attendants who are smokers said the new
policy might help them quit smoking, the St. Paul Pioneer
Press-Dispatch reported today.
   The new policy, ``Northwest Clears the Air,'' takes effect April
23 with the new federal regulations. It applies to flights within
the contiguous 48 states and to and from Alaska, Mexico, Canada,
Jamaica and the Cayman Islands.
   The longest flights covered by the smoking ban are four or five
hours, the airline said. About 30 percent of Northwest's domestic
flights and about 20 percent of all domestic flights last more than
the two-hour federal duration. Northwest flights to and from Hawaii
and overseas will offer smoking sections because those flights
``carry a greater proportion of foreign passengers who feel
differently about the issue,'' the airline said.
   A.B. Magary, Northwest's marketing chief, said the ban accedes
to passenger and employee requests. The policy is not risk-free, he
said, but ``we believe more nonsmokers will switch to Northwest
than smokers will leave.''
   That wasn't the case for Muse Air Corp. of Dallas, a regional
carrier that failed to establish itself as the only non-smoking
airline in 1985. Its research showed the policy diverted as many as
35 percent of potential fliers.
   Surveys showed customers find ``price, convenience and service
more important than non-smoking'' in an airline, Muse spokeswoman
Shari Cohen said at the time. The policy ended when Muse was sold
to Southwest Airlines Co.
   No. 2 American Airlines is watching Northwest's lead but, ``We
have no plans to follow that move,'' said American spokeswoman Mary
O'Neill. Its surveys indicate a significant number of people want
to smoke on planes.
   American and other big airlines contacted Wednesday said their
no-smoking policies would meet the new federal law, which mandates
civil fines of as much as $1,000 for smoking, $2,000 for tampering
with lavatory smoke alarms.
   ``We are ready to implement our no-smoking policy ... in line
with the federal law,'' said Dan Sheehy spokesman for United
Airline, the nation's largest airline.
   Airline analyst Anthony Hatch of Argus Research Corp., said he
did not expect other carriers to match Northwest's policy. ``It's a
gutsy move and most airlines don't make gutsy moves,'' he said.
``It could alienate some people.''
   The alienated include The Great American Smoker's Club of
Dallas, which on April 22 offers smoking flights and the same fares
as Southwest Airlines from Dallas to such cities as Austin,
Houston, New Orleans and Oklahoma City.
   Using leased planes from Las Vegas-based Royal West Airlines,
the club hopes to serve 63 cities from five hubs with 60 planes in
two years, said club president Glenn Herndon.
   ``When the smoking ban begins, we want to offer smokers an
alternative _ and, hopefully, make some money,'' he said.
Non-smokers will be allowed on board, but they will have to be
``tolerant,'' the club says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880324-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1101EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BaptistAlliance     03-24 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baptist Alliance,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Head Of Moderate Group Says Feuding Has Scared Many Baptists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MACON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new president of the Southern Baptist
Alliance says he intends to continue working within the Southern
Baptist Convention, though he says his group is taking on the
appearance of a separate denomination.
   The alliance represents a moderate group within the 14.7
million-member convention, which is dominated by fundamentalists.
   ``We are not a fringe group, we are not an avant garde faction
of the Southern Baptist Convention,'' the Rev. John Thomason said
Wednesday. ``The great majority of SBA members are denominational
loyalists.''
   Thomason said, however, that the alliance may appear to be
headed toward denominational status because of its publishing
activities and its discussions concerning the possible need for a
new seminary or divinity school.
   ``Whenever we take specific steps like that, we are acting
independently of the institutions of the Southern Baptist
Convention and that gives the appearance of independence, but it is
not our desire to forge a permanent split with the SBC,'' Thomason
said.
   Nevertheless, he said, the alliance has to be an ``advocate for
groups and causes we feel are disenfranchised. ... If this means
acting independently of the existing agencies and channels of SBC
life, then for the time being, we are willing to do that.''
   Thomason is pastor of the 561-member Northminster Baptist Church
in Jackson, Miss., the third church to join the alliance after its
formation in February 1987. The alliance has grown from 22 founders
to more than 25,000 members, including 40 churches in 11 states and
more than 2,000 individual members.
   The fundamentalists have gained control of the Southern Baptist
Convention hierarchy by electing their presidential candidates for
the past nine years. The president has broad appointive powers,
naming hundreds of people annually to various Baptist institutions,
including the boards of the six seminaries and the five major
operating agencies of the denomination.
   While both groups generally are conservative, they disagree on
key issues, including biblical inerrancy and ordination of women.
Fundamentalists, who oppose ordination of women, say the Bible is
without factual error, not only in matters of faith but also in
science and history. Moderates maintain there is room for
interpretation, especially in non-religious areas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
