<HEAD>Fire Erupts on British Ferry; No Injuries</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: DROPS extraneous word in lead to show ferry was not towed
back to Zeebrugge and restores dropped word `the' in 2nd graf.
Picks up 3rd graf, `Coast guards ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FELIXSTOWE, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A blaze erupted today in the engine
room of a British ferry shortly after it left the Belgian port of
Zeebrugge with 348 people aboard, but tugs towed the ship to port
and no one was injured.
   P and O, owners of the 18,000-ton Nordic, said the two-hour fire
wrecked the ferry's power system.
   Coast guards called a major alert after the Nordic, on a
six-hour English Channel crossing from Zeebrugge to the English
port of Felixstowe, reported fire aboard 30 minutes before it had
been due to dock.
   The Nordic, surrounded by a flotilla of tugs and life boats, was
stranded for several hours five miles off the coast before tugs got
the vessel under tow and brought it to Felixstowe, in southeast
England.
   ``Three life boats were dispatched and a helicopter was put on
standby,'' said John Davies, coast guard spokesman at the nearby
port of Harwich.
   A P and O spokesman said the fire was put out by automatic
firefighting equipment and the crew. The fire was confined to the
engine room.
   ``Everyone on board was very calm and there was no danger to
anyone,'' said P and O spokesman Chris Lamming.
   Last March, another P and O ferry, the Herald of Free
Enterprise, capsized after leaving Zeebrugge, killing 193 people.
</TEXT>
