<HEAD>Father Sought For Questioning in His Daughter's Death</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Penne is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man being sought today for questioning in his
5-year-old daughter's death was previously accused of abusing the
girl but the charge was dropped for lack of evidence, court records
show.
   Police want to question Ibrahim Thiab Mubarak, 38, a substitute
teacher, about the death of Julianna Cathleen Olson, whose
decomposed body was found in his deserted apartment.
   An autopsy conducted Wednesday showed evidence of trauma but a
ruling on the cause of death was awaiting further tests, said
Deputy Coroner Chuck Bolton.
   Based on preliminary findings, however, ``this case is being
handled as a homicide,'' Bolton said.
   In January 1986, Mubarak had been charged with one count of
felony child abuse and one count of assault after the child was
hospitalized. The charge was dismissed later in the year.
   Mubarak obtained cstody of the girl after his ex-wife, Cathleen
Olson, died in 1983. The couple had been married briefly in 1981,
separating after three weeks.
   Last fall, Mubarak won a custody dispute involving the child's
grandmother, Betty Olson of San Diego.
   In awarding custody, Superior Court Judge Napoleon Jones
expressed concern about reports in court files and ordered that no
corporal punishment was to be used on the child.
   Betty Olson continued to seek custody of the child, said her
attorney, Kathryn Ashworth
   ``She's absolutely devastated,'' Ashworth said. ``I'm pretty
devastated too. She was a lovely, charming little 5-year-old girl.''
   Julianna's body was found Tuesday in the two-bedroom apartment
by Nita Morin, who manages the seven-unit building. Deputy Coroner
Penne Hammerstead said that the girl had been dead for more than a
week.
