<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0585,0697</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran and Iraq Trade Missile Attacks; Iran Claims New Offensive</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th graf: ``There was...,'' to UPDATE
with Persian Gulf incident. Pick up 6th graf: ``Iran also...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran and Iraq fired eight missiles into
each others' capitals today, and Tehran claimed new victories in
heavy fighting in northeastern Iraq.
   Iraq said it fired six long-range missiles into Tehran at a rate
of one a minute in retaliation for Iranian artillery bombardment of
Iraqi cities. Iraq said it was destroying Tehran ``piece by piece.''
   Iran reported at least 10 civilians dead and 100 wounded after
the missiles hit two schools, two mosques and two hospitals as well
as shops and houses.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in
Nicosia, Cyprus, said Iranian Revolutionary Guards fired two
missiles into Baghdad in reprisal.
   There was no immediate confirmation of those missile strikes
from the Iraqi capital.
   In the Persian Gulf today, a ship put out a distress signal and
appeared to be the victim of an Iranian attack, maritime salvage
executives said.
   The executives, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
Friendship reported its engine room was on fire. If it was the
victim of Iranian attack, it would be Iran's 10th attack on neutral
shipping in the gulf since last Friday.
   Iran also claimed its troops routed two Iraqi commando brigades
and four armored battalions early today and advanced to within five
miles of the mountain town of Sayyid Sadiq. The reports came in the
latest phase of Iran's 9-day-old offensive into northeastern Iraq.
   Iran said today's ground assault retaliated for Iraqi chemical
bomb attacks last week that killed 5,000 Iraqi Kurds whose
hometowns were overrun by Iranian troops fighting with the
autonomy-seeking Kurds.
   Tehran's news agency said the Iranians repulsed a counterattack
by Iraq's 5th Army Corps, killing or wounding 1,000 Iraqis,
capturing 400 and knocking out 30 tanks and armored vehicles.
   But the official Iraqi news agency, also monitored in Cyprus,
said ``thousands of Iranians were killed'' in artillery barrages
and air strikes.
   ``The charlatan regime in Tehran is reaping today the harvest of
its crimes,'' said an Iraqi military communique broadcast by the
agency.
   Iranian jets flew 14 ground attack missions against Iraqi forces
in the battle zone and shot down an Iraqi warplane, Tehran's news
agency said. It said ground fire downed an Iraqi helicopter
gunship, but Baghdad denied losing any aircraft.
   Iraq has said it has fired 42 Al Hussein missiles into Tehran
since March 15 in what is known as the ``war of the cities.'' Iran
has retaliated by lobbing 14 missiles into the Iraqi capital, which
has a population of 5 million.
   Scores of other cities on both sides have been hit with
missiles, air raids and shellfire, with hundreds of civilians
killed or wounded on both sides.
   The Iranian news agency said the latest phase of the offensive,
the heaviest fighting in the northern part of the 730-mile front,
was launched in retaliatiation for Iraqi chemical bomb attacks on
Halabja, Khormal and Dojaila, three of the Kurdish towns captured
last week.
   The Iranians claimed the poison gas attacks killed 5,000 Kurdish
civilians and injured 5,000. Western reporters flown to Halabja by
the Iranians this week reported seeing hundreds of dead civilians
there with no obvious wounds.
   The correspondents reported that many people had died of
asphyxiation in their homes. Survivors were seen suffering from
burns consistent with poison gas.
   U.S. State Department spokesman Charled Redman charged in
Washington Wednesday that Iraq had used chemical weapons, banned
under a 1925 Geneva agreement, and urged the United Nations
Security Council to mount an international protest.
   Declaring the Iraqi action ``a particularly grave violation'' of
the Geneva protocol, Redman said there was evidence the Iraqis had
also fired chemical shells into Iran.
   The Iranian news agency said earlier this week that Iraqi
warplanes had dropped chemical bombs, believed to contain mustard
or phosgene gas, on eight towns in northwest Iran, causing scores
of civilian casualties.
</TEXT>
