<HEAD>Assistant State Attorneys Suspended After High Speed Police Chase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities will ask Gov. Bob Martinez to
appoint a special prosecutor to handle the case of an assistant
state attorney who police say tried to bully an officer into
letting her go.
   Chief Assistant State Atorney Mack Futch also said he is
suspending Jan Bamping until State Attorney Frank Schaub returns
next week from vacation and reviews his decision.
   Police say Ms. Bamping, 32, and a passenger, Assistant State
Attorney Jerry Blevins, 27, threatened an officer in an attempt to
avoid getting into trouble, the Bradenton Herald reported Wednesday.
   Their car had been pulled over by Bradenton Beach Patrolman Ron
Robertson early Sunday after a 1{-mile chase at speeds of up to 90
mph, police reports said.
   Robertson said he believed Ms. Bamping had been drinking, but
didn't order her from the car for a sobriety test because she was
naked from the waist down.
   When he asked Ms. Bamping why she was partially nude, Robertson
said, she became upset and answered that it's ``not against the law
to drive nude.''
   Robertson charged Ms. Bamping with fleeing to elude an officer
and improper passing.
   ``She threatened (his job) right away,'' said Acting Police
Chief Bill Tillner. ``In my opinion, (Blevins) did try to influence
the officer with his position.''
   ``She said because she was with the State Attorney's Office, she
should not be treated like this,'' Robertson said. ``I told her she
had no right to endanger other people because of her job.''
   Ms. Bamping demanded his name and identification number and said
``she would see me in court,'' he said.
   Robertson's back-up officer, Patrolman John Cosby, confirmed
Robertson's account, Tillner said.
   No charges were brought against Blevins.
   Ms. Bamping's telephone number is not published, and she could
not be located for comment. The Herald also said it had been unable
to reach her.
   But Blevins told the Herald: ``I don't think we did anything
improper as far as using this office.''
   Ms. Bamping's case was scheduled for May 11 in traffic court.
</TEXT>
