<2ND_LINE>PM-Father-Abuse,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Father Arraigned For Alleged Sexual Abuse of 5-Year-Old Daughter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY MITMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lawyer for a man charged with sexually
assaulting his daughter says the allegations are more of the same
from the man's ex-wife, who last year went to jail rather than let
him visit their children.
   Mark Russell Murabito, 33, of Derry pleaded innocent Wednesday
in Rockingham County Superior Court to the charge of felonious
sexual assault. Bail was set at $5,000 personal recognizance on the
condition that Murabito have no contact with the daughter, now 5,
or her 3{-year-old brother.
   Murabito since March 1987 has had unsupervised visits with the
children, after a judge found no evidence to back Jesse Murabito's
claims that Murabito sexually abused their daughter.
   A grand jury last week indicted Murabito based on events since
the judge's decision, County Attorney Carleton Eldredge said.
   After Wednesday's arraignment, Raymond Kellett, Murabito's
lawyer, said the charge ``is simply an extension of the divorce
proceedings ... the same type of thing that the court has already
ruled on in hearings last year.''
   ``I am fairly convinced by the evidence, or I wouldn't have gone
to the grand jury, that these children are being sexually abused,''
Eldredge said, adding that he has an ``obligation, in my job and my
conscience, to alleviate that situation.''
   Eldredge blamed the media for ruining any chance he would have
had to negotiate an out-of-court agreement with Murabito that would
result in ``long-term meaningful protection of the children without
public fanfare or trial.''
   In March 1987, Superior Court Judge Douglas Gray ruled after a
seven-day civil hearing that Mrs. Murabito and the experts she
marshaled had not proved Murabito sexually abused the girl.
   In a 19-page divorce decree, Gray admonished both parents to
stop ``tearing (the children) to pieces'' and gave Murabito
unsupervised visits, alternating weekends and holidays, as well as
two weeks each summer.
   Gray did not return a telephone call seeking comment on
Wednesday.
   A month before the divorce hearing, Gray had jailed Mrs.
Murabito for a week _ and gave Murabito temporary custody _ when
she refused to obey a court order to let her husband see the
children during supervised visits. Gray released her after she
agreed.

