<HEAD>Biden Leaves Hospital Joking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del., left the
hospital today, smiling, joking and saying he feels better than he
looks.
   ``I've decided to re-enter the race for president,'' he joked.
The senator dropped out of the Democratic race last fall.
   Biden had been in Walter Reed Army Hospital for 11 days so
surgeons could implant a small umbrella-like filter in a vein to
prevent blood clots from reaching his lungs.
   A clot formed in the wake of surgery Biden had on Feb. 12 to
correct the ballooning of an artery that supplied blood to his
brain.
   He was to have a second operation for a similar but smaller
aneurysm on the other side of his head but instead returned to
Walter Reed on March 13 and doctors discovered a blood clot in his
lung.
   The clot itself was absorbed into the body without any damage, a
hospital spokesman said, but to prevent any further problems a team
of doctors last Friday inserted a tiny filter in a major vein. The
small device was implanted in the vena cava, an area just below the
breast bone.
   Biden said doctors will allow him to work two to four hours a
day at home in Delaware and that he should walk as exercise.
   He said that for the first time in years his waist size is 34.
