<HEAD>KKK Barred From Holding Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has blocked the Ku Klux Klan from
holding a rally in a predominantly black neighborhood, citing
zoning laws that prohibit public gatherings without special
permission.
   ``We consider (the Klan) similar to clubs and other
organizations such as churches or synagogues'' which cannot hold
public gatherings in residential areas without special permits,
said Superior Court Judge William Fleming.
   Fleming on Wednesday enjoined the Klan from holding a rally and
cross-burning Friday in the yard of Robert Long, grand dragon of
the Christian Knights of the Ku Klux Klan.
   The judge ruled that the gathering was public because Klan
members had distributed flyers inviting the public.
   The group could ask for a special exemption from the zoning
board, but Long said the rally will be moved instead.
   The Richmond County Commission and Sheriff Charles Webster had
gone to court to oppose the rally.
   Last April, county investigators interrupted a cross-burning in
Long's yard and filed charges of terroristic threats and acts
against 13 people, including Long. That case is pending.
