<1ST_LINE>u a PM-RestaurantInspectors 1stLd-Writethru a0592 03-24 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Restaurant Inspectors, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0592,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Widespread Corruption found in Eatery Inspections</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with arrests and details</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-eight current and former health
inspectors were named in complaints today accusing them of
extorting hundreds of thousands of dollars from restaurants to
ignore sanitary code violations, authorities say.
   The charges in the federal complaint involve at least one-third
of the city Health Department's inspection force of 70 and 300
restaurants in all five boroughs, U.S. Attorney Andrew J. Maloney
of Brooklyn said in a news release.
   The arrests this morning culminated a three-year undercover
investigation by the FBI, the city Department of Investigation and
the U.S. attorney's office. This week agents confronted a number of
suspects to get them to wear microphones to gather evidence against
the leaders of the bribery ring.
   A report today in the New York Daily News said the operation was
code-named alternatively ``Operation Kitchen'' and ``Operation
Fork-It-Over.''
   The restaurants paid the bribes to avoid citations for
violations either real or invented, authorities said. The names of
the restaurants were not made public, but they ranged from fast
food restaurants to famous eateries, they said.
   The investigation also found that on-site inspectors split their
take with supervisors, who allegedly would punish inspectors who
were reluctant to share the extortion money with them, authorities
said.
   In one incident, inspectors demanded $1,400 from a restaurant
owner so his restaurant would not be closed for serious health
violations, according to the news release. In another, inspectors
charged a restaurant $1,200 to allow it to reopen despite serious
violations.
   Payoffs reached hundreds of thousands of dollars altogether. The
News said the restaurant owners are considered extortion victims
and are not being charged.
   Inspectors and supervisors are paid $25,000 to $30,000 annually
by the city. More than 15,000 food establishments are inspected
each year for compliance with health and cleanliness standards.
</TEXT>
