<1ST_LINE>r i PM-CulturalRevolution     03-24 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cultural Revolution,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Cultural Revolution Military Leaders Out of Prison</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four military leaders imprisoned for an alleged
coup attempt against Mao Tse-tung in 1971 have been released, a
government spokesman said today.
   All four were top assistants to Defense Minister Lin Piao during
the ultra-leftist Cultural Revolution that began in 1966, and all
were convicted of aiding him in an aborted attempt to murder Mao
and seize power.
   The releases leave only the ``Gang of Four'' still in prison
from among the 10 fallen Cultural Revolution power brokers
convicted in 1981 after a lengthy show trial.
   Lin was Mao's designated successor, a key creator of the Mao
cult and author of the ``Little Red Book'' of quotations from Mao.
He allegedly died in a plane crash in Mongolia while fleeing arrest.
   Zeng Tao, a spokesman for the National People's Congress,
China's legislature, disclosed the releases at a news conference.
   He said former air force commander Wu Faxian, former navy
political commissar Li Zuopeng and former army Gen. Jiang Tengjiao
were released on bail for medical treatment, but he did not say
when or disclose the nature of their illnesses.
   Qiu Huizuo, former director of the military's General Logistics
Department, completed his 16-year term in September and was
released, Zeng said.
   He did not explain why as recently as January, the Ministry of
Public Security insisted that all four former military leaders
remained in prison. Wu's and Li's terms end this year, while
Jiang's ends in 1989.
   Zeng said two of the Gang of Four members _ Mao's widow Jiang
Qing and former Vice Premier Zhang Chunqiao _ were being treated in
prison for unspecified ``geriatric diseases.'' Jiang Qing is 74 and
Zhang is 70.
   The Gang of Four, which also included former Politburo members
Wang Hongwen and Yao Wenyuan, was accused of ordering illegal
arrests during the decade-long Cultural Revolution and trying to
seize total power after Mao's death in 1976.
   Their arrest shortly after Mao died marked the end of the
Cultural Revolution, an era of bloody persecutions of intellectuals
and anyone suspected of lacking revolutionary fervor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880324-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1131EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Washington-AIDS     03-24 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington-AIDS,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Washington Health Officials Start To Implement New AIDS
Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID AMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Landmark AIDS legislation described by
sponsors as a model for America has gone into effect in Washington,
aimed at protecting the disease's victims and stopping its spread.
   The measure, funded by an appropriation of more than $5 million,
will tackle the killer disease through education, testing,
counseling, civil rights protection, and prosecution of people who
intentionally spread acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   Gov. Booth Gardner signed the bill Wednesday and it took effect
immediately.
   ``We must recognize that AIDS is only beginning to take its toll
on human life and in costs to our society. By acting now,
especially with a strong public education program, we hope to save
many of our citizens' lives,'' the governor said.
   Key provisions of the measure are:
   _A 10-year prison sentence for intentionally spreading the AIDS
virus.
   _Mandatory AIDS education in grades 5 through 12 and
availability in colleges and trade schools. Mandatory AIDS training
for all public school personnel, emergency services crews and
health professionals.
   _Mandatory testing and counseling for all convicted of sex
crimes, prostitution or intravenous drug use. Violent prison
inmates would be tested at the request of the prison and approval
of the local health officer.
   _A procedure is created for confronting, examining, detaining
and confining infected individuals who refuse to modify their
behavior so they don't pose a threat to others. Due process
protections are provided.
   _Regional service networks will be set up in the six most
populous counties by Oct. 1.
   _Those who carry the AIDS virus, or who are perceived to have
it, will be protected from discrimination.
   Jule Sugarman, head of the Department of Social and Health
Services, said he already had followed the bill's directive and
created a new Office on AIDS. He said he began to confer with
county health officials on setting up regional AIDS service centers
across Washington.
   Those centers will do the mandatory and voluntary AIDS testing,
counseling, public education, and outreach to ``street kids'' and
other target populations. They also will plan and coordinate
services to AIDS patients, develop volunteer networks and notify
partners of infected people.
   ``This bill will make an enormous difference,'' said Jim Holm of
the Privacy Lobby and the gay rights Dorian Group. ``We've taken a
step toward making it safe to know your antibody status, whether
you're at risk, and safe to seek public health (services).
   ``In this state we've finally said civil rights and public
health go hand-in-hand.''
   ``The important thing is that we did get a statewide policy on
AIDS,'' said state Sen. Alex Deccio, co-sponsor of the measure.
``It's the first omnibus bill of its kind in the country, so I
guess it's the best available.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
