<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DisintegratingChecks     03-24 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Disintegrating Checks,0183</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Banks Warned To Watch For Dissolving Checks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Checks that disintegrate into confetti shortly
after being deposited have cost banks nearly $50,000 this year, the
Chicago Clearing House Association says.
   It warned banks this week to be on the lookout for dissolving
checks, and the FBI has been asked to determine whether the
chemical used to destroy the checks is harmful to humans.
   Northern Trust Bank has been hit by a number of the checks, an
association memo says.
   In one case, a Northern customer deposited a $4,000 check in a
savings account on Feb. 16, then withdrew the same amount a week
later from one of the bank's branch offices, the memo said.
   The $4,000 check was returned to Northern in a check carrier on
March 2, but by then it had been ``reduced to mere confetti, small
bits of paper that appeared to be treated with chemicals that
caused the paper to break into pieces to a point where it was
impossible to identify any information on the check,'' the memo
said.
</TEXT>
