<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NorthwestAttendants     03-24 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northwest Attendants,0209</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northwest Flight Attendants Committee Agrees To Turn Over Pact For
Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A union negotiating committee has voted to
submit a tentative contract for ratification by Northwest Airlines'
6,500 flight attendants, says a Teamsters official.
   The 15-member committee met at Teamsters headquarters in
Bloomington and approved the vote Wednesday night, said Jeff Musto,
a Teamsters spokesman.
   ``My personal feeling is that yes, they will ratify it,'' Musto
said.
   It will take about 30 days to complete the vote, he said.
   Musto declined to release details of the tentative accord,
although he earlier confirmed that the contract will require all
flight attendants to join the union.
   Both sides said the March 29 strike deadline, set by the flight
attendants last week, provided the impetus for an agreement.
   The key issue has been Northwest's two-tier wage structure. The
airline had proposed extending the lower-paid, B-scale to eight
years from the current five years.
   B-scale flight attendants said the airline was trying to break a
promise that they would earn A-scale wages after five years.
   The Star Tribune of Minneapolis, citing unidentified sources,
reported today that the tentative agreement calls for B-scale
employees to move up after seven years.
</TEXT>
