<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DraftResister     03-24 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Draft Resister,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Draft Conviction Overturned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man whose conviction on a charge of
failing to comply with peacetime draft registration rules was
overturned says he has spent quite enough time in jail.
   ``I think there's a strong argument to be made that the
government should not retry this case at all, since I've already
served more time than most people convicted of failing to
register,'' said Gillam Kerley, whose conviction was thrown out
Wednesday by the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   Kerly served four months of his sentence.
   The appeals court ruled that U.S. District Judge John Shabaz
gave the jury flawed instructions.
   Shabaz sentenced Kerley to three years in prison and fined him
$10,000, one of the most severe sentences in a draft case since the
Vietnam War.
   U.S. Attorney Patrick Fiedler said he would review the decision
before deciding whether to seek a new trial.
   Kerley pleaded ``not guilty by reason of sanity'' in 1982 to a
federal indictment for failing to register. He fought the
government for 4{ years as his own attorney before being convicted
last April.
</TEXT>
