<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Gephardt-HouseSeat 3rdLd-Writethru a0609vail. 03-24
0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gephardt-House Seat, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0609,620</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts new grafs 4-5 with Jane Gephardt quote bgng ``While
Gephardt's...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Gephardt will end his campaign for the
Democratic presidential nomination and file for re-election to his
Missouri House seat if he doesn't win the Michigan caucuses on
Saturday, a campaign aide said today.
   Speaking on the condition of anonymity, the aide said Gephardt
would probably announce the end of his campaign on Monday and file
for re-election to his House seat by the Tuesday afternoon deadline.
   ``He will be out if he doesn't win in Michigan,'' said the aide.
   While Gephardt's spokesmen officially denied any decision has
been made, the congressman's wife told a radio interviewer that the
end may be near.
   ``I think Dick has to come in first or a real strong second to
remain in the race, because at some point if you don't do well
here, it becomes difficult to raise money,'' she told WTVB radio in
Coldwater, Mich. ``Dick's message will be very popular in the
industrial states, but if we don't do well here, we will not be
able to continue.''
   Gephardt is running third in the polls in Michigan behind
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson. Gephardt is
badly in need of a win after a weak showing in the Super Tuesday
contests earlier this month.
   The aide also said some consideration was being given to
Gephardt's ending his presidential bid even if he wins in Michigan.
   ``Only as Rep. Gephardt can he raise the money to pay off the
debts'' from the presidential campaign, the aide said.
   Spokesmen for Gephardt denied that a decision has been made.
   ``This notion that the decision has been made before the results
are in is false,'' said Mark Johnson in Washingon.
   Johnson also said that the campaign ``does not have a large
debt. We have virtually no bank debt. ... We have some vendor
debts.''
   ``There's never been any question that if the presidential
effort was not successful that Dick would probably run for his
House seat,'' said Ali Webb, Gephardt spokeswoman in Detroit.
``He's going to pursue his political agenda and his issues for this
country from the House, if not from the presidency. But right now,
he's running for president.''
   Publicly, Gephardt on Wednesday refused to link his showing in
Michigan to his candidacy.
   Asked if his Saturday's results would make or break his
campaign, Gephardt said, ``That's unthinkable.''
   ``All decisions are made in due time,'' he said.
   Earlier, a St. Louis Democratic leader said a weekend meeting
was scheduled among the Democratic contenders for Gephardt's
congressional seat.
   The Dallas Times Herald reported today that the participants at
that meeting would be told Gephardt was preparing to seek
re-election to the House instead of the White House.
   ``We're getting the major candidates together and talking about
procedure and unity, said the Democratic leader, Tony Ribaudo.
``That's normal in St. Louis politics. I don't know what Dick
Gephardt's going to do.''
   State Rep. Philip Barry of St. Louis County, one of the leading
contenders for the congressional seat, told the Times Herald the
meeting would be attended by six candidates who have filed for
Gephardt's seat, plus a St. Louis alderman who is expected to file
if Gephardt decides not to seek re-election.
   One of the candidates, George Kerry, an administrative aide in
Gephardt's St. Louis office, told The Assoiated Press Wednesday
night that he knew nothing of the meeting.
   Kerry, who has said he would drop out of the race if Gephardt
files for re-election, said he understood Gephardt was waiting to
see how he fared in Michigan on Saturday before making a decision.
</TEXT>
