<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AtomicTests     03-24 0110</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Atomic Tests,90</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Votes to Expand Participants' Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Judiciary Committee approved by
voice vote today legislation designed to restore legal rights to
individuals who were exposed to radiation when the United States
tested atomic weapons.
   The measure, whose chief sponsor is Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill.,
would repeal a provision of a 1985 Defense Department bill that
curtailed sharply the legal rights of civilians and veterans who
participated in the atomic testing program.
   Until 1985, radiation victims could file suit against
contractors who participated in the testing programs. The 1985 act
shifted the target of radiation suits from defense contractors to
the federal government.
</TEXT>
