<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Train Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0568,0589</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Train Collision Kills 12, Injures At Least 40</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES thruout with 12 reported killed, 40 injured. ADDS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   quotes from survivors and report that one train ran signal. ADDS
byline. No pickup.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two passenger trains collided head-on today in a
Shanghai suburb, killing 12 people and injuring more than 40, the
state-run Xinhua News Agency said. It was China's fourth fatal
train accident in three months.
   China's second official news agency, the China News Service,
said only seven were dead, including five Japanese, a Chinese
soldier and a railway worker. It said 40 to 50 people were
hospitalized.
   The Japanese Embassy confirmed that a 193-member Japanese high
school tour group was on one of the trains. It said the Japan
Travel Bureau, which arranged the tour, reported two Japanese
killed and 29 injured.
   Xinhua said 11 Japanese were killed.
   The cause of the collision in the Shanghai suburb of Fengbang
was not immediately clear, said Fu Fenghao, chief of the Shanghai
Foreign Affairs Office's public relations division.
   Xinhua, however, said one of the trains ignored a stop signal
when it left the Shanghai station.
   The crash occurred at about 2 p.m. when northbound train No.
311, leaving Shanghai for Hangzhou, collided with southbound train
No. 208 arriving from Changsha, Fu said.
   No. 311's first two cars and the luggage car of No. 208 were
knocked off the tracks, he said.
   Television footage by Japanese camera crews broadcast in Japan
showed the luggage car resting on one end of the other train's
engine. The China News Service said the two first-class passenger
cars behind the No. 311 engine were crushed together by the force
of the collision.
   The news service said Shanghai had rain and heavy fog today but
did not say if this was believed to have contributed to the
accident.
   Xinhua said the No. 311 train ``rolled out of the Kuangxiang
station, ignoring the prohibiting signal, and collided with the No.
208 train that was entering the station.''
   Kengo Kobayashi of the Japanese Embassy in Beijing said two
people from a high school in southern Japan's Kochi Prefecture were
among the dead, and 29 others were injured.
   Fu confirmed that Japanese students were among the dead and
injured but said the number was not yet determined.
   ``We haven't heard any information about other nationalities,''
he added.
   ``We were playing cards and suddenly there was a loud bang, and
things went flying all over the floor,'' said an unidentified male
student interviewed in Shanghai by the Japan Broadcasting Corp.
   ``There was a huge bump, and then one of our teachers came into
the car and told us to get out,'' said another student. ``We broke
the windows and climbed out.''
   The train tracks were blocked seven hours after the accident, Fu
said. He said soldiers, police and medical workers took the dead
and injured to nearby hospitals and that investigators were at the
scene trying to determine the cause.
   Shanghai Vice Mayor Huang Ju also went to the scene, the China
News Service said.
   In January, three separate train accidents killed 141 people.
China's minister of railways resigned this month to take
responsibility for those accidents.
   This year's train accidents, together with a plane crash outside
Chungking in January that killed all 108 people aboard, have
prompted severe calls by the Beijing government for greater
attention to safety.
</TEXT>
