<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Barges-Pier     03-24 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Barges-Pier,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Joined Barges Slam Into Pensacola Fishing Pier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pair of barges loaded with a flammable liquid
today slammed into the end of the Pensacola Fishing Pier, a former
bridge billed as the world's longest fishing pier.
   The barges were wedged into the L-shaped vehicular turnaround at
the tip of the pier, formerly a highway bridge across Pensacola Bay
connecting Pensacola and Gulf Breeze. The bridge was divided into
two sections, each becoming fishing piers. The Pensacola pier is
1.5 miles long.
   ``The wind caught it and blew him into the bridge (pier),'' said
Grey Jewett, risk manager for Escambia County, which owns the pier.
``It destroyed the end of the pier, a turnaround. It's not
reparable.''
   The pier is only 75 feet away from the new Pensacola Bay Bridge.
Officials said they planned to block traffic on the new, four-lane
bridge while attempts were made to pull the barges, which were tied
together along with a towboat, from the pier.
   The barges were loaded with benzine, a colorless, flammable
liquid used as a motor fuel and solvent in dry cleaning.
   None of the benzine apparently leaked, but officials were
worried about possible fire or explosion.
   ``It's not the benzine, it's the vapor,'' said Chuck Ramsey, an
engineering technician for the county. ``It would go with one
spark.''
   One of the barges was pushed into the shipping channel, blocking
navigation traffic.
</TEXT>
