<HEAD>Disneyland Hotel Suspends Six For Failure To Shave</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six Disneyland Hotel workers who rebelled
against the Magic Kingdom's ban on facial hair were suspended for
three days without pay and given an order to shave or be fired.
   The hotel's 1,600 workers recently came under the famed
amusement park's dress and grooming codes when their former boss,
the Wrather Corp., sold the property to the Walt Disney Co.
   The dress code, established in 1957, bans facial hair on men,
mandates short haircuts and bars women from wearing heavy makeup,
long fingernails or excessive jewelry.
   The six suspended Wednesday have until Monday to shave or lose
their jobs, said Disneyland spokesman Bob Roth.
   A dozen male employees have been issued warnings for facial
hair, and although half of those shaved, all 12 filed grievances
with their unions.
   Earlier Wednesday, the five unions representing hotel workers
united in opposition to the Disney dress code, but wouldn't say
whether they were willing to strike over it.
</TEXT>
