<HEAD>Blasts Rock Munitions Depot in Central India</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire in one of India's largest
munitions depots detonated artillery shells Thursday, forcing
evacuation of two villages and closing an airport.
   Shivraj Patal, minister of state for defense production, told
Parliament that the blaze, which began Wednesday in the central
Indian depot's underground sheds, was largely under control. But he
said sporadic explosions of ammunition continued.
   Army officials told the United News of India news agency that
the blasts in the two sheds could continue for up to 10 days. At
least 10,000 rounds reportedly were stored in the burning areas,
mainly for 105-mm artillery guns.
   Patal said the two villages were evacuated as a precaution after
the blasts in Madhya Pradesh state 155 miles east of Bhopal, the
state capital. Jabalpur's airport 28 miles away was also closed.
   Two depot workers suffered minor injuries in fighting the blaze,
Patal said. There was no word on its cause.
