<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ArmsTreaty 1stLd-Writethru a0425 03-24 0818</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arms Treaty, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0425,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pell Predicts Committee Action Early Next Week On INF</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 6 grafs new to update with vote; Picks up 2nd graf pvs,
I
would hope.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee today
rejected a move by Sen. Jesse Helms to require new intelligence
studies of what Helms says are Soviet missiles unaccounted for by
the U.S.-Soviet treaty on medium-range atomic weapons.
   The committee voted 15-2 against Helms' amendment to the treaty
which would have required President Reagan to certify the accuracy
of the Soviet claims that there are 650 SS-20 missiles. The
declared weapons will have to be destroyed after the treaty takes
effect.
   Helms, R-N.C., argued that up to 300 more SS-20s are ``hidden,''
and he cited Defense Intelligence Agency reports which he said
support his claim.
   But Sen. Daniel Evans, R-Wash., said, ``I don't believe
President Reagan would have signed this treaty'' if he believed the
Soviets had successfully hidden a large force of SS-20 missiles.
   The vote was the latest decision in which the panel decided by
large bipartisan majorities to reject attempts by Helms and Sen.
Larry Pressler, R-S.D., another conservative critic, to change the
treaty.
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the committee, said the
panel was headed toward overwhelming approval of the pact.
   ``I would hope _ and I think _ that we will continue to show
strong bipartisan support,'' said Pell after the panel voted by
lopsided margins Wednesday to reject amendments by Helms and
Pressler.
   Helms had originally proposed 36 amendments and Pressler offered
three more, despite appeals from the Reagan administration for the
Senate to approve the treaty without changes.
   After it became apparent he had few votes on his side, Helms
said he planned to drop most of his amendments.
   Pell announced that the committee will finish voting on all
amendments by Tuesday afternoon next week and will then decide on
the treaty itself.
   When the measure finally reaches the floor, overwhelming
approval is expected with no more than 10 to 12 of the 100 senators
expected to vote against it. Ratification requires a two-thirds
vote.
   The Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty, signed Dec. 8 by
President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, requires
the elimination within three years of all missiles with a range of
300 to 3,400 miles. It includes on-site inspection among its strict
verification provisions.
   Helms dropped many of his amendments after he came under fire
from fellow Republicans, some of whom claimed he was trying to
delay a final Senate vote until after the next summit meeting
between Reagan and Gorbachev.
   That meeting has now been set for May 29-June 2 in Moscow, the
White House announced Wednesday.
   Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., said: ``We're just in a delay, stall
situation which I find disagreeable. ... If you don't have the
votes and just try to overload it with amendments, that isn't
fair.''
   Meantime, Pell and other Democrats tried to work out some type
of compromise between Congress and the White House over the chief
remaining hurdle, a dispute about the legal power to interpret
treaties.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., said in a floor
speech that it will be necessary to add a reservation or an
understanding which spells out the Senate position.
   ``This matter is not going to be resolved, in my judgment, by
any exchange of letters, because a future administration can say,
`we don't agree with that interpretation at all,''' Byrd said.
   Reagan asserts that the executive branch can unilaterally change
the U.S. intepretation of a treaty, a view disputed by the Senate.
The fight arises from a difference in how to interpret the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty.
   As it worked through the treaty, the panel:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Voted down, 12-3, a Helms proposal to change the treaty and
allow the United States to deploy non-nuclear cruise missiles. The
treaty bans all cruise missiles, whether equipped with nuclear or
conventional warheads, because there is no effective way to verify
which warheads are on the missile.
   _Voted down, 12-2, a Helms amendment which would include the
Soviets' Scud B missile as one of the banned weapons. The missile
is not now banned because it has a shorter range than 300 miles,
but Helms claimed Scud B missiles sold by the Soviets to Iraq have
been fired at ranges which would fall within the INF ranges.
   _Rejected, 13-2, a Helms plan that would prohibit either side
from testing missiles in the INF range.
   _Defeated, 15-2, a Pressler amendment which would block the
treaty from taking effect until Reagan certifies that there is
parity in Europe between NATO and Warsaw Pact forces. The Soviets
have a large advantage in some categories of non-nuclear weapons
and Pressler and other treaty critics say the elimination of
medium-range atomic missiles will take away a major NATO deterrent
to a Soviet attack.
</TEXT>
