<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PuppyBurning     03-24 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Puppy Burning,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Student Says Dog Immolaton Threat Was A Prank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A philosophy student who outraged people
with his threat to publicly kill a puppy to demonstrate the
brutality of war said today the whole thing was a prank.
   ``It was a prankish threat to kill one mythical animal,'' said
David Read.
   But he said his threat to burn to death a 10-week-old dog at the
University of Wisconsin-Madison campus Monday served its purpose in
getting attention. The threat drew protest calls to the Dane County
Humane Society and local radio stations.
   ``People panicked to save the life of one mythical puppy while
thousands (of people) were dying'' elsewhere, Read said.
   The student said he opposed cruelty to animals and never
intended to carry out his threat, despite earlier claims he was
serious that prompted humane society officials and university
police to investigate.
   Police said Wednesday they would consider seeking an injunction
against Read's plan to kill the dog.
   Earlier, Read said burning the puppy would be ``an exhibition of
what suffering and cruelty is all about,'' he said. ``I think our
attitudes about war and human suffering are complacency and
numbness. This is one thing that will combat that numbness.''
   Read, 26, is chairman of the Nihilist Workers Party, a campus
organization the university said does not have its official
recognition.
   He said the group, organized two years ago, has about 12 active
members who advocate nihilism, a belief that existing social
institutions need destroying to make room for a new order.
   The group announced the puppy-burning plan Tuesday. Radio
stations, humane societies and police said Wednesday they were
flooded with telephone calls.
   Read said he anticipated the reaction. ``I'm quite pleased,'' he
said. ``I'm the most reviled character in town.''
   He said he had Nicaragua in mind when he conceived of the idea
of burning the dog to demonstrate suffering. He said people living
in the United States lead sheltered, comfortable lives and avoid
thinking about the horrors occurring in other nations.
   ``I want them to get down and wallow in the filth, which is
truth,'' he said.
   Shock is the best method of making people aware of ugliness, he
said, calling peaceful protest a waste of time.
   His organization has distributed obscene posters on the campus,
including one portraying Adolph Hitler pointing a gun and reading:
``I love you.''
</TEXT>
