<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Volcker-Candidates     03-24 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Volcker-Candidates,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Avoid ``Washington Bashing,'' Volcker Tells Candidates</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Federal Reserve Board Chairman Paul
Volcker cautioned presidential candidates on Thursday to avoid
``Washington bashing'' in their campaigning,
   Volcker spoke to a House civil service subcommittee as chairman
of the National Commission on the Public Service. His 37-member
panel is working on recommendations for making civil service more
attractive to talented individuals.
   While the presidential candidates don't seem to be ``running
against Washington'' this year, Volcker hinted he's ready with a
strong lecture for anyone who tries such an approach.
   ``We're never very far from the telephone,'' Volcker said. ``We
will try to keep after those candidates. ... We will urge them to
stay on the high road.''
   He suggested attacks by candidates on Washington institutions
have hurt the image of public service. Volcker called it ``the
Washington bashing syndrome.''
   ``Too many of the best at the upper ranks have been leaving
government, with not enough of quality being recruited at the entry
level,'' said Volcker, who retired from government service last
summer.
   Volcker, who worked for the governmment most of his life,
including eight years as head of the nation's central bank,
recently became a professor at Princeton University and chairman of
a small New York investment firm.
   Rep. Patricia Shroeder, D-Colo., chairwoman of the subcommittee,
told Volcker: ``Hopefully, we can head off a race in which everyone
sees how bad a thing they can say about public service.''
   ``The last two presidents have gratuitously slandered the
bureaucracy,'' said Ms. Schroeder, who was mentioned as a possible
1988 presidential contender herself before she withdrew from
consideration.
   Norman Ornstein, a political analyst with the American
Enterprise Institute who serves with Volcker on the commission,
told the subcommittee that ``we've been seeing a change'' toward
the positive in public attitudes toward government service.
   ``Part of this is the ironic success President Reagan has had in
getting people to feel better about the government. It's ironic
because I don't think he meant it that way. He had two campaigns
against Washington.''
   ``No candidates this time have picked up on the theme of bashing
government and bashing bureaucrats,'' Ornstein added. ``There is a
good climate to create a different set of attitudes.''
   Members of the commission also include former President Gerald
Ford and former Vice President Walter Mondale.
</TEXT>
