<HEAD>Ferry Workers Protest in Channel-blocking Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 350 government workers demonstrated Thursday
in a week-old strike that has virtually halted ferry service across
the English Channel.
   A delegation of protesters met with Pierre-Olivier Drege, chief
of staff for the Secretary of State for Maritime Affairs, where the
protest was held.
   Government officials refused to comment afterward, saying the
conflict must be settled by the sailors' employer, the state-run
railroad.
   Railroad officials have said they will not negotiate with the
strikers until they end their occupation of the ferry Nord-Pas de
Calais.
   The strikers are protesting what they say is a threatened
privatization of their company and loss of purchasing power. On the
other side of the Channel, about 2,200 employees of P and O
European Ferries have been striking for seven weeks.
   Thursday's demonstrators arrived in buses from the French port
cities of Boulogne, Calais, Dieppe and Dunkirk. They represented
about a third of the 990 officers and sailors working on ferries
for the railroads' maritime arm.
   Traffic remained backed up at Channel ports on the French side
Thursday, where only one ferry _ with a British crew _ was in
operation between Calais and the British port of Dover.
