<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-Contra-Christic     03-24 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra-Christic,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial Of Florida Lawsuit May Be Postponed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal judge in the Iran-Contra case
indicated Thursday that trial of a Florida lawsuit that accuses
former government officials of collaborating with Colombian drug
dealers may be postponed.
   The civil lawsuit is set for trial June 26. The 29 defendants in
the case include Richard V. Secord and Albert Hakim, two
businessmen who have been charged with conpiracy and theft in the
Iran-Contra case.
   Secord and Hakim, along with Oliver L. North and John M.
Poindexter, were arraigned before Judge Gerhard Gesell Thursday in
U.S. District Court.
   During the proceedings, Secord's lawyer, Thomas Green, told
Gesell about a potential conflict in scheduling between the
Iran-Contra case and the case in Miami's federal court.
   ``It will not go forward,'' Gesell said. ``A criminal case takes
precedence. This case has got to take priority.''
   Gesell said: ``I've cancelled every case I have and I've
cancelled my vacation.''
   Secord and Hakim are accused of helping North and Poindexter,
two former White House aides, secretly sell weapons to Iran and
divert the profits to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
   The Florida lawsuit was filed by Martha Honey and Tony Avirgan,
two freelance reporters based in Costa Rica. They are represented
by The Christic Institute, a liberal policy group.
   The lawsuit accuses the defendants of drug-trafficking,
gun-running and plotting assassinations. The defendants have denied
the charges.
</TEXT>
