<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Locusts     03-24 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Locusts,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Countries Coordinate War Against `Tidal Wave' of Locusts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billions of locusts are moving across
North Africa in the worst plague since 1954, blotting out the sun
and settling on the land like a black, ravenous carpet to strip it
clean of vegetation.
   Algeria, Morocco and Tunisia have put aside political
differences to fight the locusts, with help from the United States,
Western Europe and the Soviet Union, but a U.N. official said
Thursday it may not be possible to save the food supply.
   As many as 250,000 of the insects settle on each acre whent the
horde alights. They devour 100,000 tons of crops and other
vegetation at each stop, according to the Food and Agriculture
Organization, a U.N. agency based in Rome.
   Wind currents pushed the insects into northeastern Africa from
their breeding grounds, The FAO said. They fly in waves of up to 50
million per square kilometer over 400 square kilometers, which
means as many as 20 billion covering an area of 160 square miles.
   ``We are facing a very dangerous situation, which may affect
North Africa's food production for years to come,'' said Lukas
Brader, director of FAO's Emergency Center for Locust Operations.
``We are not optimistic that the situation can be effectively
controlled.''
   He said the current infestation is worse than the 1950s plague,
which lasted more than 10 years. Breeding has been aided by
abundant rains and heat in the area, Brader said.
   Edouard Saouma, director-general of the FAO, said in a
statement: ``We are in a state of general alert. Swift and decisive
action is needed to avoid a major regional food crisis later this
year.''
   Brader said $30 million had been donated by the United States,
Western Europe, the Soviet Union and others to finance the spraying
of pesticide on infested areas. He said at least $150 million will
be needed to fight the plague, which he said may peak in late
summmer.
   Algeria has sprayed more than 494,000 acres of land and Morocco
has been treating about 62,000 acres a day. No figures were
available for Tunisia.
   Published reports in Algiers say more than 40 aircraft have been
provided by Libya, the Soviet Union, France and Spain to spray crop
and pasture land threatened by locusts.
   Spraying has been hampered by inadequate and outdated pesticide
and equipment, the presence of nomads in some infested regions and
the difficulty of detecting locusts in areas of sand, rock and
scrubland, officials said.
   No estimate was available of the total damage to crops.
   Specialists say the locusts originated near the Red Sea,
invading Sudan and Chad and then swarming through the Sahel
countries below the Sahara Desert before moving north ``in a tidal
wave.'' Libya and Mauritania also are threatened.
   To coordinate logistics the Algerian agriculture minister,
Noureddine Keddara, visited Tunisia on Wednesday and Driss Basri,
Morocco's interior and information minister, was in Algiers.
   Until about two weeks ago, a long-standing territorial dispute
over the Western Sahara had stymied the exchange of information
between Morocco and Algeria about the common danger.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
