<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MideastStudy     03-24 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mideast Study,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Experts Urge Next Administration To Put Mideast Peace on Front
Burner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A panel of Mideast experts on Thursday urged
the next U.S. administration to place Mideast peace talks high on
its foreign policy agenda and to include negotiators approved by
the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   ``A prolonged impasse in the peace process could endanger
American national interests,'' the panel of 19 academicians and
former State Department officials said in a report issued by the
Brookings Institution, which sponsored the study.
   ``We would like to see a steady, high-level commitment of
American resources to the Arab-Israeli peace process,'' the report
said.
   Samuel Lewis, who served as U.S. ambassador to Israel from 1978
to 1985, said the panel ``has a very strong sense that it's going
to take a protracted investment by senior levels to achieve even
partial success.''
   Speaking at a news conference, Lewis said the Mideast peace plan
offered in 1982 by President Reagan lacked sufficient preparation,
while the one currently being proposed by Secretary of State George
P. Shultz may be the victim of bad timing.
   Any future U.S. plan must be presented at a time when both Arabs
and Israelis are ready for peace talks, he said.
   The Palestinians may be too ``eupohoric'' over their success in
the 3{-month uprising against the Israeli occupation of the West
Bank and Gaza Strip to be ready for the compromises each side must
make in negotiations, Lewis said.
   William Quandt, a senior research fellow at Brookings and the
project's coordinator, said the Mideast peace issue has not been
high on the U.S.-Soviet agenda so far. It should be explored in
that framework further to see if it can yield some solutions, he
added.
   The report's authors agreed that Israeli-Arab peace talks should
be conducted within an international framework, although such a
forum would not be empowered to impose solutions. The Shultz plan
contains a similar proviso.
   ``Palestinians should be represented in any negotiations with
Israel by spokesmen of their own choosing, whether in a joint
Jordanian-Palestinian delegation or in some other configuration,''
the report said.
   The Shultz plan envisions Palestinian representation as part of
a Jordanian delegation in peace talks. ``The tone, though, seems to
be that Jordan can choose the Palestinians,'' Quandt said.
   ``Palestinians are unlikely to come forward to negotiate with
Israel without having the implicit endorsement of the Palestine
Liberation Organization,'' the report said. Israel and the United
States refuse to negotiate with the PLO directly.
   Quandt said panel members differed on whether the PLO should be
included in negotiations, and also could not agree on whether
Palestinians should be given an independent state. Some argued that
inclusion of the PLO and the establishment of a Palestinian state
would be ``irritants'' that Israel would reject, he said.
   The experts believe substantial preparation is needed to get the
parties ``to be willing to make hard choices'' before bringing them
to the negotiating table, Quandt said.
   Shultz and other officials have conducted preparatory talks with
Israeli and Arab leaders since January, but the United States is
pressing for negotiations to begin by May 1.
</TEXT>
