<1ST_LINE>r i AM-MoneySpill     03-24 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Spill,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drivers Start Returning Cash Spilled from Armored Truck</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of honest citizens showed up at police
stations across the city Thursday to return thousands of dollars in
cash that fell out of an armored truck, police said.
   ``We have a lot of very honest people here,'' said Inspector Jim
Shaw.
   On Wednesday night, however, money-grabbing chaos erupted on
Toronto's Gardiner Expressway after the rear door of the armored
truck flew open and spewed a blizzard of bills that blew onto
windshields and covered the highway.
   Drivers stopped their cars in the middle of the road in the rush
for cash, and traffic was tied up for miles.
   A guard in the Loomis Armored Car Service truck eventually had
to pull his gun to halt the free-for-all.
   Two bags that each contained $75,000 _ worth about $60,000 U.S.
_ were scooped up by drivers who threw the booty into their cars
and sped away and have not been returned, Shaw said.
   A third bag holding the same amount broke open, spreading the
cash in the air.
   Shaw said auditors were counting up how much was returned. Under
Canadian law, the cash belongs to Loomis and not whoever finds it.
   One cab driver was charged with theft for grabbing some of the
money.
</TEXT>
