<1ST_LINE>r i AM-LiteraryPrize     03-24 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Literary Prize,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contest Jurors Stymied in Picking Best Novel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors couldn't decide on the best English-language
novel this year, so the $50,000 prize in the Ritz Paris Hemingway
literary contest will go to charity, it was announced Thursday.
   The three nominees for this year's annual prize were the South
African writer Nadine Gordimer for ``A Sport of Nature,'' American
novelist Toni Morrison for ``Beloved,'' and ``In the Skin of a
Lion,'' by Canadian writer Michael Ondaatje.
   ``To choose the best novel of the year is always a difficult
task,'' said Pierre Salinger, the ABC News journalist who served as
jury president. ``This year, three excellent authors of great
reputation were nominated. But none of the works received a
majority of the votes from the 10 jurors.''
   The contest's rules thus call for the money to go to charity.
Half was donated to the Georges Pompidou Foundation, which helps
the elderly. The other half went to the Franco-American Volunteer
Association, which helps handicapped children get involved in
sports.
   The first Ritz Paris Hemingway award was given in 1985 to
Peruvian writer Mario Vargas Llosa. The other winners were
Marguerite Duras of France and Peter Taylor of the United States.
</TEXT>
