<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson-Young     03-24 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Young,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Detroit's Black Mayor Tones Down Criticism of Jackson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Detroit Mayor Coleman Young, long at political
odds with Jesse Jackson, is striking a more conciliatory tone
toward the Democratic presidential candidate this year.
   ``I'd be a fool not to recognize the massive contribution Jesse
has made to the electoral process, and putting some color _ finally
_ in the rainbow,'' Young said. ``Obviously ... that's not enough
to win, but it's an important beginning.''
   Young still argues that Jackson's candidacy represents wasted
votes, political polarization and help for the Republicans. But he
also credits Jackson for reaching some whites with his more
mainstream Democratic candidacy this year, and expressing surprise
at his degree of support from blacks.
   Young is supporting Jackson's chief rival Michael Dukakis in
Michigan's statewide caucuses Saturday. He says his is not so much
an endorsement as a statement of whom he supports _ a distinction
Young says means the political organization that has served him for
15 years as mayor of Detroit is free to do as it wishes.
   ``Jesse has a tremendous emotional appeal to the black community
in this city,'' Young said in an interview Wednesday in his office
with several out-of-town reporters. ``I think that the chief
objective ... is to win the White House.''
   Dukakis is airing radio ads featuring Young's support, targeted
at black audiences in Detroit. He is bidding to win delegates in
the city's two largely black congressional districts, the 1st and
13th, which requires winning at least 15 percent of the vote in
those areas.
   Young maintained that he has ``truly'' released his organization
to go as it pleases and says he's not asked key supporters to
report back on whether they are siding with Dukakis, Jackson or
another candidate.
   Some politicians aren't so sure, however. State House Speaker
Gary Owen of Ypsilanti, backing Albert Gore Jr., said he understood
Young was ``coming down hard'' on his supporters to produce for
Dukakis, particularly in those key congressional districts.
   In announcing his support for Dukakis a week and a half ago,
Young said, ``Anybody who respects my opinion will do likewise.''
And Young's top political aide, Larry L. Simmons Sr., said last
week that Young would ask his staff members to inform him of their
actions in the presidential campaign.
   Young, who has seen his city's optimism decline with the fall in
federal urban aid under the Reagan administration, said a
Democratic victory in November is his paramount concern and his
reason for supporting the Massachusetts governor.
   Dukakis, he said, has the best chance to win. Jackson, he said,
``can't win.''
   Young finds fault with Jackson's lack of government experience,
but said no black candidate could be elected this year or in the
immediate future because of white resistance.
   ``I think it's rooted in race _ I don't have to look anywhere
else,'' Young said.
   Even if he should win Michigan's caucuses, Young said, Jackson
would achieve at best a plurality of the Democratic vote, not a
majority.
   ``The great majority of the black votes will follow Jesse off to
one side, whereas the great majority of the white vote will be
split among the other candidates,'' Young said. ``That is the
essense of polarization.
   ``I think the overall thrust of Jackson's campaign might very
well be to help the Republicans,'' he said.
   Young endorsed Walter Mondale in 1984 over Jackson, and he has
remained apart from Jackson this year even as some other black
leaders who were cool toward Jackson four years ago have been won
over. While there may be political risks for himself, Young said he
thinks voters' attitudes toward him won't be affected.
   ``I'm trying to preserve the unity _ I do not want to be
responsible for creating any disunity in the black community,''
Young said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
