<DOCNO> AP880324-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1317EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Nicaragua 2ndLd-Writethru a0633 03-24 0871</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Nicaragua, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0633,870</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz today
called the Nicaraguan cease-fire agreement ``an important step
forward'' and said there is ``no excuse'' for any additional Soviet
bloc weapons deliveries to the Sandinista government.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater reacted with cautious
optimism to the agreement while House Speaker Jim Wright hailed it
as ``a new chapter in the unhappy history of that war-torn
country.''
   Shultz urged Congress to immediately approve additional
humanitarian aid to the Contra rebels while they negotiate terms
for a definitive cease-fire with the Sandinista government.
   He said the agreement would not have been possible without years
of sacrifice by the rebels.
   ``Their strength and perseverance have created this opportunity
for peace and freedom,'' Shultz said. ``We consider this agreement
to be an important step forward.''
   Under questioning, Shultz said he feels the agreement may be a
ploy on the part of the Sandinistas to disarm the Contras. He said
that if the Sandinistas don't carry out their promises under the
agreement, the United States would have to reevaluate its policies.
   Both the White House and Wright promised to seek quick action on
a humanitarian aid package for the Contra rebels.
   ``We're glad that it occurred,'' the Fitzwater said, when asked
whether the administration was embracing the plan.
   ``There is a lot of room for encouragement here, yes, but
there's also a lot of room for skepticism, and I'm trying to
balance those two off,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``We're beginning the process. We need to watch it. We've seen
processes like this start before and fail,'' he said. ``This seems
like a more concrete step, and there certainly reason to be
hopeful. But I do not want to play down the skepticism side of it
either because we are skeptical.''
   Wright said he would meet Monday with House Republicans and
representatives of the White House to begin drafting a bill to send
food, clothing, shelter and medicine to the rebels before Easter.
   Fitzwater said the White House, too, hopes an aid package can be
passed ``on a bipartisan basis'' before the recess.
   Wright said the precise form of the aid package remained to be
worked out, but that it would have to conform to the cease-fire
agreement announced Wednesday night in Sapoa, Nicaragua, after
three days of talks.
   That agreement calls for ``exclusively humanitarian aid'' to be
channeled through a neutral, international relief organization.
   Wright refused to speculate on whether there would be GOP
demands to include in the package some standby procedure for
authorizing new military aid for the rebels should the peace
process become derailed.
   Republicans, contending Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega
cannot be trusted to fulfill his promises without such a threat,
have insisted on such a provision in previous debate on the issue.
   ``I think it would be counterproductive to talk about it,''
Wright told reporters. ``We don't want to rekindle the war.''
   He said he envisioned quick action on ``some minimal something
that both sides (Democrats and Republicans) can wholeheartedly
embrace.''
   ``For heaven's sake, if the Nicaraguans, who have been shooting
at each other, can agree, then surely Republicans and Democrats can
agree,'' he said.
   Wright began discussing ideas for an aid package on Wednesday in
conversations with House Minority Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill., and
White House Chief of Staff Howard Baker. But he said no deals had
been made.
   ``The cease-fire talks have made it possible, by entering into
an entirely new era, to bury our hatchets in the same trenches
where they're burying their machetes in Central America,'' Wright
said.
   The aid bill likely would be similar to a $30 million package
rejected by a narrow margin on March 3, although House Majority
Leader Thomas Foley, D-Wash., said it was unclear whether the
dollar amount would be the same.
   The rebels' last U.S. aid expired on Feb. 29.
   Earlier, interviewed on CBS television, Wright said Nicaragua is
wracked by poverty and needs to begin diverting its slender
resources to educate, feed, and clothe its people.
   ``Both sides were war-weary but were ready if they could to find
an accommodation to guarantee the integration back into their
society of these people who have been estranged from it,'' he said.
   Problems remain, Wright said, but ``there is a disposition on
both parts to enter into a more peaceful society and a more
democratic society in which freedom of the press and of expression
will be guaranteed and the rights of those who formerly made war
against that government will be fully protected.''
   ``Those of us in our Congress are anxious to do whatever we can
to encourage the fulfilment of the democratization of that
country,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, Rep. Edward Feighan, D-Ohio, said three officials
from the General Accounting Office were leaving for Honduras today
to track the disposition of small arms, ammunition, jeeps and other
materials that were brought to Honduras by U.S. troops sent last
week to respond to a Sandinista incursion.
   ``My concern is that the deployment of American troops and
weapons to Honduras could in fact be another diversion of arms to
the Contras,'' said Feighan, who requested the GAO investigation.
</TEXT>
