<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HeadRemoved     03-24 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Head Removed,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Arrested at Cryonics Lab Sue County</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIVERSIDE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six members of a laboratory group who
were detained during a search for a missing frozen head have filed
false arrest claims with the county totaling $225,000.
   The six claims, filed individually at various times this month,
stem from the December beheading of 83-year-old Dora Kent so her
head could be frozen to preserve it for theoretical revival using
as-yet undiscovered medical techniques.
   The six members of the Alcor Life Extension Foundation were
detained by police Jan. 7 during a search of the premises. They
were questioned at the police department then released.
   All six say they were arrested for investigation of obstruction
of justice.
   Filing a claim is a preliminary step toward suing. Riverside
County has the option of settling the claims, or rejecting them
after they are reviewed by claims adjustors.
   In one claim, five Alcor members contend they ``suffered
emotional stress arising from the purposeful, wrongful conduct of
the coroner's investigators.'' They seek damages totaling $125,000.
The sixth person filed a separate claim for $100,000.
   During two searches at the lab, authorities found Mrs. Kent's
hands and some equipment allegedly stolen from the University of
California, Los Angeles. Her head never was found.
   Last month, the coroner's office ruled the woman's death a
homicide, finding she had been killed by a lethal dose of
barbiturates. Alcor officials contend the woman was dead when they
began their procedure.
   The case was sent to the district attorney's office, but
Prosecutor Jay Thompson Hanks said Thursday no decision regarding
charges has been made.
</TEXT>
