<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1331EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Germany 1stLd-Writethru a0479 03-24 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Germany, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0479,450</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with Vogel quotes.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German opposition leader Hans-Jochen
Vogel today praised President Reagan's arms-control advances and
said the atmosphere had greatly improved since their last meeting
five years ago.
   Vogel, chairman of the Social Democratic Party, told reporters
after a 20-minute meeting with Reagan at the White House that he
and the president had discussed arms control, the economy and human
rights.
   ``We had a very friendly and constructive conversation with the
president,'' he said. ``I ... said, remembering five years back, we
are very impressed especially by the INF (Intermediate Nuclear
Forces) treaty, by the cooperation which developed with the Soviet
Union.''
   Vogel said he told Reagan he hoped he and Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev also would be able to agree soon on reducing long-range
nuclear forces.
   He said the president ``seemed to be satisfied about the work,
what has been done in the last two or three days. They worked very
hard, they worked very (thoroughly) through the details.''
   He was referring to a visit by Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze, who has been meeting with Secretary of State George
Shultz and Reagan in Washington this week.
   ``Remembering my visit five years ago, it is a remarkable
change. It was a relaxed conversation. There are still some points
of different views and different opinions, but there are points
which we join and which we agree (on).''
   ``In '83 we were in the middle of the argument about the
deployment of Pershing II and there have been some other fields of
different opinions. Many of them are gone. The president making the
INF treaty and preparing START is a president more close to us than
some remarks and some positions of '81 or '82 or '83,'' Vogel said.
   The Social Democrats were part of the widespread opposition to
NAT0's deployment of the U.S. medium-range Pershing II and cruise
missiles in Europe to counter Soviet SS-20 missiles aimed at
Western Europe. The INF treaty would eliminate both the U.S. and
Soviet land-based medium-range missiles.
   Vogel said Reagan listened but didn't comment when he told him
that West German Social Democrats, like the coalition government,
oppose modernization of short-range nuclear weapons in Europe. He
said he made clear that the Social Democrats go further than the
government in urging negotiations to eliminate the weapons.
   ``I think he was not surprised,'' Vogel said.
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, of the ruling Christian
Democrats, advocates a reduction in the number of the missiles but
not their elimination.
   The United States, Britain and France favor the modernization of
the short-range weapons as part of NATO's nuclear deterrent against
a Soviet bloc attack on Western Europe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
