<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Smoking     03-24 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Smoking,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-smoking Bill Introduced in Parliament</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill introduced in Parliament on Thursday would
allow Britons to demand to be segregated from smokers at work.
   The measure lacks the support of the Conservative government of
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and was given little chance of
passage, but it reflected a growing anti-smoking campaign.
   ``Smoking must now be treated like any other industrial heath
hazard,'' said George Foulkes of the opposition Labor Party, who
introduced the Health and Safety at Work Bill in the House of
Commons.
   He said there was ``overwhelming'' public support to ban smoking
at work except in designated areas.
   The bill would not require companies to set up non-smoking areas
in offices, but it would forbid them from firing or disciplining
any worker who refused to work alongside a smoker.
   Smokers are rarely segregated in British restaurants and other
public places, although smoking has been banned in London subways
and the number of British Rail cars where smoking is permitted has
been reduced from 25 percent to 20 percent.
   The Independent newspaper said a private survey of 1,000
companies found that almost half had either a voluntary or formal
agreement on no-smoking areas.
   In a report released Wednesday, the Independent Scientific
Committee on Smoking and Health said passive smoking, or
non-smokers' exposure to smoke, may cause several hundred lung
cancer deaths a year. It said passive smoking increases the risk of
lung cancer by 10 to 30 percent.
   In government reaction to the report, Junior Health minister
Edwina Currie said, ``The government accepts the thrust of the
report, which reflects established policies of voluntary
arrangements.''
   The state-funded Health Education Authority launched a $457,000
advertising campaign Thursday with full-page advertisements in
major newspapers urging non-smokers to stand up for their rights.
   The ads say, ``If you're a non-smoker who works with smokers,
you probably suffer in silence. Yet everybody has the right to a
healthy working environment.''
</TEXT>
