<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WellRescue-Movie     03-24 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Well Rescue-Movie,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Rival Associations Fighting Over Movie Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDLAND, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For 58 hours after Jessica McClure tumbled
into an abandoned well, hundreds of rescuers worked together to
free her. But now they are divided over TV movie rights and have
formed two rival groups.
   Jessica, now almost 2 years old, was trapped 22 feet down an
abandoned well after she fell in Oct. 14 and rescued after teams
bored through rock to reach her. Rescuers dug a parallel shaft and
then a tunnel into the well near the spot where Jessica was stuck.
   One of the associations formed over a TV movie is committed to
producer Larry Spivey, president of Highland Communications Group
Inc. The group's 32 members, most of them rescue volunteers, have
been asking all participants to join them.
   The group, called the Jessica McClure Rescuers' Association, is
headed by Kragg Robinson, chief of Robinson Rathole Inc. of
Albuquerque, N.M.
   Robinson diverted a rathole rig from a nearby Texas Department
of Highways and Public Transportation project to dig much of the
parallel shaft.
   Robinson's mother, Yvonne, said today that no plans have yet
been announced by the group.
   ``I don't think they have accepted a proposal,'' said Mrs.
Robinson.
   The second group, the McClure Rescue Association, is comprised
of municipal workers, including Police Chief Richard Czech, Fire
Chief James Roberts and Paramedic Robert O'Donnell, who plucked the
child from the well and brought her to the surface.
   Some rescuers have decided to stay neutral.
   ``I personally don't feel that I should join any association
until a uniform group is together,'' said Bruce Peeler. ``And that
means all people involved, whether they are with the police
department, the fire department or the lady who made hamburgers at
three in the morning.''
   Peeler is president of Air Master Equipment Corp., a Midland
company that donated jackhammers and other pneumatic equipment for
the rescue.
   He and another neutral participant, Charles Boler, president of
Boler Construction of Midland, said they have attended the
volunteers' weekly meetings for about six weeks.
   Attempts to bring the two groups together have been frustrating,
they said.
   The municipal workers' group has yet to commit its rights either
but interviewed six producers and narrowed its preference down to
one, said attorney Martin Allday of Midland.
   The girl's parents, Chip and Cissy McClure, have said they are
not interested in exploiting Jessica's story for profit but did not
want to stand in the way of other plans.
</TEXT>
