<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MosaicControversy     03-24 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mosaic Controversy,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Sues To Block Changes On Controversial Mosaic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDWARDSVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of a mosaic designer has gone
to court to try to prevent the city from altering the art work's
portrayal of a smiling black man celebrating his freedom from
slavery.
   Edward A. Kane Jr. filed suit this week seeking a preliminary
injunction barring the city from changing the mosaic outside City
Hall ``because of the love I have for my father's memory,'' he said
Wednesday.
   ``I don't want to see the change made because in my opinion you
set a precedent to change paintings, books,'' Kane said. ``It
offends me. If you don't like the smile on the Mona Lisa, are you
going to change it?''
   A hearing was set for Friday in Madison County Circuit Court.
   In his lawsuit, Kane said alterations to his late father's
``work of art'' would violate constitutional rights to free speech
and artistic expression.
   The 10- by 40-foot mosaic shows white settlers in covered wagons
and a freed slave, with a broken rope hanging from his wrists,
celebrating his freedom.
   Complaints about the portrayal began in 1986. Opponents contend
it was demeaning to blacks because it does not show them making any
contribution to the city.
   In October, City Council agreed to remove the man's smile, add
other facial features and replace the ropes with a hoe. Groups
favoring the change said they would pay for alterations.
   Tim Early, chairman of the city's Human Rights Commission and a
supporter of the change, said work would begin as weather allowed.
   Early also said the mosaic, constructed in the mid-1960s, was
not the work of Edward Kane Sr. alone but had been designed by a
committee. ``I'm sure his father assisted in terms of artistic
direction. But to give him full credit is just wrong,'' Early said.
</TEXT>
