<2ND_LINE>AM-Ortega Baptism,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>82nd Airborne Delays Christening of Nicaraguan Leader's Daughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUTCHER, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A priest who was invited to baptize
Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega's seventh child says the
ceremony was delayed when 3,200 U.S. soldiers were airlifted to
Honduras.
   ``They went into a state of alert and the baptism was called
off,'' the Rev. Ray Bourgeois said here Wednesday.
   He said he had given up was preparing to leave Managua on Friday
when he got a call from Foreign Minister Miguel D'Escoto, a fellow
Maryknoll priest, who said the ceremony was on.
   ``We drove to the president's house. It was comfortable, but no
mansion. Kids were running around all over the place. His mother
Lydia was there, his wife, Rosario, and the godparents,'' Bourgeois
said.
   Ortega was watching the CBS Evening News via satellite.
   After some small talk, everyone moved outside to the patio where
Camila, Ortega's first daughter, was baptized.
   ``I asked him (Ortega) to share one of the readings about the
greatest commandment, to love God and your neighbor as yourself,''
Bourgeois said.
   Bourgeois, 48, said Ortega extended the invitation to Managua in
December, about a month after they met at an Organization of
American States meeting in Washington.
   He said Ortega wanted to meet him because Bourgeois had recently
been released from a prison term for trespassing on government
property during a protest against the Contra rebels.
   ``The baptism was no different from the hundreds of others I've
done,'' Bourgeois said. ``It was a family affair. A religious
event, not a political event.''
