<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CholesterolScreening     03-24 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cholesterol Screening,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Program of Cholesterol Testing Set for May 4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of hospitals will offer free blood
cholesterol testing May 4 in the first national screening for the
fatty substance that is a leading contributor to heart disease and
strokes.
   The program, organized by the Voluntary Hospitals of America,
was outlined Thursday at a news confrence. Officials said they were
announcing the national program well in advance to give people
plenty of time to learn where they can go for testing.
   About 400 not-for-profit hospitals that are members of the
association have agreed to participate, and organizers estimate
400,000 Americans will get the test.
   While most will do the test free, a few will charge $3.
   A public service television spot promoting the program, called
``CountDown USA,'' will begin airing next week.
   It includes a toll-free telephone number _ 800-634-9541 _ for
people to call weekdays from 9 a.m. to 6 p.m. (EST) to find out
which hospitals in their areas will offer the testing.
   ``We want every American adult to know his or her cholesterol
level and if it's high, do something about it,'' said Dr. DeWitt S.
Goodman, professor of medicine at the Columbia University College
of Physicians and Surgeons and a member of the staff at New York
City's Presbyterian Hospital.
   Blood cholesterol levels below 200 milligrams are associated
with a low level of coronary heart disease. Levels over 240
milligrams double the risk. Twenty percent to 25 percent of
Americans have cholesterol levels in this range, the American Heart
Association says.
   Goodman, who heads the hospital organization's screening effort,
said one valuable bit of information researchers hope to gain is
insight into which people respond. ``We really don't know who will
come to be screened,'' he said.
   Don L. Arnwine, chairman of the Voluntary Hospitals of America,
acknowledged that the estimate that 400,000 people will be tested
is little more than a guess.
   ``If 4 million show up, it may be the third or fourth day before
we can get to everyone, but we will try to serve them,'' Arnwine
said.
   The screening program was developed in association with the
National Heart, Lung and Blood Institute to assure uniformity from
city to city.
</TEXT>
