<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CancerSummit     03-24 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cancer Summit,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Soviet Doctors to Share Cancer Lessons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER GILLOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Industrialist Armand Hammer says eight Soviet
and American medical specialists will discuss the latest treatment
for cancer during a fund-raising program to be broadcast in both
nations, Western Europe and the Middle East.
   The satellite television conference is an outgrowth of the 1986
summit conference between President Reagan and Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev and is part of an effort to raise $1 billion a
year for cancer research in the United States.
   Hammer, chairman of Occidental Petroleum Corp. and head of the
President's Cancer Panel, recently helped establish the non-profit
Stop Cancer Foundation whose goal is to raise $500 million a year
for cancer research.
   ``I know many people have said they hope to find a cure for
cancer,'' Hammer said during an interview Wednesday.
   ``But this time I believe we are truly on the verge of
conquering it. We just need more money.''
   Hammer, 89, said he believes a cure can be found within 10
years, adding, ``I hope to celebrate my 100th birthday ... knowing
I have achieved the last remaining mission in my life by ridding
the world of this scourge.''
   The two-hour teleconference on Tuesday will link cancer
specialists in Washington and Moscow. About half of the conference
will be composed of film clips of medical researchers and cancer
patients plus taped comments by Reagan, Gorbachev and other
political figures.
   The full conference will be broadcast to more than 1,250
hospitals in the United States for the benefit of doctors,
researchers and staff members.
   It also will be beamed to 43 cities in countries throughout
Europe and the Mideast by the U.S. Information Agency, and will be
broadcast in a shortened, one-hour form on Soviet television, which
reaches 150 million people.
   U.S. doctors participating in the conference will be Vincent T.
Devita Jr., director of the National Cancer Instititute; Steven A.
Rosenberg, chief of surgery for the NCI; Robert Gale, director of
the UCLA bone-marrow transplant unit, who treated victims of the
1986 Chernobyl nuclear plant disaster in the Soviet Union; and
Richard J. Steckel, director of the Jonsson Comprehensive Cancer
Center at UCLA.
   Hammer said Wednesday that he and nine wealthy acquaintances
agreed to donate $100,000 each to the Stop Cancer Foundation as
``seed money.''
</TEXT>
