<2ND_LINE>AM-Riot Reunion,0210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>'68 Columbia University Riot Leaders to Meet Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the leaders of violent student
demonstrations at Columbia University will gather at the campus for
a 20th anniversary reunion next month, university officials said.
   Among those expected to attend are Mark Rudd, a former leader of
the Students for Democratic Society who later became a member of
the radical Weather Underground, surrendering to police in 1978 for
his role in Chicago demonstrations in the summer of 1968. He is now
a teacher in Arizona.
   Fred Knubel, the university spokesman, said the April 22-23
reunion was not an official function, but was being organized by
the school's Episcopal chaplain, the Rev. William Starr.
   Knubel said Wednesday that the university is ``a changed place''
from the days when 700 students were arrested on campus after they
took several university officials hostage and seized some campus
buildings.
   Richard and Andrea Egan, who got married at a sit-in at one
university building, have confirmed they will attend the reunion,
he said.
   The protest was sparked by university plans to build a gym in
nearby Morningside Park and grew into a general demonstration
against the Vietnam War and government contracts for scientific
research.
