<1ST_LINE>u a PM-AlexanderSentencing 1stLd-Writethru a0675 03-24 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Alexander Sentencing, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0675,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Syracuse Mayor Lee Alexander Sentenced To 10 Years In
Prison</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to add Alexander once president of the U.S.
Conference of Mayors. SUBS 8th graf, `Alexander would ...,' to add
surrender date and Alexander to be sent to medium-security federal
prison.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM KATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Mayor Lee Alexander was sentenced
to 10 years in prison today for extorting $1.5 million in kickbacks
from businessmen during his years as the city's top elected
official.
   Alexander, 60, pleaded guilty Jan. 6 to charges of racketeering,
conspiracy to obstruct a government investigation and tax evasion
in connection with what federal prosecutors called one of the
biggest public corruption cases ever uncovered in New York state.
   At his sentencing, Alexander, who once served as president of
the U.S. Conference of Mayors, also was ordered by U.S. District
Judge Thomas J. McAvoy to pay $100,000 in restitution to the City
of Syracuse in lieu of a $100,000 fine recommended by federal
prosecutors.
   ``I've brought great pain to my loved ones and the people of my
city and stand here now ready for my punishment,'' Alexander said
before sentence was pronounced.
   Alexander said his demise occurred when an effort to build a
political war chest was ``allowed to grow into a cancer.''
   Before Alexander's 10-minute speech to the judge, his attorney,
Harold Boreanaz, made an impassioned plea for leniency.
   Boreanaz rebutted statements made by prosecutors that Alexander
had not fully cooperated with the government's efforts to identify
and turn over his assets.
   Alexander would be eligible for parole after serving a third of
his sentence. U.S. Attorney Frederick Scullin said Alexander must
surrender by April 14 and would serve his sentence at a
medium-security federal prison that has yet to be determined.
   The former mayor faced nearly seven centuries in prison after
being named in a 40-count federal grand jury indictment that
accused him of 65 separate acts of extortion.
   Alexander earlier surrendered to the government more than $1.4
million in assets the government has linked with the
extortion-kickback scheme he admitted running during his four terms
as Syracuse's chief executive between 1970 and 1986.
   The former mayor was to have been sentenced on March 10 but
questions by the government about whether Alexander had withheld
any assets caused McAvoy to delay sentencing until today. Alexander
met with government attorneys for more than 20 hours and submitted
to at least two polygraph tests during the past two weeks.
   Alexander was indicted July 16, 1986, by a special grand jury
investigating public corruption in Syracuse. Alexander initially
denied the charges, but the the overwhelming and highly detailed
evidence, including testimony from Alexander's pick-up men and
other co-conspirators, caused him to seek a plea bargain.
</TEXT>
