<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1400EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Church     03-24 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Church,0649</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Religious Activists Appeal For Ouster of Patriarch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six religious activists seeking greater religious
freedom in the Soviet Union called Thursday for a new Russian
Orthodox Church leader to replace the ailing Patriarch Pimen.
   The activists, led by the Rev. Gleb Yakunin, sent an appeal to
the 78-year-old Pimen asking that he step down because senility and
poor health make him incapable of fulfilling his duties.
   The group, who met with reporters, said they have noted some
encouraging changes in official tolerance of religion and believe
it is time for a change at the top.
   They also sent their appeal to the church Synod that meets next
week, Yakunin said, in the event Pimen does not choose to leave.
The Synod is responsible for making church appointments.
   Yakunin acknowledged that it would be unprecedented for the
church hierarchy, which is subordinate to the Communist Party
government, to oust the church leader against his will.
   ``On the shoulders of the church leader rests the heavy weight
of spiritual and historical responsibilities,'' the appeal reads.
``You, Your Supreme Holiness, are not up to bearing this weight.''
   Pimen's office recieved the appeal, church chancery director
Irina A. Tsyganova told The Associated Press.
   ``I can't say whether it will be discussed by the Synod or
not,'' she said. ``I rather doubt it as the Synod's business agenda
has been determined for a long time.''
   She said Pimen, who is widely reported to be in poor health, was
not available for comment.
   ``I doubt he will leave of his own accord,'' Yakunin said. ``But
we sent the letter with the hope that those around him who assist
him in carrying out church duties will be able to influence him.''
   Religious activist Andrei Bessmertny said Pimen rarely appears
in public and his crucial role as liaison between the Russian
Orthodox church and the government is filled by an unknown cast of
supporters.
   ``He has been seen by foreign visitors to ask his deacons where
he should go and what he should do,'' Bessmertny said. ``He has to
be led around like a very old man.''
   Yakunin and fellow priest Nikolai Gainov said they were not
appealing for any particular church official to succeed Pimen.
   Yakunin, who was imprisoned for six years because of religious
activism in the 1970s that authorities considered to be dissident
behavior, was restored to the ministry last year after 20 years of
exclusion.
   More than 200 churches have been reopened recently for the
observance of the 1,000th anniversary of the coming of Christianity
to Russia. Whether that trend will continue after the formal
observances in June is not clear, the activists said.
   Yakunin also said church activists have found it easier now to
receive religious materials from foreign affiliates, including
Bibles and magazines that once were deemed anti-Soviet.
   The appeal to Pimen also noted the positive trends, although it
criticized the dearth of monasteries, seminaries, churches and
priests.
   ``Paradoxically, it is not the church but the government that is
taking the initiative in drawing believers into the social
mainstream,'' the appeal to Pimen said. ``Society has survived a
spiritual crisis and the Russian Orthodox Church can play a
significant role in its recovery.''
   While there have been encouraging signs of change, none of the
laws instituted in 1929 to break the church's influence with the
peasantry has been repealed, Yakunin said. Those laws prohibit
charitable work by churches as well as religious education, arguing
that such work violates the principle of separation of church from
state.
   The religious activists said 54,174 churches were open at the
time of the 1917 Bolshevik Revolution, and now there are about
7,000. The number of Russian Orthodox priests has declined on a
similar scale.
</TEXT>
