<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Biden     03-24 0450</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Biden,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delaware Senator Leaves Hospital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del., thin and
full of good cheer, left the hospital Thursday saying ``I feel
good'' despite a setback that has delayed a second operation on an
artery in his head.
   ``I've asked you all to come today because I've decided to
announce that I am re-entering the race for president,'' the
Delaware senator joked to reporters waiting outside Walter Reed
Army Hospital where he had spent the last 11 days.
   Biden dropped out of the Democratic campaign last Sept. 23.
   He had undergone surgery to correct an aneurysm in an artery
that supplies blood to the brain on Feb. 12 and was scheduled to
have a second artery similarly repaired early in April.
   But on March 13 he re-entered the hospital for a suspected blood
clot in his leg. It turned out the clot had lodged in Biden's
lungs, where it dissipated and was absorbed by the body.
   To prevent more such clots, which occur frequently after medical
intrusion into the artery, doctors last Friday implanted a tiny,
umbrella-like filter in a large vein that conveys blood to the
right atrium of the heart. The arterial surgery now probably will
be the end of May.
   ``They don't want me working, but do want me walking,'' Biden
said. ``The most disturbing part of the intermediate step I've had
is the delay of the second operation for a month or so. The second
operation should be a relatively easy piece of cake.''
   He said he won't be back in the Senate until he recovers from
that surgery.
   Biden looked thin and said he is now down to a 34 inch waist.
   ``I probably don't look very hot, but I feel fine,'' he said.
   He declined to talk politics, saying that ``if you are out of
the loop more than a couple of days in this race, you are really
out of the loop.'' And of the race, he said: ``I think it would be
much better if I were still in it.''
   The senator wore a baseball cap with the letter ``D.'' He had
worn the same cap on his first hospital release and said he'd
gotten mail asking why he was a Detroit Tigers fan.
   ``This is a University of Delaware baseball hat,'' he said. ``I
hope this will put an end to the most serious problem I've
confronted in the last six weeks.''
   And, added the senator, who is nearly bald, ``the reason for the
hat is that they kind of took some of my hair off and I didn't have
a lot of hair to begin with.''
</TEXT>
