<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Disney-HazardousWaste     03-24 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Disney-Hazardous Waste,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Agency Cites Theme Park For Major Violations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walt Disney World has handled
hazardous waste materials in a sloppy and potentially dangerous
way, the state Department of Environmental Regulation reports.
   The DER told the company it would be fined $174,399 unless it
can show that the violations are not as serious as the state agency
contends.
   ``It looks as if they (Disney supervisors) do not have good
control of their hazardous waste,'' said George Gionis, enforcement
section manager for DER's Central Florida district.
   A two-day inspection of the 43-square-mile tourist attraction in
January found nine violations, seven classified as major. The DER
wants the company to test for possible groundwater contamination in
two of the nine areas inspected.
   Disney spokesman John Dreyer said Thursday the company had
``always tried to comply with DER regulations, and we will make
whatever improvements are deemed necessary.''
   The inspection was conducted after the DER received an anonymous
complaint.
   Much of the criticism involved a maintenance yard in the Epcot
Center section, where toxic paints, solvents, pesticides and other
chemicals are stored.
   The DER described the maintenance yard as an ``uncontrolled,
unsupervised, unmanaged and unposted site.''
   State inspectors said they found steel drums stored
indiscriminately and filled with waste and unknown chemicals. Many
drums were unlabeled, rusty, open or lying on their sides, with
their contents running off a concrete slab where they could
contaminate groundwater.
   There were no precautions to guard against fires, explosions or
spills, the inspectors said.
   Such dangers, plus a possible contamination of groundwater,
``could threaten human health or the environment,'' according to
the report.
   Inspectors found only one employee that had received training in
handling the materials, and the DER asked that Disney set up a
training course on hazardous-waste management.
   The park passed similar inspections in 1984 and 1985. No
inspections were made in 1986 or 1987. In 1981 and 1983, it was
cited for minor violations.
   Disney officials have 10 days to meet with the regulatory agency
to set up a plan for correcting violations and negotiate penalties.
It could take months or even years to make some of the changes
requested, Gionis said.
</TEXT>
