<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CrackFires     03-24 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crack Fires,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fifth Crack House Set Ablaze</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire officials on Thursday investigated a blaze at
an abandoned house used by crack cocaine addicts, the fifth such
fire which officials said may be the work of anti-drug vigilantes.
   ``I don't have a gut feeling whether it's the same person,''
said fire Lt. John Gilbert. ``It could be one person or four
different people. I do know that whoever it is is not serving the
community.''
   As in the other cases, police found little evidence to aid their
investigation of the fire which broke out Tuesday in a
working-class neighborhood, according to fire spokeswoman Cristy
Hickman.
   Investigators believe the blaze may be related to fires that
gutted three houses March 17 and another house two weeks ago near
Coral Gables, a suburb of Miami, Ms. Hickman said Thursday.
   One firefighter suffered a heart attack during one of the fires
last week and is still hospitalized, she said. Six other
firefighters and one civilian have also sustained minor injuries.
   The latest fire was confined to a small area of a vacant
two-story house and appeared to involve a flammable liquid. No
injuries were reported.
   Although not in the same neighborhoods, the fires have all
involved vacant buildings that were hangouts for vagrants and crack
users, and all involved a flammable liquid, fire officials said.
   ``People seem to know where they are,'' Gilbert said of the
crack houses. ``Police know where they are, too. They try their
best but as soon as they close someone down, someone else moves
in.''
   Gilbert is concerned that more people could get hurt, or even
killed, and that copycats may prompt more fires, especially since
avenging arsonists are gaining prominence around the country.
   Two men who recently set fire to a crack house in their Detroit
neighborhood were featured on three national news magazines and a
national morning television show.
   ``I resent all this attention they're getting,'' said Lt. Jon
Bozich of the Detroit Fire Department. ``The more you make heroes
out of these guys the more problems we're going to have. Everybody
wants to be a hero.''
</TEXT>
