<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Conlon     03-24 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Conlon,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Day at the Opera, a Night with the Orchestra</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orchestra conductors don't expect to have
weekends off, but James Conlon faces a Saturday that's close to
ridiculous.
   In the afternoon, he will conduct Mussorgsky's ``Khovanshchina''
at the Metropolitan Opera and in the evening he'll be next door in
Avery Fisher Hall conducting the New York Philharmonic in an
all-Mahler program.
   He knew about the double workshift about a year ago, Conlon said
Thursday. ``I thought, `I can do that.'''
   He'll be free between 5:30 and 8 p.m., Conlon said. ``I'll go
home, shower, dress again, sit quietly for an hour and a half.'' He
says he won't even need a snack between performances.
   ``It is actually less exhausting to do this than to rehearse all
day,'' said Conlon, 38. ``Rehearsals are very intense. They take a
lot out of you.
   ``Concerts wind you up and give you energy. I find, after a
concert or particularly after an opera, physically you can be
extremely stimulated, for several hours to come.''
</TEXT>
