<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1424EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MeteoriteAnalysis     03-24 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meteorite Analysis,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chemical Analysis May Be Revolutionized By Method Tested On
Meteorites</HEAD>
<NOTE>For release at 6:30 p.m. EST; time set by source</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LA JOLLA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists have used lasers to identify
organic chemicals in meteorites, and say the new technique may
revolutionize analysis of certain pollutants, oil-bearing rocks and
other chemicals.
   The procedure is much faster than standard chemical tests,
requires only a tiny sample and doesn't destroy the material, said
a statement by the Scripps Institution of Oceanography.
   The technique was developed by chemist Richard N. Zare and
colleagues at Stanford University.
   Its use to identify organic compounds in six meteorites was
outlined in a study, published in Friday's issue of the journal
Science, by Zare and his colleagues at Stanford and by Jeffrey L.
Bada, a marine chemist at Scripps, which is part of the University
of California, San Diego, located in La Jolla.
   ``The problem with standard chemical techniques for doing
organic analyses of meteorites and other rare materials is that
they are laborious, destroy the sample and require one to 10 grams
of the material to be tested,'' Bada said.
   A gram is about one-30th of an ounce.
   ``Our method can reduce the analysis time from a month or more
to just a few minutes, and we need only one millionth of a gram to
do the test,'' he said. ``In addition, the technique does not
require the use of solvents that can contaminate the sample, and is
non-destructive to the sample.''
   The new method may be used widely to analyze meteorites, cosmic
dust, environmental pollutants and oil-bearing sediments, the
Scripps statement said, adding that the technique ``may
revolutionize the way certain chemical compounds are analyzed.''
   The study found wide variation in the content and relative
amounts of organic substances known as polycyclic aromatic
hydrocarbons, or PAHs, in the meteorites that were tested.
   Scientists believe meteorites are remnants of the young solar
system, and analyzing their contents may provide clues as to why
life arose on Earth but not elsewhere in the solar system.
   The researchers placed tiny amounts of meteorite samples on a
Teflon-coated probe, then inserted the probe into a vacuum chamber.
Each sample was hit with a 10-millionth-of-a-second burst from a
carbon dioxide laser, which heated the samples to about 1,000
degrees Fahrenheit.
   The heat released molecules of the samples into the vacuum
chamber, where they then were struck by an ultraviolet laser beam.
That electrically charged the organic compunds in the meteorites so
the chemicals could be separated and identified by matching their
masses with masses of known substances.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
