<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfWar 1stLd-Writethru a0597 03-24 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf War, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0597,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gulf Sources Report Apparent Iranian Attack; Ship Captain Denies
It</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with captain saying ship not hit
by Iranians, ADDS identity of ship. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `The
executives...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A supertanker put out a distress signal
in the southern Persian Gulf today and appeared to be the victim of
an Iranian attack, but the captain denied it had been hit, maritime
salvage executives said.
   The executives, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
267,589-ton Friendship L reported in a radio contact that its
engine room was on fire. The captain did not say what caused the
fire.
   In a later contact, the captain denied his vessel had been the
target of an Iranian raid. The Iranians have launched nine attacks
on neutral shipping in the southern gulf since Friday.
   The ship attacks are part of the so-called tanker war, an
offshoot of the 7{-year-old Iraq-Iran conflict. About 500 ships
have been attacked by both sides, according to the London-basec
Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit, which monitors worldwide
navigation.
   Salvage tugboats rushed to the Friendship L, which gave its
location between the southern gulf emirates of Ajman and Ras
al-Khaimah, close to the Strait of Hormuz, said the executives. The
strait is the sole entry to the gulf. There was no immediate word
on the extent of damage.
   The executives said the vessel in distress was in almost the
same area where a Cypriot freighter, the Odysseas H, was attacked
by two Iranian gunboats on Wednesday. Eight other attacks on
freighters and tankers of different nationalities were hit by the
Iranians in the past week, all in the same vicinity.
   Salvage tugboats were still struggling to contain a blaze in the
crew quarters of the Odysseas H, 24 hours after the attack. No
casualties were reported on board.
   Strong winds were whipping up the flames and impeding the
salvage operation, the executives said. Reports indicated the
vessel was being steered in the direction of Omani waters for
shelter where the salvage operation would be completed.
</TEXT>
