<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Panama-Security     03-24 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Security,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Now Has More Than Doubled Security Personnel in Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States moved 250 more military
police into Panama this week, more than doubling the number of
security personnal assigned to the strife-torn country since March
14, the Pentagon said Thursday.
   Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard said the latest deployments
brought to 670 the total of extra security personnel airlifted to
Panama, ``and that's it.''
   ``At least, that's it for the interim,'' Howard said. ``This was
part of a general, supplemental deployment of military policemen,
and that supplemental deployment has now come to an end. So I don't
expect it to go any higher.''
   The U.S. Southern Command, which is headquartered in Panama, had
about 600 security personnel assigned to it before the United
States stepped up its campaign earlier this month to oust strongman
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega. The new deployments thus more than
double the number of security personnel in the country.
   Howard, asked why the Pentagon thought it needed to airlift
additional personnel when there were already 10,000 U.S. servicemen
in the country, said the concern was having sufficient ``people who
are trained as military policemen. ... They're trained to handle
riot control and all sorts of things. And this has to do with the
physical security of our military installations, housing areas and
the like due to civil unrest and potential for civil unrest in the
country.''
   Capt. Nancy LaLuntas, a Pentagon spokeswoman, said Thursday the
latest group of approximately 250 MPs had been drawn from the 503rd
Military Police Battalion at Fort Bragg, N.C.
   Earlier this week, the Pentagon announced it had dispatched
about 212 soldiers from that unit to Panama, at the time bringing
the ``security augmentation'' to 420.
   Although no moves have been reported against American servicemen
or their dependents, defense officials are said to be concerned
that Noriega might lash back at the United States by attacking or
sabotaging facilities there.
</TEXT>
