<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mecham 3rdLd-Writethru a0702 03-24 0748</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0702,0769</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecution Rests on Second Count Against Mecham</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with prosecution resting on
second charge, picking up 7th graf, `Asked by ....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecution rested its case today in
the second of three impeachment allegations against Gov. Evan
Mecham being tried before the Arizona Senate.
   After the prosecution called its last witness, presiding officer
Frank X. Gordon Jr. denied a defense motion to dismiss the charge
that Mecham misused $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by
loaning it to his auto dealership.
   The defense called as its first witness Roger Hagadorn, a Valley
National Bank vice president who said he had loaned money to
members of the Mecham family for decades and none had ever
defaulted.
   Earlier today, Sen. Tony West said the allegation that Mecham
loaned public money to his auto dealership is serious and could
have been the subject of a criminal investigation.
   West spoke as former state Attorney General Jack LaSota
testified that he believed the $80,000 loan from the governor's
protocol fund was illegal.
   ``Your testimony, if accurate, is either a nuclear explosion or
at least devastating,'' West said.
   A criminal charge that Mecham misused public money would be a
class 4 felony carrying a penalty of up to $150,000 and five years
in prison, the senator said.
   Jeffrey Colville, a developer and mortgage banker, testified
today that there were three previous liens totaling $3.7 million on
the Mecham Pontiac property, in addition to the deed of trust for
the $80,000 loan.
   The property was appraised at $3.35 million a year earlier,
Colville ssid. In the event of a foreclosure, the previous liens
would have to be paid off before the $80,000 loan could be repaid,
he said.
   However, defense lawyer Jerris Leonard questioned whether the
appraisal was low as part of a general industry practice.
   Asked by prosecutor Paul Eckstein if he would have made the
$80,000 loan to Mecham Pontiac based on that information, Colville
said, ``I would have to answer no.''
   The prosecution has contended the auto dealership needed the
money badly, and that the $80,000 loan was not simply a business
deal intended to benefit the protocol fund as the defense said.
   LaSota, who was attorney general under the Republican governor's
predecessor, Democratic Gov. Bruce Babbitt, testified Wednesday
that the loan violated several state laws.
   Earlier, an accountant who examined the records of the
dealership said it would have been overdrawn at its bank had Mecham
not borrowed the $80,000 on July 17, also contradicting the
governor's previous testimony.
   ``Unless these funds had been paid from the protocol fund,
Mecham Pontiac would have had an overdraft the following Wednesday
in excess of $60,000,'' said accountant Randall Sorensen.
   Mecham's lawyers contend the protocol fund, created with
fund-raising proceeds from the governor's inauguration, is private
money and the loan was merely a good business deal intended to
provide a higher interest rate to the fund.
   The prosecution, however, says the protocol fund is state money
since it is intended for the purchase of ceremonial state gifts and
other means of promoting Arizona's image.
   In January, Mecham testified before a House impeachment
committee that his dealership did not need the money to pay its
bills.
   However, Sorensen said his analysis of the dealership's records
showed that it paid First Interstate Bank $81,309 owed for six cars
on the day it received the $80,000 from the protocol fund.
   Defense attorney Jerris Leonard suggested the dealership could
have had other assets which could have been converted to cash, but
Sorsensen said he had found no such assets.
   LaSota testified that he had examined the way the protocol fund
was set up and the applicable state laws and concluded it was
public money, even though it was not officially turned over to the
state treasury.
   The $80,000 loan violated state laws against loaning state
money, failing to keep the fund intact until it was properly
disbursed and transferring money when not authorized by law, LaSota
said.
   Mecham, the first U.S. governor to be impeached in six decades,
also has been charged with obstructing the investigation of an
alleged threat and concealing a $350,000 campaign loan.
   The first-term governor also faces an April 21 criminal trial on
felony charges of concealing the campaign loan and a May 17 recall
election.
   A two-thirds vote of the 30-member Senate is required to convict
Mecham in the impeachment trial.
</TEXT>
