<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Mail-Miller     03-24 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mail-Miller,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dispute Flares Over Postal Cuts, Operations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress and the Reagan administration clashed
Thursday over who is at fault for recent cuts in postal services
and what future would be best for the embattled mail system.
   Federal budget director James C. Miller III and members of the
House Post Office and Civil Service Committee sought to place blame
for the postal cutbacks on one another _ with both sides calling
the accounting process ``smoke and mirrors.''
   The Postal Service curtailed some window hours and halted Sunday
collections and some sorting after the federal budget
reconciliation bill required it to reduce spending without
increasing revenues.
   Postage rate hikes slated for April 3, boosting a first-class
stamp price to a quarter, are unrelated to the dispute.
   In addition to finding fault with one another for the agency's
budget crisis, disagreements flared over proposals by Miller and
others to ``privatize'' the Postal Service by making it a private
firm and opening mail delivery to business competition.
   Miller said that plan would cut costs, imoprove efficiency and
probably result in better service and lower costs for consumers.
   But Moe Biller, head of the American Postal Workers Union, told
the House subcommittee on postal operations that, in his opinion,
all Miller wants is to destroy the Postal Service.
   Privatization is only political jargon for ``profitization,''
Biller said, terming the idea ``the tale of an idiot, full of sound
and fury, signifying nothing.''
   Rep. Frank Horton, R-N.Y., said he believes that instead of
improving service, turning postal services over to private hands
could well destroy the service.
   The prime bone of contention, however, was delegating blame for
the federal budget process last December that ended with the Postal
Service being directed to cut spending as part of overall
reductions in the federal budget.
   The Office of Management and Budget is not seeking to manage the
Postal Service and did not impose the cuts, Miller told the
congressmen. He said that the decision was made by members of
Congress themselves.
   Miller said he only agreed that the cuts would reduce the
federal deficit, because the Postal Service is counted in the
federal budget. ``I did not advocate it,'' he said.
   ``Who did?'' asked Horton, contending that the ``heavy hand'' of
the budget office was felt at the session where decisions were
made, because that office refused to approve other proposals that
had been made instead of the postal cuts.
   Horton and Rep. Mickey Leland, D-Texas, both said they are now
supporting a bill to take the Postal Service out of the federal
budget so it would not become involved in this type of problem in
the future. The Postal Service, an independent federal agency, was
not counted in the overall federal budget until 1985.
   ``I think the Postal Service should be placed off budget,''
Miller, who has long opposed the idea, told a momentarily stunned
audience. Then, he added: ``By making it part of the private
sector.''
   ``You take a very crass and insensitive approach to things,''
Leland said, stating that he is concerned that privatization would
lead to a loss of federal jobs and to the opportunities for
minorities that the post office has long provided.
   ``Why do you think that would end if it were transferred to the
private sector?'' Miller asked.
   Leland shot back, ``You want to break it up and sell it off and
those people who are buying do not necessarily believe in
affirmative action. Your administration does not believe in
affirmative action.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
