<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AntitrustChief     03-24 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Antitrust Chief,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Antitrust Prosecutions at Record High, Justice Official Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Justice Department official said Thursday
there are more grand jury investigations under way into
price-fixing, bid-rigging and other criminal antitrust violations
than at any time in this century.
   In a speech, Assistant Attorney General Charles F. Rule defended
the Reagan administration's approach to antitrust enforcement which
emphasizes price-fixing prosecutions while making it easier for
mergers to occur.
   ``Criminal antitrust enforcement today is at an all-time high,'
Rule said. He said that in the first seven years of the Reagan
administration, the Justice Department's antitrust division, which
he heads, has filed 555 criminal antitrust cases. The division
filed 531 criminal antitrust cases from 1890 when the Sherman Act
was passed to 1949.
   The department has vigorously pursued bid-rigging in the
roadbuilding and auction industries and other areas of business.
   ``Reporters don't believe protecting consumers is news unless
you block a merger between two steel companies or indict the head
of one of the country's biggest corporations,'' Rule said. ``In
fact, we file cases every week that have more direct impact on
consumers than both of those actions together.''
</TEXT>
