<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SmokingBan     03-24 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smoking Ban,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Smokers Say No Smoking Means No Flying on Northwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED STYCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smokers reacted with irritation Thursday to
Northwest Airline's plans to ban smoking on all domestic routes
except those to and from Hawaii.
   ``I think it stinks,'' said Dennis Kenyon, 43, as he puffed a
cigarette in a designated smoking area of Minneapolis-St. Paul
International Airport. ``I'll fly any other airline before I fly
Northwest.''
   A frequent business flier, the St. Paul Park salesman said the
ban is unreasonable. ``It's hard for me to believe that cigarette
smoke bothers someone 20 rows away,'' he said.
   Northwest, based in Eagan, Minn., announced the ban Wednesday,
becoming the first major American carrier to prohibit smoking on
extended flights.
   Airline officials said the ban, which also applies to some
foreign flights, was a response to employees' and passengers'
requests, and they predicted it would attract more people than it
would drive away.
   A.B. ``Sky'' Magary, Northwest's executive vice president for
marketing, said in New York Wednesday said a survey found that nine
out of 10 passengers prefer to sit in the no-smoking section, and
that even 30 percent of the smokers supported a ban on smoking in
flight.
   One non-smoker at the Minneapolis airport Thursday said it
didn't make much difference to him.
   ``As long as they have a smoking section, it doesn't matter,''
said Larry Briggs of Ashland, Ohio.
   Dan Bridges of Memphis, Tenn., said he travels in the
non-smoking secion ``and it's never been a problem.''
   Some analysts believe Northwest, the nation's fifth largest
carrier, risks losing customers. Other major airlines said they
have no immediate plans to follow suit.
   Kenyon's wife, Joann, who manages an airport gift shop, said she
has heard many smokers grumble about Northwest's action.
   ``They're not going to fly Northwest. They're going to do
anything they can not to fly Northwest,'' she said.
   ``When I go to California, there's no way I'm going to sit for
six hours and not smoke,'' said Todd Parron, a college student from
the Cincinnati suburb of Silverton. ``I'd find another flight and
take it.''
   However, one non-smoker at the Cincinnati airport said
Northwest's move will make her more likely to choose it over other
airlines.
   ``Those airplane cabins are too small. Even with smoking only in
the back rows, smoke still bothers me,'' said Erin Weglicki of
Memphis, Tenn. ``It would make a difference to me in choosing an
airline. It's a pretty brave move on their part.''
   Under new federal regulations going into effect April 23,
smoking will be banned on all domestic flights of less than two
hours. Violators will face civil fines of as much as $1,000.
   Northwest's policy will take effect the same day.
   Some smokers said they can live with Northwest's policy.
   ``It's probably a good idea,'' Janice Davis, a Boston real
estate broker, told the St. Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch. ``I can
get by without smoking.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
