<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1539EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WorkerNotice 2ndLd-Writethru a0643 03-24 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Worker Notice, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0643,610</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs last graf, I don't think, to include Byrd's first name,
title.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted 93-2 today to allow
Republicans to continue delaying action on a bill requiring the
government to warn workers about carcinogens and other job hazards.
   The vote against shutting off a GOP filibuster allows members of
both parties to start offering amendments to a weakened version of
the measure that was substituted Wednesday night in an effort to
win more support for it.
   Only Democratic Sens. Dennis DeConcini of Arizona and Claiborne
Pell of Rhode Island voted to stop the filibuster.
   ``Once this vote is disposed of, the bill is open to
amendments,'' Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, the bill's chief
author, said today. ``There is nothing unseemly about making
changes in a bill on the floor of the Senate.''
   However, Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, the leader of the filibuster,
called the new, weaker version a ``fire sale'' to special interests
made for ``the perception of a political victory.''
   Hatch, after refusing Wednesday to allow Democratic amendments
to weaken the bill, indicated he is prepared to continue his
filibuster.
   ``We intend to talk a little more at length to explain the
problems with this bill,'' Hatch said today. ``You can't do it in a
few hours.''
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., chairman of the Senate Labor
and Human Resources Committee, substituted the weaker version at
Metzenbaum's request in response to Hatch's filibuster.
   The legislation is aimed at what the National Institute of
Occupational Safety and Health says are the one in every four
Americans who have been exposed to carcinogens or other hazardous
substances on the job.
   The ``High Risk Occupational Disease Notification and Prevention
Act'' would establish a seven-member panel of scientists to
determine the biggest hazards in workplaces and identify what
groups of workers are most at risk.
   The government would then have to notify between 100,000 and
300,000 of those workers individually each year, and their
employers would have to provide them with annual medical monitoring
tests costing up to $250 each.
   A similar bill was passed by the House on a 225-186, largely
party-line vote last October despite vehement opposition from the
Reagan administration.
   Hatch, voicing the objections of hundreds of business groups,
said the bill could open up employers to billions of dollars in
liability damages from suits by their workers and former workers
placed in the at-risk groups.
   Metzenbaum could muster only 33 votes Wednesday to cut off
Hatch's filibuster, while 59 senators, including 16 Democrats, said
they wanted the filibuster to continue.
   ``They found out that this bill is going nowhere except to the
elephant graveyard of legislation,'' said acting Senate Republican
Leader Alan Simpson of Wyoming.
   Simpson called Kennedy's substitute a ``sweeten-the-pot theory
of legislating that I find a little disturbing.''
   The new version exempts both companies with fewer than 50
workers and farms from having to continue paying wages and benefits
for up to a year to workers ordered off the job because of the
danger that might be raised by continued exposure to hazardous
substances.
   It also puts restrictions on what information from the program
could be used by workers and former workers in pursuing liability
suits against employers.
   Democrats admitted that Kennedy's parliamentary maneuver,
although allowed by Senate rules, could be used to thwart
Republicans from offering amendments of their own. But they
maintained that was not the intent.
   ``I don't think it's fair,'' said House Democratic Leader Robert
C. Byrd, D-W.Va. ``The parliamentary landscape has shifted. We've
seen now how senators can be shut out from offering amendments
circumstantially with no malice intended.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
