<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WhiteHouseBarriers 1stLd-Writethru a0714 03-24 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-White House Barriers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0714,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Say Security Improvements Will be Attractive as Well</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs last graf to delete reference to $350,000 estimate,
which source now says in error</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Park Service says the White House
will be a safer place and have a better-looking sidewalk in front
of it when a million-dollar-plus construction project is completed
in July.
   The project, a compromise between security requirements of the
Secret Service and aesthetic standards of the Commission of Fine
Arts, has gone through several changes since it was first proposed.
   The first proposal was a 42-inch-high concrete wall, with the
White House's existing ornamental iron fence on top of it,
according to Charles H. Atherton, administative officer of the arts
panel.
   ``It would have made the White House look even more like a
fortress,'' Atherton said. The commission must approve design
changes affecting federal buildings and momuments in the central
are of Washington.
   After the terrorist attack on the Marine barracks in Lebanon in
1983, which killed 241 American servicemen, low concrete walls
called jersey barriers were erected around the White House and many
other public buildings in Washington.
   ``That was always regarded as a temporary measure,'' said Park
Service spokesman Jim McDaniel.
   After the wall was rejected, there were discussions between the
arts commission and the Park Service, with advice from the Secret
Service, resulting in the present plan.
   It consists of 274 bollards, or thick cement and aggregate
posts, each 38 inches high, placed four feet apart and joined by
chains, along 832 feet of Pennsylvania Avenue sidewalk.
   ``We, of course, would have hoped that they would be farther
apart,'' Atherton said of the bollards. ``They're actually awfully
close together.''
   The Secret Service, however, determined that this spacing was
the most effective way to stop a vehicle of a certain size, going
at a certain speed, from crashing into the White House.
   ``We certainly agree that the first order of business would be
the protection of the president at any cost, and if the aesthetic
element has to be compromised, so be it, sad as that may be,'' said
Atherton.
   ``I think the Secret Service feels that we now have a system
that will do the job physically and at the same time we hope will
be more acceptable to look at. It certainly, I think, will be more
acceptable than the original scheme.''
   McDaniel said the Park Service, which is in charge of the White
House grounds, dealt separately with the Secret Service and the
commission.
   ``You play one against the other,'' he said. ``If you work hard
at it, you can usually find a solution.''
   The first phase of the project is scheduled for completion in
July.
   McDaniel said the security work will cost $670,000 and the Park
Service is spending an additional $365,000 to replace the sidewalk
with a more decorative granite walk with trees and tree boxes.
   A second phase is expected to be completed about the end of
July, but McDaniel said the cost has not been determined.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
