<2ND_LINE>AM-Police Turmoil, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0707,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chief, Officers In Small Town Feud Other Over Incident Involving
Girl</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf to CORRECT Horne to Hensley.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>APOPKA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The police department in this Central
Florida community is in turmoil over allegations by lower-ranking
officers that a captain took a teen-age girl along on a
confidential stakeout and kissed her against her will.
   The alleged incident last month resulted in the demotion of
Capt. Doyle Hensley, 42, to lieutenant and has led to a state
investigation and several internal investigations.
   Hensley had supervised an investigation last month on similar
charges against the officer who relayed the latest allegations.
   The chief of the 45-member force is suspicious.
   ``I haven't been able to prove that it's a setup yet,'' Chief
Tom Collins said Wednesday. ``Sooner or later, I'll find out. Some
officers may be running scared right now.''
   The officers who investigated the captain and had pictures taken
of him and the 16-year-old girl deny any setup.
   Hensley declined comment.
   Collins said the problems began when Hensley asked the girl, who
lives with a roommate and works as a waitress, to join him on a
stakeout at the local high school on Feb. 26.
   The girl said this week she was interested in police work but
was ``half afraid'' of Hensley because of his flirtatious comment
that it would be cold and she might have to keep him warm. She said
she told officer Greg Horne about the invitation.
   Horne passed the girl's comment on to Sgt. Jeff Ujcic, who then
notified his lieutenant, Ralph Caldwell.
   Last month, Horne was the target of an internal investigation,
supervised by Hensley, into accusations that he was dating another
teen-ager.
   Caldwell and Ujcic enlisted former police officer Gary Granttham
to take pictures when Hensley picked up the girl at the restaurant.
Also in the parking lot was a carload of the girl's friends, whom
she had asked to follow her. Hensley realized he was being followed
and gave them the slip, Collins said.
   ``What disturbed me the most is that this was supposedly a
confidential mission'' to catch suspected burglars, Caldwell said.
``This special operation was no longer a special operation.
Everybody and their brother knew about it.''
   The chief isn't happy that his nightshift officers started
investigating a fellow officer on their own. He is investigating
Horne's role.
   Meanwhile, Horne's family has befriended the teen-ager, and she
has complained to the state attorney's office that two officers
pressured her to withdraw her complaint about Hensley.
   The chief is angry that the officers got civilians involved _
Granttham and the Horne family.
   ``I don't need their help,'' Collins said. ``I can take care of
my own shop. I will take them to court if they slander my name.''
   State Attorney Robert Eagan said in Orlando, ``We're looking at
a matter involving the police up there. We're taking statements
from witnesses.''
</TEXT>
