<2ND_LINE>PM-Honduras, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0636,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduras Protests Alleged Sandinista Incursion, Nicaragua Denies
It</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Honduran protest. Pick up
3rd graf pvs: ``It's a...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>With PM-Nicaragua Talks, Bjt
^By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honduras said today it filed a
protest with Nicaragua over an alleged incursion by Sandinista
soldiers in the same spot where Nicaraguan troops fought Contra
rebels last week.
   Nicaragua denied its troops crossed the border.
   A Foreign Ministry communique said a total of nearly 460
Sandinistas crossed the border late Tuesday. An ``energetic
protest'' was filed with Nicaragua over the incident, it said.
   It said 300 heavily armed Sandinistas entered about 8 p.m.
Tuesday in the San Andres de Bocay region in Olancho province,
where Sandinistas chased Contras back across the border last week.
It is about 150 miles east of this capital city.
   At the same time, 50 Nicaraguan soldiers entered at the village
of Pico Espanol in El Paraiso province. The village is about two
miles from the Nicaraguan border.
   The statement, read to The Associated Press by telephone, did
not say if there were any confrontations in the areas or whether
the troops were still believed to be inside the country.
   In Managua, the Nicaraguan capital, a Defense Ministry spokesman
was asked about the report. ``That's negative,'' he said, speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   A Honduran military official had reported the new incursion on
Wednesday.
   ``We don't know the purpose of this new entry and violation of
our country, but the situation is being studied by the high
command,'' the official said.
   ``It's a matter of small armed groups of Sandinistas. Because of
that, the state of alert continues for all combat units of the
armed forces,'' said the source, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The location was given as the San Andres de Bocay region in
Olancho province, but no other details were available.
   In Washington, a government source speaking on condition of
anonymity, said there had been unconfirmed reports that an
estimated 300 Sandinista soldiers had entered Honduras.
   The reported incursion did not affect peace talks then under way
between top Sandinista and Contra officials in Nicaragua, even
though both sides said their forces would stop fighting during the
talks. Late Wednesday, the talks produced an accord calling for a
60-day cease-fire beginning April 1.
   Earlier Wednesday, Pentagon officials in Washington had said
that unless the military situation in Honduran changes, the
approximately 3,200 U.S. troops sent to Honduras last week would
return home early next week.
   The U.S. troops were ordered to Honduras as a show of force
after 2,000 Sandinsta soldiers allegedly chased Contra rebels from
Nicaragua into Honduras.
</TEXT>
