<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1705EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-KindergartenTests     03-24 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kindergarten Tests,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Educators Decry Trend Toward Standardized Testing in Kindergarten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two education associations called for an end
Thursday to what they called the growing practice of subjecting
kindergarten children to standardized tests to determine promotion
to first grade.
   The groups said the same tests are being used to determine
whether a youngster is admitted to kindergarten or advised to spend
another year in preschool.
   ``Our children are being tested too early and failed too soon,
and parents should ask for what purpose,'' said Sue Bredekamp,
accreditation director of the National Association for the
Education of Young Children.
   Her group was joined by the National Association of Early
Childhood Specialists in State Departments of Education calling for
an end to mass standardized testing of children before the third
grade.
   They said they did not object to testing of individual children
whose teachers or parents suspect they have a learning or
developmental problem. But for most children, they said, ``Parents
should trust their own instincts and the observations of trained
and experienced preschool and kindergarten teachers.''
   Leaders of the groups said at a news conference they do not know
how many schools are resorting to standardized placement or
promotion tests for 4-, 5-and 6-year-olds.
   But Bredekamp said that in some areas, ``it is not unusual now
for 20 percent or more of young children to be advised to wait a
year before entering kindergarten, or to `flunk' kindergarten, or
to be assigned to a special track called `readiness,'
`transitional' or `developmental' kindergarten.''
   Georgia recently became the first state to require standardized
testing of kindergarten children. The city of Minneapolis began
testing kindergarteners in 1984 on basic math and reading skills,
and has been holding back 10 percent of the children, most of them
minorities.
   But last September the North Carolina legislature voted to
discontinue mandatory standardized tests for first and second
graders.
   Asa Hilliard, an Atlanta child psychologist and professor at
Georgia State University, said the tests are being used to hold
children back or track them into remedial programs or special
education, despite a lack of evidence that such steps improve their
schooling.
   He said the tests have ``a disproportionate impact on those
children who need school the most, the minority children.''
   Bredekamp said testing ``narrows and misdirects the curriculum.''
   ``The most important things to learn in kindergarten, such as
self-esteem, social competence, confidence, self-discipline, desire
to learn, cannot be measured on standardized tests,'' she said.
   Louise Bates Ames, co-founder of the Gesell Institute, which
produces a widely used screening test, said it was ``discouraging
that these groups have taken this political position.''
   ``Our position is that if there are 25 children in a classroom,
all acting at 5-year-old maturity level, the teacher still has to
individualize the curriculum to different ability levels. But if
you put children together at different maturity and ability levels,
then you have differences you can't possibly span,'' she said in a
telephone interview from the institute's New Haven, Conn.,
headquarters.
   Bredekamp said the testing issue ``is part of the bigger issue
of pushing academic subjects at too early an age.''
   The association's president is child psychologist David Elkind,
author of ``The Hurried Child'' and the leading critic of that
trend.
   The association has 60,000 members, including teachers and
others involved in preschool, kindergarten and early elementary
education.
</TEXT>
