<2ND_LINE>AM-Candidates Rdp,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrat Announces for Bill Green's Seat in Congress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Rep. John Jenrette, who served a prison term for an
Abscam conviction, says he plans to challenge Democrat Robin Tallon
for his old seat from South Carolina's 6th District.
   In New York, meanwhile, John B. Levitt, a Democratic district
leader from Manhattan, announced his candidacy Thursday for the
congressional seat held by Republican Bill Green.
   ``I feel there are three urgent and pressing problems and they
haven't been addressed,'' Levitt, 28, said, citing homelessness,
drug abuse and drug trafficking, and the overcrowding of hospitals
sparked by the AIDS epidemic.
   ``They haven't been effectively dealt with everywhere in our
area or in Washington. We really need aggressive leadership and
that's what I'm offering in my campaign. I think we need a
congressman who will really go down and fight in Washington and get
dollars in this area.''
   Green, 58, has represented the 15th Congressional District since
1978. He has not made a formal announcement for re-election, but
his staff said he will.
   Jenrette, who lost his seat in 1980 after being convicted in the
Abscam scandal, told The State newspaper in Columbia on Wednesday
that he expects to make a formal announcement of his candidacy
early next month.
   Tallon declined comment on Jenrette's possible candidacy.
   Jenrette, 51, acknowledged he would be an underdog in a
Democratic primary against Tallon, a 41-year-old clothing store
operator elected in 1982.
   Jenrette was convicted in October 1980 of conspiracy and
accepting a $50,000 bribe from an FBI agent posing as an Arab
sheik. On probation after 13 months in federal prison, Jenrette is
a disbarred lawyer and reformed alcoholic.
   Jenrette said he expects a federal judge to lift his probation
before the June 14 primary.
   His felony conviction apparently does not prohibit Jenrette from
running for office or taking a seat in Congress, although he is
barred from voting in elections. According to a 1965 opinion by the
South Carolina attorney general, a candidate for the U.S. House of
Representatives does not have to be a qualified elector of the
state in order to be seated.
</TEXT>
