<HEAD>10-Year-Old and Younger Sister Take Family Car, Head for Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smarting from an argument with his mother,
10-year-old Andres Rascon and his 7-year-old sister headed for
Mexico in the family car after everyone else was asleep, police
report.
   Police were alerted after the boy tried to sell the car to a
convenience store clerk Tuesday.
   By the time authorities caught up with the runaways, they had
traveled 65 miles south on Interstate 19 to Nogales on the
U.S.-Mexican border.
   ``Our officers were _ how do you call it? _ amused initially,
then amazed that he could do it,'' Nogales Police Capt. Antonio
Estrada said Wednesday.
   Though the youth said he planned the escapade after an argument
with his mother, Bertha Rascon, she said the only argument she
could remember occurred two weeks ago when she scolded Andres for
watching too much television.
   The boy apparently waited until everyone in his grandmother's
home had gone to sleep, then took $20 and his mother's keys to her
1984 Chevrolet sedan and slipped out a bedroom window. He persuaded
his sister, Maria Fernanda, to go along.
   ``He told me they were going to have a spin around Sonora,'' the
Mexican state immediately across the border, ``but then they
decided to return,'' his mother said.
   She said she thought the youngsters may have been trying to find
their father, who lives in Mexico, though neither has any idea just
where.
   Andres, who is 4-foot-6, added a pillow to the car seat so he
could see over the dash, Estrada said. Andres learned to drive when
he was 6, when his father plopped the boy on his lap and showed him
how to maneuver.
</TEXT>
