<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1708EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Hospitals     03-24 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hospitals,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bed Shortage Related to Drug Epidemic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAYNER PIKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After closing hospital beds in recent years, New
York City faces a crisis because it didn't foresee the virulence
and consequences of the narcotics epidemic, according to a study
released Thursday.
   From 1985 to 1987, time in hospitals increased for drug users
and for victims of the side effects of narcotics use _ AIDS
patients and babies born too puny to go home.
   Psychiatric admissions not related to drugs also increased, but
all other categories of patient care followed the predicted
downward trend.
   ``Had it not been for the growth in psychiatry, substance abuse,
AIDS and neonatal services, inpatient hospital use in New York City
would actually have fallen roughly 5 percent between July 1985 and
July 1987, as was expected by planners and regulators who oversaw
the closure of 1,800 hospital beds citywide during that period,''
the survey preparers said in a statement.
   They described the hospitals knotted in a ``medical gridlock''
in which ``literally hundreds of patients needing acute care
services spend each night in emergency rooms because no beds are
available on inpatient services.''
   ``Various forms of social pathology visible, but inadequately
addressed, in many parts of the community are coming home to roost
within the city's health care facilities,'' the study said.
   The study, prepared by the United Hospital Fund and the Bigel
Institute for Health Policy at Brandeis University, was based on
data from 69 of the city's 81 municipal and voluntary hospitals. It
covered about 89 percent of the approximately 35,000 certified
hospital beds in New York.
   Medical authorities are divided on what must be done, said Bruce
C. Vladeck, president of the United Hospitals Fund.
   ``The Greater New York Hospital Association's position is we
need another 1,500 to 2,000 beds in this city fast,'' said Vladeck.
   Others, including Dr. David Axelrod, the state health
commissioner, and Stuart H. Altman, dean of social policy graduate
studies at Brandeis, suggest a mix of community-based services,
nursing care and special housing.
   During 1985-87, hospital stays grew by 44 percent for acquired
immune deficiency syndrome patients, 15 percent each for
psychiatric and substance abuse patients and 14 percent for
newborns, the study found.
   The increases have been concentrated in low-income communities,
another indicator that the hospital occupancy crisis is grounded in
what Vladeck called the ``general socio-economic disintegration of
parts of the city.''
   Vladeck said crack, a form of cocaine, accounted for a large
part of the problem.
   In addition to admissions traceable to crack-induced psychosis,
``there's a lot of crack-related respiratory illness _ people
literally burn out their lungs smoking crack,'' he said.
``Obviously, a lot of those low-birth-weight newborns are to
crack-using mothers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
