<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1709EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Barges-Pier     03-24 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Barges-Pier,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bridge Closed After Barges Carrying Volatile Chemical Hits Pier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials fearing an explosion closed the
bridge between Pensacola and Gulf Breeze on Thursday after two
barges containing highly flammable chemical vapors slammed into a
fishing pier.
   Liquid cyclohexane had been unloaded from the barges before the
collision but the vessels, being pushed by a towboat, still
contained residue and dangerous vapors, said Mark Snowden,
emergency response coordinator for the Florida Department of
Environmental Regulation.
   ``If it were to explode I suspect it would be a catastrophic
explosion,'' Snowden said. Sparks from an autombile ignition or
removal efforts might be enough to set off the vapors if they
should leak, he said.
   One of the two barges was removed about two hours after the
collision about 9 a.m., but the other remained wedged into the tip
of the 1.5-mile-long Pensacola Fishing Pier.
   The pier is part of an old bridge about 75 feet from and
parallel to the U.S. 98 bridge that spans the three miles across
Pensacola Bay in the western end of the Florida Panhandle.
   The pier also was evacuated.
   The bridge was expected to remain closed for at least four
hours, and motorists faced a detour of about 50 miles. Escambia
County Administrator Gus Ellis ordered the bridge closed but he
permitted emergency vehicles to cross. The Coast Guard also ordered
all boats to stay clear.
   Authorities were waiting for representatives of Capitol Towing,
owner of the barges, to arrive from Houston before making any
decision on removing the barge.
   The vapors also could cause asphyxiation, Snowden said. The
chemical, composed in part of benzine, is used by Monstano Textile
Co. in Pensacola to make nylon for carpeting, tires and other
things. Experts from Monsanto also were on the scene.
   Weather was clear but seas were choppy and winds were gusting
from the southwest at up to 20 miles per hour when the collision
occurred.
   ``The wind caught it and blew him into the bridge (pier),'' said
Grey Jewett, risk manager for Escambia County, which owns the pier.
``It destroyed the end of the pier, a turnaround.''
   Only three anglers were at the end of the pier, and there were
no injuries.
</TEXT>
