<2ND_LINE>AM-Captive Women-Movie, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0706,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyers Haggle Over Movie, Book Rights To Heidnik Story</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts throughout to move up prosecutor's objection to
proposal, her comments, update with judge requesting briefs.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Well Rescue-Movie Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than two weeks before Gary Michael
Heidnik goes on trial on rape and murder charges, lawyers are
haggling over rights to the story that began with the discovery of
three half-naked women chained in a basement.
   A year ago Friday, police found the women, as well as the limbs
of a fourth woman in a freezer and then the naked body of a fifth
woman in a New Jersey forest.
   Heidnik's trial begins April 4, but on Wednesday in federal
bankruptcy court, attorneys for Heidnik's creditors proposed an
agreement that would assign movie, book and entertainment rights to
the estates of Heidnik and his defunct church, the United Church of
the Ministers of God. Heidnik and the church are in bankruptcy.
   In the agreement, Heidnik's attorney, A. Charles Peruto Jr.,
would get one-third of any book and movie profits. The rest would
go to Heidnik's estate for payment to the alleged victims.
   But Assistant District Attorney Harriet Brumberg argued that
state law provides that 100 percent of such profits go to victims
of crimes.
   ``If anything in the book contains any thoughts, feelings,
impressions of Mr. Heidnik, that belongs to the victims,'' Ms.
Brumberg said.
   ``If I bring in money to enhance the estates, I get one-third of
what I enhance,'' Peruto said. ``The estates would get
two-thirds.'' As part of the agreement, Peruto would not get fees
for defending Heidnik.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge David A. Scholl asked for legal briefs in
the case by Tuesday and said he would issue a ruling after that.
   One author researching a Heidnik book was in court Wednesday.
And at least one other writer is said to be working on the story.
Atlanta writer Ken Englade, who has a contract with St. Martin's
Press in New York to write the book, said the story was ``lurid,''
but facinating.
</TEXT>
