<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--CharterSigning     03-24 0168</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Charter Signing,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Summit' to Note Constitution's Religious Freedom Guarantee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group promoting the religious freedom clause
in the U.S. Constitution announced plans Thursday to hold a ``first
liberty'' summit to call attention to the religious liberties
enjoyed by Americans.
   The Williamsburg Charter Foundation said it will hold its summit
in Williamsburg, Va., June 24 and 25. During the summit national
political, business and religious leaders will sign a charter that
celebrates the religious clause in the First Amendment to the
Constitution and reaffirms freedom on conscience for people of all
faiths.
   ``The First Amendment begins with freedom on conscience, and
upon this premise all other freedoms are made possible,'' said
foundation chairman Alonzo L. McDonald. ``These clauses allow us to
live with our deepest differences and encourage pluralism and
diversity of opinion.''
   The non-sectarian foundation already has released a survey of
American attitudes on religion in public life and is sponsoring a
symposium of scholars and religious leaders next month in
Charlottesville, Va.
</TEXT>
