<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HotelFire     03-24 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hotel Fire,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds Convictions in DuPont Plaza Hotel Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court on Thursday upheld the
convictions of two men found guilty of setting a fire at hotel fire
in Puerto Rico that killed 97 people.
   The 1st U.S. Court of Appeals rejected arguments by Armando
Jimenez Rivera and Jose Francisco Rivera Lopez that the trial judge
abused his discretion in sentencing them to 75 years and 99 years
in prison, respectively.
   Jimenez Rivera and Rivera Lopez, both workers at the Dupont
Plaza Hotel, admitted setting the fire as part of a labor dispute
with hotel management.
   The fire on New Year's Eve 1986 at the beachfront hotel also
injured more than 140 people.
   In return for their guilty pleas and cooperation in the
investigation, the government had recommended a maximum penalty of
25 years in prison for Rivera Lopez and 24 years for Jimenez
-Rivera.
   U.S. District Judge Jose Antonio Fuste of Puerto Rico rejected
the government's recommendation, saying the crimes amounted to
felony murder. The judge also noted that a third man convicted in
the case was found guilty of first-degree murder.
   Jimenez Rivera and Rivera Lopez appealed on the grounds that the
judge's remarks at sentencing were improper and that Fuste failed
to consider migating factors.
   ``The judge's concern over the deaths that resulted from their
crime indicates that he determined the sentence in reference to the
particular actions'' of the two men, the appeals court said.
   The justices did, however, order Fuste to hold a new hearing on
the Rivera Lopez sentencing to determine if he relied on inaccurate
statements in a pre-sentencing report. If so, the court said he
should hold a new sentencing hearing.
</TEXT>
