<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon-Israel     03-24 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Israel,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Jets Raid Palestinian Bases in Second Day of Raids</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AHMED MANTASH</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli jets bombed Palestinian targets on
the outskirts of Sidon for the second straight day Thursday,
hitting a base of Abu Nidal's guerrilla faction.
   Police said nine people were killed and five wounded in the
raid, the third this week near the port city 25 miles south of
Lebanon.
   Police said most of the casualties were members of Nidal's
Fatah-Revolutionary Council, and the group issued a statement
pledging ``merciless retaliation.''
   A police spokesman described the attack as ``very fierce.'' He
said six Israeli warplanes dropped 30 bombs in six sorties within
55 minutes.
   Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss instructed the country's U.N.
ambassador, Rashid Fakhoury, to complain to the world body about
the Israeli attacks, state radio said.
   But Lebanon did not ask for a Security Council meeting on the
issue, it said.
   The police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity in
keeping with standing regulations, said the main target of the raid
was Nidal's guerrilla base, but the jets also hit a position of the
Marxist Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine.
   ``The Israelis plowed the olive groves where the stricken bases
are,'' he added.
   The bases were engulfed by smoke and dust as ambulances arrived
to evacuate casualties.
   The police spokesman said Nidal's guerrillas cordoned off the
bases in the villages of Bekasta, Majdelyoun, Salhiyeh and Abra on
the southern and eastern edges of Sidon.
   The attacking jets dropped scarlet balloons to deflect
heat-seeking missiles. The guerrillas fired at the roaring jets
with Soviet-made anti-aircraft guns. No hits were reported.
   ``Let the enemy wait for coming blows of our revolutionary
fighters,'' said a statement issued by the Fatah-Revolutionary
Council. ``We shall strike doubly in merciless retaliation.''
   Abu Nidal, whose real name is Sabri al-Banna, broke away from
Yasser Arafat's Palestine Liberation Organization in 1974. He has
since claimed attacks against a series of civilian targets around
the world.
   The elusive terrorist mastermind tops wanted lists in the United
States and Europe. His whereabouts are not known, altough recent
reports said he has been shuttling between Libya and Algeria.
   His group had also vowed revenge after Wednesday's strike,
saying in a statement it would ``severely strike back against the
zionist enemy's arrogance and barbarism ... At the right time and
place.''
   Wednesday's attack also targeted Abu Nidal and DFLP bases,
killing seven people and wounding 15.
   The DFLP, headed by Nayef Hawatmeh, is one of the PLO's largest
factions.
</TEXT>
