<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     03-24 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korean Government Corruption Scandal Grows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Chun Doo-hwan decided
to cut short a visit to the United States after prosecutors linked
his brother to a growing government corruption scandal, officials
said Thursday.
   The prosecutor general's office said its inquiry of corruption
involving the Saemaul development group may be expanded to
investigate other possible wrongdoings under the Chun
administration.
   Chun, who has not been implicated, yielded power on Feb. 25 to
President Roh Tae-woo. But Chun has clung to a measure of power
behind the scenes.
   Prosecutors said Thursday that about 200 Saemaul and government
officials had been questioned since Monday to find out if Chun's
younger brother, former Saemaul leader Chun Kyung-hwan, and his
aides amassed fortunes by embezzling the group's funds.
   The former president was on a three-week private visit to the
United States in which he met with President Reagan on Wednesday,
but South Korean officials said Thursday he planned to leave early.
   The opposition parties contend the government is trying to hide
the extent of corruption under Chun. They have called for a broader
inquiry that would look into any corruption by the Chun family and
supporters.
   The ruling Democratic Justice Party has rejected the charges as
an attempt to blacken the government's reputation. But its leaders
promised to investigate any official corruption.
   The semi-official Saemaul, or ``new community,'' is a group of
community leaders that has evolved into a huge organization since
it was created in 1971 to promote urban development. It has
launched projects from building model communities to organizing
neighborhood clean-ups.
   But critics have said Saemaul worked with past authoritarian
governments to organize support and dole out patronage.
   Prosecutors said Thursday they had uncovered more evidence that
Saemaul officials embezzled millions of dollars, peddled government
patronage and misappropriated property. They said they questioned
government officials to find out if they aided corrruption within
Saemaul.
   Prosecutors also said the younger Chun was suspected of
diverting Saemaul funds to personal land speculation and of making
money with influence peddling. Local newspapers reported the
younger Chun and his aides may soon be officially charged with
corruption, but prosecutors declined to confirm the reports.
   Many in South Korea believe the new government is using the
Saemaul investigation to discredit the former president.
   Roh, a former general who helped put Chun into power with
military backing in 1980, has vowed to end authoritarian rule and
has been moving to cut ties with the former president. Top Chun
supporters have been removed from the ruling party and the former
president's role as a government adviser has been reduced to a
largely ceremonial function.
   However, members of the opposition Party for Peace and Democracy
say Roe may also have been involved in the corruption when he
served as home minister in 1982.
</TEXT>
