<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KeysDrilling     03-24 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Keys Drilling,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Exploration Off Florida Keys Dropped for Five Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KEY LARGO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal plan to allow oil and gas
exploration off the Florida Keys was dropped for five years
Thursday after state officials agreed to withdraw pending legal
challenges.
   ``This is to benefit not only the environment, but the tourist
industry and the people who live along the shores,'' Gov. Bob
Martinez said at a ceremony on a Key Largo beach. ``I think this
decision is a flagship-type decision that other states will use.''
   Martinez and U.S. Interior Department Secretary Donald Hodel
announced separately the settlement which removes about 11.1
million offshore acres from a five-year leasing plan. The preserved
area goes from Key Largo south around the Keys and Dry Tortugas and
north to Naples on the Gulf Coast. The area would extend 60 miles
west of Dry Tortugas.
   Three months of negotiations with Hodel and a January snorkeling
trip the men took together on the coral reefs off Key Largo
cemented the agreement, Martinez said. The Republican governor
denied that election year politics had any effect, but said Hodel
was aware of opposition from the Florida congressional delegation
and environmental groups.
   U.S. Sen. Bob Graham, a Democrat who built a reputation as a
defender of Florida's environment while preceeding Martinez in the
governor's mansion, noted that 130,000 people signed petitions
opposing oil drilling in the Keys of Florida, which has 2,200 miles
of coastline.
   ``This is the first time that (the federal government) have ever
deleted significant areas of a lease sale from a plan,'' said
Charles Lee, senior vice president of the Florida Audubon Society.
Legal challenges similar to Florida's have been brought by
Massachusetts, California and Alaska, with little result.
   Florida Attorney General Bob Butterworth had a pragmatic
explanation for Martinez's negotiating success: ``I think most
people thought it was, at best, insane to explore for oil off the
Florida Keys.''
   Under the settlement, Martinez and Butterworth agreed to drop as
early as Monday the lawsuit against the plan, and the state also
will drop its challenge to leasing 41,000 acres to the seaward of a
protected area planned off Cape San Blas, in the Florida Panhandle.
In return, Interior will impose a one-year moratorium on
development of any leases that should be awarded there.
   That Panhandle area is believed to contain gas, not oil.
Martinez has reserved his rights to object to oil development if
any should be found off Cape San Blas.
   The Interior Department last year included the Florida Straits _
Atlantic Ocean waters off the Keys _ in a five-year plan for
developing the oil resources of the Outer Continental Shelf,
shallow waters extending 200 miles from the U.S. shoreline.
   An Interior Department study released last year concluded that
the cumulative danger from drilling, leaking tankers and other
sources added up to a 48 percent chance of a major oil spill along
Florida's coast within 35 years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
