<DOCNO> AP880324-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 2120EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PersonalIncomes     03-24 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Personal Incomes,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Personal Incomes, Consumer Spending Increased in February</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans' personal incomes rose at the
fastest clip in four months during February while consumer spending
was propelled upward by a rebound in car sales, the government
reported Thursday.
   The Commerce Department said personal incomes advanced 0.9
percent, reflecting strong employment gains in the past few months.
Spending rose 0.7 percent, up sharply from a tiny 0.1 percent
January increase.
   Economists said the new figures provided further evidence that
the economy has suffered no long-run effects from the October stock
market crash. Five months ago, analysts feared that consumer
worries about the future would cause them to cut back on spending
and could push the country into a recession.
   ``For people who were worried about a major consumer
retrenchment, these numbers are encouraging,'' said Sandra Shaber,
an economist with the Futures Group. ``As long as income gains hold
up, people will continue to spend.''
   Bruce Steinberg, an economist with Merrill Lynch, said consumer
spending will rise by about 3.5 percent in the first quarter of
this year, after adjusting for inflation, a major rebound after a
spending decline in the final three months of last year.
   He said consumer spending would be the major factor contributing
to expected economic growth during the January-March quarter of
around 2 percent, as measured by the gross national product.
   A few months ago many analysts worried that growth in the
current quarter actually would be a negative figure, indicating the
country was headed into a new recession.
   Steinberg said the fear now was that consumer spending would
spurt ahead at such a fast pace that production bottlenecks could
occur and inflation would be rekindled. But Ms. Shaber said she did
not consider this a danger because she believed slower income
growth in the months ahead would slow the growth of spending as
well.
   Analysts said the February gain in incomes, which followed a 0.3
percent January rise and was the best showing since a 1.9 percent
October increase, reflected good employment news. The jobless rate
fell to an 8{ year low of 5.7 percent during the month.
   The key category of wages and salaries climbed by $15.4 billion
in February, a 0.7 percent increase which was the fastest advance
since November.
   Disposable income, the amount left over after taxes are paid,
climbed 1.1 percent in February, almost double the 0.6 percent
January increase. It was the best showing since a 2.1 percent rise
in October and was credited in part to tax cuts showing up as
employers held back less from paychecks.
   The individual tax cuts were the last round of reductions
scheduled under the landmark 1986 tax overhaul legislation.
   The 0.7 percent increase in personal consumption spending was
the biggest advance since a 0.8 percent rise in December. It
reflected a jump of $7.4 billion in sales of durable goods as
consumers responded to new incentive programs for autos. Durable
goods sales had fallen $2.4 billion in January.
   With incomes rising faster than spending, Americans' savings
rate climbed as well, rising to 5.2 percent of after-tax income
last month, the highest level since October.
   Purchases of non-durable goods _ items not expected to last
three years _ rose $2 billion in February after having fallen $7.7
billion in January. Purchases of services, including housing costs,
increased $12.4 billion following a $13.7 billion January increase.
   Farm incomes increased $8.5 billion in February after a decline
of $8.2 billion in Janaury. The big February gain and the large
January decline were both attributed to swings in government
subsidy payments to farmers.
</TEXT>
