<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Nicaragua-Future Bjt   03-24 0663</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Future, Bjt,650</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting a0748 to correct cycle designator to AM</NOTE>
<HEAD>Agreement Could Mean Post-Contra Era</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA </BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cease-fire agreement signed by the
Nicaraguan government and resistance forces appears to signify the
onset of the post-Contra era in Nicaragua and an entirely new
political dynamic in that country.
   The administration was officially upbeat about the agreement but
the Contras, with little prospect of receiving more U.S. military
aid, were forced to drop virtually all the concessions they had
been seeking earlier this year.
   The agreement clearly falls short of the administration goal of
an ``irreversible'' democratic process in Nicaragua as its price
for suspending aid to the Contras.
   Achievement of that objective is apparently dependent on
Sandinista good will coupled with whatever diplomatic and economic
pressures the industrialized democracies can muster to prod the
Nicaraguans in that direction.
   In theory at least, the Nicaraguan war could be revived if
upcoming talks break down. But the short-term prospect is for the
dismantling of the Contras accompanied by a number of gestures by
the Sandinistas, including a phased release of prisoners,
permission for political exiles to return, participation of Contra
representatives in a national dialogue and guarantees of free
expression.
   All of this was agreed to in the Sandinista-Contra cease-fire
talks this week. Still, the Contras have relatively little to show
for their six-year effort, particularly when compared with their
goals as recently as late January.
   At the time, they still were receiving U.S. military supplies
and were cautiously optimistic about the prospects for more aid
when that issue came to a congressional vote in early February. But
Contra aid foes prevailed on that vote.
   The Contras' settlement terms in late January called for the
implementation of 17 democratic reforms during a proposed 30-day
cease-fire period. They demanded gradual disarmament of both sides,
the repatriation of Soviet bloc military advisers, formation of a
single ``apolitical'' national army, suspension of compulsory
military service and the disbanding of the Sandinista militia.
   These demands received no attention at all or were dismissed
with no more than vague references in the communique signed
Wednesday night.
   Assuming that the Contras are dismantled, several questions
arise: Will President Daniel Ortega pursue with vigor the
communization of Nicaragua, as administration hardliners fear? Will
he strengthen his ties to the leftist insurgency in El Salvador?
Will he proceed with plans to acquire MiG jet fighters from the
Soviets? Will he build up the Nicaraguan armed forces to 600,000,
as his defense minister suggested? Will he move toward a uniquely
Nicaraguan system, which is neither modeled after Cuba nor his
democratic neighbor, Costa Rica? Or will there be a genuine
national reconciliation in Nicaragua, as Ortega suggests?
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz outlined in generally
positive terms the administration's reaction to the cease-fire
agreement, calling it an ``important step forward.''
   Other officials, asking not to be identified, said they
preferred not to offer their own assessments of the agreement even
on an anonymous basis because to do so would undercut Shultz.
   This suggests continued skepticism within the administration
about the terms the Contras agreed to and continued anger with the
Congress for letting the rebels down.
   Ever since the Central America peace agreement was signed last
Aug. 7, the administration had been steadily scaling back on its
expectations in Central America.
   Last fall, the administration was asking the Congress for $270
million in Contra aid. Faced with congressional opposition,
President Reagan lowered that figure to $36.2 million, with only 10
per cent of that earmarked for military aid.
   That proposal was defeated seven weeks ago and Congress mandated
an end to all aid deliveries by Feb. 29. Slightly more than three
weeks later, the Contras settled with the Sandinistas, accepting
terms that they would have rejected out of hand not long ago.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR`S NOTE _ George Gedda has covered foreign affairs for the
Associated Press since 1968.
</TEXT>
