<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 2156EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-GMRecalls     03-24 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GM Recalls,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Orders Recall Of 1985 GM Cars And Light Trucks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly half a million 1985 cars and light
trucks made by General Motors Corp. must be recalled because they
fail to meet federal air pollution standards, the Environmental
Protection Agency said Thursday.
   A faulty thermal vacuum switch is part of the reason the
vehicles' exhaust contains excess carbon monoxide and evaporated
gasoline, the EPA said.
   The vehicles affected by the recall are equipped with 5.0 liter
(305 cubic inches) and 5.7 liter (350 cubic inches) engines, the
EPA said.
   They were sold as the Chevrolet Impala, Caprice Classic, Camaro,
Monte Carlo and El Camino; the Pontiac Firebird, Bonneville, Grand
Prix and Parisienne; and the GMC Caballero, EPA said. Models sold
in California, which are built to stricter standards, are also
included.
   ``Earlier, we offered to recall the vehicles to replace the
thermostatic vacuum switch,'' said Jane Mott, GM spokeswoman in
Detroit. ``We will review the order and determine how best to
respond.''
   Such recall orders by the EPA are rare and generally indicate
the agency and a manufacturer could not agree on something, such as
the cause of the problem, its scope, the necessary repair, terms of
the recall or something else. Most recalls are made voluntarily.
   Ms. Mott said GM told the EPA it believed replacing the switch
on the vehicles would be sufficient to bring emissions into
compliance with federal standards.
   The EPA, however, said its tests showed that ``replacement of
the (switch) alone will not completely remedy the problem and that
additional repairs may be necessary.''
   GM has 45 days either to request a public hearing to contest the
order, or to submit a repair plan for EPA's approval before notices
are mailed to owners.
   The company last year recalled more than a million vehicles from
the 1982 and 1983 model years for similar problems.
</TEXT>
