<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1614EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-S&Ls-Losses     03-24 0732</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-S&Ls-Losses,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>1987 S&L Losses Highest in Half-Century</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The savings and loan industry, drained by
insolvent institutions in Texas, last year recorded its worst loss
since the Great Depression, the government said Thursday.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board said a $3.2 billion loss in the
last three months of 1987 pushed the industry's red ink for the
year to a record $6.8 billion.
   That was nearly 50 percent greater than the previous
post-Depression record of $4.6 billion, set in 1981, when the prime
lending rate soared above 20 percent.
   ``I hope it's the worst we'll ever see,'' said James W.
Christian, chief economist of the U.S. League of Savings
Insitutions, the industry's largest trade group.
   The nation's 3,147 federally insured S&Ls lost $1.8 billion in
the third quarter of last year and $1.9 billion in the spring. They
earned $100 million in the first three months of the year and had a
modest $132 million profit for all of 1986.
   In contrast, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. said earlier
this month that the nation's 13,700 federally insured commercial
banks earned $3.7 billion in 1987. Still, it was their lowest
profit since 1933.
   Despite the overall loss for the S&L industry, 66 percent of the
S&Ls earned money in the fourth quarter. The $1.3 billion earnings
of 2,089 S&Ls partly offset the $4.5 billion losses of the
remaining 1,058 institutions.
   For the year, the profitable two-thirds of the industry earned
$6.6 billion, which was more than wiped out by the $13.4 billion
deficit of the money-losing S&Ls.
   The percentage of institutions earning a profit has declined
steadily for two years, from 81 percent in the first quarter of
1986 to 66 percent at the end of last year.
   James Barth, chief economist of the bank board, said S&L losses
were heavily concentrated in the Southwest, which is dependent on
the ailing oil and gas industry.
   Barth said the worst 20 institutions _ most of them in the
Southwest _ lost a total of $2.1 billion in the final quarter of
last year, accounting for two-thirds of the overall industry loss.
   An unprofitable instituion is not necessarily insolvent. An S&L
is considered insolvent when its loans and other assets are worth
less than what it owes to depositors and other creditors.
   The bank board said 345 S&Ls were insolvent at the end of 1987
under regulatory accounting principles, 109 of them in Texas alone.
There were 510 insolvent S&Ls under the stricter accounting
principles that will be used beginning next year.
   By another measure of health, return on assets, savings
institutions' performance was not quite as bad as 1981 and 1982.
The return was negative 0.56 percent last year, compared with
negative 0.73 percent in 1981 and minus 0.65 percent in 1982.
   Barth said some of the overall industry loss in 1987 can be
attributed to a decrease in the corporate tax rate. He said some
S&Ls decided to push profits into 1988, when the top tax rate is 34
percent, rather than take them in 1987, when the rate was 40
percent.
   Barth said he believed the industry's problems have ``plateaued
out'' and that ``there is some light at the end of the tunnel'' in
the Southwest.
   But Martin A. Regalia, chief economist of the National Council
of Savings Institutions, warned that most economists believe
interest rates will edge higher and said Southwest real estate
shows no sign of a sharp rebound.
   Regalia said the performance of the thrift industry this year
will depend on how quickly the bank board resolves problems at
Texas institutions.
   ``You have to be as expeditious as possible at getting them
closed down. So far I think (the bank board) has recognized the
problem. Now it's time to get out and do it,'' he said.
   Lack of money to pay depositors had forced the Federal Savings
and Loan Insurance Corp., which insures deposits to $100,000, to
keep many insolvent S&Ls open. Now that money is flowing into the
fund from a $10.8 billion recapitalization authorized by Congress
in August, the bank board is moving to close ailing institutions or
merge them with healthier S&Ls.
   Last month, the bank board announced a plan to spend $6 billion
to $7 billion in Texas over the next several years, but it doesn't
anticipate announcements on specific S&Ls before early April.
</TEXT>
