<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Gephardt-Options     03-24 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gephardt-Options,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Candidate Gephardt: Could Run For House and White House</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gephardt Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Gephardt could run for both the House
and the White House if he so chose _ at least temporarily.
   Under Missouri law, Gephardt could file for re-election by next
Tuesday's deadline and still remain in the presidential race at
least until May 17, the deadline for withdrawing from the state
primary ballot. If Gephardt withdrew by then and decided to
continue his presidential bid, filing for his congressional seat
would re-open for five days.
   Gephardt has another option, according to Cheri Ghan, a
spokeswoman for the Missouri secretary of state.
   He could file for re-election and would remain on the Aug. 2
Missouri state primary ballot even if he somehow managed to win a
spot on the Democratic presidential ticket in July.
   In that case, Gephardt would have a decision to make after the
state primary, if he won. Democratic officials would select the
congressional nominee if Gephardt gave up his congressional seat to
be part of the presidential ticket.
</TEXT>
