<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Meese-Pipeline     03-24 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Pipeline,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McFarlane Testifies in Meese-Iraqi Pipeline Grand Jury Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former national security adviser Robert C.
McFarlane testified for three hours Thursday before a federal grand
jury investigating Attorney General Edwin Meese III's ties to a $1
billion Iraqi oil pipeline.
   McFarlane, who declined to comment during a break in the grand
jury proceedings, became involved in the pipeline project in the
spring and summer of 1985 through contacts with Meese, longtime
Meese friend E. Robert Wallach and Wallach's client, Swiss oilman
Bruce Rappaport.
   McFarlane was accompanied to the federal courthouse by legal
counsel, Peter Morgan, who said his client is a witness in the
grand jury investigation.
   Independent counsel James McKay is investigating whether Meese
may have violated the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act in connection
with the pipeline project.
   In a September 1985 memo to Meese relating Wallach's
conversations with Rappaport, Wallach said a portion of up to $700
million from the pipeline would be paid to the Israeli Labor Party
of then-Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres.
   Meese has said he doesn't recall reading the reference to Labor
Party payments in the memo, which was found in the attorney
general's files at the Justice Department last year in connection
with McKay's investigation.
   McKay is presenting evidence to the grand jury in an attempt to
determine whether there was a conspiracy to pay bribes to Israeli
politicians to ensure that Israel would not bomb the pipeline
passing through Iraq and Jordan close to the Israeli border.
Rappaport has denied making or offering bribes, and denies that
there was any plan to do so.
   Wallach went to Meese for help on the pipeline in May 1985 and
the attorney general referred him to McFarlane, who then was
President Reagan's national security adviser.
   The referral resulted in a meeting in June 1985 between
McFarlane, Wallach and Rappaport.
   The pipeline's backers wanted to enlist the support of the U.S.
government in assembling an insurance package that would protect
the project in the event of an Israeli attack.
   On March 11 in connection with the Iran-Contra arms and money
affair, McFarlane pleaded guilty to misdemeanor charges that he
misled Congress in 1985 by assuring lawmakers the Reagan
administration was not helping arm Nicaraguan rebels during a ban
on U.S. military aid.
</TEXT>
