<1ST_LINE>u w AM-North-Demonstration     03-24 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-North-Demonstration,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pro-, Anti-North Demonstrators Exchange Insults</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Iran-Contra Arraignment Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angry shouts erupted Thursday between 30
supporters of defendants in the Iran-Contra case and three
anti-Contra protesters outside the federal courthouse.
   An elderly woman ripped up signs calling Oliver L. North an
``American hero'' and shouted obscenities at demonstrators for
addressing her as ``old lady'' and ``communist.''
   Several police officers stood a few feet away but took no action.
   The woman, who identified herself as Lillian Geckter of New
Haven, Conn., boasted that inside the court building where North,
John M. Poindexter, Richard V. Secord and Albert Hakim pleaded
innocent to a 23-count indictment, she looked North in the eye and
said: ``Don't you smile at me, traitor.''
   The pro-North demonstrators chanted, ``Ollie's right, Wright's
wrong,'' a slap at House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, who led
defeat of Contra military aid in the House.
   ``Fund the Contras, not the lawyers,'' the group shouted as
independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh, the prosecutor, told
reporters he was pleased that U.S. District Judge Gerhard Gesell
intended to handle the case expeditiously.
   Walsh, who said he would not comment on the case now that it is
under Gesell's control, was booed by the protesters as he got into
his car.
   North emerged from a door far from the demonstrators, but his
car was mobbed by supporters and scores of reporters and
photographers as it passed slowly in front of the building where
the crowd had gathered. North smiled and waved from the back seat
but remained in the gray limousine.
   ``I think Ollie is getting a bum rap out of all this,'' said
Steve Bridgett of Greenville, Ill., who said he belonged to no
political organization.
   Peter Flaherty, chairman of Citizens for Reagan, said his and
several other groups were represented. ``We came to show our
friendship and support for Ollie and our solidarity with him,'' he
said.
   For a time during the arraignment, Aron Kay of New York City was
the lone anti-Contra demonstrator.
   After North passed by and Kay shouted, ``Ollie North's a liar,''
several pro-North demonstrators taunted him with, ``Why don't you
get a job?'' and several more caustic suggestions.
   Kay, who described himself as a long-time peace activist,
shouted back, ``Our job is protesting.''
</TEXT>
