<1ST_LINE>r i AM-IslamicConference     03-24 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Islamic Conference,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranians Pull Out of Islamic Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chemical Weapons, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran angrily left an Islamic conference
Thursday after fellow Moslems decried its failure to heed
cease-fire calls in its war with Iraq and accused it of instigating
rioting in the holy city of Mecca.
   Iraq and Egypt said the withdrawal proved the ``loneliness'' of
Iran's stance toward the Islamic world.
   The Iranian envoy to the meeting of the Organization of Islamic
Conference, Mohammed Ali Taskhiri, flew out of Jordan at the head
of his five-man delegation.
   ``We were not happy,'' Taskhiri, his voice quavering with anger,
said in a telephone interview. He said his group boycotted meetings
Wednesday night and Thursday.
   ``The conference is taking place only to serve the interests of
a certain country,'' he said, referring to Iraq. ``Therefore, we
don't see why we should stay at this meeting.''
   Egypt and other Arab countries were drafting a resolution on the
Iran-Iraq conflict to submit to foreign ministers of the 46-member
conference.
   Sources close to the conference confirmed that the draft
denounces Iran's failure to heed last July's U.N. Security Council
resolution 598, which calls for a cease-fire in the 7{-year-old war.
   The sources, speaking on condition they not be identified
further, said the draft also criticizes Iran's purported leadership
of the violence in Mecca, Saudi Arabia, and calls for future
``security measures'' to protect Moslem pilgrims.
   In a statement to the Jordanian government announcing its
withdrawl, the Iranian delegation specified it was unhappy with the
draft ``resolution on the gulf war...and the resolution on the holy
places.'' The text of the statement was provided by one of the
sources.
   The conference sources also said the draft of the final
communique, likely to be issued by Friday, also called for:
   _ An immediate Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan;
   _ Support for the 15-week-old Palestinian uprising in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip;
   _ Guaranteed rights for Moslem minorities in Bulgaria and other
countries where they might suffer persecution;
   _ Unspecified measures against air piracy.
   Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz said ``Iran's withdrawal
demonstrates its loneliness'' in the ranks of Moslem countries.
``They wanted to express their voice, or better, their lies, to the
organization, but they did not find ears.''
   Egyptian Foreign Minister Esmat Abdel-Meguid, whose country was
the target of Iranian criticism earlier in the conference, echoed
Aziz, saying: ``The voice of the Iranian representative is an odd
voice and it represents the loneliness in which Iran lives.''
   The Iranians attended the meeting after boycotting last year's
summit of Islamic heads of state in Kuwait, which Tehran accuses of
aiding Iraq's war effort.
   Iran, which is Persian and not Arab, sent a low-level delegation
to the Amman meeting. Taskhiri is head of the foreign relations
department in Iran's Islamic Guidance Ministry.
   Iran and Iraq have been blasting each other's cities for more
than three weeks with missiles and air raids, and the Iranians have
pushed into northeast Iraq.
   Iran was lambasted in Amman for allegedly inciting rioting last
year in Mecca in which 402 Moslems, 275 of them Iranian, were
killed.
   Saudi authorities said the pilgrims were killed in a stampede
triggered by Iranian rioters, and in subsequent violence. Iran
claimed police mowed them down with machine guns.
   The Saudi Foreign Minister, Prince Saud al-Faisal, said his
country will restrict the number of pilgrims to Mecca this year as
a ``temporary measure'' because facilities there needed to be
expanded. He did not elaborate.
   Iran has said it will send 150,000 people to this year's
pilgrimage.
   The Saudis reportedly have made it clear that Mecca and Medina,
Islam's holiest shrines, can accommodate only around 1 million
pilgrims at a time.
</TEXT>
