<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1655EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-LaRouche-Money     03-24 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LaRouche-Money,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FEC Decides to Grant Matching Funds to LaRouche</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Election Commission on Thursday
declared fringe presidential candidate Lyndon LaRouche eligible for
federal matching funds, even as a former aide was testifying
elsewhere of being pressured to wring donations out of people for
LaRouche's 1984 campaign.
   LaRouche is standing trial in Boston federal court on a charge
relating to alleged irregularity in his 1984 campaign.
   While the Federal Election Commission was certifying LaRouche to
receive federal funds for his 1988 campaign, former aide Charles
Tate testified at the trial that LaRouche solicitors were warned in
1984 that that falling short of daily fund-raising quotas was ``the
moral equivalent of treason'' and would result in the collapse of
Western civilization.
   The FEC, on a 5-1 vote, said that LaRouche has fulfilled the
requirements for eligibility to receive matching funds. But the
commission also said special review procedures would be undertaken
to evaluate each of his submissions for matching funds, in light of
irregularities found in his first submission.
   LaRouche spokeswoman Mary Jane Freeman said the ruling was
``terrific.'' She noted the campaign had ``no problem with the
conditions'' the FEC imposed.
   In voting with the majority, Commissioner Scott Thomas said,
``Presidential candidates and campaigns can come in many different
shapes and colors.''
   ``Overall it does look like there is substantial support for a
presidential campaign from American citizens for Mr. LaRouche,'' he
said noting that Larouche has raised more than $2 million from
contributors.
   But Commissioner Joan Aikens opposed the majority, saying an FEC
survey of LaRouche contributors raised ``a question of patent
irregularity'' in fund raising.
   A survey by the FEC's audit staff had indicated that 6 percent
of 713 LaRouche contributors contacted had not intended their
checks to go to his campaign.
   The survey was undertaken because some contributor checks had
the letters ``LDC,'' presumably for LaRouche Democratic Committee,
written over ``SDI'' as the payee. And some checks contained memo
notations regarding AIDS or SDI _ the first referring to the
disease and the second referring to President Reagan's Strategic
Defense Initiative _ suggesting the donors may not have intended to
give money to a presidential campaign, but to one of those causes.
   FEC auditors said many people who responded to the survey
``described instances where he@she 1. felt pressured into making a
contribution, 2. made contributions believing that the contribution
was for a specific purpose other than furthering Lyndon H. LaRouche
Jr.'s presidential nomination campaign, 3. made loans to the
campaign, and 4. had contributed to a number of LaRouche's
interests, while making all checks payable to LDC.''
   The auditors had recommended that LaRouche be found ineligible
for matching funds, but the FEC legal staff had said ``patent
irregularities indicated by the survey results do not justify an
unfavorable eligibility report.''
   Instead of the usual five-day approval period, a review period
of 25 days will be allowed in which the FEC staff will check for
irregularities in the checks he submits to be matched.
   In addition any checks written out simply to LDC, or those with
memo notations ``indicating lack of donative intent'' will not be
matched, the commission said.
   To be certified for matching funds, a candidate must raise
$100,000 across 20 states in individual contributions of $250 or
less. After becoming eligible, the candidates can receive matching
funds for each contribution of $250 or less that they raise
privately.
   LaRouche is on trial in Boston, charged with conspiracy to
obstruct a grand jury investigation into alleged credit card fraud
and other irregularities in his 1984 campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
