<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Reagan-School     03-24 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-School,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Praises `Free-Market' Trend in Rewarding Teachers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Thursday lauded a trend
toward ``free-market principles'' in education that provide
incentives for teachers who achieve superior performance.
   Joining Education Secretary William J. Bennett in a visit to
Oakton High School just outside Washington, Reagan said recent
tours of this sort ``have strengthened my confidence in our
country's future.''
   But the president said much work still lies ahead if the nation
is to bring about the sort of educational reforms called for in a
1983 government report, ``A Nation at Risk.''
   The president said he expects a status report on American
education, which he is to receive next month from Bennett, to
``tell us what things we still must do'' as well as what progress
has been made.
   He also said that interest in teaching has increased in recent
years, partly because ``we've begun to introduce free-market
principles like incentivies and accountability to education.''
   He praised Fairfax County, in which Vienna is located, for
initiating a plan in which ``career ladders, performance-based pay
and other initiatives help to keep good teachers in the
profession.''
   But Reagan said no improvements in the caliber of instruction or
the quality of teachers will be helpful ``if a school has a drug
problem.''
   ``If students are using drugs, then no education reform can
work,'' the president told several hundred students and teachers in
the school auditorium.
   Reagan made several light-hearted references to his boyhood
school days, saying he wasn't a particularly good student, and
telling how he'd been called to the principal's office once. ``It
wasn't an invitation,'' he quipped.
   When a student asked Reagan whether he could attend the seniors'
high school graduation June 15, he smiled broadly and said he
didn't know if he could make it.
   ``Some people think I'm the most powerful man in the world,'' he
said, (but) ``every day they hand me a piece of paper that tells me
everything I'm going to be doing every 15 minutes.''
</TEXT>
