<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KeysBridge     03-24 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Keys Bridge,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Broken Bridge Leaves Hundreds Stranded In the Florida Keys</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMORADA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A broken drawbridge that stranded
hundreds of motorists, some holding parties and others asleep in
their cars, was fixed just in time for Thursday's morning
rush-hour, police said.
   ``There are a lot of happy people out there,'' said Monroe
County Sheriff's Sgt. Lee Pinder.
   The Snake Creek Bridge reopened to traffic at 8:10 a.m. after
several gears jammed on the bridge Wednesday and locked it in the
upright position for more than 15 hours, snarling traffic for 30
miles on U.S. 1, the main highway from Miami to Key West.
   Every hotel room on both sides of the drawbridge at Plantation
Key was taken, and hundreds of people spent the night in their
cars. Police said motorists were remarkably patient.
   ``There were no arrests, no wrecks, no real problems,'' Pinder
said.
   One man who suffered a mild heart attack had to be ferried
across Snake Creek to an ambulance, Pinder said.
   A crane arrived from Key West at about 1 a.m. Thursday, and two
barges were brought in to aid state Department of Transportation
workers who fixed the bridge, said Monroe County Sgt. Scott
Cockrell.
   James Rocheleau, 25, and his friend George Kotval, 23, sat in
their car at the front of the line going north.
   ``You just have to roll with the punches,'' said Rocheleau, who
said he served with the Marines in Beirut, Lebanon. ``I got it
worse in the Marine Corps anyway. We'll just sit and wait.''
   Some Florida State University students on spring break had a
party at the Holiday Isle hotel.
   ``I had 10 rooms and I rented them all in about 10 minutes,''
said Alfrieda Bressler, night manager at the Chesapeake Motel in
Islamorada. ``It's not unusual for the bridge to get stuck, but
it's usually only for an hour or two. This is the worst I've ever
seen it.''
   In Florida City, the Highway Patrol set up a roadblock to turn
back southbound drivers.
   The Snake Creek Bridge is expected to remain closed to boat
traffic for two to three weeks, restricting boat traffic to those
small enough to move under the span, Pinder said.
</TEXT>
