<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0627EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-StockCrash     03-24 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Stock Crash,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Markey Plans To Draft Market Reforms Without Administration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House finance subcommittee
said Wednesday he will write legislation reforming the nation's
financial markets without waiting for the Reagan administration to
resolve disputes among warring regulatory agencies.
   ``For the investors of this country, justice delayed is justice
denied,'' said Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass.
   At a four-hour hearing of his House Energy and Commerce
subcommittee on finance, Markey sharply criticized the creation of
an administration working group to coordinate recommendations on
what should be done to prevent a recurrence of the Oct. 19 stock
market crash.
   The panel, headed by Treasury Undersecretary George D. Gould,
has the job of trying to resolve a turf fight among the Federal
Reserve Board, Securities and Exchange Commission and the Commodity
Futures Trading Commission over regulating the various financial
markets.
   President Reagan signed an order last Friday creating the panel
and gave it 60 days to report back to him. His spokesman, Marlin
Fitzwater, warned that the issues ``may not be resolved quickly or
without considerable reflection.''
   Markey, however, complained that the recommendations delivered
in Janaury by a presidential task force headed by former New Jersey
Sen. Nicholas Brady should have been enough for the administration
to make up its mind.
   He complained that waiting two more months would make it
increasingly difficult to pass legislation this year, adding, ``In
my judgment Congress must act this year.''
   ``The greatest danger facing our financial system is the safe
course of delay,'' he said.
   Gould responded that his panel, which will include
representatives of the SEC, the Federal Reserve and the commodities
commission, is not conducting another study.
   ``We are anxious to create action from this, not simply more
discussion,'' he said.
   Markey said his committee, with the help of Brady, would proceed
on a ``parallel track'' without waiting for Gould's group to
formulate a position.
   Brady's commission called for giving the Federal Reserve the
power to coordinate regulation of the stock, options and futures
markets.
   The SEC, which regulates stocks and options, also wants
jurisdiction over stock futures, which currently are overseen by
the commodities commission. That agency opposes jurisdictional
changes, and the Fed has rejected taking on the additional
responsibility recommended by Brady.
   Markey has called for one regulator over stocks and stock
futures, but did not say which agency should get that power.
   Brady, who agreed to help Markey write his bill, said he did not
agree that the creation of the Gould group would unduly delay
action and said he did not see why Congress and the administration
could not work simultaneously.
   Meeting with reporters after the hearing, Brady moderated
earlier remarks on the urgency for reform.
   In a line that has become much quoted, Brady had compared the
markets to a gun and said, ``We are looking down the barrel of the
same gun, and it is still loaded.''
   But on Wednesday, he said, ``I didn't say anybody was going to
pull the trigger.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
