<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru a0761 03-24 0835</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0761,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nicaraguan Cease-Fire Gets Warm Response in Washington</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS grafs 10-11 pvs, `Congressional leaders ... similar
group,' with 2 grafs to FIX that talks began Wednesday, sted
Thursday, and to INSERT dropped word `aid'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress and the Reagan administration warmly
welcomed a Nicaraguan cease-fire agreement Thursday, and some
officials said it could usher in a new era of bipartisan U.S.
policymaking on Central America.
   ``We consider this agreement to be an important step forward,''
said Secretary of State George Shultz, who added that the truce
leaves ``no excuse'' for continued Soviet-bloc weapons shipments to
the leftist Managua government.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, said the Nicaraguan agreement
marks ``a new chapter in the unhappy history of that war-torn
country'' and vowed to move ahead before Easter on a package of
humanitarian aid for the Contra rebels.
   ``This is a bad day for the cynics,'' said Sen. Christopher
Dodd, D-Conn., a leading Contra opponent. ``A piece of paper has
been signed by people who many thought would never be able to sit
down face to face.''
   But the White House and some in Congress also said the accord,
while a strong sign of new health for the regional peace process,
rests heavily on promises of future moves by both sides that could
prove difficult.
   President Reagan, getting into his limousine after speaking to
high school students in suburban Vienna, Va., was asked whether he
thought the cease-fire agreement would hold up.
   ``I don't know. We're looking carefully at it,'' he replied.
   ``There is a lot of room for encouragement here, yes, but
there's also a lot of room for skepticism, and I'm trying to
balance those two off,'' said White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater.
   ``We're beginning the process. We need to watch it. We've seen
processes like this start before and fail,'' he said. ``This seems
like a more concrete step, and there certainly reason to be
hopeful. But I do not want to play down the skepticism side of it
either because we are skeptical.''
   Congressional leaders and the administration began conferring on
a new package of aid to the Contras on Wednesday, and more meetings
were scheduled for Monday. Wright said a vote could come later next
week and food, clothing and medicine could begin flowing to the
rebels by Easter.
   The cease-fire agreement reached Wednesday night in Sapoa,
Nicaragua, calls for ``exclusively humanitarian'' aid for the
rebels to be channeled through a ``neutral'' organization,
presumably the United Nations, the Red Cross, the Organization of
American States or some similar group.
   Wright said any aid package would have to conform to that
language, and Democratic leaders on the issue said that would rule
out provisions for future military aid to the rebels.
   But some Republicans insisted that any aid bill include
provision for a quick vote in Congress on new military aid if the
Sandinistas fail to live up to promises made in the cease-fire
agreement, including amnesty and the release of prisoners.
   ``I think it is important to keep in there some speeded-up
mechanism for the president and Congress to get together in case
the peace process fails,'' said Sen. Dan Evans, R-Wash., a sponsor
of a Contra aid package that includes such a guaranteed vote.
   ``It's a recognition that there is still lots of skepticism,
maybe even suspicion, all the way around,'' Evans said. ``People
have been at each other's throats, and that's not going to
dissipate easily.''
   But of such suggestions, Wright said: ``I think it would be
counterproductive to talk about it ... We don't want to rekindle
the war.''
   House Majority Whip Tony Coelho, D-Calif., said compromise on
language about future Contra aid was possible.
   ``We are willing to talk to the Republicans about anything, but
we are not willing to set up a process that the Nicaraguans could
interpret as allowing for more military aid,'' Coelho said.
   ``It looks like there may be a pretty good possibility of
Congress getting together on something the administration could
buy,'' Evans said.
   ``We haven't had a strong voice for American policy in Central
America in five years'' because of partisan divisions over the
administration's Contra policy,'' he said. ``We would finally be
sending a clear message.''
   ``For heaven's sake, if the Nicaraguans, who have been shooting
at each other, can agree, surely Republicans and Democrats can
agree,'' Wright said.
   The promises of quick action on a new aid package for the rebels
contrasted sharply with the inaction of recent weeks. The issue had
been stalled since the House narrowly defeated a $30 million
humanitarian aid package on March 3, and the rebels have been
without U.S. assistance since Feb. 29.
   Coelho said lawmakers had been intentionally moving slowly on
the issue since March 17, when Contra leaders called Wright's
office and said they were optimistic about achieving a cease-fire
in the talks that began Monday and asked that Congress hold back on
voting for new aid.
</TEXT>
