<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Taiwan-Plutonium     03-24 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taiwan-Plutonium,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taiwan Reminded By US On Nuclear Non-Proliferation Pledge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department's chief spokesman said on
Wednesday that Taiwan has been ``repeatedly'' reminded to stick to
a pledge against building nuclear weapons, but he declined to
comment on a report the United States pressured the Asian nation to
stop work on a plutonium processing plant.
   Taiwan halted work on the secret plant, which could have
processed plutonium, a key component of nuclear weapons, and shut
its largest civilian research reactor at U.S. insistence, The New
York Times reported.
   It was not clear whether the planned installation, which could
have extracted plutonium from spent reactor fuel, indicated a
decision to build a bomb or just an attempt to keep open a nuclear
option, according to unnamed officials quoted by newspaper.
   State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman would neither
confirm nor deny the report, but he acknowledged that the United
States has expressed concerns to Taiwan about the proliferation of
nuclear weapons. And his comments suggested that if the United
States did indeed use pressure to stop the Taiwanese program, the
pressure worked.
   ``We've repeatedly conveyed the importance that the United
States, including both the administration and the Congress places
on Taiwan's adherence to its non-proliferation commitments, and we
are confident that Taiwan understands this,'' Redman said.
   ``It is our belief that Taiwan is not engaged in activities
which are inconsistent with its commitments,'' he said.
   He noted statements by Taiwanese leaders that they have no
intention of developing nuclear weapons. Also, Redman said that
Taiwan has undertaken obligations of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation
Treaty, in which countries agree to let international inspectors
monitor programs to make sure nuclear material is not being
diverted to use in weapons.
   ``All nuclear materials on Taiwan are subject to safeguards
applied by the International Atomic Energy Agency,'' Redman said.
``We are not aware of any violation of those safeguards.''
   According to officials quoted by the Times, the United States
learned of the project from Col. Chang Hsien-Yi, a top-level
informant at a Taiwanese research institute who left Taiwan a few
months ago with the help of the Central Intelligence Agency.
   Chang, deputy director of the nuclear energy research center at
the military-run Chungshan Institute of Science and Technology, has
been missing since January.
   Taiwanese newspaper reports said he might have fled to the
United States with documents showing that Taiwan planned to make
nuclear weapons. His whereabouts is unknown.
   U.S. officials said the effort to build an installation capable
of plutonium extraction violated Taiwan's secret commitment to the
United States that it would not undertake research to develop
atomic weapons, the Times reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880324-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1737EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Ozone-DuPont     03-24 0756</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ozone-Du Pont,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Major Maker of Ozone-Destroying CFCs Agrees To Stop Their
Manufacture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Du Pont Co., producer of one-quarter of
the chemicals destroying the Earth's ozone shield, plans to stop
making them because of new research showing decay of the ozone, the
company said Thursday.
   The company gave no deadline for ending manufacture of the
``fully halogenated chlorofluorocarbons,'' or CFCs. These
non-toxic, non-flammable compounds that Du Pont helped develop in
the 1930s are widely used as refrigeration fluids, cleaning
solvents, plastic foam blowing agents and, outside the United
States, as aerosol propellants.
   ``I don't see it in the near term,'' not for five years, but at
the end of such a period policymakers and the chemical industry
should know ``how rapidly the transition can take place,'' Joe
Steed, environment manager in Du Pont's Freon Products division,
said in an interview.
   ``Our intention is to move as smoothly as possible from these
compounds into alternatives,'' Steed said.
   Du Pont announced in January it had developed a substitute foam
blowing agent. Also, Petroferm Inc. has announced a replacement
solvent for CFCs, and other chemicals are in the works at several
companies.
   On Thursday the company began notifying customers, competitors,
employees and members of Congress of its new policy.
   Environmentalists were quick with praise, hailing Du Pont's
``courage'' and ``leadership.''
   As recently as March 4, Du Pont said a proposal from three
senators that the company immediately stop making CFCs was
``unwarranted and counterproductive.'' The senators _ Robert
Stafford, R-Vt.; Max Baucus, D-Mont.; and David Durenberger,
R-Minn. _ had written Du Pont Chairman Richard E. Heckert calling
on him to redeem the company's mid-1970s pledge to end CFC
production if a threat to health were shown.
   A March 15 report of scientists convened by the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration found a 2.3 percent decline in
ozone at mid-latitudes between 1969 and 1986, most probably the
result of CFC accumlations high in the atmosphere. That is
``important new information,'' Heckert wrote members of the
subcommittee on which the three senators serve.
   ``I hope it's clear that it's the science of last week we're
responding to,'' Steed said.
   Heckert's letter said the company believes ``the short-term risk
to health and the environment from CFCs is negligible'' but
``additional actions should be taken.''
   Ozone, a pollutant at ground level, at high altitudes blocks
ultraviolet rays of the sun that cause skin cancer. The
Environmental Protection Agency has estimated that a 1 percent
decrease in ozone thickness _ it would be only 3 millimeters thick
if it were at sea level _ causes a 2 percent to 3 percent increase
in ultraviolet and a 4.8 percent to 7.5 percent increase in the
most common skin cancers.
   Last fall in Montreal, major producers agreed on a treaty, now
signed by 31 nations but ratified only by the United States and
Mexico, agreeing to cut CFC production 20 percent in 1992 and
another 30 percent in 1998. The Environmental Defense Fund has
estimated that the two cuts could amount to only 35 percent instead
of 50 percent if all the exemptions are used.
   The treaty was accelerated, many experts acknowledge, by a 1985
finding that over Antarctica, ozone declines sharply each spring _
by 50 percent last year.
   Du Pont plans ``to urge all nations to treat the new scientific
information seriously, accelerate ratification of the Montreal
protocol, and then immediately initiate the protocol's assessment
process to consider further global limitations,'' Heckert's letter
said.
   Richard Barnett, chairman of the trade group Alliance for a
Responsible CFC Policy, said in a statement President Reagan should
``personally contact the heads of government'' of participating
countries asking that they ratify the Montreal agreement.
   ``This is a sterling example of corporate environmental
leadership that ought to be emulated worldwide,'' and shows that
``technology can solve environmental problems,'' in this case by
coming up with substitutes, said Dan Dudek, an economist with the
Environmental Defense Fund.
   About 2.3 billion pounds of CFC compounds are made worldwide
each year, with more than 2,000 Du Pont employees producing about
25 percent from plants in Canada, Japan, Brazil, Argentina, Mexico,
the Netherlands and the United States. The company says it gets
$600 million annually from CFC sales, about 2 percent of total
sales revenue.
   Steed said that ``Over the long term, it's our goal'' that jobs
making replacement compounds should offset lost CFC jobs.
   The U.S. plants are in Antioch, Calif.; Louisville, Ky.;
Montague, Mich.; Corpus Christi, Texas; and Deepwater, N.J.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880324-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1738EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Summit     03-24 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Belittles Soviet Technology For Spotting Nuclear Missiles On
Ships</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States belittled Soviet technology
for detecting nuclear missiles aboard ships and snubbed an
invitation this week to see the process before the May 29-June 2
summit meeting in Moscow, a senior U.S. official said Thursday.
   During three days of pre-summit talks in Washington this week,
Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze offered to let the
United States participate in an experiment to test the system in
April.
   Shevardnadze hailed the system as a technological milestone in
missile detection that would help the superpowers achieve their
goal of a summit agreement to cut long-range nuclear arsenals.
   The senior U.S. official said, however, ``we're not interested''
because the system doesn't detect nuclear sea-launched cruise
missiles, as the Soviets claim.
   ``The Soviets could not explain how this experiment would tell
us more than we already know,'' the official said. ``Such
technology would not be effective under realistic conditions.''
   It could not, for example, tell the difference between nuclear
warheads and atomic propulsion systems used on many surface ships,
the official said.
   ``Our people know a great deal about the ideas that the Soviets
have advanced, and we've looked into it carefully,'' the official
said.
   When they agreed in principle last December to hold a springtime
summit in Moscow, President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev said they wanted to sign an agreement to cut the numbers
of long-range nuclear missiles and bombers by 30 percent to 50
percent.
   With little progress _ notably on the verification issues _
during Shevardnadze's visit to Washington for three days this week,
neither side predicted the agreement would be ready in time.
   The senior U.S. official said, moreover, that until the
negotiators prove they can verify elimination of the various types
of weapons involved, they won't know which ones will be covered in
a treaty.
   Another official, noting that the two nations also disagree on
such explosive issues as Afghanistan, the Middle East, Central
America and human rights warned against expecting ``easy
solutions'' to U.S.-Soviet problems.
   The official described the most recent talks as ``grueling,''
notably in the 11 hours of discussion on the regional hot spots.
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater sought to dispel
suggestions that the summit meeting _ in the twilight of Reagan's
presidency _ would be a ceremonial and symbolic visit short on
substantive accomplishments.
   During Shevardnadze's talks in Washington ``we made enough
progress to keep going and presumably we will make more in the days
ahead,'' the spokesman told reporters.
   During the talks this week both sides ``faced all the tough
problems'' and left no confusion about where both sides stand, he
said.
   The summit ``will be well prepared; there will be substance to
discuss; there will be good prospects for success,'' Fitzwater said.
   He added that ``there will be a number of important and
substantive and meaningful issues to be resolved and all of those
things will occur at the Moscow summit. It meets all the criteria
that needs to be met.''
   ``I think this summit will be quite productive, well defined,
well prepared,'' the spokesman said without citing any specific
areas of agreement.
</TEXT>
