<1ST_LINE>r p AM-IowaDemocrats     03-24 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iowa Democrats,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iowa Quietly Continues Democratic Delegate Selection Process</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six weeks after the precinct caucuses
that put Iowa in the national spotlight and provided the first test
of Democratic candidates' strength, Democrats here are quietly
proceeding with the next step in their delegate-selection process.
   The conventions in the 99 counties this weekend are the second
step in the complex process of choosing 52 of Iowa's 58 delegates
to the Democratic National Convention.
   The field has shifted dramatically since Feb. 8, when the
much-publicized precinct caucuses were held. Rep. Richard Gephardt,
the Missouri congressman who won the Democratic contest, has gone
on to weak showings elsewhere.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, Jesse Jackson and Tennessee
Sen. Albert Gore have surged to the front of the Democratic pack.
   Supporters who put Gephardt on top last month probably won't
flee his sagging candidacy for other Democratic candidates in
county conventions this weekend, Democratic leaders said Wednesday.
   Dukakis supporters are making a low-key effort to lure
supporters from other camps, but working hard to keep their
expectations low.
   ``It's informal,'' said Harry Baxter of Burlington. ``I'm sure
all of the campaigns are trying to lobby.''
   At the precinct caucuses, party activists elected delegates to
the county conventions, based on the proportion of support for the
various presidential candidates.
   At the county conventions, delegates will be elected to
congressional district conventions later in the spring.
   Despite Gephardt's slide, Baxter said Dukakis backers won't be
making a major effort to convince his delegates to switch at the
county conventions.
   Other activists agreed, saying backers of Gephardt and Illinois
Sen. Paul Simon, who finished second in the precinct caucuses, will
wait to see results in tests in Michigan and Wisconsin before
making a decision.
   Michigan is considered a last-ditch effort for Gephardt, and
that state's caucuses also are Saturday.
   As long as those candidates remain in the race, it's unlikely
their supporters will switch, and other campaigns are avoiding a
strident pitch soas not to offend potential future supporters.
   ``Our county chairs and the people we had in place for the
campaign are working, contacting supporters from other camps,''
said Dukakis backer Tom Jochum, a state representative from
Dubuque. ``If I were a Gephardt supporter, I'd be waiting to see
what the results are in Michigan.''
   Since Iowa's precinct caucuses, former Arizona Gov. Bruce
Babbitt and Gary Hart have formally dropped from the race. Few
delegates are at stake there as Hart got less than 1 percent while
Babbitt got 6 percent in the caucuses.
   ``People are going to wait to see what happens,'' said Iowa
Democratic Party spokesman Phil Roeder. ``The only people who are
going to move are the Babbitt people. The Gephardt people are going
to wait.''
   Caucus-goers selected 15,000 delegates to the county conventions
and 30,000 alternates. They will elect 3,001 delegates to the six
congressional district conventions May 14. Those delegates will
pick 52 of the state's 58 national delegates.
   The state has six ``super'' delegates, who are elected officials
and party leaders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
