<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1753EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest     03-24 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0701</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moscow Uses New Plan, Helicopters to Combat Armenian Annexation
Drive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kremlin laid out an 8-year plan Thursday night
to pacify a Caucasus region shaken by ethnic strife. At the same
time, army helicopters were reported circling over the Armenian
capital to prevent further unrest.
   The carrot-and-stick approach seemed aimed at cooling feelings
inflamed by a noisy Armenian campaign to annex the region of
Nagorno-Karabakh from neighboring Azerbaijan and to warn Armenian
activists to end their protests.
   Activists have said specifically that government efforts to
improve poor economic and social conditions of Armenians in the
Caucasus mountain region near the Soviet border with Iran would not
meet their demands.
   Armenian newspaper editor Regyen Sarkisyan said Yerevan, capital
of Armenia and scene of mass pro-annexation demonstrations in
February, was being patrolled by Red Army helicopters and soldiers.
He said no violence was reported.
   Sarkisyan told The Associated Press in a telephone interview
that most Armenians were showing patience in awaiting resolution of
the issue.
   On Feb. 28, rioting broke out in Sumgait, Azerbaijan, and
officials said 32 people were killed.
   Nagorno-Karabakh, which is smaller than Delaware, has a
population that is 75 percent Armenian but has been a part of
Azerbaijan since 1923.
   The Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the nation's highest
government body, rejected as ``intolerable'' Wednesday the campaign
for annexation of the region, indicating it would not bend to
pressure from mass protests.
   The Presidium, meanwhile, ordered ministries to solve ``pressing
problems of the economic, social and cultural development'' of the
region. The ruling Communist Party Politburo made public details of
their proposals Thursday.
   The plan for 1988-95 calls for stepping up the pace of
construction of schools, hospitals, apartments and roads in the
region and for increasing the publication of Armenian literature.
   ``Work will also be completed to ensure a steady reception of
the national television program, as well as ... telecasts of
Armenian and Azerbaijani television,'' the officia Tass news agency
said in a report on the Politburo meeting.
   The plan calls for increasing by 50 percent the industrial
output of the region.
   The plan approved by the Politburo was formulated by the Central
Committee, the Communist Party's policy-making body, and the
government Council of Ministers, Tass said.
   It said the Politburo deemed it ``essential to resolutely
discourage the slightest manifestations of nationalism or
disrespect for national sentiments of members of various ethnic
groups.''
   Last week, a prominent Soviet journalist writing in the Moscow
News weekly said residents of Nagorno-Karabakh suffer cultural and
economic disadvantages.
   Karen Khachaturov said people there have difficulty getting
books in their native language and officials have not made good on
pledges to build a sports complex and children's institutions.
   Moscow dissident Valery Senderov said Thursday that a
correspondent for an unofficial human rights journal called from
Yerevan to say Soviet army helicopters were patrolling the city,
but no widespread disorder was reported.
   Sarkisyan, a senior editor of the Armenian Communist Party
newspaper Kommunist, confirmed the helicopter report and added that
soldiers were deployed around Yerevan to ensure order.
   Activists in Yerevan had called for another show of support for
the annexation drive with demonstrations and strikes beginning
Saturday, when a group of activists and officials plans to meet to
discuss a future course of action.
   Sarkisyan says it is his personal belief that Nagorno-Karabakh
should be united with Armenia. He said he does not expect a large
turnout at the demonstrations or widespread participation in the
strikes called for by activists.
   Moscow-based dissidents say they've been told thousands plan to
take to the streets.
   The Presidium did not directly address the question of
annexation. Last month's mass protests in Yerevan subsided after
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev appealed on Feb. 26 for calm and
promised a party review of the annexation question.
   Demonstrations were held again in Yerevan this week after a
report in the Communist Party daily Pravda said the annexation
drive had a ``clear anti-socialist spirit.'' Activists said 7,000
people took part in a protest march Monday.
</TEXT>
