<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Vanunu     03-24 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Vanunu,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Israeli Nuclear Worker Convicted Of Treason, Spying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOCELYN NOVECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former nuclear technician who claimed he
revealed Israel's atomic secrets for the good of humanity was
convicted Thursday of espionage and treason and could be sentenced
to 20 years in prison.
   Mordechai Vanunu, 34, was found guilty by a three-judge panel
after a trial that had been closed to the public since it began in
September. His lawyer said the Vanunu would appeal the verdict to
Israel's Supreme Court.
   ``Mordechai is very disappointed,'' said defense attorney
Avigdor Feldman. ``The court decided that he was a traitor, and he
had hoped to be seen differently. But he is not broken. He is
looking ahead to the appeal.''
   The conviction carries a maximum sentence of death. However,
prosecutor Uzi Chasson said he would ask the court for a sentence
of life imprisonment, which in Israel is limited to 20 years.
Sentencing is set for Sunday.
   Vanunu, who worked nine years at the nuclear facility in Dimona,
was charged for revealing details of Israel's atomic capacity to
The Sunday Times of London in October 1986.
   The newspaper said Vanunu's information showed Israel had
stockpiled the world's sixth-largest nuclear arsenal.
   Israel never has responded directly to allegations of its
nuclear capacity, saying only it would not be the first country to
introduce such weapons into the Middle East.
   Vanunu has insisted he made his revelations to alert the Middle
East and the world to the dangers of nuclear weapons. The state
argued he intended to harm Israel's security.
   He was kept under heavy security during the trial, which was
closed to the public because authorities feared an open hearing
would harm state security.
   Vanunu has been held in near isolation for the last 18 months
and has been permitted to see only his attorney and family.
   The precautions were taken after Vanunu managed to flash a
message to reporters at a pre-trial appearance by scribbling it on
the palm of his hand. In the message he said he had been kidnapped
in Rome, presumably by Israeli agents, and brought to Israel for
trial.
   Vanunu was fired from the Dimona nuclear center in 1985 and went
to Australia, where he became acquainted with a priest and
converted to Christianity.
   He later traveled to London, but disappeared in October 1986,
just days before The Sunday Times published his revelations.
Israeli officials acknowledged several weeks later he was in
custody in Israel.
   Details of Vanunu's journey back to Israel were revealed by his
brother, Meir Vanunu, who said Vanunu was lured from London to Rome
by an American woman named Cindy, who promised him sex. In Rome, he
was abducted by Israeli agents and spirited home, Meir said.
   During the trial, Feldman argued Vanunu did not hurt Israel's
security because information about Israel's nuclear capacity was
available in the academic world. He said Vanunu had in fact helped
state security because allegations of Israel's nuclear strength
served as a deterrent to Arab enemies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880324-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0636EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ShipwreckPreservation     03-24 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shipwreck Preservation,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel OKs Senate Bill To Protect Historic Shipwrecks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation pushed by archaeologists to save
historic shipwrecks won House committee approval Wednesday despite
complaints from recreational divers that the bill could block their
enjoyment of the undersea landmarks.
   The bill is designed to clear up the murky legal status of
shipwreck jurisdiction by giving states authority over certain
downed vessels in state waters, preventing salvage operators from
destroying historic remains.
   The House Merchant Marine and Fisheries Committee put aside a
House version of the measure and passed 29-10, largely along party
lines, a bill sponsored by Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., that the
Senate passed in December.
   Democrats led by Rep. Charles E. Bennett, D-Fla., who has
advocated a shipwreck preservation law for a decade, said they
agreed with an amendment proposed by Rep. Norman D. Shumway,
R-Calif., mandating that states make shipwrecks accessible to
divers.
   But Bennett and others noted that an amended bill would need
Senate approval again, and they were afraid the measure would die
there as it has in past years. This is the first time the Senate
has approved a shipwreck bill.
   ``Don't kill this bill by making it perfect,'' Bennett urged.
``I'm afraid it's going to be a better corpse.''
   Shumway, pointing to vocal opposition from sport diving groups,
said the legislation should spell out guarantees for divers.
   ``I think this bill can be vastly improved,'' he said.
   Bennett retorted that ``if you don't pass this bill, there won't
be any shipwrecks to dive on.'' Rep. Claudine Schneider, R-R.I.,
who said she is a recreational diver, agreed, joining Democrats in
defeating the Shumway amendment 25-14.
   Bennett said later that he expected easy passage on the House
floor. The Reagan administration supports the measure.
   The committee agreed to place in a report that accompanies the
bill language stating that it is the intent of Congress for states
to make shipwrecks accessible to divers.
   Under the legislation, states would have jurisdiction over
historic shipwrecks within their three-mile state limits. They
would be charged with establishing protective areas, allowing
recreational exploration and overseeing public and private salvage
efforts.
   Under admiralty laws, discoverers of wrecks can salvage
abandoned vessels. Those laws are at odds with many state statutes.
</TEXT>
