<HEAD>Israeli Jets Raid Palestinian Bases for Second Day</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to CORRECT 2nd graf to south of Beirut, not
south of Lebanon; makes it Abu Nidal throughout to conform to
style; SUBS last two grafs, Wednesday's attack ... UPDATING
casualty figures</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AHMED MANTASH</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli jets bombed Palestinian targets on
the outskirts of Sidon on Thursday for the second straight day,
hitting a base of the notorious Abu Nidal guerrilla faction.
   Police said nine people were killed and five wounded in the
raid, the third this week near the port city 25 miles south of
Beirut.
   Police said most of the casualties were members of Abu Nidal's
Fatah-Revolutionary Council, and the group issued a statement
pledging ``merciless retaliation.''
   A police spokesman described the attack as ``very fierce.'' He
said six Israeli warplanes dropped 30 bombs in six sorties within
55 minutes.
   Prime Minister Salim Hoss instructed Lebanon's U.N. ambassador,
Rashid Fakhoury, to complain to the world body about the attacks,
state radio said.
   But Lebanon did not ask for a Security Council meeting on the
issue, it said.
   The police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity in
keeping with standing regulations, said the main target was Abu
Nidal's guerrilla base, but the jets also hit a position of the
Marxist Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine.
   ``The Israelis plowed the olive groves where the stricken bases
are,'' he added.
   The bases were engulfed by smoke and dust as ambulances arrived
to evacuate casualties.
   The police spokesman said Abu Nidal's guerrillas cordoned off
the bases in the villages of Bekasta, Majdelyoun, Salhiyeh and Abra
on the southern and eastern edges of Sidon.
   The jets dropped scarlet balloons to deflect heat-seeking
missiles. The guerrillas fired at the roaring jets with Soviet-made
anti-aircraft guns. No hits were reported.
   ``Let the enemy wait for coming blows of our revolutionary
fighters,'' said a statement issued by the Fatah-Revolutionary
Council. ``We shall strike doubly in merciless retaliation.''
   Abu Nidal _ real name Sabri al-Banna _ broke from Yasser
Arafat's Palestine Liberation Organization in 1974. He has since
claimed attacks against a series of civilian targets around the
world.
   The elusive terrorist mastermind tops wanted lists in the United
States and Europe. His whereabouts are not known, altough recent
reports said he has been shuttling between Libya and Algeria.
   His group also vowed revenge after Wednesday's strike, saying in
a statement it would ``severely strike back against the Zionist
enemy's arrogance and barbarism ... at the right time and place.''
   Wednesday's attack targeted bases of the Abu Nidal and the
Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine, a PLO faction
headed by Nayef Hawatmeh. Police said eight people were killed and
15 wounded in the attacks.
   In all, 48 people have been killed and 63 wounded in five
Israeli air raids this year, by Lebanese police count.
</TEXT>
