<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SovietJewry     03-24 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Jewry,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Embassy Demonstration for Soviet Jews Tests New Supreme Court
Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of Soviet Jews tested a new Supreme
Court ruling Wednesday that knocked down rules banning peaceful
demonstrations within 500 feet of foreign embassies in Washington.
   The dozen demonstrators, accompanied for a time by Sens. Frank
Lautenberg, D-N.J., and Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., gave speeches on
the sidewalk in front of the Soviet Embassy. Then seven of them sat
down on the sidewalk, prayed and sang. Some taunted Soviet
officials as they moved freely in and out of the embassy gate.
   The police, whose numbers rivaled those of the demonstrators,
did nothing to impede the protest. They quietly ensured that the
driveway and embassy gate remained clear and they steered
pedestrians through the maze of protesters and the accompanying
phalanx of reporters and photographers. Police made no move to
arrest anyone.
   In fact, they stopped traffic on busy 16th Street so the
demonstrators could move back and forth to the embassy.
   ``They can't block the driveway,'' said Sgt. Gary Nelson of the
District of Columbia police. ``They can't block free passage of the
sidewalk.''
   Rabbi Avi Weiss of New York, the chairman of the Student
Struggle for Soviet Jewry, was a leader of Wednesday's
demonstration. He has been arrested several times for violating the
limits on protests near the Soviet Embassy.
   ``There are those who say the (Supreme Court) ruling takes away
the dramatic tool of arrest,'' Weiss said before the demonstration
began. But he warned, ``If the necessity arises that we'll have to
sit peacefully in front of the gates, then that's something I'd be
willing to do.''
   In Tuesday's Supreme Court ruling, Justice Sandra Day O'Connor,
writing for the court, said police may disperse groups of three or
more congregating near embassies when they ``reasonably believe
that a threat to the security or peace of the embassy is present.''
Banning such gatherings ``does not prohibit peaceful
congregations,'' she wrote, adding that the ban ``is limited to
groups posing a security threat.''
   Weiss said the court's ruling ``allows a far greater voice for
Soviet Jews specifically at a time when so many have been duped by
`glasnost.''' Glasnost is the Russian word for ``openness.''
   He condemned an upcoming trip by Commerce Secretary C. William
Verity and some 500 business executives to the Soviet Union.
   ``There cannot be an increase of trade, an increase of loans
without a concession on human rights on the other side,'' Weiss
said.
   As the demonstration commenced in front of the embassy, a dozen
Soviet officials sat in the patio on the other side of the gates,
enjoying the suddenly springlike weather, chatting amongst
themselves and occasionally gazing at the demonstrators.
   As the protestors sang at one point, a Soviet official walked
into the front gate, barely suppressing a smile.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
