<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1812EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-24 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Record Warmth in Northeast, Rain in North-Central States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Parts of the Northeast basked in record warmth Tuesday, with
temperatures in the 60s and 70s, while showers and thunderstorms
dampened the north-central states.
   The showers reached from southern Michigan across northern Iowa,
northeast Nebraska, eastern South Dakota and Minnesota. Rain also
fell from the lower Great Lakes across east-central New York and
along the northern Pacific Coast.
   Advisories warned of snow and blowing snow across the northern
mountains of Colorado. Winds gusted to 55 mph at Pueblo, Colo., and
58 mph at Cheyenne, Wyo.
   Balmy weather held sway across sections of the Northeast. Record
highs included 66 at Bridgeport, Conn., 72 at Newark, N.J., 75 at
New York, and 76 in Philadelphia.
   By contrast, Klamath Falls, Ore., had a record low temperature
of 19 degrees.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. EST
included 0.77 inch at Boothville, La., 0.60 inch at Quillayute,
Wash., 0.55 inch at Astoria, Ore., and 0.47 inch at Minot, N.D.
   Temperatures at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 26 degrees at
Yellowstone, Wyo., to 90 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif. The
morning low was 4 degrees at Yellowstone.
   Friday's forecast called for rain along the northern Pacific
Coast; snow scattered over northeast Minnesota, becoming rain over
the remainder of eastern Minnesota, Wisconsin and upper Michigan as
well as from New York across central and southern New England, and
showers and occasional thunderstorms from northeast Illinois across
lower Michigan, the Ohio Valley, the Tennessee Valley, and the
central Gulf Coast.
   Temperatures were expected to climb into the 30s and 40s in
northern New England, Upper Michigan, northern Wisconsin, the upper
Mississippi Valley, the northern Plains and the upper Missouri
Valley; into the 70s from the central Atlantic Coast across
Georgia, Alabama and the Florida Panhandle, the central Gulf Coast,
much of Texas, and northern California, into the 80s over the
Florida Peninsula, and southern Texas; into the 80s to low 90s
across southern California and the desert Southwest, and the 50s
and 60s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
