<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1831EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Gephardt 2ndLd-Writethru a0805 03-24 0829</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gephardt, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0805,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gephardt Aides Say He'll Quit If He Loses Michigan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB 11th graf bgng ``Gephardt is'' with later Gephardt quote</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Gephardt, pressing on with his hard-line
trade stance, on Thursday denied statements from aides that he
would shut down his campaign for the 1988 Democratic presidential
nomination if he does not win Saturday's Michigan caucuses.
   Amid turmoil over reports that Michigan was a do-or-die state
for him, Gephardt delivered a speech here and denounced a
``dogmatic and outdated'' free trade theology that has cost the
nation jobs.
   Gephardt brushed aside questions about the future of his
campaign, but aides spoke privately of a decision hinging on the
Michigan caucus outcome.
   Plans are in motion for the Missouri congressman to file for
re-election to his House seat by the Tuesday deadline, said the
aides, if Michigan does not give him his first victory since the
South Dakota primary on Feb. 23.
   ``That's right. He will be out if doesn't win in Michigan,''
said a campaign aide who would not be quoted by name.
   Asked if that aide's comment was accurate, Gephardt told
reporters:
   ``No. I'm running for president and I've doing very well here in
Michigan. ... I'm going to win in Michigan. I'm going to continue
and do well.''
   ``My mother always told me to cross one bridge at a time. That's
what I'm trying to do,'' he added. ``Rather than trying to guess
all the different hypotheticals of what might happen, I just think
we have to be patient, wait to see the outcome and then decide what
other steps should be taken.''
   Gephardt aides said publicly that nothing has changed in the
past 48 hours, that it has been understood since Super Tuesday that
Gephardt would end his race if he does not win here. The
candidate's wife put it this way on Thursday:
   ``I think Dick has to come in first or a real strong second to
remain in the race, because at some point if you don't do well
here, it becomes difficult to raise money,''' said Jane Gephardt in
an interview with WTVB radio. ``Dick's message will be very popular
in the industrial states, but if we don't do well here, we will not
be able to continue.''
   Gephardt is running third in the polls in Michigan, behind
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson. Later
Thursday, Gephardt mimicked Dukakis' claim of turning around the
Massachusetts economy, adapting it to his campaign by saying ``This
Saturday we're going to have a miracle in Michigan _ the Michigan
miracle.''
   Tuesday is the deadline for Gephardt to file for re-election for
his House seat. A meeting has been scheduled this weekend for the
Democrats who have filed for the seat.
   One reason for the withdrawal _ and the congressional race _
would be to take care of any debts left over from the presidential
bid.
   ``Only as Rep. Gephardt can he raise the money to pay off the
debts'' from the presidential campaign, one aide said.
   But Gephardt spokesman Mark Johnson denied the campaign had a
big debt and said that is not a factor.
   One of Gephardt's problems was inadvertantly emphasized by the
presence of United Auto Workers president Owen Bieber at Gephardt's
news conference.
   The UAW has not endorsed any candidate, and Bieber refused to
say he would vote for Gephardt in the caucuses. Union backing would
be a major boost to a candidate in the low-turnout caucus process,
but particularly for Gephardt, whose trade policies have had strong
UAW backing.
   ``I come here today because I want to pay my respects to Rep.
Gephardt and the respects of my union to a person who has fought
very hard to bring about fair trade,'' Bieber said.
   Gephardt gave a lengthy speech to the Detroit Economic Club,
trying to explain again his trade positions and the reasons his
ideas have encountered such resistance.
   ``We will not open markets abroad until we first open minds here
at home,'' the Missouri congressman said, adding ``The free market
is not sacred.''
   He mentioned only one opponent by name, chiding Dukakis for now
supporting trade legislation that he earlier opposed.
   ``I welcome converts,'' Gephardt said. ``But we need more than a
political tactic _ we need a real policy commitment.''
   Gephardt laid out in his speech why he thought his trade
legislation has been denounced so strongly.
   ``The powerful voices ... are dogmatic and outdated,'' he
said.``They see things, not as they are, but as they wish them to
be.''
   `Many of our trading partners are using our outdated assumptions
_ our theology _ to take advantage of us,'' he said.
   And Gephardt rejected the allegation that his trade policies are
somehow racist.
   ``Those of us who are calling for more realistic trade polices
are accused of Japanese-bashing,'' he said. ``The issue here is not
nationality, but the rationality of our trading arrangements.''
</TEXT>
