<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--EasternAirlines     03-24 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Eastern Airlines,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Airlines Employees, Supporters Demonstrate At Capitol</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angry unionized employees of Eastern Airlines
and supporters from other labor organizations rallied outside the
Capitol on Wednesday in an effort to bring attention to their
disputes with the carrier.
   The demonstrators, estimated at 1,200 by their leaders, heard
speeches from several union leaders and from Sen. Tom Harkin,
D-Iowa.
   ``I want airline pilots who belong to strong unions, so if they
know they have unsafe conditions or unsafe airplanes, they can park
that airplane and know they still have their jobs,'' Harkin told
the crowd.
   Some Eastern pilots have complained that they have been
pressured by company officials to fly aircraft that they believe
need repairs. Eastern officials have said they would never allow
unsafe planes to fly.
   Unions at Eastern have been battling the airline on a number of
issues in recent years, aiming much of their fire at Frank Lorenzo,
the chief executive of the Miami-based carrier. Lorenzo has been
trying to reduce costs at the financially ailing airline, but the
unions say his goal is to reduce the power of labor.
</TEXT>
