<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 2142EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Meese-Bork     03-24 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Bork,380</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release 8 p.m. EST; time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>Meese Says Bork Was Victim of `Character Assassination'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judge Robert H. Bork was a victim of
``political muscle and character assassination'' who would have
fought excesses by the judiciary had he been seated on the Supreme
Court, Attorney General Edwin Meese III said Thursday.
   Bork's Supreme Court nomination was turned down 58-42 in the
Senate on Oct. 23 by ``those partisans who would impermissibly seek
to reshape the Constitution into a vehicle for their own limited
political beliefs,'' Meese said in remarks prepared for delivery
Thursday night to the Joseph Story Society, a conservative lawyers'
group.
   A copy of Meese's remarks was released at the Justice Department.
   ``No one ... deserves a seat on the U.S. Supreme Court more than
Robert H. Bork,'' Meese said of the appeals court judge who drew
strong opposition for his conservative views on the role of the
judiciary and other constitutional issues.
   Meese said the forces opposed to Bork's nomination ``used
political muscle and character assassination to thwart the
appointment of a most deserving person.''
   Bork and legal scholar Raoul Berger, who were being honored at
an awards banquet of the society, have fought unwarranted judicial
activism which has been ``advocated by those forces who like to be
called `progressive,''' Meese said.
   ``But ... their version of modern progressivism has passed
democracy by, leaving it to today's conservatives to do what
yesterday's progressives did: defend democracy,'' the attorney
general said.
   Meese cited as an example of judicial activism a federal judge's
ruling in Kansas City ordering additions to the facilities of local
schools, and ``a doubling of the property tax rate to pay for
them.''
   He also criticized the ruling of a judge in St. Louis who
decreed a busing scheme for schools and vowed to require higher
property taxes to pay for it if the voters failed to do so.
   Meese said judicial activism forecloses opportunities for local
expression and leaves ``a drastically reduced scope for the
institutions that are representative of citizen views.''
   ``The pattern here is a subtle but dangerous transformation of
the Constitution, such that it becomes less a plan of government
and more an instrument for the regulation of potentially every
personal action or policy decision _ regulation that the people
themselves become powerless to control,'' Meese said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
