<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Gore-Loans 1stLd-Writethru a0737 03-24 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gore-Loans, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0737,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Used Future Federal Matching Funds As Collateral For Loans</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Gore campaign releasing details on
loans; no pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr.'s presidential campaign
confirmed Thursday it borrowed more than $1.4 million early this
month, putting up collateral that included future federal matching
funds and a personal guarantee by the candidate himself.
   Gore, who was questioned about the loans earlier in the day,
said he did not object to releasing the details.
   Gore spokesman Mark Armour said the loans were secured by the
campaign's federal matching funds, plus accounts receivable and a
personal guarantee totaling $40,000 by Gore himself.
   The campaign issued a statement saying it borrowed $750,000 from
Sovran-D.C. National Bank on March 1, pledging future
contributions, federal matching funds and other future income as
collateral.
   The Gore campaign also borrowed $400,000 on March 11 from Union
Planters Bank in Memphis, Tenn., secured by a guarantee from Gore
and future matching funds.
   The campaign said it borrowed $100,000 from each of three
smaller banks in Tennessee on March 1, also secured by the
candidate's guarantee and future matching funds.
   Armour denied that the banks showed any special favor in
granting the loans, stating, ``They were all handled at arm's
length through lawyers on both sides.''
   ``There's nothing that is in any violation of any laws or
regulations and there's no cause for suggesting that there is,''
Gore said at a news conference.
   The Gore campaign previously has acknowledged only that it had
established a $1 million line of credit to be used as necessary for
television advertising on Super Tuesday.
   On Thursday, The Tennessean newspaper in Nashville reported that
Gore's campaign had put up the proceeds of future fund-raisers and
federal matching funds as collateral for almost $1.5 million
borrowed from banks about two weeks ago.
   ``I have no problem with telling you the amount of the loans and
which banks they came from, be glad to,'' Gore told reporters.
   Gore said details of the loans would be contained in reports to
be filed in the next two or three weeks with the Federal Election
Commission ``so if you can wait two or three weeks all of that will
be available, but as for now I have no problem with giving you the
amount of the loans, the banks et cetera.''
   The next FEC reporting date is April 20. The loans were taken
out after Feb. 29 so they did not have to be disclosed March 20.
   The due date for the Gore loans is July 15, three days before
the Democratic National Convention begins in Atlanta.
   The latest Gore FEC disclosure, made public Sunday, covers the
period from Feb. 1 to Feb. 29.
   It shows that, to date, Gore has spent $6 million on his
presidential bid, and had $342,964 in cash on hand as of Feb. 29.
   The capaign has taken in $1.5 million this month, Armour said.
   The Gore campaign also announced Thursday that it has retained
media consultant David Garth to manage all of Gore's media for the
critical New York primary on April 19.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
