<1ST_LINE>r a AM-InvestorPlea     03-24 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Investor Plea,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wall Street Whiz Kid Likely to Plead Guilty to Fraud Charges</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: A version moved on financial wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 23-year-old investment adviser accused of
using $10 million in clients' money to buy himself an art
collection, a beach house, fancy cars and other luxuries will
probably plead guilty to fraud, his lawyer said Thursday.
   David Bloom briefly appeared before a federal magistrate
Thursday and waived his right to have the case heard by a grand
jury. He is charged with mail fraud and securities fraud.
   Although Bloom entered an innocent plea at the proceeding, his
lawyer, Peter Morrison, said Bloom is expected to plead guilty
March 31.
   Prosecutors said Bloom, who wasn't licensed as an investment
adviser, told clients their funds were invested in the stock market
when he actually was pouring the money into private purchases.
   They included artworks totaling $5.5 million; an $830,000
Manhattan apartment; a $1.9 million beach house in East Hampton, an
Aston-Martin convertible and Mercedes-Benz worth a combined
$200,000, and home furnishings that cost $800,000.
   Bloom also bought expensive jewelry and deluxe trips to Europe
and the Caribbean for himself, his family and friends, according to
the government.
   He is also accused of falsely telling investors that he managed
money for prominent individuals and investors, including the
Rockefeller family, the Sultan of Brunei and Bill Cosby.
   If found guilty, Bloom faces a maximum sentence of five years in
prison on each count and a maximum fine of twice the amount lost by
investors.
   Bloom was arrested Jan. 14. He had begun investing money for
friends while at Duke University and had 130 clients at the time of
his arrest.
</TEXT>
