<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Gephardt-HouseRace     03-24 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gephardt-House Race,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gephardt's Plan Throws Wrench in Potential Successors' Intentions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gephardt Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN BALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats who had hoped to succeed
Rep. Richard Gephardt faced the prospect Thursday of having to bow
out amid reports Gephardt would abandon his presidential bid and
seek re-election to the House.
   ``I'm a little upset,'' said state Rep. Phil Barry, a St. Louis
County Democrat considered one of the leading contenders to replace
Gephardt, the 3rd Congressional District representative for six
terms.
   ``I'm saddened. I guess that's a nice way to put it,'' said
Barry, who has the endorsement of labor and other groups and has
raised about $27,000.
   Six Democrats have filed for the seat, and at least two others
are considering a bid.
   A Gephardt campaign aide who insisted on anonymity said
Wednesday that if Gephardt did not win the Michigan caucuses
Saturday he probably would announce the end of his campaign Monday
and file for re-election.
   Gephardt later denied that he was considering such a move.
   Missouri Democratic Party Chairman Karen Schafer said she
thought that if Gephardt decided to seek re-election the other
candidates would not have much choice but to step aside.
   ``It's going to be a big blow to some of them but they all knew
when they got in that Gephardt could come back,'' Mrs. Schafer
said. ``They're prepared for it.''
   Barry said he most likely would step aside if Gephardt wanted to
keep his congressional seat.
   John Temporiti, the first Democrat to file for the seat and an
active campaigner, was out of his office Thursday, his secretary
said. Temporiti is a lawyer and former chief of staff for St. Louis
Mayor Vincent C. Schoemehl Jr.
   To be a candidate for his congressional seat, Gephardt would
have to file with the Missouri secretary of state's office by the
close of business Tuesday.
   He could file for the House seat and remain in the presidential
race but would have to withdraw from the congressional race if he
were to win the presidential nomination.
   Other Democrats to file are George Kerry, Gephardt's top St.
Louis aide; James Whitt, a house painter; Barbara Vires, a retired
high school teacher, and Ed Roche, who has run for Congress five
times.
   Four Republicans have filed, but none was expected to be a
serious challenge in the heavily Democratic district.
</TEXT>
