<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Highlights     03-24 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Highlights,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Highlights of Sandinista-Contra Truce Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the key points of the cease-fire agreement reached
between Nicaragua's Sandinista government and the Contra rebels and
some of the issues that remain unsettled:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SETTLED:
   -A 60-day cease-fire begins April 1, with a temporary truce in
effect until then.
   _Rebels move into specified zones in Nicaragua during the first
15 days of April.
   _Creation of a truce verification commission headed Cardinal
Miguel Obando y Bravo, Nicaragua's Roman Catholic leader, and the
secretary-general of the Organization of American States,
Ambassador Joao Baena Soares.
   _Contras will stop taking military aid from the United States.
   _Contras will be represented in Sandinista talks with internal
opposition known as the national dialogue and will take part in the
electoral process.
   _Amnesty for political prisoners, return of political exiles,
release of 1,400 jailed Contras and 1,800 former National Guardsmen
imprisoned since the 1979 Sandinista revolution.
   _Government guarantees freedom of expression without
restrictions, in accordance with a regional peace plan signed last
August by President Daniel Ortega and the presidents of four other
Central American countries.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   UNSETTLED:
   _Details of a permanent truce. Negotiations begin April 6 in
Managua.
   _Location of the rebel zones. Negotiations begin Monday in Sapoa.
   _Laying down of Contra arms.
   _Military conscription. This will be discussed as part of the
national dialogue between the Sandinistas and the opposition,
including the Contras.
   _Contra delegates to the national dialogue.
   _Which neutral organizations will channel humanitarian aid to
the Contras.
   _Precise dates for prisoner releases.
   The government agreed to free 100 Contra prisoners on Sunday.
Half of the remaining 1,300 will be freed after rebels are in
specified zones. The other half and the former guardsmen will be
freed after a permanent truce is in place.
</TEXT>
