<2ND_LINE>AM-Howard, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0848,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Howard `Very Critical' After Collapsing on Golf Course</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs 7th graf pvs bgng: Howard's staff ... to UPDATE with
statement by Howard's office.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. James Howard suffered a heart attack
Thursday and was hospitalized in very critical condition, officials
said.
   Howard, 60, chairman of the House Public Works and
Transportation Committee, collapsed on a Maryland golf course near
Washington at about 10 a.m., his office said.
   The New Jersey Democrat was taken to Montgomery General Hospital
in Olney, Md., where doctors revived him after two hours, hospital
spokeswoman Linda Janzik said.
   He had suffered a heart attack, which stopped his heart, and he
was listed in very critical condition, Ms. Janzik said.
   He later was taken by helicopter to the cardiac unit of the
Washington Hospital Center, she said.
   ``He was breathing on his own,'' Ms. Janzik said.
   Howard's office said Wednesday night he was in ``critical
condition'' and under intensive care. His wife, Marlene, and
daughter, Marie, were with him.
   Howard, the victim of two previous heart attacks, collapsed at
the Manor Country Club in Rockville, Md.
   Coleman Plecker, a golf pro at the club, told the Montgomery
(Md.) Journal that he saw Howard collapse. The pro said he ran over
and started administering cardiopulmonary resuscitation.
   Two Montgomery County firefighters who happened to be golfing at
the time then took over resuscitation efforts until a rescue squad
arrived, Plecker said.
   ``If anything could be done for that guy, he was lucky to have
those guys right there,'' Plecker said.
   Howard was hospitalized for several days in 1984 in an episode
doctors attributed to fatigue. He is a heavy cigarette smoker.
   A former schoolteacher and principal, Howard has been in
Congress since 1965.
   He gained his congressional seat on the coattails of President
Johnson's 1964 victory. During the Reagan landslide of 1980, Howard
retained his seat by a margin of only about 2,000 votes over his
GOP challenger.
   In 1986, the Democrat won re-election with 59 percent of the
vote in a largely Republican district.
   He has been chairman of the public works committee since 1981.
The panel considers multibillion-dollar highway and water projects
</TEXT>
