<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Pool     03-24 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Pool,0791</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Frigate Shadows Landing Craft</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD USS SAMUEL B. ROBERTS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Speeding through stiff winds
and heavy seas early Thursday, we closed in on an Iranian landing
craft that served as mother ship for speedboat attacks on neutral
ships in the Strait of Hormuz.
   The decks were lashed by 15-foot waves and winds gusting to 50
knots but Cmdr Paul X. Rinn, skipper of this 445-foot guided
missile frigate, covered the the 45 miles to the Hengham-class
landing craft and halted his pursuit 4,600 yards from his quarry.
   While there was no actual confrontation, not even a radio
exchange, the presence of the American warship appeared to distract
the landing craft Tomb from its mission. U.S. officers said that
mission apparently was to serve as a floating base for speedboats
that attack ships with machine-gun and rocket grenade fire.
   ``He now knows we know where he is. We can come back now and
find him any time we want,'' Rinn told reporters in a Pentagon news
pool aboard the Roberts.
   Increasingly, warships such as U.S. Navy Fast Frigate No. 88 are
closely monitoring the activities of Iranian warships in the
southern Persian Gulf.
   Their purpose apparently is to discourage Iranian attacks on
neutral shipping in the waterway, where Iran and Iraq have been at
war since September 1980.
   Such missions may reflect a subtle but potentially significant
shift in Navy policy under Rear Adm. Anthony A. Less, who took
command of the Joint Task Force Middle East and its gulf component
last month.
   American officers say there is no change in the ``rules of
engagement.'' Those permit Navy ships to offer ``humanitarian
assistance'' to neutral ships in distress that request help but
prohibit them from interceding to stop an attack on a ship not
flying the Stars and Stripes
   However, with the success of its primary mission to escort
convoys of U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti tankers through these hazardous
waters, the Navy may be adopting a more visible role to deter
Iranian attacks.
   Rinn, a 40-year New Yorker who now lives in Summerville, S.C.,
parried questions about any new mission. His instructions
concerning Iranian activity remain clear, he said: ``Do not close
(on) him; do not harass him; leave him alone.''
   The first sign of a shift in approach comes at a time when Iran
and Iraq have resumed attacks on gulf shipping.
   Iraq uses warplanes to strike shuttle tankers carrying Iranian
oil through the gulf. Tehran retaliates with raids by speedboats
and larger vessels on neutral shipping.
   Nearly 500 ships have been damaged since the war began and more
than 300 sailors have been killed.
   After the dash to draw within close range of the Iranian craft,
Rinn said it tried to turn the tables by approaching to within
1,200 yards of the Roberts soon after dawn Thursday. The American
warship abruptly changed course, wheeling on the approaching
Iranian, and it altered course.
   The Tomb kept to a parallel course as the Roberts sailed into
the Strait of Hormuz, the narrow southern gate to the Persian Gulf,
and joined its sister ship Jack Williams and the frigate USS Bagley.
   They sailed westward into the teeth of a continuing shamal, a
gulf storm that blows from the northwest and typically lasts about
24 hours. Winds exceeded 25 knots most of the day. Seas ran more
than 15 feet, rolling the ships on their beams.
   Under clear skies, the roaring winds churned the relatively
shallow Persian Gulf into a white-capped maelstrom. Waves crashed
over the bows of the warships and their hulls were exposed to view
as they hobby-horsed up the Hormuz.
   Although routine for the 202 crew members, pursuit of the
Iranian vessel had considerable minute-by-minute drama. The Roberts
combat information center, its computer screens aglow like a video
arcade, tracked a variety of unidentified air and sea ``contacts''
as the ship headed south.
   Rinn ordered his second gas turbine engine fired up to help
drive the ship at up to 26 knots, then varied speed as the Tomb
became a visible light in the distance.
   Huge waves were illuminated by phosphorescent plankton and
jellyfish, glowing like submerged flashlights of green, blue and
white.
   The 4,200-ton Roberts rolled as much as 35 degrees during the
dash down the gulf, causing equipment not lashed down to clatter
across the decks, tipping over chairs in the officers' wardroom and
spilling some off-duty sailors from their berths.
   The seas became so rough that the lookout stationed in a chair
on the ship's ``bullnose'' was pulled in for fear he might be
washed overboard.
</TEXT>
