<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Soldier,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burial For British Soldier Killed At an IRA Funeral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of two British soldiers killed by the Irish
Republicn Army at a funeral last week was buried Thursday with full
military honors.
   Cpl. Derek Wood, 24, of the Royal Corps of Signals was buried
next to his mother's grave at St. Peter's Church, Carshalton, near
London, where he was christened.
   Army comrades carried his casket, which was draped in the
British flag and had Wood's army cap resting on it. A lone bugler
sounded taps and an army firing party shot off three volleys in the
air toward his grave.
   Wood and Cpl. David Howes, 23, also of the Royal Corps of
Signals, were attacked by members of the Roman Catholic procession
when they drove up to the funeral cortege of IRA guerrilla Kevin
Brady in west Belfast last Saturday.
   An inscription on an unsigned card with a floral spray at Wood's
funeral read: ``Corporals Derek Wood and David Howes died heroes
whilst amongst cowards. God bless and rest in peace.''
   In scenes that shocked television audiences around the world,
members of the enraged crowd were seen to drag the two soldiers
from their car, strip them and beat them with iron bars. The two
were then taken to a nearby Gaelic football ground where IRA gunmen
shot them to death.
</TEXT>
