<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Boesky     03-24 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boesky,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Financier Spends First Full Day In Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOMPOC, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fallen financier Ivan F. Boesky on
Thursday spent his first full day at a minimum-security prison
nicknamed ``Club Fed,'' where he was sent to serve a three-year
sentence for insider trading.
   Boesky's arrival Wednesday received more attention than anyone
else's since White House aide H.R. Haldeman reported to serve time
for his part in the Watergate scandal, said Chuck LaRoe, the
warden's executive assistant.
   Boesky, 51, pleaded guilty to conspiracy to lie to the
Securities and Exchange Commission. The earliest he can be released
from prison is March 22, 1989.
   The federal prison camp is situated 150 miles north of Los
Angeles. It is on 44,000 acres of heavily forested land.
   It has earned a reputation as a country club among prisons
because it offers cable television, tennis, weightlifting, boccie,
billiards and other activities to inmates.
   Jobs open to Boesky include work in the prison's furniture
factory, dairy farm or cattle ranch. The once high-flying Wall
Street speculator could also take a clerical job, LaRoe said. Pay
ranges from 11 cents to $1.10 an hour.
   Boesky has declined all contact with the news media and signed a
statement requesting privacy, LaRoe said. He cannot conduct
business while in prison but can receive visitors for up to 50
hours a month.
   Boesky paid the SEC a record $100 million fine in 1986 to settle
civil charges of insider trading, the use of confidential
information to profit in securities deals. He has cooperated
extensively with federal investigators.
   The prison, designed to hold 450 inmates, houses 630.
Overcrowding has forced double-bunking, LaRoe said.
</TEXT>
