<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Mecham 1stLd-Writethru a0799 03-24 0812</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mecham, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0799,0832</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecution Rests Case on Second Charge in Mecham Impeachment
Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with later testimony; RECASTS and
reorganizes throughout. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Testimony from a former Arizona attorney
general that Gov. Evan Mecham broke the law in borrowing $80,000
from a ``protocol fund'' for his auto dealership was likened to a
``nuclear explosion'' by a lawmaker Thursday.
   The lawmaker, Republican Sen. Tony West, said that according to
former Attorney General Jack LaSota's analysis, Mecham's action
constituted a felony punishable by up to five years in prison and a
$150,000 fine.
   LaSota testified Wednesday that the $80,000 was public money and
thus an illegal loan.
   The testimony from LaSota came shortly before the prosecution
rested Thursday on the second impeachment charge against the
first-term Republican governor. LaSota served under Mecham's
predecessor, Democrat Bruce Babbitt.
   ``We have seen some hand grenades go off here. We have seen some
bombshells,'' West told the witness. ``But I think your testimony,
if accurate, is either a nuclear explosion or at least
devastating.''
   ``Why do we not have the proper prosecutorial authorities
investigating this?'' demanded West.
   Impeachment charges against Mecham include misusing or
embezzling public funds through the loan in July from a fund
intended to promote the image of Arizona.
   Senators, who are sitting as judge and jury, previously heard
testimony on a charge that Mecham tried to thwart an investigation
of an alleged death threat by an aide. Still to be heard is a
charge that Mecham concealed a $350,000 campaign loan.
   Mecham is the first U.S. governor to face an impeachment trial
in six decades. He also faces a May 17 recall election and an April
21 trial April 21 on felony charges that he concealed the $350,000
loan.
   The protocol fund was set up with $92,000 raised by Mecham's
inaugural ball. State law barred its intended use to pay off
campaign debts, and an agreement was reached to place it in a fund
for promoting the image of Arizona.
   The prosecution has contended the fund was public money, while
the defense has contended it was private.
   Mecham's lawyer Jerris Leonard has said Mecham will testify that
his car dealership did not need the money and that his only motive
was to increase the protocol fund by borrowing from it at higher
interest than it was then receiving.
   As the defense opened its case on the loan Thursday, the
governor's banker testified he would have given Mecham an $80,000
loan with no collateral because he was a trusted customer.
   Roger Hagadorn, a Valley National Bank vice president who said
he has done business with Mecham, his dealership and his brothers
for 20 years, said the Mechams had good credit and had never
defaulted on a loan.
   Hagadorn said that if he had been asked last summer, he would
have given Mecham an $80,000 loan without collateral and would have
charged him interest of 9.5 or 10 percent. The governor borrowed
from the protocol fund at 9 percent.
   Later, during cross-examination Hagadorn appeared stunned when
prosecutor Paul Eckstein produced a letter showing that Mecham in
fact had defaulted on a loan from Valley National for $101,905.
Hagadorn conceded he might have thought twice about granting
another loan if he had known.
   The bank's letter demanding payment was written on the same day
that Mecham received the $80,000 loan from the protocol fund.
   Earlier, prosecution witness Jeffrey Colville, who said he has
never done business with the governor, said he would have refused
the loan based on financial records of Mecham Pontiac. Colville, a
developer and mortgage banker, said the company was encumbered by
liens for more than the business' appraised value.
   Colville cited liens for $3.7 million and said the most recent
appraisal of the business put its value at $3.35 million.
   Leonard suggested that Colville did not have the complete
records, was misinterpreting the record he did have and didn't know
the banking business well enough to give expert testimony. He also
suggested the appraisal of Mecham Pontiac was too low.
   Mecham's former chief of staff, Jim Colter, has testified he
processed the $80,000 loan without checking the financial condition
of Mecham Pontiac.
   Later in the day, Mecham's former special assistant, Sam
Steiger, testified he thought the loan was ``stupid politically''
but not illegal. He said he had advised Mecham's chief of staff
that the funds could not be construed as public funds.
   ``The argument I used then was these are not taxes; these are
not fees; these are not licenses,'' he said. ``By no stretch of the
imagination would be it be possible to construe these were public
funds.''
   Asked whether he thought Mecham's loan broke the law, Steiger
said, ``I thought it was stupid politically, but I at no time
considered it would be illegal.''
</TEXT>
