<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 2131EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Contraceptives-Cancer     03-24 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contraceptives-Cancer,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study: Long-Term Use Does Not Increase Long-Term Risk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Long-term use of birth-control pills, even by
women who began taking them as teen-agers, does not increase the
risk of breast cancer, a new study of more than 9,000 women
concludes.
   The findings were reported in Friday's Journal of the American
Medical Association.
   Previous studies disagreed over whether the pill increases the
risk of breast cancer for women through middle age. Some
researchers have suggested the conflicting conclusions might be the
result of a long-term latent effect from early use.
   ``But we found no direct human evidence for such a latent
effect,'' said Dr. Bruce Stadel, one of the study's authors. Stadel
was at the National Institutes of Health when the study was
conducted and now is with the Food and Drug Administration in
Bethesda, Md.
   ``This was a very, very large study ... and these data are
immensely reassuring,'' he said. ``Nonetheless, everyone in the
field believes additional large studies should be conducted in the
1990s, when the women we interviewed will be in their mid-60s.''
   Early and prolonged use were defined as using oral
contraceptives for at least six years before age 25, according to
Stadel and his colleagues, who were from the Uniformed Services
University of the Health Sciences at Bethesda, Md.
   Researchers collected case histories and interviewed 4,714 women
through age 54 who had developed breast cancer, then matched them
with a control group of 4,540.
   ``We looked at many different facets, and broke the subjects
into many different groups to isolate other factors,'' said Stadel.
   ``But the thing we consistently found is that women who used the
pill for a long time, whether they were young when they began ...
the relative risks were the same when compared to women who never
used the pill when young.''
   The study did not examine the effects of short-term use.
   For women in general, the risk of developing breast cancer
during one's lifetime is about one in 10, Stadel said. More than 50
million women worldwide are on the pill, he said.
</TEXT>
