<HEAD>Honduras Protests Alleged Nicaraguan Incursion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: 10 new grafs UPDATE with Hondurans' saying Nicaraguan
soldiers now out. Picks up 10th graf pvs, Foreign Minister ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honduras filed an ``energetic
protest'' with Nicaragua over what it said were new incursions this
week by 350 Nicaraguan troops, the Foreign Minstry said Thursday.
   Ministry spokesman Eugenio Castro later said the Nicaraguan
troops had pulled out.
   Nicaragua had denied that its soldiers penetrated Honduran
territory.
   Castro said Honduran air force reconnaissance flights on
Thursday found there were no longer Sandinista troops on the
Honduran side of the border.
   ``The situation at the border apparently is calm,'' he told The
Associated Press by telelphone.
   A ministry communique earlier Thursday said 300 heavily armed
Sandinista soldiers crossed the border in the San Andres de Bocay
region, scene of fighting last week when Nicaraguan troops drove
Contra rebels back into Honduras. The area is about 150 miles east
of Tegucigalpa.
   The latest incursion occurred about 8 p.m. Tuesday, about the
same time as 50 other Sandinista soldiers entered Honduras near
Pico Espanol, a village in El Paraiso province about two miles from
the border, the communique said.
   It did not say if there was any combat.
   In Managua, Nicaragua's capital, a Defense Ministry spokesman
was asked about the Honduran report. ``That's negative,'' he said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Honduran President Jose Azcona Hoyo declined Thursday to discuss
the reported incursions.``We continue to act with prudence,'' he
said.
   Foreign Minister Carlos Lopez Contreras was in Guatemala on
Thursday for a meeting with other Central American foreign
ministers.
   The government said last week there were up to 2,000 Sandinista
troops in Honduras and later said all had retreated back to
Nicaragua.
   Honduran jets raided Nicaraguan targets in the Bocay region
twice last week and Azcona said then that he would send more
warplanes to attack Nicaraguan troops if they did not leave.
   That incursion and a request for help by Azcona Hoyo resulted in
the emergency deployment of 3,200 U.S. troops to Honduras last week.
   The Americans, who are conducting joint training exercises with
Honduran soldiers, are expected to leave this country early next
week, the Pentagon said.
   Meanwhile, Honduras has asked U.S. Ambassador Everett Briggs for
a clarification on reported comments by U.S. Defense Secretary
Frank Carlucci about the reason American soldiers are in Honduras.
   In a news release late Wednesday, Lopez Contreras said he wanted
to know why U.S. authorities were saying the Americans were here to
protect Contra rebels in Honduras.
   ``These (American) troops that came to Honduras were requested
by the government of President Jose Azcona Hoyo regarding the
threat of incursions from the Sandinista army against the national
territory ... and not for the principal objective of fortifying or
protecting the Nicaraguan insurgents who are struggling against the
Sandinista regime,'' Lopez Contreras said.
   He proposed the creation of a peacekeeping force along the
border region.
   Briggs refused to meet leaders of seven citizens organizations
at the U.S. Embassy in Tegucigalpa Thursday.
   The leaders, whose groups are united under the umbrella
Coordinating Committee for Popular Organizations, later met at a
plaza where about 200 people had gathered and read a letter
protesting U.S. troops in Honduras.
   The letter said the presence of U.S. troops in Honduras meant
``that our country has been converted into a battle platform in the
Central American region.''
</TEXT>
