<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Summit 1stLd-Writethru a0831 03-24 0844</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Summit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0831,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Belittles Soviet Technology For Spotting Nuclear Missiles On
Ships</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 10 grafs after 2nd graf to add U.S. proposals
regarding space-based weapons systems; Picks up 4th graf pvs bgng:
The senior ..., editing to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States belittled Soviet technology
for detecting nuclear missiles aboard ships and snubbed an
invitation this week to see the process before the May 29-June 2
summit meeting in Moscow, a senior U.S. official said Thursday.
   During three days of pre-summit talks in Washington this week,
Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze offered to let the
United States participate in an experiment to test the system in
April.
   Meanwhile, the United States offered some new proposals of its
own regarding space-based weapons systems.
   One was the exemption of spy satellites from treaty
restrictions, an idea that the Soviets apparently found interesting.
   ``We think they're useful to our security,'' a senior
administration official said Thursday. ``They think they're useful
to theirs.''
   The other idea was that U.S. and Soviet negotiators make a
special effort to define space-based testing and deployment.
   ``Then we could also work on the idea of having
confidence-building measures or what we call predictability
measures which could reduce the difficulties between the two sides
with respect to other types of systems that might be tested or
other kinds of devices,'' the official said.
   Details of that proposal have not been settled, but officials
said the most likely approach would be to allow only a limited
number of space weapons prototypes to be tested in a region of
space where they would have little value in an actual missile
defense.
   The two proposals were intended to resolve the contentious
battle over the U.S. Strategic Defense Initiative, known also as
Star Wars, which is possibly the biggest obstacle to reaching
agreement to cut long-range nuclear weapons.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz said Wednesday that the two
issues would be negotiated separately but that agreements in the
two areas should be ``completed more or less at the same time so
the two things move in parallel.'' The United States has long said
that the two issues should be handled separately.
   Shevardnadze, meanwhile, said Wednesday night that ``of course
there is'' a linkage between resolving the defense in space issues
and the treaty to reduce long-range strategic weapons.
   ``There will be no treaty on the 50 percent reduction in
strategic offensive arms if there is no observance of the ABM
treaty, at least for an agreed period of time,'' Shevardnadze said.
The Soviets, as well as some in Congress, say SDI would violate the
1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
   Shevardnadze hailed the system to detect nuclear missiles on
ships as a technological milestone in missile detection that would
help the superpowers achieve their goal of a summit agreement to
cut long-range nuclear arsenals.
   The senior U.S. official said, however, ``we're not interested''
because the system doesn't detect nuclear sea-launched cruise
missiles, as the Soviets claim.
   ``The Soviets could not explain how this experiment would tell
us more than we already know,'' the official said. ``Such
technology would not be effective under realistic conditions.''
   It could not, for example, tell the difference between nuclear
warheads and atomic propulsion systems used on many surface ships,
the official said.
   ``Our people know a great deal about the ideas that the Soviets
have advanced, and we've looked into it carefully,'' the official
said.
   When they agreed in principle last December to hold a springtime
summit in Moscow, President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev said they wanted to sign an agreement to cut the numbers
of long-range nuclear missiles and bombers by 30 percent to 50
percent.
   With little progress _ notably on the verification issues _
during Shevardnadze's visit to Washington for three days this week,
neither side predicted the agreement would be ready in time.
   The senior U.S. official said, moreover, that until the
negotiators prove they can verify elimination of the various types
of weapons involved, they won't know which ones will be covered in
a treaty.
   Another official, noting that the two nations also disagree on
such explosive issues as Afghanistan, the Middle East, Central
America and human rights warned against expecting ``easy
solutions'' to U.S.-Soviet problems.
   The official described the most recent talks as ``grueling,''
notably in the 11 hours of discussion on the regional hot spots.
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater sought to dispel
suggestions that the summit meeting _ in the twilight of Reagan's
presidency _ would be a ceremonial and symbolic visit short on
substantive accomplishments.
   During Shevardnadze's talks in Washington ``we made enough
progress to keep going and presumably we will make more in the days
ahead,'' the spokesman told reporters.
   During the talks this week both sides ``faced all the tough
problems'' and left no confusion about where both sides stand, he
said.
   The summit ``will be well prepared; there will be substance to
discuss; there will be good prospects for success,'' Fitzwater said.
</TEXT>
