<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Shultz-MiddleEast 1stLd-Writethru a0728 03-24 0834</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Middle East, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0728,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US-Soviet Talks On Mideast Extended</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Adds 4 grafs on report of Israeli practice bombing runs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S.-Soviet talks on the Middle East were
extended Thursday while Arabs and Israelis continued to delay a
response to an American plan for negotiations.
   Vladimir Polyakov, a specialist in the Soviet Foreign Ministry,
met with Assistant Secretary of State Richard W. Murphy despite
what U.S. officials described as a fundamental difference in the
two superpowers' positions.
   The Soviets are seeking an active role in any peace conference,
while Secretary of State George P. Shultz said Wednesday night he
did not want any interference in Arab-Israeli negotiations.
   ``It's quite clear the Soviet concept of how to go about this is
really sharply different from ours,'' Shultz told reporters after
three days of talks with Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir also objects to an active
Soviet role, but King Hussein of Jordan is seeking Soviet
participation in the negotiations.
   Shevardnadze left Polyakov behind to continue the discussions
with Murphy and flew home to Moscow. U.S. envoy Philip C. Habib,
meanwhile, completed talks in Amman with Hussein and returned to
Washington to report to Shultz.
   Shultz said that despite having no direct reply from the
Israelis or Arabs to his plan to open negotiations by May 1 he
would not give up.
   ``We will continue to work with the parties directly involved,
and we will continue to try, in every way we can, to find our way
to the direct, face-to-face negotiations that we believe are the
only way in which you can really resolve these issues,'' he said.
   ``Now how to get there is difficult, and we will continue to
push for and, at the same time, maintain the limitations on the
kind of conference we've called for. And, we'll just have to see
how that goes.''
   Shultz said ``nobody seems to be ready to climb on our
bandwagon, including the Soviet Union. On the other hand, everybody
wants to keep it rolling, so we'll keep it rolling.''
   Asked if he planned to return to the Middle East, Shultz said he
had not made a decision. He said his lengthy talks with
Shevardnadze had made it difficult for him ``to come up for air''
and evaluate reports from the region.
   Shultz presented his plan for negotiations to Arab and Israeli
leaders three weeks ago and asked for a reply by mid-March.
   ``I am ready to go to the Middle East anytime it seems as though
there is even a remote chance of being constructive,'' Shultz said.
``I don't have to have a high probability.''
   The U.S. plan excludes the Palestine Liberation Organization
from proposed negotiations but provides for a joint
Jordanian-Palestinian delegation.
   Meantime Thursday, Murphy told the House Appropriations
subcommittee on foreign operations ``it's a tough question but I
don't think it's insuperable'' to find a credible Palestinian
leader to participate without driving Israel away from the
bargaining table.
   Murphy added that the PLO ``remains for Palestinians, by and
large, the only leadership they accept.'' But he did not say a
Palestinian participant would necessarily have to be a PLO
representative.
   Five demonstrators wearing T-shirts reading ``Stop U.S. Aid to
Israel'' stood silently against a hearing room wall throughout most
of Murphy's testimony and left without incident after about an hour.
   Murphy said ``it would be the dangerous to the peace process''
for the United States to reduce its annual payment of $2.2 billion
in military and economic aid to Israel to protest its handling of
Palestinian unrest on the occupied West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
   The State Department official said any such aid reduction might
be interpreted in Arab capitals as a weakening of ties between the
United States and Israel and might invite a renewal of military
assaults against the Jewish state.
   Under questioning, Murphy said the United States had assurances
from ``the highest levels'' in Saudi Arabia and China that the
medium-range missiles that China recently agreed to provide to the
Saudis contain conventional and not nuclear warheads.
   The Washington Post reported in Friday's editions that the
Israeli Air Force has been conducting unusually intensive low-level
bombing practice runs at the same time Saudi Arabia is digging in
its new missiles.
   The newspaper quoted U.S. intelligence officials as saying that
the bombing could be in preparation for a pre-emptive strike
against the missiles, as a senior Israeli official warned Sunday.
However, the officials said they had no hard evidence that an
Israeli strike was imminent.
   Satellite photography and other intelligence have revealed that
Israel has been flying F-15 fighter bombers in attack profiles and
that Saudi Arabia has been building shelters for its missiles, the
Post reported.
   Saudi Arabia has sent a warning through the United States that
it will retaliate with its surviving missiles with a range of up to
1,500 miles if Israel tries to bomb its missiles, diplomatic
sources told the newspaper.
</TEXT>
