<HEAD>Charleston Orders Police, Firefighters To End Sick-out</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-8 bgng `Firemen and ...' to restore dropped
first reference to Gardner and to DELETE extraneous material,
picking up 9th graf `Gardner declined ...' and INSERTS 1 graf after
24th graf `Under the ...' to ADD background on pvs raises.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN L. HERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly all of Charleston's police
officers and firefighters called in sick Thursday to protest a 2
percent pay raise, then ignored back-to-work orders from a judge
and the City Council.
   Less than an hour before an emergency council meeting Thursday
afternoon, Kanawha County Circuit Judge Patrick Casey issued a
temporary injunction ordering firefighters to work immediately and
police to report at their next scheduled shift.
   The missing police officers did not report for the 3 p.m. shift,
however, and firefighters also refused to report.
   ``We just want an honest living,'' said Fire Department Lt. Walt
Cavender, who was on duty at the city's station No. 1. ``We're
going backward in pay.''
   The ``blue flu'' in West Virginia's capital and largest city
began Wednesday night when officers began refusing to show up for
work.
   At the 6 a.m. shift change, 16 of 17 uniformed police officers
and 42 of 44 firefighters scheduled to report failed to show up.
   Firemen and police officers who were on duty overnight were
retained on overtime, giving the fire department a full complement
of men, and process servers took return-to-work orders to the
absent personnel Thursday afternoon, said Mayor Chuck Gardner.
   Gardner declared a state of civil emergency earlier in the day,
saying the policemen and firefighters must return because ``the
safety of the citizens of Charleston is not a bargaining chip.''
   Police Chief Ed Garnett told an emergency meeting of the city
council that only 13 officers, covering all grades, showed up
Thursday morning, ``most of them supervisors.'' He said only three
cars were on patrol Thursday morning, with two officers in each car.
   Garnett also told the council members that since Wednesday night
68 officers and 42 firemen had called in sick as of 9 a.m.
   The city budget, approved Monday night, includes appropriations
for 165 policemen, 147 firefighters and 10 paramedics for the city
of 63,000.
   Garnett said the firefighters who were on the job had been there
since 8 a.m. Wednesday and were tiring quickly.
   ``I don't know how long they can stay there,'' he said.
   The council unanimously suspended the city's sick-leave policy,
meaning that any more officers calling in sick would have to have a
doctor's excuse to get paid for any additional days absent from
work.
   Gardner, facing his first crisis since taking over as mayor four
months ago, said it wasn't illegal to call the council into
emergency session on less than four hours' notice and suspend
sections of the city code. The code requires two days' notice of
emergency meetings.
   No police or firefighters picketed Thursday, but about 20 police
wives marched in front of City Hall and carried signs. Passing
motorists honked their horns in support and some _ aware that
patrols were down _ took the opportunity to run red lights.
   ``We have several police officers that qualify for welfare,''
said police wife Val Lockard.
   Kanawha County Sheriff Danny Jones said his department would
provide assistance to the city only ``if there's a murder or
something.''
   ``We don't have the manpower to work the city,'' Jones said.
   State police Superintendent W.F. Donohoe said Gardner had asked
the governor for state police help. ``We will answer calls on a
priority basis to the very best of our ability,'' Donohoe said.
   The police officers believe their 2 percent raise will be eaten
up by a higher deductible on their health insurance and an increase
in the city's incinerator fee from $30 to $85.
   ``It's not easy to raise the incinerator fee. But without a
raise in the incinerator fee, we didn't have money to increase
salaries,'' said Councilwoman Maggie McCoy.
   Under the budget approved this week, salaries for uniformed
police officers range from $27,673 for a captain with 20 years'
experience to $18,589 for a patrol officer with three years'
experience.
   Mayoral Aide Ed Esposito said that no raises had been given this
year but that police and firefighters had received a 3 percent
raise in the 1986-87 fiscal year and raises totaling 8 percent over
the past five years.
   By comparison, at the Kanawha County Sheriff's Department, where
deputies have gotten raises totaling 25 percent over the past 3{
years, a deputy with three years' experience will make $21,720 as
of July 1, Jones said.
   City firefighters' pay ranges from $27,673 for an assistant fire
chief with 20 years' experience to $18,409 for a first-year
firefighter.
</TEXT>
