<HEAD>Man With Perpetual Frown Given Deserves More, Court Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state appeals court Wednesday rejected as
too low a $3,500 damage award to a salesman left with a perpetual
frown after an auto accident.
   ``Such scars are of a greater consequence to a 24-year-old
single man who has chosen a career in sales than that amount
reflects,'' a two-judge panel ruled in ordering a new trial on the
issue of damages for Robert Tronolone.
   Tronolone was a passenger in a car that struck a utility pole in
Bridgewater Township.
   A jury found the driver, Peter Palmer, negligent and awarded
Tronolone $750, but the judge at the trial found it inadequate and
raised it to $3,500. Tronolone appealed.
