<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia-Drugs 2ndLd-Writethru   03-24 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Drugs, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0929,0637</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security Chief For Anti-Drug Newspaper Slain</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to fix typo in gunmen and SUBS 13th graf pvs `The
Justice Ministry ...' to fix spelling of Ochoa.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MEDELLIN, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen ambushed and killed on
Wednesday the security chief for a newspaper that had urged the
government not to back down in its war on drug traffickers, police
said.
   Jorge Alberto Stefan Gomez was hit by five bullets fired by
three men on motorcycles, police said in a news release. His
10-month-old daughter was grazed by a bullet and hospitalized in
satisfactory condition, police said.
   Colombia's Council of State meanwhile ordered the temporary
suspension of arrest orders for five members of the Medellin
cartel, a group said to dominate cocaine trafficking in Colombia.
   The suspension of the arrest orders Wednesday is almost certain
to bring an angry reaction from U.S. authorities, who have begun to
question the Colombian government's position on rounding up drug
traffickers.
   Stefan and family were waiting for a taxi near their home when
three men on motorcycles opened fire with pistols and a submachine
gun, the police said. His wife was not hurt.
   Police said they didn't know who was responsible for Stefan's
killing.
   Stefan was chief of security for Medellin's El Colombiano
newspaper, which has urged the government not to give in to drug
traffickers. He also served as security chief for the newspaper's
publisher, Juan Gomez Martinez, who was elected mayor on March 13.
Gomez takes office June 1.
   On March 10, two bombs were thrown from a speeding car into the
entryway of El Colombiano. A guard threw the bombs back into the
street and a passer-by was killed.
   In November, gunmen shot up Gomez's home. The gunmen apparently
were trying to kidnap Gomez in an attempt to get the government to
suspend extraditions of Colombians to the United States to face
drug trafficking charges.
   Many drug traffickers live and process cocaine base in Medellin.
   Colombian drug traffickers have killed a justice minister, an
attorney general, 21 judges, two newspaper editors and scores of
policemen and soldiers in the last four years.
   The suspension of arrest orders for the Medellin cartel was
announced by Supreme Court Justice Samuel Buitrago, a member of the
Council of State.
   The Justice Ministry in January ordered the arrest of alleged
Medellin cartel members Pablo Escobar, Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha and
three brothers, Jorge Luis Ochoa, Juan David Ochoa and Fabio Ochoa.
   Buitrago, making the announcement during an interview by the
Bogota radio station Caracol, said the arrest orders were being
suspended while the government studies possible charges in Colombia
against the five men.
   Buitrago said the suspension of the arrest orders is temporary
until the council decides if it will permanently cancel the orders.
It could be up to two months before the council makes its final
decision.
   Meanwhile, Escobar's wife and 25 of his guards appeared before a
judge in Medellin after a shootout at Escobar's home near that
northwest Colombian city.
   Escobar apparently was at home when the shootout began but
escaped. The U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration says Escobar is
among the world's biggest cocaine traffickers. He is wanted for
trial in the United States.
   Army troops surrounded the Escobar home Tuesday, setting off a
sophisticated alarm system of sirens and flashing lights, the
army's 4th Brigade headquarters in Medellin said in a news release.
   A gunbattle ensued, and one Escobar guard was wounded, the army
said.
   The army found numerous guns, lots of ammunition and
sophisticated communications equipment, the Colombian radio chain
RCN said.
   Escobar's wife, Maria Victoria Henao de Escobar, was released by
the Medellin judge, RCN said, quoting a source with the attorney
general's office.
</TEXT>
