<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PanchoVillaPlot     03-24 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pancho Villa Plot,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NMSU Professors Say Documents Show Villa Was Targeted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS CRUCES, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two New Mexico State University history
professors said Wednesday that government documents indicate Army
intelligence officers attempted to kill Mexican revolutionary
Pancho Villa by poisoning in 1916.
   Charles H. Harris III and Louis Sadler presented the findings in
a paper submitted at a monthly meeting of the Latin American
studies forum at New Mexico State.
   They said the attempt came during an American expedition into
Mexico in pursuit of Villa and his men. The expedition followed a
raid by Villa on the New Mexico community of Columbus that left 17
American soldiers and civilians dead.
   The attempt was made in the town of Jimenez, Mexico, four months
after the raid on Columbus, according to Sadler and Harris.
   The plot called for two Japanese men who were employed as secret
agents for the American government to put poison in a cup of coffee
intended for Villa, the professors said.
   The two agents posed as peddlers and wanted Villa to think they
were sympathetic to his revolutionary cause. Villa foiled the
assassination attempt by pouring part of the coffee into another
man's cup, the professors said.
   The fate of the man into whose cup Villa poured the coffee was
not known, the professors said. The poison was supposed to be
odorless and tasteless and cause death three days after ingestion.
   Historians consider the Columbus raid a turning point in the
Mexican revolution because it rallied American public opinion
against Villa and his men. Gen. John J. Pershing led the
retaliatory expedition.
   ``We can't prove it but there is no doubt in my mind that he
knew'' of the plot, Sadler said.
   The professors said that while there were official inquiries
into the alleged plot, Pershing denied any knowledge of it. The
assassination attempt, according to the professors, was covered up.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880324-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0034EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     03-24 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Rashomon' Revived Tellingly off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The telling and retelling of a story of rape and
murder from various points of view makes for little suspense, but
good acting and direction keep up interest in an off-Broadway
revival of the 1959 stage version of ``Rashomon.''
   The play by Fay and Michael Kanin is based on the 1951 Japanese
movie of the same name and on stories by Ryunosuke Akutagawa
published in 1915.
   It is the story of a samurai and his wife who encounter a bandit
in the forest. The wife is raped and the samurai is found dead. But
the circumstances vary depending on who does the telling.
   Knowing the rape and death will be depicted several times, the
audience can focus on how each person tells the story to paint
himself or herself to best advantage.
   The husband's ghost, conjured up in a courtroom, tells of
suicide, while the bandit and the wife both confess to murder. The
bandit figures he'll be executed anyway; the wife thinks she'll be
pardoned. It would shame them more to be publicly revealed as
lacking in the personality they've presented to the world than to
proclaim that they were driven to kill.
   The final version, told by a woodcutter who witnessed the
encounter from a hiding place, is hilarious as husband and wife
bicker and the honorable samurai and daring bandit are afraid to
fight.
   The entire cast is Asian in this first major revival of the play
since it played on Broadway in 1959 starring Claire Bloom, Rod
Steiger, Noel Willman and Oscar Homolka.
   The cast includes James Saito as the bandit who turns
somersaults during swordfights; Kiya Ann Joyce, who can take on
many womanly aspects depending whose story she is acting; Philip
Moon, who usually is bound and gagged as the husband; Peter
Yoshida, the woodcutter, and Thom Sesma, a priest.
   David Leong expertly directed fights and movement. Mina
Albergo's setting is a forest clearing, alabaster with bamboo-leaf
tracings, with the Rashomon Gate at one side. The set enhances the
openness with which director Robert Kalfin places this ``Rashomon''
before the audience. The play will run through May 8.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
