<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Dominican-Trip     03-24 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dominican-Trip,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Balaguer Leaves For Washington Thursday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUDDY L. GONZALEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Joaquin
Balaguer will leave for the United States Thursday, where he will
meet with President Reagan and discuss this nation's $4 billion
foreign debt, officials said.
   Foreign Minister Donald Reid Cabral told a news conference
Balaguer also is expected to discuss the U.S. sugar quota with
Reagan Friday.
   Balaguer will meet with International Monetary Fund and World
Bank officials while in Washington, the minister said Wednesday
night.
   He said the president will have his eyes checked in Boston
before returning home. The 80-year-old president suffers from
glaucoma and is nearly blind.
   Balaguer, elected to his fifth four-year term of office 19
months ago, is seeking to find ways to turn the Dominican
Republic's economy around.
   He announced a 25 percent increase in the minimum wage this
month following riots that left five people dead and 20 injured.
   Last year, the government paid around $700 million to service
its foreign debt.
   Officials in Santo Domingo say part of the reason for this
Caribbean nation's economic slump is the cut in the U.S. quota for
Dominican sugar, this nation's most important export.
   The U.S. quota for Dominican sugar now is 160,000 tons compared
to 525,000 tons in 1983.
   U.S. aid to the Dominican Republic is $150 million. The republic
also receives an additional $35 million annually in surplus food.
   Traveling with Balaguer will be the U.S. ambassador to the
Dominican Republic, Lowell Kilday, and 10 government officials,
according to Reid Cabral. Balaquer will stay at the home of the
Dominican ambassador, Jose Leon Asencio, while in Washington.
</TEXT>
