<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1136EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-ProgeriaTeen Adv25   03-24 1021</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Progeria Teen, Adv 25,1053</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday PMs, March 25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Progeria Victim Beating the Odds at Age 15</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVAN RAMSTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONGVIEW, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At age 15, Mickey Hays has appeared in a
feature-length movie, has learned to hunt and to ride an off-road
motorcycle, and has traveled and made a lot of friends.
   ``If I die today, I feel like I've had a good life,'' says the
boy, who suffers from progeria, a rare condition that has caused
his diminutive body to age far beyond his years.
   Most children with progeria die before reaching their teens,
usually of a stroke or heart-related cause.
   Experts say the condition strikes one in 8 million children, and
only about 70 cases have ever been reported. Only 15 or so people
are alive today who suffer from the disease, thought to be caused
by a genetic pituitary disorder, according to Baylor University
Medical Center's Dr. Geoff Sherwood.
   And yet, except for the fact that he doesn't go to school,
Mickey tries to be a typical teen-ager. His life is an ongoing
defiance of the odds and medical convention about his condition.
   ``When they first told my parents about progeria, they said I
wouldn't live more than a month,'' Mickey says of the time at age 4
when doctors finally put a name on the condition that had hardened
his skin and caused his hair to fall out.
   ``They keep pushing it back. When I was 5, they said 7. When I
was 7, they said 10. When I was 10, they said 12. Now I'm 15, and
they say 18.''
   It's gotten so that Mickey doesn't listen anymore and visits a
physician just once a year for a checkup.
   ``I feel fine. I feel great,'' he said in a recent interview in
his rural Longview home.
   Two years ago, Mickey suffered congestive heart failure brought
on by progeria, but now his only disability seems to be that
sunshine or other bright light hurts his eyes.
   Still, he didn't let the sun keep him from going on a
church-sponsored youth trip to a water park in Dallas, 100 miles
away, or from being outside with friends. He simply wears a cap.
   As he nears his 16th birthday on June 30, Mickey looks forward
to a rite of passage: obtaining a driver's license and a pickup
truck _ ``a jet black Nissan hardbody,'' he says.
   Extenders attached to the controls of his mother's van helped
Mickey, who is only 3 feet tall, learn to drive. But like many of
his friends, Mickey drives his own four-wheel motorcycle through
the piney woods that surround his home.
   ``Just about everybody has motorcycles and four-wheelers,''
Mickey explains. ``There's a hill everybody goes to called `The
Mountain.' It's the highest point in Gregg County and from there
you can look down on Longview. It's real nice.''
   Over pizza, two of Mickey's friends, Holly Santos and Kim Head,
talked about rock concerts they've attended with him in Shreveport,
La., and Dallas. They teased him about new cowboy boots and about
not attending school.
   ``I'd stay in school just to be around everybody,'' Holly said.
   But Mickey, who would be in 10th grade, doesn't attend classes:
``I quit after seventh grade. I got in too much trouble. I didn't
like being told to shut up.''
   When his friends are in school, Mickey spends his days working
on his four-wheeler, hunting in season (he has bagged five deer and
16 raccoons), watching soap operas, listening to pop musicians
Tiffany and Whitesnake, and playing with his toddler brother, Jared.
   He mows yards for neighbors and occasionally works in his mother
Cindy Wilkerson's income tax preparation office and his stepfather
Larry Wilkerson's business machine outlet.
   ``There's always a way to make money,'' Mickey said, adding that
his favorite way would be to work in show business again.
   He played a gentle old visitor from space in ``The Aurora
Encounter,'' a 1985 feature-length movie, and now envisions a part
in a credit card commercial:
   ``Do you know me?'' he would ask. ``I'm not an alien who visited
Texas in the 19th century just to be killed by a frightened Texas
Ranger. That's just a movie role I played.''
   Because of the movie part, Mickey says he became ``somebody''
rather than ``somebody different.''
   ``People before always used to notice me as somebody
different,'' Mickey said. ``Now I go somewhere and people recognize
me as Mickey Hays, someone who played in a movie.''
   The role is one of two experiences in recent years that Mickey
said built his self-esteem. The second was meeting Fransie
Geringer, the progeric son of a South African coal miner, in 1982.
It was the first time either boy had met someone else with progeria.
   They met at Disneyland and Mickey later visited Fransie in
Orkney, South Africa. Now, the two have linked with about 15 other
progeric children and many of them started attending an annual
reunion a few years ago.
   Of the progeric children who attend, Mickey said he is the
oldest and possibly the healthiest. A Canadian girl, six months
older than Mickey, died recently, according to his mother.
   ``Mickey and I have had a nice life, but there are times when
you start feeling sorry for yourself,'' Mrs. Wilkerson said. ``If
someone says, `I know how you feel,' well, it's nice, but at the
reunions, other parents really do know how I feel.''
   Mrs. Wilkerson takes pictures of Mickey as an infant, when he
looked like any normal baby, to the reunions to show the other
parents.
   ``They look at Mickey and I and see what's ahead. They really
can't imagine what their children will be like. Mickey being so
outgoing gives them hope.''
   Progeric children should consider themselves very lucky if they
live to age 20, Dr. Sherwood said.
   Still, when the conversation turns to mortality, Mickey speaks
without hesitation of his Baptist upbringing.
   ``I think I'll live as long as God wants me to live. Everybody's
got to die sometime.''

</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Friday PMs, March 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880324-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1019EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-PersonalFile-VanHoutte Adv25   03-24 0861</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Personal File-Van Houtte, Adv 25,0889</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Friday, March 25 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Raymond Van Houtte Wore Many Different Hats</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Van Houtte's one-year term as NYSBA president is set expire
by mid-May. This is also moving on the financial circuits.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ask Raymond A. Van Houtte what his childhood
ambitions were and it's unlikely that running a couple of arms
companies, practicing law, accounting, teaching or banking would
have appeared on his list.
   Yet Van Houtte, who set out to become an engineer and now heads
a small bank in upstate New York and one of the nation's most
powerful banking trade groups, has done all of them with varying
degrees of success.
   ``I don't think of myself as ambitious. I'm just interested in
many things,'' said Van Houtte, the son of a Detroit grocer. ``If
you ever get the idea you'd like to try something different, do
it.''
   Even now the 63-year-old Van Houtte continues to try on
different hats, so to speak.
   As current president of the New York State Bankers Association,
which represents many of the nation's biggest commercial banks, he
hobnobs with the likes of former Federal Reserve Chairman Paul A.
Volcker and other prominent bankers and has lobbied vigorously in
Washington, D.C. and Albany for broader banking powers.
   Van Houtte is one of the most outspoken opponents of the
Glass-Steagall Act, a Depression-era law that separates investment
banking from commercial banking, and a similar ``mini
Glass-Steagall'' in New York. He believes the laws eventually will
be repealed and envisions banks offering a wider range of financial
services in the next five years, like a one-stop shopping network.
   If it were up to Van Houtte, banks would be permitted to sell
insurance or underwrite corporate securities but those involved in
risky businesses wouldn't be eligible for deposit insurance.
   At Tompkins County Trust Co., a community bank in a college town
where Van Houtte started out as a director in the mid 1960s, the
small-town granderfatherly image emerges. There, the bank president
of 15 years meets with the local Boy Scouts of America and the
chamber of commerce, two of the many community groups in which he's
been involved.
   Van Houtte knows many of his customers on a first-name basis,
and he's been known to accommodate depositers in need of emergency
cash long after closing hours, something unheard of in a big city.
   Van Houtte, a well-dressed man with whitish hair and a pleasant
smile, recalled his first loan at Tompkins came out of his own
pocket.
   ``I had a young woman who asked me if she could borrow $20 to
buy a dress and get a job at Cornell (University). I said, `A bank
doesn't loan you $20,' so I gave her the $20 myself,'' he said in a
recent interview. ``She bought the dress, came back and showed it
to me.''
   The woman got the job and repaid the loan $5 every two weeks _
``with 6 percent interest,'' he said, betraying his stait-laced
banker's streak.
   ``I never realized I would be a banker. These are things I'm
able to do that make me feel so good,'' Van Houtte said. ``Lawyers
(for instance) don't make things happen. They sometimes prevent
things from happening.''
   His career as a lawyer spanned about 10 years and followed his
stint as a certified public accountant, which overlapped his
teaching and accounting job at the now-defunct Eastern Military
Academy in Cold Spring Harbor, N.Y., shortly after World War II.
Running two arms companies, Poly-Choke Co. in Hartford, Conn., and
Ithaca Gun Co. in Ithaca, N.Y., came somewhere in between.
   As a young lawyer he specialized in mergers and acquisitions,
but he said he also arranged a few overseas adoptions of babies
abandoned during World War II.
   The pay back then for accounting or law wasn't great, Van Houtte
said, and with a wife and three children to support, including an
infant daughter struggling with a birth defect, he found himself
living from paycheck to paycheck.
   His job at Poly-Choke, which specialized in customized gun
barrels and whose customers included Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower,
``finally gave us enough money so we could afford a two-bedroom
apartment instead of one.'' That job eventually led to Ithaca Gun,
where he served as president from 1966 to 1968.
   These days, Van Houtte and his wife, Margaret, live a
comfortable life in Ithaca, dividing their time between the bank
and community activities. Van Houtte's biggest personal
satisfaction, he says, is in helping families, businesses and
community groups get off the ground financially.
   One of his successes, he said, was arranging for a new home to
be built for the Ladies Union Benevolent Society, a century-old
organization in Ithaca that provides retirement housing for
indigent women.
   ``I really have a wonderful life as a banker,'' he said. ``You
feel good because you've helped people.''
   Next year, Van Houtte plans to retire and is looking forward to
doing a lot more traveling, fishing, gardening and shell
collecting. ``I have a lot of things I'd like to do.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Friday editions, March 25</NOTE>
