<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0559</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has delivered two welcome
pieces of economic news: consumer prices rose just 0.2 percent in
February and the economy in late 1987 expanded at the liveliest
pace in nearly two years.
   Falling energy and food prices in February helped restrain the
rise in the Labor Department's Consumer Price Index after a 0.3
percent increase in January, the government said Wednesday.
   In a separate report, the Commerce Department said the economy
grew at a brisk 4.8 percent annual pace in the final three months
of last year. It was the second upward revision in the
fourth-quarter GNP.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corporations' after-tax profits shot up 8.4
percent in 1987, the best performance in three years, as U.S.
manufacturers benefited from the weaker dollar, the government says.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday that after-tax profits
rose to $137.4 billion last year, the first increase since a 12
percent rise in 1984.
   U.S. companies have been enjoying an export boom this past year
as declines in the dollar made American products competitive again
on overseas markets.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chrysler Corp. selling surge ran counter to a
slight overall decline in mid-March domestic car sales, automakers
have reported.
   Analysts said Wednesday that higher-than-expected sales due to
incentives and a stock-crash rebound appeared to be tapering off.
   The eight companies that make autos in the United States sold
189,245 cars in the eight sales days from March 11-20, down from
217,939 in nine sales days in the comparable 1987 period.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. has won final bankruptcy
court approval for a plan that would settle its multibillion-dollar
dispute with Pennzoil Co. and bring it out of Chapter 11 protection
early next month.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge Howard Schwartzberg on Wednesday
confirmed the reorganization plan, which features an agreement by
Texaco to pay Pennzoil $3 billion to drop a $10.3 billion judgment
held by Pennzoil against Texaco.
   When the plan goes into effect on April 7, Texaco officially
will be free from legal constraints that have limited its
operations since its historic bankruptcy filing last April 12.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines says it will ban smoking on
all its domestic flights except to and from Hawaii and on some
foreign routes.
   The ban announced Wednesday makes Minneapolis-based Northwest
the first major U.S. airline to mandate a smoke-free travel
environment in the air. It goes beyond federal regulations, which
will outlaw smoking on all domestic flights of two hours or less
starting April 23.
   Northwest's stringent non-smoking policy appears to be aimed at
attracting new passengers but could backfire and cost the carrier
some traffic, some analysts believe.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, in a decision three
justices called anti-union, has ruled the government may limit a
family's eligibility for food stamps when a family member is on
strike.
   The court said Wednesday that a 1981 federal law imposing such
limits does not violate any constitutional rights.
   In another decision, the court ruled in an Illinois case that
short-term notes used to finance public housing projects are not
exempt from federal estate taxes.
</TEXT>
