<1ST_LINE>r f PM-MooreMcCormack     03-24 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Moore McCormack,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moore McCormack Announces Recapitalization Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hostile takeover target Moore McCormack
Inc. has unveiled a $400 million recapitalization plan and says it
is holding talks with unidentified parties over a possible
alternative buyout.
   The company, target of a hostile $35 a share, or $441 million,
buyout offer from Houston-based Southdown Inc., said Wednesday its
proposed recapitalization would pay shareholders a special dividend
valued at more than $33 per share in cash and securities.
   But Moore McCormack acknowledged that it would abandon the
dividend payout if it received a buyout offer that ``produces
higher values'' for shareholders, said Paul R. Tregurtha, chairman
and chief executive.
   In trading Wednesday on New York Stock Exchange, Moore McCormack
rose $1.62{ to close at $38.75 a share.
   Under terms of a plan approved by the company's board of
directors, shareholders would receive a cash dividend of $26.60 per
common share and a newly created, 15-year subordinated debenture
with a face value of $6.62.
   In addition, the board instructed management ``to begin
immediately implementing a program that will maximize cash flow,
... reduce costs, and raise cash through the sale'' of the
company's oil and gas operations and certain other assets,
Tregurtha stated.
   Moore McCormack last month rejected the initial bid of
$31-a-share, or $391 million, from Southdown, a cement and energy
company.
   Southdown sweetened its offer to $35 per share, but Moore
McCormack's board last week called the offer inadequate and
recommended the company's shareholders reject it.
   Tregurtha said in a statement that ``the board believes that the
recapitalization is superior to the revised Southdown tender
offer.''
   He said the special dividend provided shareholders with
immediate value and allowed them to retain a long-term equity
investment in Moore McCormack.
   The company said it will proceed with the dividend payout even
if Southdown terminates its offer, unless it is acquired.
   Chemical Bank has agreed to provide up to $420 million in loans
to fund the dividends and related costs.
   With the recapitalization plan, Moore McCormack has projected
its income before interest and taxes will range from $46.2 million
in 1988 to $66.4 million in 1992.
   The company posted a profit of $21.6 million on revenue of
$357.8 million in 1987.
   Moore McCormack makes cement, concrete products and aggregates,
primarily in the southeastern United States, and is engaged in oil
and gas exploration and production.
</TEXT>
