<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0213EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Hawaii-Japanese Bjt   03-24 0859</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hawaii-Japanese, Bjt,0888</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honolulu Mayor Leads Assault Against Japanese Investment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A recent wave of Japanese purchases of
everything from farmland to memberships at prestigious country
clubs has sparked a backlash from residents peeved at a resulting
rise in property taxes and longer lines at the golf course.
   The Japanese have been investing in the Hawaiian islands since
statehood, but have drawn criticism because of recent high-profile
acquisitions made at premium prices.
   Many economists and local officials oppose the latest round of
``Japan bashing,'' calling the foreign-based investment a boon to
the state and a sign of Japanese confidence in the U.S. economy.
   But others, including Honolulu Mayor Frank Fasi, want to limit
Japanese investment here.
   ``They just about own downtown,'' Fasi said Wednesday.
   Fasi has proposed state legislation to prohibit the sale of
residential, agricultural or preservation property to anyone who is
not a U.S. citizen, has no plans to become a citizen or would not
live on the land at least half the year.
   The proposal, based on similar statutes in Nebraska, Wisconsin
and Mississippi, would not affect the sale of commercial, resort
and industrial land. It has little chance of being considered by
the state legislature because it was submitted late in the session.
   Fasi blames the Japanese for skyrocketing property taxes
resulting from rising home prices as well as longer waits for
tee-off times at the Honolulu Country Club, where Japanese
nationals pay $150,000 for memberships. But he denies his proposal
is racist.
   ``All I'm trying to do is stop the speculators from doing here
what they've already done in Japan,'' which is price out the
average buyer, Fasi said.
   Earlier this week it was announced that a Japanese real estate
firm paid a record $280 a square foot _ about $14 million total _
for a parcel of land in Honolulu's Kapiolani business district.
   Japanese investors have paid a total of $99 million for property
along Kapiolani Boulevard since 1986.
   Another Japanese investor sparked protests last month over his
plans to evict an elderly couple from the agricultural land they
had leased for 10 years so he could build a golf course.
   A Japanese real estate firm recently paid $21 million for ``Casa
Blanca Del Mar,'' the highest price ever paid for a private home in
the exclusive southern Oahu beachfront area of Waialae-Kahala. The
average value of homes in the neighborhood has risen between 30
percent and 100 percent under the latest city property assessments,
mostly because foreign investors have been snapping up houses at
high prices.
   Area residents say they have received unsolicited offers in
their mailboxes and been offered millions of dollars in cash for
their homes.
   Wali Osman, associate economist of the Bank of Hawaii, said the
strength of the Japanese yen and the ability to borrow against
high-priced Tokyo properties allows the Japanese to pay more than
U.S. buyers.
   ``What the Japanese are doing is perfectly logical,'' Osman
said. ``They would be foolish not to take advantage of the strength
of their yen.''
   The Japanese have invested heavily in Hawaii since the 1960s.
Osman said the latest surge _ about $3 billion invested since 1986
_ attracted attention only because so many properties were
purchased in a short time.
   ``Maybe they put in a little too much money a little too fast,''
Osman said. ``But $3 billion is a small portion of the total assets
in the state.''
   Osman said Fasi's proposal ignores the rights of the seller and
discriminates against the Japanese.
   ``People have been selling their houses to the Japanese for
twice as much as they could get elsewhere,'' Osman said. ``They've
been getting rich. What about their right to sell to whoever offers
the highest price?''
   Hawaii Lt. Gov. Ben Cayetano dismisses Fasi's plan as political
rhetoric.
   ``The man's running for re-election,'' Cayetano said. ``But he's
a hypocrite. On the one hand he's telling the Japanese to pour in
their money for business development and then he's saying they
can't invest in houses here.''
   Fasi has proposed that Japanese firms be allowed to build a
convention center here and that they help finance a light rail
rapid transit system.
   Cayetano said Fasi was fueling an anti-Japanese attitude that
could cause a backlash against Japanese-Americans _ who make up
about 25 percent of Hawaii's population _ and Japanese visitors,
who have invigorated the state's tourist industry.
   According to the Hawaii Vistors Bureau, about 20 percent of the
5.7 million people who vacationed in the islands last year were
from Japan. They accounted for 33 percent of vistor expenditures,
more than triple the share of their counterparts from the mainland
and Canada.
   ``He (Fasi) is doing what is politically popular at the
moment,'' Cayetano said. ``But here, where the Japanese are so
important, it's especially insulting.''
   Osman said that if Fasi's proposal was rejected, the current
wave of anti-Japanese sentiment should blow over, as it had in the
past.
   ``This isn't the first time politicians have used this tactic,''
Osman said. ``But we aren't about to become a colony of Japan, and
people who think so are just overreacting.''
</TEXT>
