<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0223EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Canada-Hyundai Bjt   03-24 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Hyundai, Bjt,0676</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Industry Assesses Impact of Hyundai Victory in Canadian Dumping
Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Dollar figures are U.S. unless otherwise noted.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. and General Motors Corp. warned of
future job losses and free-trade problems after a Canadian tribunal
dismissed their claims of damages from the sale of inexpensive
Hyundai Motor Co. cars from South Korea.
   The Canadian Import Tribunal ruled Wednesday that it found no
evidence of material injury to Ford or GM subsidiaries because of
the cut-price compact cars that Hyundai has sold in Canada since
1984.
   The three-member government panel ordered a halt to anti-dumping
proceedings against Hyundai and a refund of some $8 million in
bonds the company had posted.
   Wednesday's ruling has implications for all North American car
makers: the Canadian auto industry is linked with U.S. operations
under a 1965 trade agreement treating the continent as a single
market.
   Hyundai was forced to post the bonds when Revenue Canada, the
government tax collector, upheld the dumping complaint last
November and imposed preliminary import duties averaging 26 percent.
   Dumping is the practice of exporting goods at a price below what
they cost in the domestic market.
   Ford and GM accused Hyundai of introducing its Pony, Stellar and
Excel models in Canada at below-cost prices to get a foothold in
North America. They complained they lost profits when they had to
slash prices and offer rebates to remain competitive.
   At hearings that ended March 10, Hyundai acknowledged its aim
was to gain a path to the lucrative U.S. market. But the company
denied harming Ford, GM or the Canadian auto industry.
   Hyundai said the U.S. car giants did not make subcompacts in
Canada and contended Ford was making handsome profits here.
Furthermore, both companies have business links to other South
Korean carmakers, Hyundai noted.
   The Canadian government's Bureau of Competition Policy
intervened on behalf of Hyundai to say the company had fostered
competition in the small-car market and kept prices down.
   Within a year of introducing its $4,500 Pony hatchback, Hyundai
cornered 7 percent of the Canadian car market. It then expanded to
the United States where it sold 264,000 Excels last year.
   But recent Canadian sales were depressed because of the dumping
case. If upheld, the duties would have added $800 to the price of a
new Hyundai.
   The Canadian Importers Association called the decision a
``triumph'' for consumers, while Hyundai issued a statement from
Seoul welcoming the decision.
   Whatever the outcome of the case, the South Korean conglomerate
had pledged to proceed with plans for a $259 million manufacturing
plant in Bromont, Quebec, and a parts factory in Newmarket, Ontario.
   Ford and GM have 10 days to appeal to the Federal Court of
Canada. They said they would decide after receiving the tribunal's
detailed explanations next month.
   Both companies warned that unfair foreign competition could lead
to job losses in the Canadian industry, which employs 140,000
workers directly and another 400,000 indirectly, mostly in southern
Ontario and Quebec Province.
   ``It has been and remains our contention that continued
unrestrained dumping by Hyundai will result in lost jobs and
investment in the Canadian auto industry,'' stated George Peapples,
president of GM Canada.
   Ford spokesman Jim Hartford complained of flaws in Canadian
trade law and said the case set a bad precedent for the Canada-U.S.
free trade agreement due for ratification by the Canadian
Parliament and by Congress later this year.
   Hartford said the law forced the tribunal to look at Ford
production and sales only in Canada, where small-car output has
been phased out, instead of examining Ford's integrated operations
throughout the continent.
   ``We're alarmed by the implications today's decision has for
other industries which may become rationalized under the free-trade
agreement,'' Hartford said.
   He said the shortcoming must be fixed in the first years of the
free-trade treaty or more industries will come in for ``predatory
dumping.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
