<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0230EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Koppers     03-24 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koppers,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beazer Makes Higher Koppers Proposal; Koppers Workers Demonstrate</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PG2 of March 23</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The investment group pursuing Koppers Co. has
proposed a negotiated buyout at $60 a share, topping its current
hostile offer of $56 a share, while hundreds of Koppers employees
demonstrated against the ongoing takeover attempt.
   The new proposal has an indicated value of about $1.68 billion,
compared with $1.57 billion for the alternative hostile bid. It was
made in a letter sent late Wednesday to Koppers Chairman Charles R.
Pullin from British investor Brian C. Beazer.
   Beazer has teamed with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., the New York
investment banker, in its attempt to acquire the Pittsburgh
building materials, paving services and chemical company. The
hostile tender offer remains in effect, said Beazer spokeswoman
Lissa Perlman.
   Koppers spokesman Robert J. O'Gara said the company had no
immediate comment on the latest proposal.
   Kopper's board of directors has rejected Beazer's $56 a share
offer as inadequate, and reiterated it was exploring a possible
defensive recapitalization that would include a one-time payment to
shareholders.
   ``We believe we are able to offer greater value to your
stockholders than any plan you are presently considering,'' Beazer
stated in his letter to Pullin. ``If you have a recapitalization
plan that provides your stockholders and employees with more
benefits than we are prepared to provide, we, and your other
stockholders, are anxious to see it.''
   Separately, about 250 of the company's employees cut up an
estimated 175 charge cards from American Express Co., which owns 60
percent of Shearson, during a downtown protest.
   ``We're damn mad,'' said Koppers Vice President J. Roger
Beidler. ``We want American Express to know that this gathering is
just the tip of the iceberg.''
   Management also has canceled its American Express account,
through which the company had been buying about $1.5 million per
year in goods and services, said O'Gara.
   Koppers has accused Shearson Lehman of offering to defend the
company from hostile takeovers at the same time that it was
plotting its attack with Beazer.
   ``That's quite a deal, and we're saying no,'' Beidler said.
``We're going to send our cards back to American Express in
pieces.''
   American Express and Shearson also have come under fire from
state officials for their role in the hostile bid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880324-0293 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0230EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Lotus     03-24 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lotus,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delay In New Software Depresses Lotus Stock</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lotus Development Corp.'s stock could
remain depressed for some time following the company's announcement
of a six-month delay in the release of a new version of its
high-selling 1-2-3 software, industry watchers say.
   Wall Street analysts this week scaled back their earnings
estimates for the company after it delayed the new Release 3
software. In addition, Lotus executives sold off large blocks of
stock and a top executive resigned.
   ``I think the stock is going to underperform until we get closer
to the release date on shipment of the 1-2-3 Release 3,'' David J.
Readerman, an analyst with Smith Barney & Co., said Wednesday.
   Lotus fell $3.50 a share to $25.25 a share in over-the-counter
trading Wednesday, a 12 percent drop in market value.
   Last month, Lotus President Jim P. Manzi sold 250,000 shares of
company stock, and several vice presidents sold between 12,800
shares and 95,800 shares. Charles J. Digate, senior vice president
in charge of software development, left the company last week.
   Lotus said some of the stock sales occurred because executives
exercised stock options last August and had to wait six months
before selling to meet tax payments.
   But Readerman said: ``The timing of the sales just raises a
credibility issue. That is as much a reason why the stock is down.
If it was just the product slip date, I don't think you'd see the
stock where it is.''
   Analysts said Lotus is trailing its competitors in developing
new spreadsheet programs and said they expected some of the 3.5
million Lotus 1-2-3 users to defect to other brands.
   ``For some reason Lotus just hasn't kept pace with the industry
in bringing out new products,'' said Rick Sherlund of Goldman,
Sachs & Co. ``They've been long on promise in announcing new
products but short on delivery.''
   Analysts cut Lotus' 1988 earnings per share estimates to between
$1.55 and $1.65 from about $1.95. They also trimmed revenue
forecasts for the year to about $400 million from $465 million.
   Lotus last year reported net income of $72 million, or $1.58 per
share, on revenue of $395.6 million.
   The upgraded 1-2-3 software originally was expected in June. The
company said the new program, which promises to print better
graphs, work faster and combine many spreadsheets, will be
available in the fourth quarter.
   Analysts said the delay would give Borland International Corp.
of Scotts Valley, Calif., and Microsoft Corp. of Redmond, Wash., a
chance to gain market share with new software products designed to
compete with 1-2-3.
   Last November, Borland released its Quattro spreadsheet, which
has been praised as better than 1-2-3, and Microsoft, the leading
personal computer software maker, released its Windows Excel
software.
   Martin Fahey, Lotus' investor relations director, said the
company needs more time to make the new 1-2-3 programs small enough
to work with personal computers.
   ``We obviously are concerned about the delay,'' Fahey said.
``Any time a product slips it's not good. (But) we think it's going
to be worth waiting for.''
   The new 1-2-3 will cost $495, same as the old one. People who
have an authorized copy of the current 1-2-3 can upgrade for $150.
Analysts project $100 million to $150 million in sales in the first
12 to 18 months of its release.
   Lotus on Wednesday named W. Frank King III, a former vice
president of development for International Business Machines
Corp.'s personal computer division, to replace Digate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
