<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0940EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-WarholLabel     03-24 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Warhol Label,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warhol-Art Label Goes On Limited Edition Wine</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wine in the $3,200 bottle was an
acclaimed 1984 merlot, but there was something even rarer about the
Cuvaison magnum that Texan Steven Schwartz bought at a recent
Dallas charity auction.
   The grape art label on the Napa Valley wine was believed to be
the first work designed for wine by the pop art pioneer Andy
Warhol, who died last year in New York at age 58.
   Warhol donated the art to the Cuvaison winery in the late 1970s.
It is a striking, bias-cut piece based on a stylized vision of what
Warhol thought nature should have made grapes look like: the six
grapes are in hues of red and deep green.
   The overall label, which was placed on just 84 bottles, has
Warhol's name cut in above the art. It was designed and completed
last year by California graphic artist Channing Rudd under
commission by Cuvaison President Manfred Esser.
   Said Rudd, ``The label was at first considered to be very
strange,'' but, like the wine, the work improved with age and came
into increasing favor. Esser finally ordered the art made into a
finished label, and Rudd readied it for reproduction in a week.
   ``Warhol did many commercial things, but basically Warhol was a
fine artist,'' said Rudd. ``He was a painter who experimented with
silk-screening and avant-garde techniques. I tried to do the same
thing, only convert it into something marketable.''
   Still under wraps are Warhol's creations for two other labels,
one for white wine, the other for rose. No plans for them have been
announced.
   As a memorial to Warhol's talent, Switzerland's industrialist
Schmidheiny family, which owns Cuvaison, ordered the current
labeling limited to 84 bottles.
   Alexander and Christina Schmidheiny were friends of Warhol's,
and thought to use his work to evoke a fine-arts theme for special
wines.
   ``We intended this label to be one of a series of artist's
labels for Cuvaison's special bottlings,'' Mrs. Schmidheiny said.
``When the 1984 Cuvaison merlot was released, we decided to use his
label only on 84 magnum bottles on the occasion of the 15th
anniversary of the winery.''
   ``As it turned out, the wine itself was very well
received...hopefully a small memorial to Mr. Warhol's great
talent.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
