<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     03-24 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Steadies at Lower Levels, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar steadied at lower levels early in
Europe today after a sell-off during Asian trading.
   Gold prices rose.
   Traders said the dollar was driven downward in Asia by trading
benefitting the yen and British pound.
   U.S. economic indicators due later today, including personal
income for February, were not likely to move the market since an
upward revision of the U.S. gross national product for the fourth
quarter was disregarded Wednesday, dealers said.
   The growth rate was revised to an annual rate of 4.8 percent, up
from the previously reported 4.5 percent.
   ``There is still room for the yen and the pound to strengthen,''
said a trader in Frankfurt. That means the dollar could fall a
little lower during the course of the day, he said.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar closed at 126.30 yen, down 0.85 yen
   Later, in London, it was quoted at 126.00 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.6858 West German marks, down from
1.6915; 1.3940 Swiss francs, down from 1.3990; 5.7305 French
francs, down from 5.7450; 1.8943 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9005;
1,248.95 Italian lire, down from 1,253.25; 1.2440 Canadian dollars,
up from 1.2434.
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.8425, compared
with $1.8358 Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $452.40 a troy ounce,
compared with late Wednesday's $453.00. At mid-morning today, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$453.90.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $453.25, up from $450.40 late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $3.34 to close at $455.40 an
ounce.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.67 a troy
ounce, up from Wednesday's $6.63.
</TEXT>
