<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Boesky 1stLd-Writethru   03-24 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boesky, 1st Ld-Writethru,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boesky's Home: 700-Man Prison with Slaughterhouse, Boccie</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to update with prison confirming Boesky's
arrival, picks up 7th graf pvs, ``Our people ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted stock speculator Ivan F. Boesky, who
made millions trading on inside information, would earn a maximum
of 44 cents an hour at tasks ranging from landscaping to milking
cows as an inmate in the prison recommended by his sentencing judge.
   Boesky, 51, arrived Wednesday afternoon at the Lompoc, Calif.,
prison camp, to begin serving his three-year term, the prison said.
   U.S. District Judge Morris Lasker, who sentenced Boesky on Dec.
18, had given him until today to surrender.
   The Lompoc facility, a 700-inmate minimum security facility
about 150 miles northwest of Los Angeles near the Pacific coast, is
located on about 44,000 acres of heavily forested countryside and
contains a dairy, slaughterhouse and furniture factory. Inmates
sleep in a former army barracks.
   Lompoc warden Richard Rison said in a telephone interview last
week that if Boesky would have no special privileges or cushy
prison jobs.
   ``Our people are assigned based on where our needs are,'' said
Rison. ``He could be in the slaughterhouse, he could be in the
landscape crew, he could be working in the dairy operation. He will
be required to work a fulltime assignment.''
   Rison said the pay scale ranged from 11 cents to 44 cents an
hour for a 40-hour week. As in other federal prison facilities, the
money is credited to an account at the prison commissary, where
inmates can buy toiletries, cigarettes and candy.
   During off hours, Rison said, inmates can play tennis on a
single concrete court, lift weights, roll boccie ball, shoot
billiards or watch cable television at a half-dozen sets placed
around the facility. Inmates have access to eight telephones but
Rison said there's a 15-minute limit on calls.
   Lompoc has been home to some other famous convicts, including
former Nixon administration aide H.R. Haldeman and fireworks
magnate W. Patrick Moriarty, who was convicted in a major
government-bribery and influence-peddling scandal. Convicted spy
Christopher Boyce was incarcerated in Lompoc's maximum-security
section but escaped and led authorities on a chase for several
months before he was seized in the Northwest.
   Boesky, formerly one of Wall Street's best known speculators,
stunned the financial world in November 1986 when he paid the
Securities and Exchange Commission a record $100 million fine to
settle civil charges of insider trading, the misuse of confidential
information to profit in securities deals.
   Since then he has cooperated extensively with federal
investigators. In exchange, he was allowed to plead guilty to a
single criminal count of conspiracy to lie to the SEC.
   Boesky's revelations reportedly have led to death threats
against him, and there was speculation he had sought federal
custody early because he feared for his life.
   Last month, John Mulheren, a former Boesky friend and fellow
speculator, was arrested on charges he threatened to kill Boesky
and Boesky's former head trader, Michael Davidoff, who also has
pleaded guilty to securities fraud and is cooperating with
investigators.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880324-0299 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0848EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks     03-24 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Stocks Sharply Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were sharply lower at midday Thursday
as the market's budget-related rally finally ran out of steam.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange index of 100 stocks was off
27.8 points, or 1.5 percent, at 1,804.4.
   Volume was 297.3 million shares at midday, up from 211.2 million
shares at the same time a day earlier.
   Dealers said the market was marked down heavily soon after
trading started.
   The 100-stock index had moved well above the 1,800-point level
prior to Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson's March 15 budget
statement. Investors predicted the budget would include major tax
cutting measures and bullish forecasts on the British economy.
   The announcement of the budget met those expectations, but since
then, the market has been unable to push much higher.
   ``Having seen not much follow-through since the budget in terms
of buying, the question was whether there would be selling,'' said
Chris Chaitow, an analyst at Morgan Grenfell Securities. ``Today
has shown that there is selling.''
   Dealers said the market's nervousness was exacerbated by rumors
of a major selling program by County Natwest Securities. But
dealers at the brokerage firm denied there had been such a program
Thursday.
</TEXT>
