<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0944EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-FirstCity     03-24 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-First City,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First City Chairman: Bondholders Should Not Hold Out For Better
Terms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The future chairman of First City Bancorporation
of Texas Inc. says the banking concern's restructuring plans, and
the economic well-being of Texas, are being jeopardized by a group
of dissident debtholders.
   ``It's not in their best interest to hang onto the bonds if
they're going to crater the deal in the process,'' A. Robert Abboud
said Wednesday before the French-American Chamber of Commerce.
   Abboud, a Chicago investor who would become of First City under
a federal bailout plan, is seeking to complete a $1.5 billion
restructuring of the Houston company.
   The restructuring deal requires 90 percent participation by the
close of business next Tuesday. But as of late Tuesday only about
51 percent of the holders of First City notes totaling $225.9
million had tendered their securities.
   Senior debt holders have been offered 45 cents on the dollar for
their debt, while subordinated debt holders have been offered 35
cents.
   ``On a liquidation basis, their investment is worth zero,''
Abboud said, referring to the $100 million in subordinated debt.
``Once the preconditions are established, we have to stick to
them.''
   Abboud is trying to restructure First City using $970 million in
assistance from the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation, and
another $500 in privately raised capital.
   Abboud said he was optimistic a deal could be closed. First City
shareholders already have voted to support the Abboud plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
