<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1024EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-US     03-24 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-US,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Japan Positions Toughen on Beef, Citrus Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan seeks an agreement with the United States by
the end of March on opening the Japanese market wider to American
beef and citrus fruit, but there still are conflicting opinions in
Japan on the issue, a government official said Thursday.
   The current agreement on Japan's quotas on those items expires
March 31.
   Separately, a senior aide to Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita
left for Washington Thursday for talks aimed at a political
solution to a dispute over U.S. access to Japan's construction
market.
   On the agricultural issue, U.S. Trade Representative Clayton
Yeutter said this week the United States wants all quotas dropped
by April 1, or it will take the issue to the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade, an international forum for settling trade
disputes.
   Yoshifumi Matsuda, spokesman for the Foreign Ministry, said
Thursday, ``Our interest is to have a coordinated result, an
agreement between the two governments by the end of the month.''
   Asked how far Japan was willing to go to compromise short of
total liberalization, he said there were conflicting opinions and
the government was not ready to make a statement.
   The United States refuses to negotiate unless Japan sets a clear
timetable for liberalization, something Japan has been unwilling to
do. Members of Japan's ruling Liberal-Democratic Party have
expressed strong opposition to liberalization.
   ``GATT is a good place to fight this out,'' said Tsutomu Hata,
head of the LDP's Agriculture Committee, after arguing in a meeting
Wednesday that producing beef and oranges is essential to domestic
farmers, and these must be protected.
   ``A country should be able to produce basic food items on its
own,'' said Mitsuru Yoshida of the Livestock Industry Promotion
Corp. ``The United States is a very big country and so can produce
a lot. But Japan is very small and thus needs to protect itself.''
   While farmers and many consumers fear liberalization will
destroy the domestic beef and citrus industry, leading to
unemployment and a dangerous dependence on foreign sources of food,
Yeutter commented: ``If it did mean some structural adjustment,
that's the price we pay for a free and open trading system. We've
had some adjustment, too.''
   Last month, a senior Economic Planning Agency official predicted
that imports of beef would be liberalized within two years, with a
lifting of restrictions on citrus fruit even sooner.
   Tentative moves to appease foreign critics include proposals
announced Thursday by an advisory council to the Ministry of
Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries for a revision of the upper and
lower ceilings on domestic beef and pork price supports, said a
ministry official who requested anonymity.
   Deputy Chief Cabinet Secretary Ichiro Ozawa, who is traveling to
the United States to discuss agricultural issues, is scheduled to
meet with U.S. Commerce Secretary William Verity and other U.S.
officials.
   An aide to Ozawa declined to specify what new offers, if any,
Ozawa would make to U.S. officials in an attempt to settle the
dispute.
   Following the failure of working-level negotiations earlier this
month, U.S. officials gave Japan two weeks to come up with a
satisfactory proposal to end the dispute. Otherwise, they said the
United States may invoke a law calling for compensation from Japan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
