<HEAD>Other Airlines Seen Reluctant to Follow Northwest on Smoking Ban</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT 3 grafs after 15th graf bgng `It's a...' to include
passenger and flight attendants' reaction; pick up 16th pvs, `The
new ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major U.S. airlines have no immediate plans to
match Northwest Airlines' bold new move to ban smoking on most of
its flights, and some industry analysts say the carriers are
unlikely to do so.
   Northwest, the nation's fifth-largest airline, announced
Wednesday it will prohibit smoking on all its domestic flights
except those to and from Hawaii and on some foreign routes.
   The ban makes Minneapolis-based Northwest the first major U.S.
airline to mandate a smoke-free environment in the air. It goes
beyond federal regulations that will outlaw smoking on all domestic
flights of two hours or less beginning April 23.
   Northwest said its prohibition was a response to passenger and
employee requests. A.B. ``Sky'' Magary, Northwest's executive vice
president for marketing, told a news conference in New York that
while the policy is not without risk, ``we believe more nonsmokers
will switch to Northwest than smokers will leave.''
   Wall Street seemed unimpressed by Northwest's smoke-free
innovation. The airline's stock closed on the New York Stock
Exchange at $45.75 a share, down 12{ cents from Tuesday.
   Some analysts believe Northwest risks chasing away potential
passengers, and other big airlines appear reluctant to follow the
carrier's lead.
   ``We have no plans to follow that move,'' said Mary O'Neill, a
spokeswoman for No. 2 American Airlines. Recent surveys conducted
by American indicated a significant segment of people who want to
smoke on planes, despite a growing demand for smoke-free areas, she
said.
   American and several other big airlines contacted Wednesday
stressed that they planned to establish no-smoking policies in line
with the new federal law.
   Under those rules, passengers who insist on lighting up will
face civil fines of as much as $1,000, and fliers who tamper with
smoke alarms in airplane lavatories face up to $2,000 in penalties.
   ``We are ready to implement our no-smoking policy ... in line
with the federal law,'' said United Airlines spokesman Dan Sheehy.
United, the nation's largest airline, has had a smoking ban in
place since Jan. 1 on all its flights within California, in
accordance with a state law.
   Fourth-ranked Delta Air Lines has garnered a lot of support for
its own California smoking ban, spokesman Jim Lundy said.
   He said Delta's reaction to Northwest's move was ``really tough
to call,'' but did not rule out further action by his airline.
   ``We will of course take a look at what Northwest is doing and
see if we want to make an adjustment to our program,'' Lundy said.
   Anthony Hatch, an airline analyst for Argus Research Corp., said
he did not expect the other carriers to match Northwest's policy.
   ``It's a gutsy move and most airlines don't make gutsy moves,''
Hatch said. ``It could alienate some people.''
   Three smokers, who were waiting to depart on Northwest flights
Wednesday from Minneapolis-St. Paul International Airport, said
they don't object to the carrier's new smoking ban.
   ``It's probably a good idea,'' Janice Davis, a Boston real
estate broker, told the St. Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch. ``I can
get by without smoking.''
   Even some Northwest flight attendants, who are smokers, told the
newspaper the new policy might help them quit smoking.
   The new policy, called ``Northwest Clears the Air,'' will take
effect April 23, the same day as the new federal regulations. It
will apply to flights within the contiguous 48 states and flights
to and from Alaska, Mexico, Canada, Jamaica and the Cayman Islands.
   The longest flights covered by the smoking ban are four or five
hours, according to the airline. About 30 percent of Northwest's
domestic flights and about 20 percent of all domestic flights last
more than the two-hour duration covered by the new federal smoking
regulations.
   Northwest flights to and from Hawaii and overseas will continue
offering smoking sections because those flights ``carry a greater
proportion of foreign passengers who feel differently about the
issue,'' the airline stated.
   ``We still have (foreign) competitors that are handing out
cigars to passengers on board,'' Magary said.
   But even that could be changing. Air U.K. Ltd., a small British
airline that flies to destinations in Britain and Western Europe,
is banning smoking on all its flights effective next Sunday.
   And a spokesman in London for British Airways PLC, one of the
world's largest airlines, said the carrier was looking ``quite
seriously'' at the possibility of banning smoking on both short and
long flights.
   The trend also has appeared in Southwest Asia.
Government-controlled Singapore Airlines unveiled plans Wednesday
to introduce the first no-smoking commercial flights in the region
next month.
   Smoking will be barred on four of the 14 daily shuttle flights
between Singapore and Kuala Lumpur, the capital of neighboring
Malaysia, starting April 4. The trip takes about 45 minutes.
</TEXT>
