<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Ford     03-24 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Ford,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Leaders Head to Detroit To Try to Change Ford's Mind</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British labor union delegation left Thursday for
Detroit in hopes of persuading Ford Motor Co. to change its mind
and locate an electronic components plant in Scotland.
   ``We have a monumental task ahead of us,'' Gavin Laird, head of
the Amalgamated Engineering Union, said before the five-member
delegation left London's Heathrow Airport.
   The delegation left a day after the Trades Union Congress,
Britain's national labor federation, agreed to Ford demands for a
single-union deal at the proposed plant in Dundee, Scotland.
   The group included TUC general secretary Norman Willis.
   After five months of squabbling among British unions about the
deal, Ford announced this week it would not locate the $73 million
plant in Britain.
   Prodded by this, the Trades Union Congress' General Council on
Wednesday voted 23-15 for the single-union deal. The Transport and
General Workers' Union, Britain's largest union, remained opposed.
   The TGWU represents two-thirds of Ford's more than 32,000
British workers and was insisting on being allowed into the Dundee
plant.
   The plant was expected to employ 450 workers.
</TEXT>
