<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened narrowly
mixed today in quiet trading on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat futures were slightly lower. The market is caught in a
tug-of-war between traders expecting seasonal price weakness to
develop and those looking for new export business to push prices
higher, said Walter Spilka, an analyst in New York with Smith
Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   The corn and soybean markets were quiet and likely will stay
that way through next Thursday, when the Agriculture Department
releases its first estimates of this year's planted acreage, Spilka
said.
   Recent volatility in the precious metals and currency futures
markets has had surprisingly little impact on grain futures prices,
probably because grain traders are beginning to look more at
supply-and-demand fundamentals and paying less attention to the
prices of other commodities, he said.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent to 1{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.06{ a bushel; corn was unchanged
to } cent higher with May at $2.06{ a bushel; oats were \ cent
higher across the board with May at $1.68 a bushel; soybeans were }
cent to 1} cents higher with May at $6.40{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent lower to .20 cent higher with April at
74.50 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .30 cent lower
with March at 82.37 cents a pound; hogs were .20 cent lower to .50
cent higher with April at 45.95 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .05 cent lower to .30 cent higher with March at 55.40 cents a
pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
