<HEAD>Brewer Posts 8.5 Percent Profit Gain</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS new grafs 6-7 to UPDATE with arrest of Parnes; picks up
6th graf pvs bg'ng, Guinness has ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guinness PLC, the British brewing company, said
Thursday its earnings more than quadrupled in 1987 due to
extraordinary items.
   Guinness said it earned 474 million pounds, or $867 million, up
from 113 million pounds in 1986.
   The company attributed the increase to one-time gains of 217
million pounds, including 29 million pounds of unauthorized
payments relating to the April 1986 takeover of Distillers Co.
   Sales fell 9 percent to 2.82 billion pounds from 3.1 billion
pounds.
   Police have charged six people, including former Guinness
Chairman Ernest Saunders, for alleged offenses related to the
Distillers takeover.
   On Thursday, police arrested British stockbroker Anthony Parnes
in connection with the Guinness scandal when he voluntarily
returned to London after being held in a Los Angeles jail for six
months for extradition proceedings.
   Parnes, 42, who was arrested at Heathrow airport, faces 19
charges including aiding and abetting the theft of money from the
brewing company. He is accused of setting up and operating an
illegal share support operation during the Guinness takeover bid
for Distillers in 1986.
   Guinness has admitted it paid outsiders millions of pounds to
buy Guinness stock to make the brewer's cash and stock offer for
Distillers, a gin and whisky maker, more attractive than a rival
bid.
   The company did not break down its quarterly or six-month
results. Corporations are not required to do so under British law.
</TEXT>
