<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1156EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Chrysler-Acustar     03-24 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Chrysler-Acustar,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Will Treat Parts Unit As Separate Business</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The for sale sign on Chrysler Motors Corp.'s
Acustar subsidiary has been taken down, but Chrysler is pushing the
parts-making company farther from the corporate nest.
   ``The objective is to have it be much more independent,
especially in the administration, so you don't have a lot of people
in Acustar filing reports to Chrysler about what they will be
doing,'' said Baron Bates, vice president of public relations.
   The idea came up when Chrysler was reviewing whether to sell the
$3 billion subsidiary, Bates said. The company backed away from
selling Acustar after the United Auto Workers union revolted and
threatened strikes at Acustar plants where local contracts were
unresolved.
   The 10-month-old subsidiary has continued as a part of the
company's structure and functioned almost as a Chrysler Motors
department.
   ``One of the things we're contemplating in-house is ... why
don't we pretend we sold Acustar and really treat them as a
completely self-contained business responsible for their own
bottom-line results and let them do whatever they have to do to get
there?'' Acustar Chairman Robert Lutz said.
   Acustar financial results would be reported with Chrysler's, and
Chrysler still would handle the company's labor relations, but
Acustar no longer would report to Chrysler administratively, Bates
said.
   One reason Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee Iacocca said Chrysler
considered selling Acustar was the expense of research and
development necessary for competitive parts technology.
   Lutz said part of Acustar's strategy would involve buying new
technology and forming partnerships with parts companies rather
than developing new technology on its own.
   The idea has been endorsed by Chrysler's executive committee and
Lutz has been urged to complete the change quickly, he said. He
declined to be more specific about a timetable.
   Of the Big Three automakers, Chrysler purchases more of its
parts from outside suppliers than industry leader General Motors
Corp. or Ford Motor Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
