<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1309EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-US-Investment     03-24 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Investment,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Treasury Secretary Baker Opposes Disclosure of Foreign Investors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III told
Congress on Thursday that disclosing names of foreign investors
would damage the United States.
   Proposals for some disclosure are in trade bills now before
Congress.
   ``If enacted, the ... provision would have a chilling effect on
foreign investment in the United States _ thereby costing jobs,
raising interest rates, lowering productivity, closing off
opportunities for technological and managerial improvements, and
undermining our efforts to liberalize investments abroad,'' Baker
said.
   His opposition was in a written statement sent to the Senate
Commerce Committee. Sponsors of the proposal, Sen. Tom Harkin and
Rep. John Bryant, came to a committee hearing and said they were
sorry Baker did not appear in person.
   ``Not one of the G-7 countries (United States, Japan, West
Germany, Britain, France, Canada, Italy) has a publicly available
national register of foreign investments of the type prescribed by
Bryant,'' Baker wrote.
   ``Not one discloses to the public ongoing information about the
status of specific private investors and their investments; not one
requires systematic reporting by foreign investors or domestic
firms for this purpose.''
   Baker's views were challenged by Harkin, though he did not refer
to Baker. Harkin said most countries require more information than
his bill is seeking, and in addition require their governments to
clear investments in advance. His proposal does not seek that kind
of clearance.
   ``Even Switzerland keeps a public registry of Swiss companies
with foreign ownership,'' he said.
   ``Japan's preclearance process seems one of the most stringent,
in part because it is the most explicit ... Japan flatly prohibits
foreign ownership of more than 25 percent in any of its high-tech
companies.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
