<1ST_LINE>u f PM-CalMat-Brierly 2ndLd-Writethru f0117 03-24 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CalMat-Brierly, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0117,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brierly Bids $988 Million for 81 Pct of CalMat He Doesn't Own</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS in lead that Brierly from New Zealand sted
Australia; uppicks 2nd graf: Brierly made...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Zealand investor Ronald Brierly is
offering $988 million to take over CalMat Co., a major construction
materials and real estate concern with operations in Southern
California and Arizona.
   Brierly made his unsolicited $40-per-share offer for the 81
percent of CalMat he does not already own through a subsidiary of
Australia-based Industrial Equity (Pacific) Inc., CalMat said
Wednesday.
   CalMat has 30.5 million shares outstanding.
   Los Angeles-based CalMat was created in 1984 by the merger of
two construction industry giants _ California Portland Cement Co.
and Conrock Co. The merged companies' core businesses are in
cement, ready-mixed concrete, aggregate, hot-mixed asphalt and real
estate holdings.
   Brierly's offer sent CalMat's stock soaring by $13.50 per share
to $45.37{ in heavy trading Wednesday on the New York Stock
Exchange. The stock was up $1.87| on Tuesday amid speculation the
company might become a takeover target.
   In a brief statement, CalMat chief executive A.F. Gerstell said
that in the past three years the company ``has taken significant
steps...to enhance shareholder value through the disposition of
assets and the reallocation of proceeds to the company's
higher-margin core businesses.''
   In addition, Gerstell said, the company and its investment
adviser, J.P. Morgan & Co., have for some time been looking at
``additional, more aggressive steps which the company can take to
continue this ongoing process.''
   CalMat intends to convene a special board meeting to compare
Brierly's offer with its own restructuring options, Gerstell said.
   In 1987, the company earned $78.1 million on revenue of $658.9
million. The profit included a $24 million gain on the sale of
assets. In 1986, CalMat earned $44.1 million on revenue of $619
million.
   Gerstell has been CalMat's chief executive, president and chief
operating officer since the company was created. For the previous
three years, he was presdient of California Portland Cement.
   CalMat's chairman, William Jenkins, was president of Conrock
before the merger.
   Brierly, whose holdings range from real estate to oil and gas to
financial services, characterizes himself as a long-term investor
but not necessarily a passive one.
   In 1986, he made an unsuccessful bid to acquire control of
Beverly Hills-based Wrather Corp., best known as the operator of
the Disneyland Hotel in Anaheim and the Spruce Goose and Queen Mary
tourist attractions in Long Beach.
   Subsequently, a joint venture of Brierly and Burbank-based Walt
Disney Co. bought Wrather for $152 million. Disney has become
manager of the Disneyland Hotel, which sits on its property, but no
agreement has been reached on how the assets will be split.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
