<DOCNO> AP880324-0317 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1426EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TexasS&L     03-24 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texas S&L,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sexual Payoffs Charged by Justice Department</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department today charged a former
Texas savings and loan executive with providing sexual payoffs to
the institution's officers and board members in a conspiracy to
violate the federal bank and bribery statute.
   John Hill, former vice president of Vernon Savings and Loan
Association, arranged for paid female companionship for officers
and directors at a three-day June 1985 board meeting in Solana
Beach, Calif., said a one-count felony information.
   Hill, who the Justice Department said has agreed to plead
guilty, intended that sexual favors would be available to the
executives in connection with their service to the institution,
said court papers filed in U.S. District Court in Dallas.
   According to a Justice Department statement, Hill and others
created false board minutes on the renewal and extension of some
commercial real estate loans. The bogus minutes indicated the
renewals and extensions had been approved by the board when no such
approval had occurred.
   Hill falsified documentation justifying $100,000 in payments to
a consultant in connection with a loan from an S&L, according to
papers filed in federal court in Dallas.
   In addition, according to the felony information, Hill conspired
with a Vernon official to make $5,400 in illegal state and federal
campaign contributions to specific candidates, based on the
understanding that he would be reimbursed through false expense
vouchers submitted to Vernon.
   The contributions allegedly included $1,000 to former Texas
congressman Thomas Loeffler in February 1986, $2,000 to the
Loeffler for Government campaign in April 1986, $400 to the
campaign of U.S. Rep. Martin Frost, D-Texas, in September 1985, and
$2,000 to Citizens for Jack Kemp in June 1986.
   There were no allegations that any of the campaign organizations
or candidates knew the contributions were actually coming from the
S&L.
   Disguising payments to the consultant and concealing
reimbursements for the illegal campaign contributions impeded the
Internal Revenue Service in determining the amount of income taxes
due by the consultant, by Hill, by Vernon and by the association's
holding company, Dondi Financial Corp.
   Hill, who has agreed to cooperate in an ongoing probe of Vernon,
could be sentenced to five years in prison and a $250,000 fine on
the conspiracy charge.

</TEXT>
