<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market lapsed into a sharp decline
today as the dollar slumped in foreign exchange and U.S. interest
rates headed higher.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 41.28 points to
2,026.36 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 6 to 1 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 230 up, 1,367 down
and 333 unchanged.
   With the dollar losing ground, prices of long-term government
bonds dropped about $5 for each $1,000 in face value today, putting
their yields in the 8.75 to 8.8 percent range.
   At their best recent levels, yields on Treasury bonds were as
low as 8.3 percent.
   Analysts said pressure on the dollar prompted concern in markets
around the world. Prices fell in both the London and Tokyo stock
markets.
   Against that background, brokers said, Wall Street investors
moved quickly to cash on the U.S. market's gains since late last
year.
   Among actively traded blue chip and technology issues, General
Electric dropped 1[ to 41{; International Business Machines 1~ to
109}; Digital Equipment 3{ to 107~; and American Telephone &
Telegraph { to 27}.
   In the securities industry group, Merrill Lynch fell 1 to 23\;
Salomon 1 to 21]; First Boston ~ to 25\; Morgan Stanley | to 59],
and Charles Schwab ] to 8\.
   International Clinical Laboratories jumped 8 to 33} in
over-the-counter trading. Smithkline Beckman made a $32-a-share bid
for the company, which had agreed to an acquisition by Corning
Glass Works for $26 a share.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
2.77 to 149.05. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down 3.13 at 297.28.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 133.31 million shares with two
hours to go.
