<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Rolls-Royce     03-24 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Rolls-Royce,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airplane Engine Maker Posts 12 Percent Profit Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rolls-Royce PLC, the airplane engine maker
privatized by the government last year, on Thursday reported a 12
percent increase in its net profit for 1987.
   Strong gains in the group's civil aviation division more than
offset a sharp rise in research and development costs, the company
said.
   Rolls-Royce, which is a separate company from the luxury car
maker, reported 1987 net profit of 134 million pounds, or $247
million, up from 120 million pounds, or $221 million a year earlier.
   Per share earnings came to 20.1 pence, or 37 cents, compared
with 18.9 pence, or 35 cents, a year earlier.
   Sales increased 14 percent to 2.06 billion pounds, or $3.8
billion, from 1.8 billion pounds, or $3.3 billion in 1986.
   Rolls-Royce Chairman Sir Francis Tombs said: ``Our order book is
strong and our wide stable of competitive engines gives us an
excellent opportunity to consolidate our existing customer base and
secure some of the attractive new sales opportunities which are
appearing around the world.''
   The company did not break out quarterly or six-month results. It
isn't required to under British law.
</TEXT>
