<HEAD>Soybeans Close Sharply Higher; Grains Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed sharply higher
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade due to a late surge of
speculative buying. Grain futures closed mixed.
   The soybean runup in the last 1{ hours of trading coincided with
a rally in silver futures prices that may have sparked buying
interest in soybeans, said Walter Spilka, an analyst in New York
with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   ``There was no new fundamental news during the session but
sometimes the soybeans will trade with the precious metals
markets,'' he said.
   ``The grain markets had looked strong before today and the rise
in silver prices may have led to inflationary ideas,'' Spilka said.
   The dollar also weakened Thursday, making U.S. goods cheaper
overseas. Expectations that the dollar will remain weak against
other currencies may also have supported the soybean market, he
said.
   At the close, wheat was \ cent to 2 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.07 a bushel; corn was { cent to
1{ cents lower with May at $2.06} a bushel; oats were { cent to 1\
cents higher with May at $1.68\ a bushel; soybeans were 7{ cents to
10\ cents higher with May at $6.50 a bushel.
</TEXT>
