<1ST_LINE>r f AM-DelawareGroup     03-24 0167</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delaware Group,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delaware Group To Be Acquired in LBO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delaware Management Co., a Philadelphia-based
money management firm that oversees $18 billion in assets, said
Thursday it was being acquired in a leveraged buyout valued in
excess of $200 million.
   Delaware's management joined with Legend Capital L.P. in
acquiring the company for ``a price in excess of $200 million in
equity and debt,'' said Charles Storer, a spokesman for the
companies. Further details were not available.
   Legend Capital is a private investment firm formed last year by
John Castle, the former chief executive of Donaldson Lufkin &
Jenrette, and partner Leonard Harlan, who heads a real estate
investment firm.
   Delaware Management handles $15 billion in pension money for 225
corporate and public pension funds, including those of
International Business Machines Corp. and Amoco Corp. The firm also
manages $5 billion in assets in 16 mutual funds.
   Legend had $125 million in investments from pension funds,
endowments and indviduals as of last November.
</TEXT>
