<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 2204EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-PhoneCosts     03-24 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Phone Costs,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McGraw-Hill Says Phone Costs Steady In First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business phone costs held steady in the first
three months of 1987, the first quarter since 1984 in which they
have have not fallen, according to a report Thursday.
   A 10 percent rise in rates for interstate private lines offset
declines of 7 percent in rates for both WATS and toll calls, said
CCMI-McGraw-Hill, which conducts the quarterly survey.
   The firm's Telecommunications Price Index remained level at
77.3, down from a base of 100 in 1984.
   The big three long-distance companies seem to be adjusting their
rates to make it attractive for business customers to switch from
private lines to WATS and toll service, said George Christie, chief
economist for McGraw-Hill Information Systems Co.
   American Telephone & Telegraph Co. dominates the interstate
long-distance market, with MCI Communications Corp. and US Sprint
Communications Co. trailing.
   The cost of local business calling remained stable during the
period.
   Christie said any changes in phone rates in the final days of
the month would have an insignificant effect on the first-quarter
index.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
