<DOCNO> AP880324-0326 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 2218EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Tax-Lawsuit     03-24 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tax-Lawsuit,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Fighting Suit That Could Cost $140 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court challenge to a Florida tax on
insurance premiums and annuities will decide whether the Department
of Revenue owes out-of-state insurance companies $140 million in
refunds.
   The companies don't like the way the state currently assesses
taxes on money that consumers pay to insurers _ a 2 percent tax on
premiums and 1 percent tax on annuities.
   The tax is paid only by out-of-state companies, not by
Florida-based insurers. The out-of-state companies say that isn't
fair, and many of them have asked for refunds.
   The law was changed last year to require all insurance
companies, including those based in Florida, to pay the premium
insurance tax, but that change won't take effect until July 1.
   The state targeted one case _ Continental Insurance Co. _ to be
a test case in circuit court.
   ``If (the case) comes down in our favor, we'll be all right
financially,'' said Walter Wood, an attorney in the Department of
Banking and Finance, one of three state agencies in the case. ``If
not, there's a lot of money involved.''
   New York-based Continental sought a refund of $1.5 million that
it paid in taxes in 1983, 1984 and 1985. It is one of 210 companies
that have filed for a total of $140 million in refunds _ an amount
roughly equal to the entire budget for the Department of Banking
and Finance.
   ``It's substantial,'' said Daniel Brown of the Department of
Legal Affairs, which is handling the case.
   In its refund claim, Continental argued that the U.S. Supreme
Court ruled in 1985 that such disriminatory taxing policies were
unconstitutional.
   According to the state comptroller's office, out-of-state
insurance companies have filed claims to recover taxes paid as long
ago as the mid-1970s.
   Brown argued on the state's behalf that the Florida tax law
should be considered legal until courts rule on its
constitutionality.
   Brown also claimed that the out-of-state insurance companies
passed along the tax to consumers through its premiums and
refunding the money would unjustly enrich the companies.
   The Department of Banking and Finance is involved because the
comptroller rules on requests for tax refunds. The Department of
Revenue both collects the tax and makes the refunds, while the
Department of Insurance regulates the insurance industry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
