<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1713EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   03-24 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0574</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices took a sharp drop Thursday as the
dollar slumped in foreign exchange and U.S. interest rates headed
higher.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials fell 43.77 points to
2,023.87.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by more than 5 to 1 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 269 up, 1,379 down and 347 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 184.91 million shares, against 167.37
million in the previous session. The NYSE's composite index dropped
2.82 to 149.00.
   As the dollar lost ground, prices of long-term government bonds
fell about $5 for each $1,000 in face value during the morning,
putting their yields in the 8.75 to 8.8 percent range. At their
best recent levels, yields on Treasury bonds were as low as 8.3
percent.
   Bonds later recovered a good part of their early losses, but
stocks did not follow suit.
   Analysts said pressure on the dollar prompted concern in markets
around the world. Prices fell in both the London and Tokyo stock
markets.
   Against that background, brokers said, investors moved quickly
to cash on the U.S. market's gains since late last year.
   Thursday's session marked the fourth time the Dow Jones
industrial average came close to, but did not quite reach, the
50-point plus or minus limit set by the NYSE Feb. 4 at which
restrictions go into effect on the use of its computer trading
facilities for so-called index arbitrage trading.
   Though this ``collar,'' as exchange officials call it, has never
been activated, many Wall Streeters say it appears to have become a
sort of de facto limit on daily price swings, and possibly a target
for traders as well.
   Among actively traded blue chip and technology issues, General
Electric dropped } to 41~; International Business Machines 1~ to
109}; Digital Equipment 3} to 107|, and American Telephone &
Telegraph { to 27}.
   Digital Equipment, which has a wide following among investing
institutions as a leading technology company, dropped below its
lowest point in the October crash.
   In the securities industry group, Merrill Lynch fell } to 23{;
Salomon 1[ to 21\; First Boston 1[ to 25; Morgan Stanley } to 59\,
and Charles Schwab ] to 8\.
   Some stocks involved in takeover developments bucked the
downtrend. Irving Bank, which jumped 6| to 66\, said that it was
negotiating with unnamed ``third parties'' about a possible merger,
restructuring or sale of assets as an alternative to a hostile bid
by Bank of New York.
   International Clinical Laboratories climbed 8 to 33} in
over-the-counter trading. Smithkline Beckman made a $32-a-share bid
for the company, which had agreed to an acquisition by Corning
Glass Works for $26 a share.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $46.65 billion, or 1.75
percent, in value.
   Nationwide turnover in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 215.22 million shares.
   Standard & Poor's index of 400 industrials fell 6.72 to 305.31,
and S&P's 500-stock composite index was down 5.56 at 263.35.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
dropped 4.49 to 375.60. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 297.30, down 3.11.
</TEXT>
