<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1716EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     03-24 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Continues Slide; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precedes BC-LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar continued to slide Thursday, reaching
levels against the Japanese yen and West German mark not seen for
two months as a bearish sentiment pervaded currency markets.
   Gold prices firmed. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a
bid price for gold of $453.15 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up
from Wednesday's late bid of $451.15 an ounce.
   Traders said the dollar continued to suffer from comments made
Wednesday by Martin Feldstein, former chief economic advisor to the
president, who said the currency should fall to 120 yen in the near
term.
   In an address at New York University, Feldstein also predicted
the dollar would decline against other currencies over the next
several years.
   ``Those comments are not new, but they triggered losses'' in the
dollar, said Earl Johnson, a vice president at Irving Trust Co.
   The dollar, which closed at 125.575 yen in New York, last traded
at that level in mid-January. Traders said the yen continues to
strengthen ahead of the close of the Japanese fiscal year on March
31 and on the expectation that the Japanese economy will forge
ahead.
   The dollar also weakened somewhat on government reports that
personal income grew 0.9 percent in February and that personal
consumption expenditures grew 0.7 percent during the month.
   The figures indicated that consumer spending is picking up
again, which likely will result in wider trade deficits, said Nigel
Green, a trader at EBC-Amro Bank in London.
   Johnson echoed that sentiment, saying that the ``mildly bearish
sentiment'' toward the dollar is being spurred by ``the realization
that there will be larger trade deficits later in the year.''
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar closed at 126.30 yen, down 0.85 yen. Later in London, it was
quoted at a lower rate of 125.75 yen.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.8435 from Wednesday's
$1.8358. In New York, it cost $1.8420 to buy one pound, more
expensive than Wednesday's $1.83725.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared to late Wednesday,
included: 1.67725 West German marks, down from 1.6916; 1.38625
Swiss francs, down from 1.3985; 5.7045 French francs, down from
5.7470; 1,242.50 Italian lire, down from 1,251.875, and 1.2421
Canadian dollars, down from 1.2430.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday,
included: 1.6800 West German marks, down from 1.6915; 1.3885 Swiss
francs, down from 1.3990; 5.7120 French francs, down from 5.7450;
1.8980 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9005; 1,246.95 Italian lire,
down from 1,253.25, and 1.2426 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2434.
   Gold prices moved mostly higher. On the New York Commodity
Exchange, gold closed at $454.10, up from $451.10 an ounce
Wednesday.
   In London gold fell to a late bid price of $452 a troy ounce,
compared with late Wednesday's $453. In Zurich, gold rose to close
at a bid $452, compared with $450.50 late Wednesday. Earlier, in
Hong Kong, gold rose $3.34 to close at $455.40 an ounce.
   Silver closed at $6.735 an ounce on New York's Comex, up from
$6.610 on Wednesday. In London, the metal was trading at a late bid
price of $6.61 a troy ounce, compared with Wednesday's $6.63.
</TEXT>
