<DOCNO> AP880324-0329 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1735EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneySupply     03-24 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Supply,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Supply Measures Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two broadest measures of the nation's money
supply jumped in mid-March, the Federal Reserve Board reported
Thursday.
   The report had no impact on interest rates in the credit
markets, however.
   The Fed said the measure known as M2 rose $11.2 billion to a
seasonally adjusted $2,965.5 billion in the week ended March 14
from $2,954.3 billion the previous week.
   An even broader measure, M3, increased $14.8 billion to a
seasonally adjusted $3,740.3 billion from $3,725.5 billion.
   The narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, rose $4.7 billion
to a seasonally adjusted $760.5 billion from $755.8 billion. For
the latest 13 weeks, M1 rose 2.6 percent to an average of $755.7
billion.
   M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts
and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings
deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid
accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations
of $100,000.
   In setting its monetary policy, the Fed has indicated it is
monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates. It also has
shifted its attention from M1 to the two broader money supply
measures
   The Fed said in early 1988 that it would like annual growth for
M2 and M3 to be between 4 percent and 8 percent, which is slightly
lower than the 1987 target of 5.5 percent to 8.5 percent. The Fed
has not set a specific target range for M1 since early 1987.
   In other reports:
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of New York reported commercial and
industrial loans at major New York City banks fell $48 million in
the week ended March 16 compared with a decline of $1.24 billion a
week earlier.
   _The Federal Reserve said bank borrowings from the Federal
Reserve System averaged $325 million a day in the week ended
Wednesday, up from $153 million in the previous week.
   _The Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis reported that the
monetary base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank
reserves held at Federal Reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and
in circulation, was $274.2 billion in the two-week period ended
Wednesday, up from $272.1 billion two weeks earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880324-0330 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1746EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     03-24 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Silver, Copper Futures Surge On GNP Growth, Inflation Signals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices for future delivery of silver and copper posted steep
gains Thursday on expections of increasing demand among industrial
users of the metals.
   Gold futures prices also advanced on perceptions of rising
inflation.
   On other markets, soybean futures surged while grain futures
were mixed; stock-index futures fell; energy futures and livestock
and meat futures were mixed.
   Wednesday's government figures showing the economy grew at a
higher-than-expected 4.8 percent rate in the fourth quarter of 1987
had a delayed impact on silver and copper futures on New York's
Commodity Exchange, said Bernard Savakl, a metals analyst for
PaineWebber.
   ``Silver and copper are industrial metals that have to play
catch-up on the upside now following the GNP report,'' Savakl said.
``What the government is saying is contrary to the majority of
expectations: the economy did not slow to a grinding halt but
gathered upward momentum, and that's very positive for industrial
metals.''
   Silver, which is also a precious metal and thus perceived as an
investment hedge against inflation, also gained in reaction to
generally higher futures prices for other commodities, Savakl said.
   The Commodities Research Bureau's index of 21 commodity markets
gained 1.25 points Thursday, a moderate advance.
   Analyst Stephen W. Platt of Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.,
attributed the silver rally to Far Eastern buying of the metal and
to the dollar's decline in value against foreign currencies.
   Platt also noted that copper is in short supply. Tight supplies
of copper have been cited to explain the metal's steady increase in
value since late February.
   Copper settled .50 cent to 6.25 cents higher with the contract
for delivery in March at $1.1395 a pound.
   Gold settled $2.20 to $3 higher with April at $454.30 a troy
ounce; silver was 12.5 cents to 13.4 cents higher with March at
$6.735 a troy ounce.
   The silver rally may have sparked buying interest in soybean
futures, which gained as much as 9{ cents a bushel on the Chicago
Board of Trade. Grains were mixed.
   ``There was no new fundamental news during the session but
sometimes the soybeans will trade with the precious metals
markets,'' said Walter Spilka, an analyst in New York with Smith
Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   ``The grain markets had looked strong before today and the rise
in silver prices may have led to inflationary ideas,'' he said.
   Expectations that the dollar will remain weak, making U.S. goods
cheaper overseas, may also have supported the soybean market, he
said.
   Wheat settled unchanged to 2 cents lower with May at $3.06} a
bushel; corn was } cent to 1\ cents higher with May at $2.07 a
bushel; oats were } cent to 1\ cents higher with May at $1.68{ a
bushel; soybeans were 7 cents to 9{ cents higher with May at $6.49\
a bushel.
   Stock-index futures tumbled on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
where the contract for June delivery of the Standard & Poor's 500
index settled 6.30 points lower at 264.10.
   Stock and stock-index futures prices opened sharply lower in
reaction to the dollar's weakness and continued to fall throughout
the session, said John Mitchell, an analyst for Elders Futures Inc.
   Oil prices finished mixed in moderate trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, reflecting uncertainty over the OPEC pricing
committee's ability to calm the turbulent market, analysts said.
   The group meets next month to discuss stabilizing sagging prices.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 2 cents to 10 cents
higher with May at $16.96 a barrel; heating oil was .16 cent to .41
cent lower with April at 47.40 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline
was .20 cent lower to .08 cent higher with April at 47.33 cents a
gallon.
   Cattle futures finished mostly lower and pork futures were
mostly higher in a day of choppy trading on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   Traders were wary of the sharp drop in stock prices, fearing a
repeat of the cattle market collapse that followed the stock
market's historic plunge in October, said Charlie Richardson, an
analyst in Denver with Lind-Waldock & Co.
   ``Everbody was keeping an eye on the indexes and what the stock
market was doing,'' he said.
   Live cattle settled .53 cent lower to .05 cent higher with April
at 74.40 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent to .65 cent
lower with March at 82.20 cents a pound; hogs were .20 cent lower
to .40 cent higher with April at 46.07 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .35 cent to .60 cent higher with March at 55.45 cents
a pound.
</TEXT>
