<1ST_LINE>u f AM-SmithKline-ICL     03-24 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SmithKline-ICL,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SmithKline Bids For Company Promised To Corning Glass</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pharmaceutical giant SmithKline Beckman
Corp. on Thursday launched a $32-a-share tender offer for
International Clinical Laboratories Inc., which already has
accepted a bid from Corning Glass Works.
   SmithKline valued its offer for the clinical testing firm at
$340 million, which includes the assumption of debt. SmithKline
owns about 1 percent of ICL's 7.6 million outstanding shares.
   In over-the-counter trading, ICL jumped $8 to close at $33.75 a
share.
   ICL, based in Nashville, Tenn., announced earlier this month
that it reached a definitive agreement to be acquired by Corning's
MetPath Inc. subsidiary for $26 a share, or about $260 million.
   A spokesman at Corning headquarters in Corning, N.Y., had no
comment on whether the company might increase its bid.
   Analysts said, however, that Corning, which earned $162.2
million last year, is financially capable of challenging SmithKline.
   ``Corning can go considerably higher if they found it
worthwhile,'' said Charles K. Ryan, an analyst with Merrill Lynch &
Co. in New York.
   Under terms of its merger agreement, Corning has an option to
buy 3 million unissued ICL shares as well as ``all the shares owned
by certain directors and officers'' for $26 each.
   Ryan said the directors and officers hold 800,000 shares, which
would value the options at about $99 million. Companies sometimes
grant such ``lock-up'' options to keep others at bay by making a
subsequent bids more expensive.
   Henry Wendt, chairman and chief executive officer of
Philadelphia-based SmithKline, said in a statement that the offer
is ``consistent with our corporate strategy to invest in our key
businesses and will build on the success of our clinical
laboratories network.''
   SmithKline Bio-Science Laboratories, the company's clinical
laboratory segment headquartered in King of Prussia, Pa., operates
22 regional laboratories. It reported sales of $431 million last
year.
   SmithKline is ``No. 1, and they want to get even bigger'' by
acquiring ICL, said David Lippman, an analyst with Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc.
   Corning's MetPath subsidiary, which is headquartered in
Teterboro, N.J., operates a testing laboratory there as well as 12
others nationwide.
   ICL's 13 clinical testing laboratories are located in the South
and West. The company has a substantial contract to conduct AIDs
tests on 27,000 federal prisoners in 47 prisons and recently
announced the opening of a new division in Nashville to market its
laboratory testing service to the insurance industry nationwide.
   For the fiscal year ended last Aug. 31, ICL reported profits of
$4.8 million on sales of $205.5 million.
   As a condition of its offer, which expires at midnight April 20,
SmithKline said that two Tennessee laws governing takeovers must be
found invalid or inapplicable.
   Corning's offer expires April 5.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
