<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 0650EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BoeingOrder     03-24 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boeing Order,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lufthansa Orders 20 Boeing Jets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lufthansa German Airlines has ordered 20 Boeing
737 airliners and taken options on 20 more of the twin-engined
jets, Boeing Commercial Airplanes said Wednesday.
   Under terms of the order, worth approximately $535 million,
Lufthansa will begin receiving the new aircraft in October 1990,
with deliveries continuing through May 1991, said Boeing spokesman
Tom Cole.
   Cole said the jets will be a mix of 141-passenger 737-300s and
98-passenger 737-500s, but the number of each type of plane has not
yet been decided.
   The 737-500 is the smallest commercial jet Boeing sells. It is
now under development and is scheduled to be introduced in February
1990.
   The 737-500 is nearly identical to the 737-300, except that at
97 feet, 9 inches it is 7 feet, 10 inches shorter. Crews rated for
one model can also fly the other.
   Lufthansa plans to use the new aircraft to replace older
aircraft in its fleet, Cole said. The new planes will be powered by
CFM56-3B1 engines made by General Electric of the United States and
SNECMA of France.
   Lufthansa, which bought the first 737 from Boeing in 1965, now
has ordered 90 of the planes.
   Boeing has now received 2,028 orders for all 737 models, the
most-popular commercial jetliner ever made.
</TEXT>
