<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Davis-Lorimar     03-24 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Davis-Lorimar,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Davis, Snubbed in Lorimar Bid, Weighs Suit, Hostile Tender Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor Marvin Davis, snubbed in his $770
million takeover bid for Lorimar Telepictures Corp., sought
Wednesday to turn up the heat in his fight for the entertainment
concern.
   Davis said he would consider other ``alternative courses of
action'' if Lorimar continues to hold merger talks only with Warner
Communications Inc., the New York-based entertainment conglomerate.
   A Lorimar spokesman said those options included filing suit
against Lorimar or making a hostile tender offer.
   Noting that the price of Lorimar stock has risen more than 50
percent since Lorimar disclosed on March 3 that it was talking with
Warner, Davis said, ``I believe you have passed the point of no
return ... It is time to quickly and efficiently provide equal
access (to non-public information) to all serious bidders.''
   He added, ``It is upsetting to me, as it must be to all
shareholders, that only one of the parties interested in acquiring
LT has had the opportunity to inspect its books and records.''
   Davis is offering $17 per share for Lorimar's 45.3 million
shares. No details of the price being discussed by Warner has been
disclosed, but analysts have estimated could fetch a price in the
high teens.
   The company's stock closed unchanged at $15 a share Wednesday on
the American Stock Exchange.
   Davis also indicated that he owned a ``substantial block'' of
Lorimar stock. A spokesman said it was less than the 5 percent
which an investor must disclose and most, if not all, of the stock
was acquired before Davis made his takeover proposal on March 7.
   Lorimar spokeswoman Sue Binford said Wednesday that the company
had no comment on Davis' announcement and declined to comment on
the status of talks with Warner.
   Lorimar dismissed Davis' proposal in rather summary fashion just
hours after it was disclosed two weeks ago, saying only that it
``would bear Davis' letter in mind.''
   Lorimar, based in suburban Culver City, is a leading producer of
original television programming, but in recent years has been
troubled as its ambitious plans to expand into other areas have
disintegrated and sometimes caused hevy losses for the company.
   In the first nine months of its current fiscal year, Lorimar
lost $82.6 million on revenues of $616.8 million. The deficit
included $45 million in writedowns on five movies and $22 million
in reserves for possible future losses in its home-video unit.
</TEXT>
