<DOCNO> AP880324-0335 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 2226EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-MotorolaElectronics     03-24 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Motorola Electronics,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Motorola To Pay $16.7 Million In Fines For Navy Mischarges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorola Inc.'s electronics group has agreed
to pay the government $16.7 million and to plead guilty to a
criminal information accusing it of mischarging for labor and
materials on Navy satellite and missile contracts, the Justice
Department announced Thursday.
   In documents filed in U.S. District Court in Phoenix, Motorola's
Government Electronics Group in Scottsdale, Ariz., was accused of
inflating costs for a component of a Navy satellite communications
and mischarging $2.5 million in labor, materials and other costs.
The money actually was spent on other work, the government said.
   The Defense Department, relying on the inflated amounts, paid
some $5 million more than it should have on a second contract for
the satellite communications system, said the government.
   Motorola, one of the nation's top 50 defense contractors, agreed
to plead guilty to three counts of making false statements.
   The firm said in a statement from Motorola headquarters in
Schaumburg, Ill., that ``it is now clear in retrospect'' that the
electronics group's ``systems were not adequate to ensure total
compliance with applicable laws and regulations.''
   ``The conduct of the employees involved in these programs failed
to conform to Motorola's own internal standards,'' the statement
added. The electronics group ``has greatly expanded its compliance
efforts'' with reforms which ``are now an integral part of the way
GEG does business.''
   Under the agreement, which still must be approved by a court,
the government has agreed not to prosecute the company further on
the contracts, but reserves the right to prosecute individuals.
   The court documents also say the firm mischarged labor costs for
work on 10 contracts involving production of target detecting
devices for the Navy's Standard missile.
   The third count in the criminal information said Motorola
mischarged labor costs on a contract for the production of
targeting detecting devices for the Navy's Phoenix missile.
   Motorola will pay $16.7 million in criminal fines, restitution
and civil penalties. The company already has paid $6.8 million to
the Defense Department.
   The pleas result from an investigation into labor and materials
charging and pricing practices by Motorola from 1979 to 1984.
</TEXT>
