<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AtlantisReorganization     03-24 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Atlantis Reorganization,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Atlantis Reorganization Plan Denied</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy court judge rejected on
Thursday a financial reorganization plan for Elsinore Corp.'s
Atlantis Casino Hotel, but attorneys for the gaming hall say they
are confident they can amend the proposal to the judge's
satisfaction.
   Judge Rosemary Gambardella, in a 90-page decision, objected to a
proposal that Elsinore would be free from future claims if any were
filed.
   ``The present release and discharge provisions of the plan stand
as an obstacle to confirmation of the plan as presently
constituted,'' she wrote.
   She said, however, she would consider amendments to the plan if
the company wanted to submit changes.
   Marvin E. Jacob, attorney for the Atlantis, said he will move to
eliminate the offending provision of the reorganization plan,
perhaps as early as Friday.
   The Atlantis, a casino hotel in Atlantic City, has been
operating under Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection since November
1985.
   After the court ruling, Atlantis President Jeanne Hood told the
state Casino Control Commission he was confident the reorganization
plan is still viable. The commission is in the midst of relicensing
hearings for the Atlantis.
   The Atlantis has more than 15,000 creditors, but the pay-back
plan concentrates on about 700 main creditors.
   Under the reorganization plan, Elsinore will raise $70 million
by refinancing its two Nevada casinos and will receive about $20
million from the sale of a note.
</TEXT>
