<FILEID>AP-NR-03-24-88 1953EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-LordGeller     03-24 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lord Geller,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Client Drops Ad Agency, Another Puts Account Up for Review</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York television station said Thursday it
was dropping WPP Group PLC's Lord, Geller, Federico, Einstein unit
as its advertising agency, and another Lord Geller client said it
would review its ad assignment.
   Meanwhile, a New York state court judge set a hearing for Monday
on the agency's request for an injunction against a half-dozen
former top Lord Geller executives who left the agency abruptly last
week to start their own ad firm.
   The executives have indicated they felt constrained under the
management of WPP Group, the British firm that acquired Lord Geller
in July 1987.
   Since the executives quit, about 20 other Lord Geller employees
have followed their former bosses to the new agency, Lord,
Einstein, O'Neill & Partners.
   Lord Geller has filed suit in New York State Supreme Court to
try to prevent the former executives from signing its clients and
hiring its workers for their new agency.
   Lord Geller employs more than 300 people and handles billings of
about $245 million. Billings are what companies spend on
advertising; agencies usually get a percentage of billings for
their work.
   WNBC-TV, a New York television station that has been a client of
Lord Geller for four years, said it had notified WPP Group's chief
executive, Martin Sorrell, that it was assigning its ad business to
the new agency.
   Linda Lipman, director of advertising and promotions for the
station, said station executives felt they had built up a special
relationship with Richard Lord, the former chairman and chief
executive of Lord Geller who resigned to start the new firm, and
would be ``better serviced'' at the new agency.
   Separately, Fuji Photo Film USA Inc., based in Elmsford, N.Y.,
said it was planning to review its advertising accounts now being
handled by Lord Geller.
   Lord Geller is the agency for Fuji divisions that market audio
and video tape and floppy disks.
   Gene Kern, advertising manager for Fuji's magnetic products
division, said the decision was made ``after studying recent
changes at the agency.''
   He said Fuji planned to invite specific agencies to participate
in the review but declined to say if Lord Geller or Lord Einstein
would be invited.
   Neither WNBC-TV nor Fuji would say how much they billed through
Lord Geller. A third Lord Geller client, New Yorker magazine, has
already indicated that it plans to drop the agency and sign on with
the new firm.
   Lord Geller's biggest account is International Business Machines
Corp., based in Armonk, N.Y. IBM reportedly accounts for about half
of Lord Geller's total billings, and has said it is ``concerned''
about recent events at the agency and has told the agency so.
</TEXT>
