<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Markets     03-24 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stock Prices Down In Early Tokyo Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar slid further against the Japanese
yen in early trading Friday in Tokyo following an overnight decline
in New York, and stock prices fell sharply.
   The dollar opened at 125.68 yen, down from Thursday's close of
126.30 yen.
   Ken Iiya of the Bank of Tokyo, said buyers were supporting the
dollar somewhat, keeping the currency above its overnight close of
125.575 yen in New York, its lowest level there since mid-January.
   He said trading was quiet due to the absence of market-affecting
news on the week's final day of currency dealings.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, down 113.95 points on Thursday, fell another
252.84 points, or 0.98 percent, to 25,528.44 in the first 25
minutes of trading.
   Share prices in the first section were lower across the board as
almost all issues posted losses, dealers said.
</TEXT>
