<1ST_LINE>u f BC-MooreMcCormack     03-24 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Moore McCormack,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Southdown Ups Offer For Moore McCormack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southdown Inc. has increased its offer to take
over Moore McCormack Resources Inc. to $40 in cash and securities
per share, the company said Thursday.
   Southdown, which previously had offered $35 cash a share to
acquire the Connecticut-based cement and energy company, made the
sweetened offer in a letter to Paul R. Tregurtha, chairman and
chief executive officer of Stanford, Conn.-based Moore McCormack.
   Southdown offered to pay $35 cash plus debt securities valued at
$5 for each of Moore McCormack's 12.8 million common shares
outstanding, an indicated total value of $512 million. Southdown
also has offered to acquire Moore McCormack preferred stock and
subordinated debt.
   The proposal came one day after Moore McCormack unveiled a
defensive recapitalization plan under which it would borrow up to
$420 million and sell assets to finance a special dividend to
shareholders of $24.60 per share in cash and debt securities with a
face value of $6.62 per share.
   In the letter to Moore McCormack, Southdown president and chief
executive Clarence C. Comer said the securities contained in its
sweetened offer would carry the same financial terms as those
offered under Moore McCormack's recapitalization plan.
   Moore McCormack's board has rejected Southdown's $35 a share
cash offer and an earlier $31 a share bid that began the takeover
battle on Feb. 23.
   Officials from Moore McCormack could not be reached for comment
Thursday afternoon.
   Both firms are in the cement and concrete businesses, with minor
holdings in oil and gas.
   Also Thursday, a Southdown subsidiary, SDW Inc., amended its
pending tender offer to increase the price to be paid for share of
common stock of Moore McCormack to $40 per share. SDW offered to
decrease the maximum number of common shares that it would purchase
in the tender offer to about 11.4 million shares, on a fully
diluted basis.
   Southdown's offer expires at midnight on Wednesday, April 6,
unless extended.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
